\par THE PROPHET
\par The prophet was drowning men on Great Wyk when they came to tell him that the king was dead. 
\par It was a bleak, cold morning, and the sea was as leaden as the sky. The first three men had offered their lives to the Drowned God fearlessly, but the fourth was 
weak in faith and began to struggle as his lungs cried out for air. Standing waist-deep in the surf, Aeron seized the naked boy by the shoulders and pushed his head back down as he tried to snatch a breath. \'93Have courage,\'94 he said. \'93
We came from the sea, and to the sea we must return. Open your mouth and drink deep of god\rquote s blessing. Fill your lungs with water, that you may die and be reborn. It does no good to fight.\'94 
\par Either the boy could not hear him with his head beneath the waves, or else his faith had
 utterly deserted him. He began to kick and thrash so wildly that Aeron had to call for help. Four of his drowned men waded out to seize the wretch and hold him underwater. \'93Lord God who drowned for us,\'94
 the priest prayed, in a voice as deep as the sea, \'93let Emmond your servant be reborn from the sea, as you were. Bless him with salt, bless him with stone, bless him with steel.\'94 
\par Finally, it was done. No more air was bubbling from his mouth, and all the strength had gone out of his limbs. Facedown in the shallow sea floated Emmond, pale and cold and peaceful. 
\par That was when the Damphair realized that three horsemen had joined his drowned men on the pebbled shore. Aeron knew the Sparr, a hatchet-faced old man with watery eyes whose quavery voice was law on th
is part of Great Wyk. His son Steffarion accompanied him, with another youth whose dark red fur-lined cloak was pinned at the shoulder with an ornate brooch that showed the black-and-gold warhorn of the Goodbrothers. }{\cs28\i One of Gorold\rquote s sons,
}{ the priest decided at a glance. Three tall sons had been born to Goodbrother\rquote 
s wife late in life, after a dozen daughters, and it was said that no man could tell one son from the others. Aeron Damphair did not deign to try. Whether this be Greydon or Gormond or Gran, the priest had no time for him. 
\par He growled a brusque command, and his drowned men seized the dead boy by his arms and legs to carry him above the tideline. The priest followed, naked but for a sealskin clout that covered his private parts. Goosefleshed and dri
pping, he splashed back onto land, across cold wet sand and sea-scoured pebbles. One of his drowned men handed him a robe of heavy roughspun dyed in mottled greens and blues and greys, the colors of the sea and the Drowned God. Aeron donned the robe and p
u
lled his hair free. Black and wet, that hair; no blade had touched it since the sea had raised him up. It draped his shoulders like a ragged, ropy cloak, and fell down past his waist. Aeron wove strands of seaweed through it, and through his tangled, uncu
t beard. 
\par His drowned men formed a circle around the dead boy, praying. Norjen worked his arms whilst Rus knelt astride him, pumping on his chest, but all moved aside for Aeron. He pried apart the boy\rquote s cold lips with his fingers and gave Emmond the kiss of
 life, and again, and again, until the sea came gushing from his mouth. The boy began to cough and spit, and his eyes blinked open, full of fear. 
\par }{\cs28\i Another one returned.}{ It was a sign of the Drowned God\rquote s favor, men said. Every other priest lost a man from 
time to time, even Tarle the Thrice-Drowned, who had once been thought so holy that he was picked to crown a king. But never Aeron Greyjoy. He was the Damphair, who had seen the god\rquote s own watery halls and returned to tell of it. \'93Rise,\'94
 he told the sputtering boy as he slapped him on his naked back. \'93You have drowned and been returned to us. What is dead can never die.\'94 
\par \'93But rises.\'94 The boy coughed violently, bringing up more water. \'93Rises again.\'94 Every word was bought with pain, but that was the way of the world; a man must fight to live. \'93Rises again.\'94 Emmond staggered to his feet. \'93
Harder. And stronger.\'94 
\par \'93You belong to the god now,\'94 Aeron told him. The other drowned men gathered round and each gave him a punch and a kiss to welcome him to the brotherhoo
d. One helped him don a roughspun robe of mottled blue and green and grey. Another presented him with a driftwood cudgel. \'93You belong to the sea now, so the sea has armed you,\'94 Aeron said. \'93
We pray that you shall wield your cudgel fiercely, against all the enemies of our god.\'94 
\par Only then did the priest turn to the three riders, watching from their saddles. \'93Have you come to be drowned, my lords?\'94 
\par The Sparr coughed. \'93I was drowned as a boy,\'94 he said, \'93and my son upon his name day.\'94 
\par Aeron snorted. That Steffarion Sparr had been given to the Drowned God soon after birth he had no doubt. He knew the manner of it too, a quick dip into a tub of seawater that scarce wet the infant\rquote 
s head. Small wonder the ironborn had been conquered, they who once held sway everywhere the sound of waves was heard. \'93That is no true drowning,\'94 he told the riders. \'93
He that does not die in truth cannot hope to rise from death. Why have you come, if not to prove your faith?\'94 
\par \'93Lord Gorold\rquote s son came seeking you, with news.\'94 The Sparr indicated the youth in the red cloak. 
\par The boy looked to be no more than six-and-ten. \'93Aye, and which are you?\'94 Aeron demanded. 
\par \'93Gormond. Gormond Goodbrother, if it please my lord.\'94 
\par \'93It is the Drowned God we must please. Have you been drowned, Gormond Goodbrother?\'94 
\par \'93On my name day, Damphair. My father sent me to find you and bring you to him. He needs to see you.\'94 
\par \'93Here I stand. Let Lord Gorold come and feast his eyes.\'94 Aeron took a leather skin from Rus, freshly filled with water from the sea. The priest pulled out the cork and took a swallow. 
\par \'93I am to bring you to the keep,\'94 insisted young Gormond, from atop his horse. 
\par }{\cs28\i He is afraid to dismount, lest he get his boots wet.}{ \'93I have the god\rquote s work to do.\'94 Aeron Greyjoy was a prophet. He did not suffer petty lords ordering him about like some thrall. 
\par \'93Gorold\rquote s had a bird,\'94 said the Sparr. 
\par \'93A maester\rquote s bird, from Pyke,\'94 Gormond confirmed. 
\par }{\cs28\i Dark wings, dark words.}{ \'93The ravens fly o\rquote er salt and stone. If there are tidings that concern me, speak them now.\'94 
\par \'93Such tidings as we bear are for your ears alone, Damphair,\'94 the Sparr said. \'93These are not matters I would speak of here before these others.\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i These others}{ are my drowned men, god\rquote s servants, just as I am. I have no secrets from them, nor from our god, beside whose holy sea I stand.\'94 
\par The horsemen exchanged a look. \'93Tell him,\'94 said the Sparr, and the youth in the red cloak summoned up his courage. \'93The king is dead,\'94 he said, as plain as that. Four small words, yet the sea itself trembled when he uttered them. 
\par Four kings there were in Westeros, yet Aeron did not need to ask which one was meant. Balon Greyjoy ruled the Iron Islands, and no other. }{\cs28\i The king is dead. How can that be?}{ Aeron had seen his eldest brother not a moon\rquote 
s turn past, when he had returned to the Iron Islands from harrying the Stony Shore. Balon\rquote s grey hair had gone half-white whilst the priest had been away, and the stoop in his shoulders was more pronounced than w
hen the longships sailed. Yet all in all the king had not seemed ill. 
\par Aeron Greyjoy had built his life upon two mighty pillars. Those four small words had knocked one down. }{\cs28\i Only the Drowned God remains to me. May he make me as strong and tireless as the sea.}{ \'93Tell me the manner of my brother\rquote s death.
\'94 
\par \'93His Grace was crossing a bridge at Pyke when he fell and was dashed upon the rocks below.\'94 
\par The Greyjoy stronghold stood upon a broken headland, its keeps and towers built atop massive stone stacks that thrust up from the sea. Bridges knotted Pyke together; arched bridges of carved stone and swaying spans of hempen rope and wooden planks. \'93
Was the storm raging when he fell?\'94 Aeron demanded of them. 
\par \'93Aye,\'94 the youth said, \'93it was.\'94 
\par \'93The Storm God cast him down,\'94
 the priest announced. For a thousand thousand years sea and sky had been at war. From the sea had come the ironborn, and the fish that sustained them even in the depths of winter, but storms brought only woe and grief. \'93My brother Balon made us great
 again, which earned the Storm God\rquote s wrath. He feasts now in the Drowned God\rquote s watery halls, with mermaids to attend his every want. It shall be for us who remain behind in this dry and dismal vale to finish his great work.\'94
 He pushed the cork back into his waterskin. \'93I shall speak with your lord father. How far from here to Hammerhorn?\'94 
\par \'93Six leagues. You may ride pillion with me.\'94 
\par \'93One can ride faster than two. Give me your horse, and the Drowned God will bless you.\'94 
\par \'93Take my horse, Damphair,\'94 offered Steffarion Sparr. 
\par \'93No. His mount is stronger. Your horse, boy.\'94 
\par The youth hesitated half a heartbeat, then dismounted and held the reins for the Damphair. Aeron shoved a bare black foot into a stirrup and swung himself onto the saddle. He was not fond of horses\emdash 
they were creatures from the green lands and helped to make men weak\emdash but necessity required that he ride. }{\cs28\i Dark wings, dark words.}{ A storm was brewing, he could hear it in the waves, and storms brought naught but evil. \'93
Meet with me at Pebbleton beneath Lord Merlyn\rquote s tower,\'94 he told his drowned men, as he turned the horse\rquote s head. 
\par The way was rough, up hills and woods and stony defiles, along a narrow track that oft seemed to disappear beneath the horse\rquote s hooves. Great Wyk was the largest of the Iron
 Islands, so vast that some of its lords had holdings that did not front upon the holy sea. Gorold Goodbrother was one such. His keep was in the Hardstone Hills, as far from the Drowned God\rquote s realm as any place in the isles. Gorold\rquote 
s folk toiled down in Gorold\rquote s mines, in the stony dark beneath the earth. Some lived and died without setting eyes upon salt water. }{\cs28\i Small wonder that such folk are crabbed and queer.}{ 
\par As Aeron rode, his thoughts turned to his brothers. 
\par Nine sons had been born from the loins of Quellon Greyjoy, the Lord of the Iron Islands. Harlon, Quenton, and Donel had been born of Lord Quellon\rquote 
s first wife, a woman of the Stonetrees. Balon, Euron, Victarion, Urrigon, and Aeron were the sons of his second, a Sunderly of Saltcliffe. For a third 
wife Quellon took a girl from the green lands, who gave him a sickly idiot boy named Robin, the brother best forgotten. The priest had no memory of Quenton or Donel, who had died as infants. Harlon he recalled but dimly, sitting grey-faced and still in a 
windowless tower room and speaking in whispers that grew fainter every day as the greyscale turned his tongue and lips to stone. }{\cs28\i One day we shall feast on fish together in the Drowned God\rquote s watery halls, the four of us and Urri too.}{ 

\par Nine sons had been born
 from the loins of Quellon Greyjoy, but only four had lived to manhood. That was the way of this cold world, where men fished the sea and dug in the ground and died, whilst women brought forth short-lived children from beds of blood and pain. Aeron had be
en the last and least of the four krakens, Balon the eldest and boldest, a fierce and fearless boy who lived only to restore the ironborn to their ancient glory. At ten he scaled the Flint Cliffs to the Blind Lord\rquote 
s haunted tower. At thirteen he could run a longship\rquote 
s oars and dance the finger dance as well as any man in the isles. At fifteen he had sailed with Dagmer Cleftjaw to the Stepstones and spent a summer reaving. He slew his first man there and took his first two salt wives. At seventeen Balon capta
ined his own ship. He was all that an elder brother ought to be, though he had never shown Aeron aught but scorn. }{\cs28\i I was weak and full of sin, and scorn was more than I deserved. Better to be scorned by Balon the Brave than beloved of Euron Crow
\rquote s Eye.}{ And if age and grief had turned Balon bitter with the years, they had also made him more determined than any man alive. }{\cs28\i He was born a lord\rquote s son and died a king, murdered by a jealous god,}{ Aeron thought, }{\cs28\i 
and now the storm is coming, a storm such as these isles have never known.}{ 
\par It was long after dark by the time the priest espied the spiky iron battlements of the Hammerhorn clawing at the crescent moon. Gorold\rquote s keep was hulking and blocky, its great stones quarried from the cliff that loomed behind it. Below 
its walls, the entrances of caves and ancient mines yawned like toothless black mouths. The Hammerhorn\rquote s iron gates had been closed and barred for the night. Aeron beat on them with a rock until the clanging woke a guard. 
\par The youth who admitted him was the image of Gormond, whose horse he\rquote d taken. \'93Which one are you?\'94 Aeron demanded. 
\par \'93Gran. My father awaits you within.\'94 
\par The hall was dank and drafty, full of shadows. One of Gorold\rquote s daughters offered the priest a horn of ale. Another poked at a sullen fir
e that was giving off more smoke than heat. Gorold Goodbrother himself was talking quietly with a slim man in fine grey robes, who wore about his neck a chain of many metals that marked him for a maester of the Citadel. 
\par \'93Where is Gormond?\'94 Gorold asked when he saw Aeron. 
\par \'93He returns afoot. Send your women away, my lord. And the maester as well.\'94 He had no love of maesters. Their ravens were creatures of the Storm God, and he did not trust their healing, not since Urri. }{\cs28\i No proper man would choose a life of
 thralldom, nor forge a chain of servitude to wear about his throat.}{ 
\par \'93Gysella, Gwin, leave us,\'94 Goodbrother said curtly. \'93You as well, Gran. Maester Murenmure will stay.\'94 
\par \'93He will go,\'94 insisted Aeron. 
\par \'93This is my hall, Damphair. It is not for you to say who must go and who remains. The maester stays.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i The man lives too far from the sea,}{ Aeron told himself. \'93Then I shall go,\'94 he told Goodbrother. Dry rushes rustled underneath the cracked soles of his bare black feet as he turned and stalked away. It seem
ed he had ridden a long way for naught. 
\par Aeron was almost at the door when the maester cleared his throat, and said, \'93Euron Crow\rquote s Eye sits the Seastone Chair.\'94 
\par The Damphair turned. The hall had suddenly grown colder. }{\cs28\i The Crow\rquote s Eye is half a world away. Balon sent him off two years ago, and swore that it would be his life if he returned.}{ \'93Tell me,\'94 he said hoarsely. 
\par \'93He sailed into Lordsport the day after the king\rquote s death, and claimed the castle and the crown as Balon\rquote s eldest brother,\'94 said Gorold Goodbrother. \'93
Now he sends forth ravens, summoning the captains and the kings from every isle to Pyke, to bend their knees and do him homage as their king.\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 Aeron Damphair did not weigh his words. \'93Only a godly man may sit the Seastone Chair. The Crow\rquote s Eye worships naught but his own pride.\'94 
\par \'93You were on Pyke not long ago, and saw the king,\'94 said Goodbrother. \'93Did Balon say aught to you of the succession?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Aye.}{ They had spoken in the Sea Tower, as the wind howled outside the windows and the waves crashed restlessly below. Balon had shaken his head in despair when he heard what Aeron had to tell him of his last remaining son. \'93
The wolves have made a weakling of him, as I feared,\'94 the king had said. \'93I pray god that they killed him, so he cannot stand in Asha\rquote s way.\'94 That was Balon\rquote 
s blindness; he saw himself in his wild, headstrong daughter, and believed she could succeed him. He was wrong in that, and Aeron tried to tell him so. \'93No woman will ever rule the ironborn, not even a woman such as Asha,\'94
 he insisted, but Balon could be deaf to things he did not wish to hear. 
\par Before the priest could answer Gorold Goodbrother, the maester\rquote s mouth flapped open once again. \'93By rights the Seastone Chair belongs to Theon, or Asha if the prince is dead. That is the law.\'94 
\par \'93Green land law,\'94 said Aeron with contempt. \'93What is that to us? We are ironborn, the sons of the sea, chosen of the Drowned God. No woman may rule over us, nor any godless man.\'94 
\par \'93And Victarion?\'94 asked Gorold Goodbrother. \'93He has the Iron Fleet. Will Victarion make a claim, Damphair?\'94 
\par \'93Euron is the elder brother . . .\'94 began the maester. 
\par Aeron silenced him with a look. In little fishing towns and great stone keeps alike such a look from Damphair would make maids feel faint and send children shrieking to their mothers, and it was more than sufficient to quell the chain-neck thrall. \'93
Euron is elder,\'94 the priest said, \'93but Victarion is more godly.\'94 
\par \'93Will it come to war between them?\'94 asked the maester. 
\par \'93Ironborn must not spill the blood of ironborn.\'94 
\par \'93A pious sentiment, Damphair,\'94 said Goodbrother, \'93but not one that your brother shares. He had Sawane Botley drowned for saying that the Seastone Chair by rights belonged to Theon.\'94 
\par \'93If he was drowned, no blood was shed,\'94 said Aeron. 
\par The maester and the lord exchanged a look. \'93I must send word to Pyke, and soon,\'94 said Gorold Goodbrother. \'93Damphair, I would have your counsel. What shall it be, homage or defiance?\'94 
\par Aeron tugged his beard, and thought. }{\cs28\i I have seen the storm, and its name is Euron Crow\rquote s Eye.}{ \'93For now, send only silence,\'94 he told the lord. \'93I must pray on this.\'94 
\par \'93Pray all you wish,\'94 the maester said. \'93It does not change the law. Theon is the rightful heir, and Asha next.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93Silence!\'94}{ Aeron roared. \'93Too long have the ironborn listened to you chain-neck maesters prating of the green lands and their laws. It is time we listened to the sea again. It is time we listened to the voice of god.\'94
 His own voice rang in that smoky hall, so full of power that neither Gorold Goodbrother nor his maester dared a reply. }{\cs28\i The Drowned God is with me,}{ Aeron thought. }{\cs28\i He has shown me the way. }{
\par Goodbrother offered him the comforts of the castle for the night, but the priest declined. He seldom slept beneath a castle roof, and never so far from the sea. \'93Comforts I shall know in the Drowned God\rquote 
s watery halls beneath the waves. We are born to suffer, that our sufferings might make us strong. All that I require is a fresh horse to carry me to Pebbleton.\'94 
\par That Goodbrother was pleased to provide. He se
nt his son Greydon as well, to show the priest the shortest way through the hills down to the sea. Dawn was still an hour off when they set forth, but their mounts were hardy and surefooted, and they made good time despite the darkness. Aeron closed his e
yes and said a silent prayer, and after a while began to drowse in the saddle. 
\par The sound came softly, the scream of a rusted hinge. \'93Urri,\'94 he muttered, and woke, fearful. }{\cs28\i There is no hinge here, no door, no Urri.}{ A flying axe took off half of Urri\rquote s hand 
when he was ten-and-four, playing at the finger dance whilst his father and his elder brothers were away at war. Lord Quellon\rquote s third wife had been a Piper of Pinkmaiden Castle, a girl with big soft breasts and brown doe\rquote 
s eyes. Instead of healing Urri\rquote s h
and the Old Way, with fire and seawater, she gave him to her green land maester, who swore that he could sew back the missing fingers. He did that, and later he used potions and poltices and herbs, but the hand mortified and Urri took a fever. By the time
 the maester sawed his arm off, it was too late. 
\par Lord Quellon never returned from his last voyage; the Drowned God in his goodness granted him a death at sea. It was Lord Balon who came back, with his brothers Euron and Victarion. When Balon heard what had befallen Urri, he removed three of the maester
\rquote s fingers with a cook\rquote s cleaver and sent his father\rquote s Piper wife to sew them back on. Poltices and potions worked as well for the maester as they had for Urrigon. He died raving, and Lord Quellon\rquote s third wife
 followed soon thereafter, as the midwife drew a stillborn daughter from her womb. Aeron had been glad. It had been his axe that sheared off Urri\rquote s hand, whilst they danced the finger dance together, as friends and brothers will. 
\par It shamed him still to recall the years that followed Urri\rquote 
s death. At six-and-ten he called himself a man, but in truth he had been a sack of wine with legs. He would sing, he would dance (but not the finger dance, never again), he would jape and jabber and make mock. He played t
he pipes, he juggled, he rode horses, and could drink more than all the Wynches and the Botleys, and half the Harlaws too. The Drowned God gives every man a gift, even him; no man could piss longer or farther than Aeron Greyjoy, as he proved at every feas
t. Once he bet his new longship against a herd of goats that he could quench a hearthfire with no more than his cock. Aeron feasted on goat for a year, and named the longship }{\cs28\i Golden Storm,}{
 though Balon threatened to hang him from her mast when he heard what sort of ram his brother proposed to mount upon her prow. 
\par In the end the }{\cs28\i Golden Storm}{ went down off Fair Isle during Balon\rquote s first rebellion, cut in half by a towering war galley called }{\cs28\i Fury}{ when Stannis Baratheon caught Victarion in his trap and smashed 
the Iron Fleet. Yet the god was not done with Aeron, and carried him to shore. Some fishermen took him captive and marched him down to Lannisport in chains, and he spent the rest of the war in the bowels of Casterly Rock, proving that krakens can piss far
ther and longer than lions, boars, or chickens. 
\par }{\cs28\i That man is dead.}{ Aeron had drowned and been reborn from the sea, the god\rquote s own prophet. No mortal man could frighten him, no more than the darkness could . . . nor memories, the bones of the soul. }{\cs28\i The sound 
of a door opening, the scream of a rusted iron hinge. Euron has come again.}{ It did not matter. He was the Damphair priest, beloved of the god. 
\par \'93Will it come to war?\'94 asked Greydon Goodbrother as the sun was lightening the hills. \'93A war of brother against brother?\'94 
\par \'93If the Drowned God wills it. No godless man may sit the Seastone Chair.\'94 }{\cs28\i The Crow\rquote s Eye will fight, that is certain.}{
 No woman could defeat him, not even Asha; women were made to fight their battles in the birthing bed. And Theon, if he lived, was just as hopeless, a boy of sulks and smiles. At Winterfell he proved his worth, such that it was, but the Crow\rquote 
s Eye was no crippled boy. The decks of Euron\rquote s ship were painted red, to better hide the blood that soaked them. }{\cs28\i Victarion. The king must be Victarion, or the storm will slay us all.}{ 
\par Greydon left him when the sun was up, to take the news of Balon\rquote s death to his cousins in their towers at Downdelving, Crow Spike Keep, and Corpse Lake. Aeron continued on alone, up hills and down vales along a st
ony track that drew wider and more traveled as he neared the sea. In every village he paused to preach, and in the yards of petty lords as well. \'93We were born from the sea, and to the sea we all return,\'94
 he told them. His voice was as deep as the ocean, and thundered like the waves. \'93The Storm God in his wrath plucked Balon from his castle and cast him down, and now he feasts beneath the waves in the Drowned God\rquote s watery halls.\'94
 He raised his hands. \'93}{\cs28\i Balon is dead! The king is dead!}{ Yet a king will come again! For what is dead may never die, but rises again, harder and stronger! }{\cs28\i A king will rise!}{\'94 
\par Some of those who heard him threw down their hoes and picks to follow, so by the time he heard the crash of waves a dozen men walked behind his horse, touched by god and desirous of drowning. 
\par Pebbleton was home to several thousand fisherfolk, whose hovels huddled round the base of a square towerhouse with a turret at each corner. Twoscore of Aeron\rquote s drowned men there awaited him, camped along a grey sand beach in 
sealskin tents and shelters built of driftwood. Their hands were roughened by brine, scarred by nets and lines, callused from oars and picks and axes, but now those hands gripped driftwood cudgels hard as iron, for the god had armed them from his arsenal 
beneath the sea. 
\par They had built a shelter for the priest just above the tideline. Gladly he crawled into it, after he had drowned his newest followers. }{\cs28\i My god,}{ he prayed, }{\cs28\i 
speak to me in the rumble of the waves, and tell me what to do. The captains and the kings await your word. Who shall be our king in Balon\rquote 
s place? Sing to me in the language of leviathan, that I may know his name. Tell me, O Lord beneath the waves, who has the strength to fight the storm on Pyke?}{ 
\par Though his ride to Hammerhorn had left him weary, Aeron Damphair was restless in his driftwood shelter, roofed over with black weeds from the sea. The clouds rolled in to cloak the moon and stars, and the darknes
s lay as thick upon the sea as it did upon his soul. }{\cs28\i Balon favored Asha, the child of his body, but a woman cannot rule the ironborn. It must be Victarion.}{
 Nine sons had been born from the loins of Quellon Greyjoy, and Victarion was the strongest of them, a bull of a man, fearless and dutiful. }{\cs28\i And therein lies our danger.}{
 A younger brother owes obedience to an elder, and Victarion was not a man to sail against tradition. }{\cs28\i He has no love for Euron, though. Not since the woman died.}{ 
\par Outside, beneath the snori
ng of his drowned men and the keening of the wind, he could hear the pounding of the waves, the hammer of his god calling him to battle. Aeron crept from his little shelter into the chill of the night. Naked he stood, pale and gaunt and tall, and naked he
 walked into the black salt sea. The water was icy cold, yet he did not flinch from his god\rquote 
s caress. A wave smashed against his chest, staggering him. The next broke over his head. He could taste the salt on his lips and feel the god around him, and his ears rang with the glory of his song. }{\cs28\i 
Nine sons were born from the loins of Quellon Greyjoy, and I was the least of them, as weak and frightened as a girl. But no longer. That man is drowned, and the god has made me strong.}{ The cold salt sea surrounded him, 
embraced him, reached down through his weak man\rquote s flesh and touched his bones. }{\cs28\i Bones,}{ he thought. }{\cs28\i The bones of the soul. Balon\rquote s bones, and Urri\rquote 
s. The truth is in our bones, for flesh decays and bone endures. And on the hill of Nagga, the bones of the Grey King\rquote s Hall . . . }{
\par And gaunt and pale and shivering, Aeron Damphair struggled back to the shore, a wiser man than he had been when he stepped into the sea. For he had found the answer in his bones, and the way was plain before him. The night was so cold 
that his body seemed to steam as he stalked back toward his shelter, but there was a fire burning in his heart, and sleep came easily for once, unbroken by the scream of iron hinges. 
\par When he woke the day was bright and windy. Aeron broke his fast on a broth of clams and seaweed cooked above a driftwood fire. No sooner had he finished than the Merlyn descended from his towerhouse with half a dozen guards to seek him out. \'93
The king is dead,\'94 the Damphair told him. 
\par \'93Aye. I had a bird. And now another.\'94 The Merlyn was a bald round fleshy man who styled himself \'93Lord\'94 in the manner of the green lands, and dressed in furs and velvets. \'93
One raven summons me to Pyke, another to Ten Towers. You krakens have too many arms, you pull a man to pieces. What say you, priest? Where should I send my longships?\'94 
\par Aeron scowled. \'93Ten Towers, do you say? What kraken calls you there?\'94 Ten Towers was the seat of the Lord of Harlaw. 
\par \'93The Princess Asha. She has set her sails for home. The Reader sends out ravens, summoning all her friends to Harlaw. He says that Balon meant for her to sit the Seastone Chair.\'94 
\par \'93The Drowned God shall decide who sits the Seastone Chair,\'94 the priest said. \'93Kneel, that I might bless you.\'94 Lord Merlyn sank to his knees, and Aeron uncorked his skin and poured a stream of seawater on his bald pate. \'93
Lord God who drowned for us, let Meldred your servant be born again from the sea. Bless him with salt, bless him with stone, bless him with steel.\'94 Water ran down Merlyn\rquote s fat cheeks to soak his beard and fox-fur mantle. \'93
What is dead may never die,\'94 Aeron finished, \'93but rises again, harder and stronger.\'94 But when Merlyn rose, he told him, \'93Stay and listen, that you may spread god\rquote s word.\'94 
\par Three feet from the water\rquote s edge the waves broke around a rounded granite boulder. It was there that Aeron Damphair stood, so all his school might see him, and hear the words he had to say. 
\par \'93We were born from the sea, and to the sea we all return,\'94 he began, as he had a hundred times before. \'93The Storm God in his wrath plucked Balon from his castle and cast him down, and now he feasts beneath the waves.\'94 He raised his hands. \'93
}{\cs28\i The iron king is dead!}{ Yet a king will come again! For what is dead may never die, but rises again, harder and stronger!\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93A king shall rise!\'94}{ the drowned men cried. 
\par \'93He shall. He must. But who?\'94 The Damphair listened a moment, but only the waves gave answer. }{\cs28\i \'93Who shall be our king?\'94 }{
\par The drowned men began to slam their driftwood cudgels one against the other. }{\cs28\i \'93Damphair!\'94}{ they cried. }{\cs28\i \'93Damphair King! Aeron King! Give us Damphair!\'94 }{
\par Aeron shook his head. \'93If a father has two sons and gives to one an axe and to the other a net, which does he intend should be the warrior?\'94 
\par \'93The axe is for the warrior,\'94 Rus shouted back, \'93the net for a fisher of the seas.\'94 
\par \'93Aye,\'94 said Aeron. \'93
The god took me deep beneath the waves and drowned the worthless thing I was. When he cast me forth again he gave me eyes to see, ears to hear, and a voice to spread his word, that I might be his prophet and teach his truth to those who
 have forgotten. I was not made to sit upon the Seastone Chair . . . no more than Euron Crow\rquote s Eye. For I have heard the god, who says, }{\cs28\i No godless man may sit my Seastone Chair!}{\'94 
\par The Merlyn crossed his arms against his chest. \'93Is it Asha, then? Or Victarion? Tell us, priest!\'94 
\par \'93The Drowned God will tell you, but not here.\'94 Aeron pointed at the Merlyn\rquote s fat white face. \'93Look not to me, nor to the laws of men, but to the sea. Raise your sails and unship your oars, my lord, and take yourself to Old Wyk. You, 
and all the captains and the kings. Go not to Pyke, to bow before the godless, nor to Harlaw, to consort with scheming women. Point your prow toward Old Wyk, where stood the Grey King\rquote s Hall. In the name of the Drowned God I summon you. }{\cs28\i 
I summon all of you!}{ Leave your halls and hovels, your castles and your keeps, and return to Nagga\rquote s hill to make a kingsmoot!\'94 
\par The Merlyn gaped at him. \'93A kingsmoot? There has not been a true kingsmoot in . . .\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93. . . too long a time!\'94}{ Aeron cried in anguish. \'93
Yet in the dawn of days the ironborn chose their own kings, raising up the worthiest amongst them. It is time we returned to the Old Way, for only that shall make us great again. It was a kingsmoot that chose Urras Ironfoot for High King, and plac
ed a driftwood crown upon his brows. Sylas Flatnose, Harrag Hoare, the Old Kraken, the kingsmoot raised them all. And from }{\cs28\i this}{ kingsmoot shall emerge a man to finish the work King Balon has begun and win us back our freedoms. Go }{\cs28\i not
}{ to Pyke, nor to the Ten Towers of Harlaw, but to Old Wyk, I say again. Seek the hill of Nagga and the bones of the Grey King\rquote s Hall, for in that holy place when the moon has drowned and come again we shall make ourselves a worthy king, a }{
\cs28\i godly}{ king.\'94 He raised his bony hands on high again. \'93}{\cs28\i Listen!}{ Listen to the waves! Listen to the god! He is speaking to us, and he says, }{\cs28\i We shall have no king but from the kingsmoot!}{\'94 
\par A roar went up at that, and the drowned men beat their cudgels one against the other. \'93A }{\cs28\i kingsmoot!}{\'94 they shouted. }{\cs28\i \'93A kingsmoot, a kingsmoot. No king but from the kingsmoot!\'94}{
 And the clamor that they made was so thunderous that surely the Crow\rquote s Eye heard the shouts on Pyke, and the vile Storm God in his cloudy hall. And Aeron Damphair knew he had done well. 
