\par The blood oranges are well past ripe,\'94 the prince observed in a weary voice, when the captain rolled him onto the terrace. 
\par After that he did not speak again for hours. 
\par It was true about the oranges. A few had fallen to burst open on the pale pink marble. The sharp sweet smell of them filled Hotah\rquote s nostrils each time he took a breath. No doubt the prince could smell them too, as he sat beneath the trees i
n the rolling chair Maester Caleotte had made for him, with its goose-down cushions and rumbling wheels of ebony and iron. 
\par For a long while the only sounds were the children splashing in the pools and fountains, and once a soft }{\cs28\i plop}{ as another orange drop
ped onto the terrace to burst. Then, from the far side of the palace, the captain heard the faint drumbeat of boots on marble. 
\par }{\cs28\i Obara.}{ He knew her stride; long-legged, hasty, angry. In the stables 
by the gates, her horse would be lathered, and bloody from her spurs. She always rode stallions, and had been heard to boast that she could master any horse in Dorne . . . and any man as well. The captain could hear other footsteps as well, the quick soft
 scuffing of Maester Caleotte hurrying to keep up. 
\par Obara Sand always walked too fast. }{\cs28\i She is chasing after something she can never catch,}{ the prince had told his daughter once, in the captain\rquote s hearing. 
\par When she appeared beneath the triple arch, Areo Hotah swung his longaxe sideways to block the way. The head was on a shaft of mountain ash six feet long, so she could not go around. \'93My lady, no farther.\'94
 His voice was a bass grumble thick with the accents of Norvos. \'93The prince does not wish to be disturbed.\'94 
\par Her face had been stone before he spoke; then it hardened. \'93You are in my way, Hotah.\'94 Obara was the eldest Sand Snake, a big-boned woman near to thirty, with the close-set eyes and rat-brown hair of the Oldtown whore who\rquote 
d birthed her. Beneath a mott
led sandsilk cloak of dun and gold, her riding clothes were old brown leather, worn and supple. They were the softest things about her. On one hip she wore a coiled whip, across her back a round shield of steel and copper. She had left her spear outside. 
For that, Areo Hotah gave thanks. Quick and strong as she was, the woman was no match for him, he knew . . . but }{\cs28\i she}{ did not, and he had no wish to see her blood upon the pale pink marble. 
\par Maester Caleotte shifted his weight from foot to foot. \'93Lady Obara, I tried to tell you . . .\'94 
\par \'93Does he know that my father is dead?\'94 Obara asked the captain, paying the maester no more mind than she would a fly, if any fly had been foolish enough to buzz about her head. 
\par \'93He does,\'94 the captain said. \'93He had a bird.\'94 
\par Death had come to Dorne on raven wings, writ small and sealed with a blob of hard red wax. Caleotte must have sensed what was in that letter, for he\rquote 
d given it Hotah to deliver. The prince thanked him, but for the longest time he would not break the seal. All afternoon he\rquote 
d sat with the parchment in his lap, watching the children at their play. He watched until the sun went down and the evening air grew cool enough to drive them inside; then he watched the starlight on the water. It was moonrise before he sen
t Hotah to fetch a candle, so he might read his letter beneath the orange trees in the dark of night. 
\par Obara touched her whip. \'93Thousands are crossing the sands afoot to climb the Boneway, so they may help Ellaria bring my father home. The septs are packed
 to bursting, and the red priests have lit their temple fires. In the pillow houses women are coupling with every man who comes to them, and refusing any coin. In Sunspear, on the Broken Arm, along the Greenblood, in the mountains, out in the deep sand, e
verywhere, }{\cs28\i everywhere,}{ women tear their hair and men cry out in rage. The same question is heard on every tongue\emdash what will Doran do? }{\cs28\i What will his brother do to avenge our murdered prince?}{\'94
 She moved closer to the captain. \'93And you say, }{\cs28\i he does not wish to be disturbed!}{\'94 
\par \'93He does not wish to be disturbed,\'94 Areo Hotah said again. 
\par The captain of guards knew the prince he guarded. Once, long ago, a callow youth had come from Norvos, a big broad-shouldered boy with a mop of dark hair. That hair was white now, 
and his body bore the scars of many battles . . . but his strength remained, and he kept his longaxe sharp, as the bearded priests had taught him. }{\cs28\i She shall not pass,}{ he told himself, and said, \'93
The prince is watching the children at their play. He is }{\cs28\i never}{ to be disturbed when he is watching the children at their play.\'94 
\par \'93Hotah,\'94 said Obara Sand, \'93you will remove yourself from my path, else I shall take that longaxe and\emdash \'94 
\par \'93Captain,\'94 came the command, from behind. \'93Let her pass. I will speak with her.\'94 The prince\rquote s voice was hoarse. 
\par Areo Hotah jerked his longaxe upright and stepped to one side. Obara gave him a lingering last look and strode past, the maester hurrying at her heels. Caleotte was no more than five feet tall and bald as an egg. His face was s
o smooth and fat that it was hard to tell his age, but he had been here before the captain, had even served the prince\rquote s mother. Despite his age and girth, he was still nimble enough, and clever as they came, but meek. }{\cs28\i 
He is no match for any Sand Snake,}{ the captain thought. 
\par In the shade of the orange trees, the prince sat in his chair with his gouty legs propped up before him, and heavy bags beneath his eyes . . . though whether it was grief or gout that kept him sleepless, Hotah could not say. Below, in t
he fountains and the pools, the children were still at their play. The youngest were no more than five, the oldest nine and ten. Half were girls and half were boys. Hotah could hear them splashing and shouting at each other in high, shrill voices. \'93
It was not so long ago that you were one of the children in those pools, Obara,\'94 the prince said, when she took one knee before his rolling chair. 
\par She snorted. \'93It has been twenty years, or near enough to make no matter. And I was not here long. I am the whore\rquote s whelp, or had you forgotten?\'94 When he did not answer, she rose again and put her hands upon her hips. \'93
My father has been murdered.\'94 
\par \'93He was slain in single combat during a trial by battle,\'94 Prince Doran said. \'93By law, that is no murder.\'94 
\par \'93He was your }{\cs28\i brother.}{\'94 
\par \'93He was.\'94 
\par \'93What do you mean to do about his death?\'94 
