wned. Then we need only hail Myrcella as the First of Her Name, Queen of the Andals, the Rhoynar, and the First Men, and lawful heir to the Seven Kingdoms of Westeros, and wait for the lions to come.\'94 
\par \'93The }{\cs28\i lawful}{ heir?\'94 The prince snorted. 
\par \'93She is older than her brother,\'94 explained Tyene, as if he were some fool. \'93By law the Iron Throne should pass to her.\'94 
\par \'93By }{\cs28\i Dornish}{ law.\'94 
\par \'93When good King Daeron wed Princess Myriah and brought us into his kingdom, it was agreed that Dornish law would always rule in Dorne. And }{\cs28\i Myrcella}{ is in Dorne, as it happens.\'94 
\par \'93So she is.\'94 His tone was grudging. \'93Let me think on it.\'94 
\par Tyene grew cross. \'93You think too much, Uncle.\'94 
\par \'93Do I?\'94 
\par \'93Father said so.\'94 
\par \'93Oberyn thought too little.\'94 
\par \'93Some men }{\cs28\i think}{ because they are afraid to }{\cs28\i do.}{\'94 
\par \'93There is a difference between fear and caution.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, I must pray that I never see you }{\cs28\i frightened,}{ Uncle. You might forget to breathe.\'94 She raised a hand . . . 
\par The captain brought the butt of his longaxe down upon the marble with a thump. \'93My lady, you presume. Step from the dais, if it please you.\'94 
\par \'93I meant no harm, Captain. I love my uncle, as I know he loved my father.\'94 Tyene went to one knee before the prince. \'93I have said all I came to say, Uncle. Forgive me if I gave offense; my heart is broken all to pieces. Do I still have your love?
\'94 
\par \'93Always.\'94 
\par \'93Give me your blessing, then, and I shall go.\'94 
\par Doran hesitated half a heartbeat before placing his hand on his niece\rquote s head. \'93Be brave, child.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, how not? I am }{\cs28\i his}{ daughter.\'94 
\par No sooner had she taken her leave than Maester Caleotte hurried to the dais. \'93My prince, she did not . . . here, let me see your hand.\'94 He examined the palm first, then gently turned it upside down to sniff at the back of the prince\rquote 
s fingers. \'93No, good. That is good. There are no scratches, so . . .\'94 
\par The prince withdrew his hand. \'93Maester, could I trouble you for some milk of the poppy? A thimble cup will suffice.\'94 
\par \'93The poppy. Yes, to be sure.\'94 
\par \'93Now, I think,\'94 Doran Martell urged gently, and Caleotte scurried to the stairs. 
\par Outside the sun had set. The light within the dome was the blue of dusk, and all the diamonds on the floor were dying. The prince sat in his high seat beneath the Martell spear, his face pale with pain. After a long silence he turned to Areo Hotah. \'93
Captain,\'94 he said, \'93how loyal are my guards?\'94 
\par \'93Loyal.\'94 The captain did not know what else to say. 
\par \'93All of them? Or some?\'94 
\par \'93They are good men. Good }{\cs28\i Dornishmen.}{ They will do as I command.\'94 He thumped his longaxe on the floor. \'93I will bring the head of any man who would betray you.\'94 
\par \'93I want no heads. I want obedience.\'94 
\par \'93You have it.\'94 }{\cs28\i Serve. Obey. Protect. Simple vows for a simple man.}{ \'93How many men are needed?\'94 
\par \'93I will leave that for you to decide. It may be that a few good men will serve us better than a score. I want this done as quickly and as quietly as possible, with no blood spilled.\'94 
\par \'93Quick and quiet and bloodless, aye. What is your command?\'94 
\par \'93You will find my brother\rquote s daughters, take them into custody, and confine them in the cells atop the Spear Tower.\'94 
\par \'93The Sand Snakes?\'94 The captain\rquote s throat was dry. \'93All . . . all eight, my prince? The little ones, also?\'94 
\par The prince considered. \'93Ellaria\rquote s girls are too young to be a danger, but there are those who might seek to use them aga
inst me. It would be best to keep them safe in hand. Yes, the little ones as well . . . but first secure Tyene, Nymeria, and Obara.\'94 
\par \'93As my prince commands.\'94 His heart was troubled. }{\cs28\i My little princess will mislike this.}{ \'93What of Sarella? She is a woman grown, almost twenty.\'94 
\par \'93Unless she returns to Dorne, there\rquote s naught I can do about Sarella save pray that she shows more sense than her sisters. Leave her to her . . . game. Gather up the others. I shall not sleep until I know that they are safe and under guard.\'94 

\par \'93It will be done.\'94 The captain hesitated. \'93When this is known in the streets, the common folk will howl.\'94 
\par \'93All Dorne will howl,\'94 said Doran Martell in a tired voice. \'93I only pray Lord Tywin hears them in King\rquote s Landing, so he might know what a loyal friend he has in Sunspear.\'94
