\par CERSEI
\par She dreamt she sat the Iron Throne, high above them all. 
\par The courtiers were brightly colored mice below. Great lords and proud ladie
s knelt before her. Bold young knights laid their swords at her feet and pleaded for her favors, and the queen smiled down at them. Until the dwarf appeared as if from nowhere, pointing at her and howling with laughter. The lords and ladies began to chuck
le too, hiding their smiles behind their hands. Only then did the queen realize she was naked. 
\par Horrified, she tried to cover herself with her hands. The barbs and blades of the Iron Throne bit into her flesh as she crouched to hide her shame. Blood ran red
 down her legs, as steel teeth gnawed at her buttocks. When she tried to stand, her foot slipped through a gap in the twisted metal. The more she struggled the more the throne engulfed her, tearing chunks of flesh from her breasts and belly, slicing at he
r arms and legs until they were slick and red, glistening. 
\par And all the while her brother capered below, laughing. 
\par His merriment still echoed in her ears when she felt a light touch on her shoulder, and woke suddenly. For half a heartbeat the hand seemed part of the nightmare, and Cersei cried out, but it was only Senelle. The maid\rquote 
s face was white and frightened. 
\par }{\cs28\i We are not alone,}{ the queen realized. Shadows loomed around her bed, tall shapes with chainmail glimmering beneath their cloaks. Armed men had no business here. }{\cs28\i Where are my guards?}{
 Her bedchamber was dark, but for the lantern one of the intruders held on high. }{\cs28\i I must show no fear.}{ Cersei pushed back sleep-tousled hair, and said, \'93What do you want of me?\'94
 A man stepped into the lantern light, and she saw his cloak was white. \'93Jaime?\'94 }{\cs28\i I dreamt of one brother, but the other has come to wake me. }{
\par \'93Your Grace.\'94 The voice was not her brother\rquote s. \'93The Lord Commander said come get you.\'94 His hair curled, as Jaime\rquote s did, but her brother\rquote s hair was beaten gold, like hers, where this man\rquote 
s was black and oily. She stared at him, confused, as he muttered about a privy and a crossbow, and said her father\rquote s name. }{\cs28\i I am dreaming still,}{ Cersei thought. }{\cs28\i 
I have not woken, nor has my nightmare ended. Tyrion will creep out from under the bed soon and begin to laugh at me. }{
\par But that was folly. Her dwarf brother was down in the black cells, condemned to die this very day. She looked 
down at her hands, turning them over to make certain all her fingers were still there. When she ran a hand down her arm the skin was covered with gooseprickles, but unbroken. There were no cuts on her legs, no gashes on the soles of her feet. }{\cs28\i 
A dream, that\rquote s all it was, a dream. I drank too much last night, these fears are only humors born of wine. I will be the one laughing, come dusk. My children will be safe, Tommen\rquote s throne will be secure, and my twisted little}{ valonqar }{
\cs28\i will be short a head and rotting. }{
\par Jocelyn Swyft was at her elbow, pressing a cup on her. Cersei took a sip: water, mixed with lemon squeezings, so tart she spit it out. She could hear the night wind rattling the shutters, and she saw with a strange sharp clarity. Jocelyn was trembling li
ke a leaf, as frightened as Senelle. Ser Osmund Kettleblack loomed over her. Behind him stood Ser Boros Blount, with a lantern. At the door were Lannister guardsmen with gilded lions shining on the crests of their helmets. They looked afraid as well. }{
\cs28\i Can it be?}{ the queen wondered. }{\cs28\i Can it be true?}{ 
\par She rose, and let Senelle slip a bedrobe over her shoulders to hide her nakedness. Cersei belted it herself, her fingers stiff and clumsy. \'93My lord father keeps guards about him, night and day,\'94 she said. Her tong
ue felt thick. She took another swallow of lemon water and sloshed it round her mouth to freshen her breath. A moth had gotten into the lantern Ser Boros was holding; she could hear it buzzing and see the shadow of its wings as it beat against the glass. 

\par \'93The guards were at their posts, Your Grace,\'94 said Osmund Kettleblack. \'93We found a hidden door behind the hearth. A secret passage. The Lord Commander\rquote s gone down to see where it goes.\'94 
\par \'93Jaime?\'94 Terror seized her, sudden as a storm. \'93Jaime should be with the }{\cs28\i king}{ . . .\'94 
\par \'93The lad\rquote s not been harmed. Ser Jaime sent a dozen men to look in on him. His Grace is sleeping peaceful.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Let him have a sweeter dream than mine, and a kinder waking.}{ \'93Who is with the king?\'94 
\par \'93Ser Loras has that honor, if it please you.\'94 
\par It did not please her. The Tyrells were only stewards that the dragon-kings had upjumped far above their station. Their vanity was exceeded only by their ambition. Ser Loras might be as pretty as a maiden\rquote 
s dream, but underneath his white cloak he was Tyrell to the bone. For all she knew, this night\rquote s foul fruit had been planted and nurtured in Highgarden. 
\par But that was a suspicion she dare not speak aloud. \'93Allow me a moment to dress. Ser Osmund, you shall accompany me to the Tower of the Hand. Ser Boros, roust the gaolers and make certain the dwarf is still in his cell.\'94 She would not say his name. }
{\cs28\i He would never have found the courage to lift a hand against Father,}{ she told herself, but she had to be certain. 
\par \'93As Your Grace commands.\'94 Blount surrendered the lantern to Ser Osmund. Cersei was not displeased to see the back of him. }{\cs28\i Father should never have restored him to the white.}{ The man had proved himself a craven. 
\par By the time they left Maegor\rquote s Holdfast, the sky had turned a deep cobalt blue, though the stars still shone. }{\cs28\i All but one,}{ Cersei thought. }{\cs28\i The bright star of the west has fallen, and the nights will be darker now.}{
 She paused upon the drawbridge that spanned the dry moat, gazing down at the spikes below. }{\cs28\i They would not dare lie to me about such a thing.}{ \'93Who found him?\'94 
\par \'93One of his guards,\'94 said Ser Osmund. \'93Lum. He felt a call of nature, and found his lordship in the privy.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i No, that cannot be. That is not the way a lion dies.}{ The queen felt strangely calm. She remembered the first time she had lost a tooth, when she was just a little girl. It hadn\rquote 
t hurt, but the hole in her mouth felt so odd she could not stop touching it with her tongue. }{\cs28\i Now there is a hole in the world where Father stood, and holes want filling. }{
\par If Tywin Lannister was t
ruly dead, no one was safe . . . least of all her son upon his throne. When the lion falls the lesser beasts move in: the jackals and the vultures and the feral dogs. They would try to push her aside, as they always had. She would need to move quickly, as
 she had when Robert died. This might be the work of Stannis Baratheon, through some catspaw. It could well be the prelude to another attack upon the city. She hoped it was. }{\cs28\i 
Let him come. I will smash him, just as Father did, and this time he will die.}{ Stannis did not frighten her, no more than Mace Tyrell did. No one frightened her. She was a daughter of the Rock, a lion. }{\cs28\i 
There will be no more talk of forcing me to wed again.}{ Casterly Rock was hers now, and all the power of House Lannister. No one would eve
r disregard her again. Even when Tommen had no further need of a regent, the Lady of Casterly Rock would remain a power in the land. 
\par The rising sun had painted the tower tops a vivid red, but beneath the walls the night still huddled. The outer castle was so hushed that she could have believed all its people dead. }{\cs28\i 
They should be. It is not fitting for Tywin Lannister to die alone. Such a man deserves a retinue to attend his needs in hell. }{
\par Four spearmen in red cloaks and lion-crested helms were posted at the door of the Tower of the Hand. \'93No one is to enter or leave without my permission,\'94 she told them. The command came easily to her. }{\cs28\i 
My father had steel in his voice as well. }{
\par Within the tower, the smoke from the torches irritated her eyes, but Cersei did not weep, no more than her father would have. }{\cs28\i I am the only true son he ever had.}{
 Her heels scraped against the stone as she climbed, and she could still hear the moth fluttering wildly inside Ser Osmund\rquote s lantern. }{\cs28\i Die,}{ the queen thought at it, in irritation, }{\cs28\i fly into the flame and be done with it. }{

\par Two more red-cloaked guardsmen stood atop the steps. Red Lester muttered a condolence as she passed. The queen\rquote s breath was coming fast and short, and she could feel her heart fluttering in her chest. }{\cs28\i The steps,}{ she told herself, }{
\cs28\i this cursed tower has too many steps.}{ She had half a mind to tear it down. 
\par The hall was full of fools speaking in whispers, as if Lord Tywin were asleep and they were afraid to wake him. Guards and s
ervants alike shrank back before her, mouths flapping. She saw their pink gums and waggling tongues, but their words made no more sense than the buzzing of the moth. }{\cs28\i What are they doing here? How did they know?}{
 By rights they should have called her first. She was the Queen Regent, had they forgotten that? 
\par Before the Hand\rquote s bedchamber stood Ser Meryn Trant in his white armor and cloak. The visor of his helm was open, and the bags beneath his eyes made him look still half-asleep. \'93Clear these people away,\'94 Cersei told him. \'93
Is my father in the privy?\'94 
\par \'93They carried him back to his bed, m\rquote lady.\'94 Ser Meryn pushed the door open for her to enter. 
\par Morning light slashed through the shutters to paint golden bars upon the rushes strewn across the floor of the bedch
amber. Her uncle Kevan was on his knees beside the bed, trying to pray, but he could scarcely get the words out. Guardsmen clustered near the hearth. The secret door that Ser Osmund had spoken of gaped open behind the ashes, no bigger than an oven. A man 
would need to crawl. }{\cs28\i But Tyrion is only half a man.}{ The thought made her angry. }{\cs28\i No, the dwarf is locked in a black cell.}{ This could not be his work. }{\cs28\i Stannis,}{ she told herself, }{\cs28\i 
Stannis was behind it. He still has adherents in the city. Him, or the Tyrells . . . }{
\par There had always been talk of secret passages within the Red Keep. Maegor the Cruel was supposed to have killed the men who built the castle to keep the knowledge of them secret. }{\cs28\i How many other bedchambers have hidden doors?}{
 Cersei had a sudden vision of the dwarf crawling out from behind a tapestry in Tommen\rquote s bedchamber with blade in hand. }{\cs28\i Tommen is well guarded,}{ she told herself. But Lord Tywin had been well guarded too. 
\par For a moment she did not recognize the dead man. He had hair like her father, 
yes, but this was some other man, surely, a smaller man, and much older. His bedrobe was hiked up around his chest, leaving him naked below the waist. The quarrel had taken him in his groin between his navel and his manhood, and was sunk so deep that only
 the fletching showed. His pubic hair was stiff with dried blood. More was congealing in his navel. 
\par The smell of him made her wrinkle her nose. \'93Take the quarrel out of him,\'94 she commanded. \'93This is the King\rquote s Hand!\'94 }{\cs28\i And my father. My lord father. Should I scream and tear my hair?}{
 They said Catelyn Stark had clawed her own face to bloody ribbons when the Freys slew her precious Robb. }{\cs28\i Would you like that, Father?}{ she wanted to ask him. }{\cs28\i Or would you want me to be strong? Did you weep for your own father?}{
 Her grandfather had died when she was only a year old, but she knew the story. Lord Tytos had grown very fat, and his heart burst one day when he was climbing the steps to his mistress. Her father was off in King\rquote s Landin
g when it happened, serving as the Mad King\rquote s Hand. Lord Tywin was often away in King\rquote s Landing when she and Jaime were young. If he wept when they brought him word of his father\rquote s death, he did it where no one could see the tears. 

\par The queen could feel her nails digging into her palms. \'93
How could you leave him like this? My father was Hand to three kings, as great a man as ever strode the Seven Kingdoms. The bells must ring for him, as they rang for Robert. He must be bathed and dressed as befits his statu
re, in ermine and cloth-of-gold and crimson silk. Where is Pycelle? }{\cs28\i Where is Pycelle?}{\'94 She turned to the guardsmen. \'93Puckens, bring Grand Maester Pycelle. He must see to Lord Tywin.\'94 
\par \'93He\rquote s seen him, Your Grace,\'94 said Puckens. \'93He came and saw and went, to summon the silent sisters.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i They sent for me last.}{ The realization made her almost too angry for words. }{\cs28\i And Pycelle runs off to send a message rather than soil his soft, wrinkled hands. The man is useless.}{ \'93Find Maester Ballabar,\'94 she commanded. \'93
Find Maester Frenken. Any of them.\'94 Puckens and Shortear ran to obey. \'93Where is my brother?\'94 
\par \'93Down the tunnel. There\rquote s a shaft, with iron rungs set in the stone. Ser Jaime went to see how deep it goes.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He has only one hand,}{ she wanted to shout at them. }{\cs28\i One of you should have gone. He has no business climbing ladders. The men who murdered Father might be down there, waiting for him.}{
 Her twin had always been too rash, and it would seem that even losing a hand had not taught him caution. She was about to command the guards to go down after him and bring him back when Puckens and Shortear returned with a grey-haired man between them. 
\'93Your Grace,\'94 said Shortear, \'93this here claims he was a maester.\'94 
\par The man bowed low. \'93How may I serve Your Grace?\'94 
\par His face was vaguely familiar, though Cersei could not place him. }{\cs28\i Old, but not so old as Pycelle. This one has some strength in him still.}{ He was tall, though slightly stooped, with crinkles around his bold blue eyes. }{\cs28\i 
His throat is naked.}{ \'93You wear no maester\rquote s chain.\'94 
\par \'93It was taken from me. My name is Qyburn, if it please Your Grace. I treated your brother\rquote s hand.\'94 
\par \'93His stump, you mean.\'94 She remembered him now. He had come with Jaime from Harrenhal. 
\par \'93I could not save Ser Jaime\rquote s hand, it is true. My arts saved his arm, however, mayhaps his very life. The Citadel took my chain, but they could not take my knowledge.\'94 
\par \'93You may suffice,\'94 she decided. \'93If you fail me you will lose more than a chain, I promise you. Remove the quarrel from my father\rquote s belly and make him ready for the silent sisters.\'94 
\par \'93As my queen commands.\'94 Qyburn went to the bedside, paused, looked back. \'93And how shall I deal with the girl, Your Grace?\'94 
\par \'93Girl?\'94 Cersei had overlooked the second body. She strode to the bed, flung aside the heap of bloody coverlets, and there she was, naked, cold, and pink . . . save for her face, which had turned as black as Joff\rquote 
s had at his wedding feast. A chain of linked golden hands was half-buried in the flesh of her throat, twisted so tight that it had broken the skin. Cersei hissed like an angry cat. \'93What is }{\cs28\i she}{ doing here?\'94 
\par \'93We found her there, Your Grace,\'94 said Shortear. \'93It\rquote s the Imp\rquote s whore.\'94 As if that explained why she was here. 
\par }{\cs28\i My lord father had no use for whores,}{ she thought. }{\cs28\i After our mother died he never touched a woman.}{ She gave the guardsman a chilly look. \'93This is not . . . when Lord Tywin\rquote 
s father died he returned to Casterly Rock to find a . . . a woman of this sort . . . bedecked in his lady mother\rquote s jewels, wearing one of her gowns. He stripped them o
ff her, and all else as well. For a fortnight she was paraded naked through the streets of Lannisport, to confess to every man she met that she was a thief and a harlot. That was how Lord Tywin Lannister dealt with whores. He never . . . this woman was he
re for some other purpose, not for . . .\'94 
\par \'93Perhaps his lordship was questioning the girl about her mistress,\'94 Qyburn suggested. \'93Sansa Stark vanished the night the king was murdered, I have heard.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s so.\'94 Cersei seized on the suggestion eagerly. \'93He was questioning her, to be sure. There can be no doubt.\'94 She could see Tyrion leering, his mouth twisted into a monkey\rquote s grin beneath the ruin of his nose. }{\cs28\i 
And what better way to question her than naked, with her legs well spread?}{ the dwarf whispered. }{\cs28\i That\rquote s how I like to question her too. }{
\par The queen turned away. }{\cs28\i I will not look at her. }{Suddenly it was too much even to be in the same room as the dead woman. She pushed past Qyburn, out into the hall. 
\par Ser Osmund had been joined by his brothers Osney and Osfryd. \'93There is a dead woman in the Hand\rquote s bedchamber,\'94 Cersei told the three Kettleblacks. \'93No one is ever to know that she was here.\'94 
\par \'93Aye, m\rquote lady.\'94 Ser Osney had faint scratches on his cheek where another of Tyrion\rquote s whores had clawed him. \'93And what shall we do with her?\'94 
\par \'93Feed her to your dogs. Keep her for a bedmate. What do I care? }{\cs28\i She was never here.}{ I\rquote ll have the tongue of any man who dares to say she was. Do you understand me?\'94 
\par Osney and Osfryd exchanged a look. \'93Aye, Your Grace.\'94 
\par She followed them back inside and watched as they bundled the girl up in her father\rquote s bloody blankets. }{\cs28\i Shae, her name was Shae.}{ They had last spoken the night before the dwarf\rquote 
s trial by combat, after that smiling Dornish snake offered to champion him. Shae had been ask
ing about some jewels Tyrion had given her, and certain promises Cersei might have made, a manse in the city and a knight to marry her. The queen made it plain that the whore would have nothing of her until she told them where Sansa Stark had gone. \'93
You were her maid. Do you expect me to believe that you knew nothing of her plans?\'94 she had said. Shae left in tears. 
\par Ser Osfryd slung the bundled corpse up over his shoulder. \'93I want that chain,\'94 Cersei said. \'93See that you do not scratch the gold.\'94 Osfryd nodded and started toward the door. \'93No, not through the yard.\'94
 She gestured toward the secret passage. \'93There\rquote s a shaft down to the dungeons. That way.\'94 
\par As Ser Osfryd went down on one knee before the hearth, the light brightened within, and the queen heard noises. Jaime emerged bent over like an old woman, his boots kicking up puffs of soot from Lord Tywin\rquote s last fire. \'93Get out of my way,\'94
 he told the Kettleblacks. 
\par Cersei rushed toward him. \'93Did you find them? Did you find the killers? How many were there?\'94 Surely there had been more than one. One man alone could not have killed her father. 
\par Her twin\rquote s face had a haggard look. \'93The shaft goes down to a chamber where half a dozen tunnels meet. They\rquote re closed off by iron gates, chained and locked. I need to find keys.\'94 He glanced around the bedchamber. \'93
Whoever did this might still be lurking in the walls. It\rquote s a maze back there, and dark.\'94 
\par She imagined Tyrion creeping between the walls like some monstrous rat. }{\cs28\i No. You are being silly. The dwarf is in his cell.}{ \'93
Take hammers to the walls. Knock this tower down, if you must. I want them found. Whoever did this. I want them killed.\'94 
\par Jaime hugged her, his good hand pressing against the small of her back. He smelled of ash, but the morning sun was in his hair, giving it a golden glow. She wanted to draw his face to hers for a kiss. }{\cs28\i Later,}{ she told herself, }{\cs28\i 
later he will come to me, for comfort.}{ \'93We are his heirs, Jaime,\'94 she whispered. \'93It will be up to us to finish his work. You must take Father\rquote s place as Hand. You see that now, surely. Tommen will need you . . .\'94 
\par He pushed away from her and raised his arm, forcing his stump into her face. \'93A Hand without a hand? A bad jape, sister. Don\rquote t ask me to rule.\'94 
\par Their uncle heard the rebuff. Qyburn as well, and the Kettleblacks, wrestling their bundle through the ashes. Even the guardsmen heard, Puckens and Hoke the Horseleg and Shortear. }{\cs28\i It will be all over the castle by nightfall.}{
 Cersei felt the heat rising up her cheeks. \'93Rule? I said naught of ruling. I shall rule until my son comes of age.\'94 
\par \'93I don\rquote t know who I pity more,\'94 her brother said. \'93Tommen, or the Seven Kingdoms.\'94 
\par She slapped him. Jaime\rquote s arm rose to catch the blow, cat-quick . . . but this cat had a cripple\rquote s stump in place of a right hand. Her fingers left red marks on his cheek. 
\par The sound brought their uncle to his feet. \'93Your father lies here }{\cs28\i dead.}{ Have the decency to take your quarrel outside.\'94 
\par Jaime inclined his head in apology. \'93Forgive us, Uncle. My sister is sick with grief. She forgets herself.\'94 
\par She wanted to slap him again for that. }{\cs28\i I must have been mad to think he could be Hand.}{ She would sooner abolish the office. When had a Hand ever brought her anything but grief? Jon Arryn put Robert Baratheon in her bed, and before he died he
\rquote d begun sniffing about her and Jaime as well. Eddard Stark took up right where Arryn had left off; his meddling had forced her to rid he
rself of Robert sooner than she would have liked, before she could deal with his pestilential brothers. Tyrion sold Myrcella to the Dornishmen, made one of her sons his hostage, and murdered the other. And when Lord Tywin returned to King\rquote 
s Landing . . . 
\par }{\cs28\i The next Hand will know his place,}{ she promised herself. It would have to be Ser Kevan. Her uncle was tireless, prudent, unfailingly obedient. She could rely on him, as her father had. }{\cs28\i The hand does not argue with the head.}{
 She had a realm to rule, but she
 would need new men to help her rule it. Pycelle was a doddering lickspittle, Jaime had lost his courage with his sword hand, and Mace Tyrell and his cronies Redwyne and Rowan could not be trusted. For all she knew they might have had a part in this. Lord
 Tyrell had to know that he would never rule the Seven Kingdoms so long as Tywin Lannister lived. 
\par }{\cs28\i I will need to move carefully with that one.}{ The city was full of his men, and he\rquote d even managed to plant one of his sons in the Kingsguard, and meant to plant his daughter in Tommen\rquote 
s bed. It still made her furious to think that Father had agreed to betroth Tommen to Margaery Tyrell. }{\cs28\i The girl is twice his age and twice widowed.}{ Mace Tyrell claimed his daughter was still virgin, but Cersei had her doubts. Joffr
ey had been murdered before he could bed the girl, but she had been wed to Renly first . . . }{\cs28\i A man may prefer the taste of hippocras, yet if you set a tankard of ale before him, he will quaff it quick enough.}{
 She must command Lord Varys to find out what he could. 
