\par Sam was reading about the Others when he saw the mouse. 
\par His eyes were red and raw. }{\cs28\i I ought not rub them so much,}{ he always told himself as he rubbed them. The dust made
 them itch and water, and the dust was everywhere down here. Little puffs of it filled the air every time a page was turned, and it rose in grey clouds whenever he shifted a stack of books to see what might be hiding on the bottom. 
\par Sam did not know how long it had been since last he\rquote d slept, but scarce an inch remained of the fat tallow candle he\rquote d lit when starting on the ragged bundle of loose pages that he\rquote 
d found tied up in twine. He was beastly tired, but it was hard to stop. }{\cs28\i One more book,}{ he had told himself, }{\cs28\i then I\rquote ll stop. One more folio, just one more. One more page, then I\rquote ll go up and rest and get a bite to eat.}
{ But there was always another page after that one, and another after that, and another book waiting underneath the pile. }{\cs28\i I\rquote ll just take a quick peek to see what this one is about,}{ he\rquote 
d think, and before he knew he would be halfway through it. He had not eaten since that bowl of bean-and-bacon soup with Pyp and Grenn. }{\cs28\i Well, except for the bread and cheese, but that was only a nibble,}{ he tho
ught. That was when he took a quick glance at the empty platter, and spied the mouse feasting on the bread crumbs. 
\par The mouse was half as long as his pinky finger, with black eyes and soft grey fur. Sam knew he ought to kill it. Mice might prefer bread and
 cheese, but they ate paper too. He had found plenty of mouse droppings amongst the shelves and stacks, and some of the leather covers on the books showed signs of being gnawed. 
\par }{\cs28\i It is such a little thing, though. And hungry.}{ How could he begrudge it a few crumbs? }{\cs28\i It\rquote s eating books, though . . . }{
\par After hours in the chair Sam\rquote s back was stiff as a board, and his legs were half-asleep. He knew he was not quick enough to catch the mouse, but it might be he could squash it. By his elbow rested a massive leather-bound copy of }{\cs28\i 
Annals of the Black Centaur,}{ Septon Jorquen\rquote s exhaustively detailed account of the nine years that Orbert Caswell had served as Lord Commander of the Night\rquote 
s Watch. There was a page for each day of his term, every one of which seemed to begin, \'93Lord Orbert rose at dawn and moved his bowels,\'94 except for the last, which said, \'93Lord Orbert was found to have died during the night.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i No mouse is a match for Septon Jorquen.}{
 Very slowly, Sam took hold of the book with his left hand. It was thick and heavy, and when he tried to lift it one-handed, it slipped from his plump fingers and thumped back down. The mouse was gone in half a heartbeat, skittery-quick. Sam was relieved.
 Squishing the poor little thing would have given him nightmares. \'93You shouldn\rquote t eat the books, though,\'94 he said aloud. Maybe he should bring more cheese the next time he came down here. 
\par He was surprised at how low the candle had burned. Had the bean-and-bacon soup been today or yesterday? }{\cs28\i Yesterday. It must have been yesterday.}{
 The realization made him yawn. Jon would be wondering what had become of him, though Maester Aemon would no doubt understand. Before he had lost his sight, the maester had loved boo
ks as much as Samwell Tarly did. He understood the way that you could sometimes fall right into them, as if each page was a hole into another world. 
\par Pushing himself to his feet, Sam grimaced at the pins and needles in his calves. The chair was very hard and cut into the back of his thighs when he bent over a book. }{\cs28\i I need to remember to bring a cushion.}{
 It would be even better if he could sleep down here, in the cell he\rquote d found half-hidden behind four chests full of loose pages that had gotten separated fro
m the books they belonged to, but he did not want to leave Maester Aemon alone for so long. He had not been strong of late and required help, especially with the ravens. Aemon had Clydas, to be sure, but Sam was younger, and better with the birds. 
\par With a 
stack of books and scrolls under his left arm and the candle in his right hand, Sam made his way through the tunnels the brothers called the wormways. A pale shaft of light illuminated the steep stone steps that led up to the surface, so he knew that day 
had come up top. He left the candle burning in a wall niche and began the climb. By the fifth step he was puffing. At the tenth he stopped to shift the books to his right arm. 
\par He emerged beneath a sky the color of white lead. }{\cs28\i A snow sky,}{ Sam thought, squinting up. The prospect made him uneasy. He remembered that night on the Fist of the First Men when the wights and the snows had come together. }{\cs28\i Don\rquote 
t be so craven,}{ he thought. }{\cs28\i You have your Sworn Brothers all around you, not to mention Stannis Baratheon and all his knights.}{ Castle Black\rquote 
s keeps and towers rose about him, dwarfed by the icy immensity of the Wall. A small army was crawling over the ice a quarter of the way up, where a new switchback stair was creeping upward to meet the remnants of the old one.
 The sounds of their saws and hammers echoed off the ice. Jon had the builders working night and day on the task. Sam had heard some of them complaining about it over supper, insisting that Lord Mormont never worked them half so hard. Without the great st
a
ir there was no way to reach the top of the Wall except by the chain winch, however. And as much as Samwell Tarly hated steps, he hated the winch cage more. He always closed his eyes when he was riding it, convinced that the chain was about to break. Ever
y time the iron cage scraped against the ice his heart stopped beating for an instant. 
\par }{\cs28\i There were dragons here two hundred years ago,}{ Sam found himself thinking, as he watched the cage making a slow descent. }{\cs28\i They would just have flown to the top of the Wall.}{
 Queen Alysanne had visited Castle Black on her dragon, and Jaehaerys, her king, had come after her on his own. Could Silverwing have left an egg behind? Or had Stannis found one egg on Dragonstone? }{\cs28\i 
Even if he has an egg, how can he hope to quicken it?}{ Baelor the Blessed had prayed over his eggs, and other Targaryens had sought to hatch theirs with sorcery. All they got for it was farce and tragedy. 
\par \'93Samwell,\'94 said a glum voice, \'93I was coming to fetch you. I was told to bring you to the Lord Commander.\'94 
\par A snowflake landed on Sam\rquote s nose. \'93Jon wants to see me?\'94 
\par \'93As to that, I could not say,\'94 said Dolorous Edd Tollett. \'93I never wanted to see half the things I\rquote ve seen, and I\rquote ve never seen half the things I wanted to. I don\rquote t think wanting comes into it. You\rquote 
d best go all the same. Lord Snow wishes to speak with you as soon as he is done with Craster\rquote s wife.\'94 
\par \'93Gilly.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s the one. If my wet nurse had looked like her, I\rquote d still be on the teat. Mine had whiskers.\'94 
\par \'93Most goats do,\'94 called Pyp, as he and Grenn emerged from around the corner, with longbows in hand and quivers of arrows on their backs. \'93Where have you been, Slayer? We missed you last night at supper. A whole roast ox went uneaten.\'94 
\par \'93Don\rquote t call me Slayer.\'94 Sam ignored the gibe about the ox. That was just Pyp. \'93I was reading. There was a mouse . . .\'94 
\par \'93Don\rquote t mention mice to Grenn. He\rquote s terrified of mice.\'94 
\par \'93I am not,\'94 Grenn declared with indignation. 
\par \'93You\rquote d be too scared to eat one.\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote d eat more mice than you would.\'94 
\par Dolorous Edd Tollett gave a sigh. \'93When I was a lad, we only ate mice on special feast days. I was the youngest, so I always got the tail. There\rquote s no meat on the tail.\'94 
\par \'93Where's your longbow, Sam?\'94 asked Grenn. Ser Alliser used to call him }{\cs28\i Aurochs,}{ and every day he seemed to g
row into the name a little more. He had come to the Wall big but slow, thick of neck, thick of waist, red of face, and clumsy. Though his neck still reddened when Pyp twisted him around into some folly, hours of work with sword and shield had flattened hi
s belly, hardened his arms, broadened his chest. He was }{\cs28\i strong,}{ and shaggy as an aurochs too. \'93Ulmer was expecting you at the butts.\'94 
\par \'93Ulmer,\'94 Sam said, abashed. Almost the first thing Jon Snow had done as Lord Commander was institute daily archery drill f
or the entire garrison, even stewards and cooks. The Watch had been placing too much emphasis on the sword and too little on the bow, he had said, a relic of the days when one brother in every ten had been a knight, instead of one in every hundred. Sam sa
w the sense in the decree, but he hated longbow practice almost as much as he hated climbing steps. When he wore his gloves he could never hit anything, but when he took them off he got blisters on his fingers. Those bows were }{\cs28\i dangerous.}{
 Satin had torn off half his thumbnail on a bowstring. \'93I forgot.\'94 
\par \'93You broke the heart of the wildling princess, Slayer,\'94 said Pyp. Of late, Val had taken to watching them from the window of her chamber in the King\rquote s Tower. \'93She was looking for you.\'94 
\par \'93She was not! Don\rquote t say that!\'94 Sam had only spoken to Val twice, when Maester Aemon called upon her to make sure the babes were healthy. The princess was so pretty that he oft found himself stammering and blushing in her presence. 
\par \'93Why not?\'94 asked Pyp. \'93She wants to have your children. Maybe we should call you Sam the Seducer.\'94 
\par Sam reddened. King Stannis had plans for Val, he knew; she was the mortar with which he meant to seal the peace between the northmen and the free folk. \'93I don\rquote t have time for archery today, I need to go see Jon.\'94 
\par \'93Jon? Jon? Do we know anyone named Jon, Grenn?\'94 
\par \'93He means the Lord Commander.\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i Ohhh.}{ The Great Lord Snow. To be sure. Why do you want to see him? He can\rquote t even wiggle his ears.\'94 Pyp wiggled his, to show he could. They were large ears, and red from cold. \'93He\rquote s }{\cs28\i Lord}{
 Snow for true now, too bloody highborn for the likes of us.\'94 
\par \'93Jon has duties,\'94 Sam said in his defense. \'93The Wall is his, and all that goes with it.\'94 
\par \'93A man has duties to his friends as well. If not for us, Janos Slynt might be our lord commander. Lord Janos would have sent Snow ranging naked on a mule. \lquote Scamper on up to Craster\rquote s Keep,\rquote  he would have said, \lquote 
and fetch me back the Old Bear\rquote s cloak and boots.\rquote  We saved him from that, but now he has too many }{\cs28\i duties}{ to drink a cup of mulled wine by the fire?\'94 
\par Grenn agreed. \'93His duties don\rquote t keep him from the yard. More days than not, he\rquote s out there fighting someone.\'94 
\par That was true, Sam had to admit. Once, when Jon came to consult with Maester Aemon, Sam had asked him why he spent so much time at swordplay. \'93The Old Bear never trained much when he was Lord Commander,\'94
 he had pointed out. In answer, Jon had pressed Longclaw into Sam\rquote s hand. He let him feel the lightness, the balance, had him turn the blade so that ripples gleamed in the smoke-dark metal. \'93Valyrian steel,\'94 he said, \'93
spell-forged and razor-sharp, nigh on indestructible. A swordsman should be as good as his sword, Sam. Longclaw is Valyrian steel, but I\rquote m not. The Halfhand could have killed me as easy as you swat a bug.\'94 
\par Sam handed back the sword. \'93When I try to swat a bug, it always flies away. All I do is slap my arm. It stings.\'94 
\par That made Jon laugh. \'93As you will. Qhorin could have killed me as easy as you eat a bowl of porridge.\'94 Sam was fond of porridge, especially when it was sweetened with honey. 
\par \'93I don\rquote t have time for this.\'94 Sam left his friends and made his way toward the armory, clutching his books to his chest. }{\cs28\i I am the shield that guards the realms of men,}{
 he remembered. He wondered what those men would say if they realized their realms were being guarded by the likes of Grenn, Pyp, and Dolorous Edd. 
\par The Lord Commander\rquote s Tower had been gutted by fire, and Stannis Baratheon had claimed the King\rquote s Tower for his own residence, so Jon Snow had established himself in Donal Noye\rquote 
s modest quarters behind the armory. Gilly was leaving as Sam arrived, wrapped up in the old cloak he\rquote d given her when they were fleeing Craster\rquote s Keep. She almost rushed right past him, but Sam caught her arm, spilling two books as he did. 
\'93Gilly.\'94 
\par \'93Sam.\'94 Her voice sounded raw. Gilly was dark-haired and slim, with the big brown eyes of a doe. She was swallowed by the folds of Sam\rquote 
s old cloak, her face half-hidden by its hood, but shivering all the same. Her face looked wan and frightened. 
\par \'93What\rquote s wrong?\'94 Sam asked her. \'93How are the babes?\'94 
\par Gilly pulled loose from him. \'93They\rquote re good, Sam. Good.\'94 
\par \'93Between the two of them it\rquote s a wonder you can sleep,\'94 Sam said pleasantly. \'93Which one was it that I heard crying last night? I thought he\rquote d never stop.\'94 
\par \'93Dalla\rquote s boy. He cries when he wants the teat. Mine . . . mine hardly ever cries. Sometimes he gurgles, but . . .\'94 Her eyes filled with tears. \'93I have to go. It\rquote s past time that I fed them. I\rquote 
ll be leaking all over myself if I don\rquote t go.\'94 She rushed across the yard, leaving Sam perplexed behind her. 
\par He had to get down on his knees to gather up the books he\rquote d dropped. }{\cs28\i I should not have brought so many,}{ he told himself as he brushed the dirt off Colloquo Votar\rquote s }{\cs28\i Jade Compendium,}{
 a thick volume of tales and legends from the east that Maester Aemon had commanded him to find. The book appeared undamaged. Maester Thomax\rquote s }{\cs28\i Dragonkin, Being a Hi
story of House Targaryen from Exile to Apotheosis, with a Consideration of the Life and Death of Dragons}{
 had not been so fortunate. It had come open as it fell, and a few pages had gotten muddy, including one with a rather nice picture of Balerion the Blac
k Dread done in colored inks. Sam cursed himself for a clumsy oaf as he smoothed the pages down and brushed them off. Gilly\rquote s presence always flustered him and gave rise to . . . well, }{\cs28\i risings.}{ A Sworn Brother of the Night\rquote 
s Watch should not be feeling the sorts of things that Gilly made him feel, especially when she would talk about her breasts and . . . 
\par \'93Lord Snow is waiting.\'94 Two guards in black cloaks and iron halfhelms stood by the doors of the armory, leaning on their spears. Hairy Hal was the one who\rquote 
d spoken. Mully helped Sam back to his feet. He blurted out thanks and hurried past them, clutching desperately at the stack of books as he made his way past the forge with its anvil and bellows. A shirt of ringmail rested on his workbench, half-complete
d. Ghost was stretched out beneath the anvil, gnawing on the bone of an ox to get at the marrow. The big white direwolf looked up when Sam went by, but made no sound. 
\par Jon\rquote s solar was back beyond the racks of spears and shields. He was reading a parchment when Sam entered. Lord Commander Mormont\rquote 
