\par A cold rain was falling, turning the walls and ramparts of the Red Keep dark as blood. The queen held the king\rquote s hand and led him firmly across the muddy yard to where her litter waited with its escort. \'93Uncle Jaime said I could rid
e my horse and throw pennies to the smallfolk,\'94 the boy objected. 
\par \'93Do you want to catch a chill?\'94 She would not risk it; Tommen had never been as robust as Joffrey. \'93Your grandfather would want you to look a proper king at his wake. We will not appear at the Great Sept wet and bedraggled.\'94 }{\cs28\i 
Bad enough I must wear mourning again.}{ Black had never been a happy color on her. With her fair skin, it made her look half a corpse herself. Cersei had risen an hour before dawn to bathe and fix her hair, and she did no
t intend to let the rain destroy her efforts. 
\par Inside the litter, Tommen settled back against his pillows and peered out at the falling rain. \'93The gods are weeping for grandfather. Lady Jocelyn says the raindrops are their tears.\'94 
\par \'93Jocelyn Swyft is a fool. If the gods could weep, they would have wept for your brother. Rain is rain. Close the curtain before you let any more in. That mantle is sable, would you have it soaked?\'94 
\par Tommen did as he was bid. His meekness troubled her. A king had to be strong. }{\cs28\i Joffrey would have argued. He was never easy to cow.}{ \'93Don\rquote t slump so,\'94 she told Tommen. \'93
Sit like a king. Put your shoulders back and straighten your crown. Do you want it to tumble off your head in front of all your lords?\'94 
\par \'93No, Mother.\'94 The boy sat straight and reached up to fix the crown. Joff\rquote s crown was too big for him. Tommen had always inclined to plumpness, but his face seemed thinner now. }{\cs28\i Is he eating well?}{
 She must remember to ask the steward. She could not risk Tommen growing ill, not with Myrcella in the hands of the Dornishmen. }{\cs28\i He will grow into Joff\rquote s crown in time.}{
 Until he did, a smaller one might be needed, one that did not threaten to swallow his head. She would take it up with the goldsmiths. 
\par The litter made its slow way down Aegon\rquote s High Hill. Two Kingsguard rode before them, white knights on white horses with white cloaks hanging sodden from their shoulders. Behind came fifty Lannister guardsmen in gold and crimson. 
\par Tommen peered through the drapes at the empty streets. \'93I thought there would be more people. When Father died, all the people came out to watch us go by.\'94 
\par \'93This rain has driven them inside.\'94 King\rquote s Landing had never loved Lord Tywin. }{\cs28\i He never wanted love, though. \'93You cannot eat love, nor buy a horse with it, nor warm your halls on a cold night,\'94}{
 she heard him tell Jaime once, when her brother had been no older than Tommen. 
\par At the Great Sept of Baelor, that magnificence in marble atop Visenya\rquote s Hill, the little knot of mourners were outnumbered by the gold cloaks that Ser Addam Marbrand had drawn up across the plaza. }{\cs28\i More will turn out later,}{
 the queen told herself as Ser Meryn Trant helped her from the litter. Only the highborn and their retinues were to be admitted to the morning service; there would be another in the aftern
oon for the commons, and the evening prayers were open to all. Cersei would need to return for that, so that the smallfolk might see her mourn. }{\cs28\i The mob must have its show.}{
 It was a nuisance. She had offices to fill, a war to win, a realm to rule. Her father would have understood that. 
\par The High Septon met them at the top of the steps. A bent old man with a wispy grey beard, he was so stooped by the weight of his ornate embroidered robes that his eyes were on a level with the queen\rquote s breasts . . . though his
 crown, an airy confection of cut crystal and spun gold, added a good foot and a half to his height. 
\par Lord Tywin had given him that crown to replace the one that was lost when the mob killed the previous High Septon. They had pulled the fat fool from his litter and torn him apart, the day Myrcella sailed for Dorne. }{\cs28\i 
That one was a great glutton, and biddable. This one . . . }{This High Septon was of Tyrion\rquote s making, Cersei recalled suddenly. It was a disquieting thought. 
\par The old man\rquote s spotted hand looked like a chicken claw as it poked from a sleeve encrusted with golden scrollwork and small crystals. Cersei knelt on the wet marble and kissed his fingers, and bid Tommen to do the same. }{\cs28\i 
What does he know of me? How much did the dwarf tell him?}{ The High Septon smiled as he escorted her into the sept. But was it a threatening smile full of unspoken knowledge, or just some vacuous twitch of an old man\rquote 
s wrinkled lips? The queen could not be certain. 
\par They made their way through the Hall of Lamps beneath colored globes of leaded glass, Tommen\rquote 
s hand in hers. Trant and Kettleblack flanked them, water dripping from their wet cloaks to puddle on the floor. The High Septon walked slowly, leaning on a weirwood staff topped by a crystal orb. Seven of the Most Devout attend
ed him, shimmering in cloth-of-silver. Tommen wore cloth-of-gold beneath his sable mantle, the queen an old gown of black velvet lined with ermine. There\rquote 
d been no time to have a new one made, and she could not wear the same dress she had worn for Joffrey, nor the one she\rquote d buried Robert in. 
\par }{\cs28\i At least I will not be expected to don mourning for Tyrion. I shall dress in crimson silk and cloth-of-gold for that, and wear rubies in my hair.}{ The man who brought her the dwarf\rquote s head would be raised to lordship, sh
e had proclaimed, no matter how mean and low his birth or station. Ravens were carrying her promise to every part of the Seven Kingdoms, and soon enough word would cross the narrow sea to the Nine Free Cities and the lands beyond. }{\cs28\i 
Let the Imp run to the ends of the earth, he will not escape me.}{ 
\par The royal procession passed through the inner doors into the cavernous heart of the Great Sept, and down a wide aisle, one of seven that met
 beneath the dome. To right and left, highborn mourners sank to their knees as the king and queen went by. Many of her father\rquote 
s bannermen were here, and knights who had fought beside Lord Tywin in half a hundred battles. The sight of them made her feel more confident. }{\cs28\i I am not without friends. }{
\par Under the Great Sept\rquote s lofty dome of glass and gold and crystal, Lord Tywin Lannister\rquote s body rested upon a stepped marble bier. At its head Jaime stood at vigil, his one good hand curled about the hilt of a tall gold
en greatsword whose point rested on the floor. The hooded cloak he wore was as white as freshly fallen snow, and the scales of his long hauberk were mother-of-pearl chased with gold. }{\cs28\i 
Lord Tywin would have wanted him in Lannister gold and crimson,}{ she thought. }{\cs28\i It always angered him to see Jaime all in white.}{
 Her brother was growing his beard again as well. The stubble covered his jaw and cheeks, and gave his face a rough, uncouth look. }{\cs28\i He might at least have waited till Father\rquote s bones were interred beneath the Rock. }{
\par Cersei led the king up three short steps, to kneel beside the body. Tommen\rquote s eyes were filled with tears. \'93Weep quietly,\'94 she told him, leaning close. \'93You are a king, not a squalling child. Your lords are watching you.\'94
 The boy swiped the tears away with the back of his hand. He had her eyes, emerald green, as large and bright as Jaime\rquote s eyes had been when he was Tommen\rquote s age. Her brother had been such a }{\cs28\i pretty}{
 boy . . . but fierce as well, as fierce as Joffrey, a true lion cub. The queen put her arm around Tommen and kissed his golden curls. }{\cs28\i He will need me to teach him how to rule and keep him safe from his enemies.}{
 Some of them stood around them even now, pretending to be friends. 
\par The silent sisters had armored L
ord Tywin as if to fight some final battle. He wore his finest plate, heavy steel enameled a deep, dark crimson, with gold inlay on his gauntlets, greaves, and breastplate. His rondels were golden sunbursts; a golden lioness crouched upon each shoulder; a
 maned lion crested the greathelm beside his head. Upon his chest lay a longsword in a gilded scabbard studded with rubies, his hands folded about its hilt in gloves of gilded mail. }{\cs28\i Even in death his face is noble,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i 
although the mouth . . . }{The corners of her father\rquote s lips curved upward ever so slightly, giving him a look of vague bemusement. }{\cs28\i That should not be.}{
 She blamed Pycelle; he should have told the silent sisters that Lord Tywin Lannister never smiled. }{\cs28\i The man is as useless as nipples on a breastplate.}{
 That half smile made Lord Tywin seem less fearful, somehow. That, and the fact that his eyes were closed. Her father\rquote s eyes had always been unsettling; pale green, almost luminous, flecked with gold. His eyes could see inside you, could see h
ow weak and worthless and ugly you were down deep. }{\cs28\i When he looked at you, you knew. }{
\par Unbidden, a memory came to her, of the feast King Aerys had thrown when Cersei first came to court, a girl as green as summer grass. Old Merryweather had been nattering about raising the duty on wine when Lord Rykker said, \'93
If we need gold, His Grace should sit Lord Tywin on his chamber pot.\'94 Aerys and his lickspittles laughed loudly, whilst Father stared at Rykker over his wine cup. Long after the merriment had died that g
aze had lingered. Rykker turned away, turned back, met Father\rquote s eyes, then ignored them, drank a tankard of ale, and stalked off red-faced, defeated by a pair of unflinching eyes. 
\par }{\cs28\i Lord Tywin\rquote s eyes are closed forever now,}{ Cersei thought. }{\cs28\i It is my look they will flinch from now, my frown that they must fear. I am a lion too.}{ 
\par It was gloomy within the sept with the sky so grey outside. If the rain ever stopped, the sun would slant down through the hanging crystals to drape the corpse in rainbows. The Lord of Casterly Rock deserved rainbows. He had been a great man. }{\cs28\i 
I shall be greater, though. A thousand years from now, when the maesters write about this time, you shall be remembered only as Queen Cersei\rquote s sire.}{ 
\par \'93Mother.\'94 Tommen tugged her sleeve. \'93What smells so bad?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i My lord father.}{ \'93Death.\'94
 She could smell it too; a faint whisper of decay that made her want to wrinkle her nose. Cersei paid it no mind. The seven septons in the silver robes stood behind the bier, beseeching the Father Above to judge Lord Tyw
in justly. When they were done, seventy-seven septas gathered before the altar of the Mother and began to sing to her for mercy. Tommen was fidgeting by then, and even the queen\rquote 
s knees had begun to ache. She glanced at Jaime. Her twin stood as if he had been carved from stone, and would not meet her eyes. 
\par On the benches, their uncle Kevan knelt with his shoulders slumped, his son beside him. }{\cs28\i Lancel looks worse than Father.}{ Though only seventeen, he might have passed for seventy; grey-faced, gaunt, with ho
llow cheeks, sunken eyes, and hair as white and brittle as chalk. }{\cs28\i How can Lancel be among the living when Tywin Lannister is dead? Have the gods taken leave of their wits? }{
\par Lord Gyles was coughing more than usual and covering his nose with a square of red silk. }{\cs28\i He can smell it too.}{ Grand Maester Pycelle had his eyes closed. }{\cs28\i If he has fallen asleep, I swear I will have him whipped.}{
 To the right of the bier knelt the Tyrells: the Lord of Highgarden, his hideous mother and vapid wife, his son Garlan and his daughter Margaery. }{\cs28\i Queen Margaery,}{ she reminded herself; Joff\rquote s widow and Tommen\rquote 
s wife-to-be. Margaery looked very like her brother, the Knight of Flowers. The queen wondered if they had other things in common. }{\cs28\i Our little rose has a good many ladies waiting attendance on her, night and day.}{
 They were with her now, almost a dozen of them. Cersei studied their faces, wondering. }{\cs28\i Who is the most fearful, the most wanton, the hungriest for favor? Who has the loosest tongue?}{ She would need to make a point of finding out. 
\par It was a relief when the singing finally ended. The smell coming off her father\rquote s corpse seemed to have grown stronger. Most of the mourners had the decency to pretend that nothing was amiss, but Cersei saw two of Lady Margaery\rquote 
s cousins wrinkling their little Tyrell noses. As she and Tommen were walking back down the aisle the queen thought she heard someone mutter \'93privy\'94
 and chortle, but when she turned her head to see who had spoken a sea of solemn faces gazed at her blankly. }{\cs28\i They would never have dared make japes about him when he was still alive. He would have turned their bowels to water with a look. }{

\par Back out in the Hall of Lamps, the mourners buzzed about them thick as flies, eager to shower her with useless condolences. The Redwyne twins b
oth kissed her hand, their father her cheeks. Hallyne the Pyromancer promised her that a flaming hand would burn in the sky above the city on the day her father\rquote 
s bones went west. Between coughs, Lord Gyles told her that he had hired a master stonecarver t
o make a statue of Lord Tywin, to stand eternal vigil beside the Lion Gate. Ser Lambert Turnberry appeared with a patch over his right eye, swearing that he would wear it until he could bring her the head of her dwarf brother. 
\par No sooner had the queen escaped the clutches of that fool than she found herself cornered by Lady Falyse of Stokeworth and her husband, Ser Balman Byrch. \'93My lady mother sends her regrets, Your Grace,\'94 Falyse burbled at her. \'93
Lollys has been taken to bed with the child and she felt t
he need to stay with her. She begs that you forgive her, and said I should ask you . . . my mother admired your late father above all other men. Should my sister have a little boy, it is her wish that we might name him Tywin, if . . . if it please you.
\'94 
\par Cersei stared at her, aghast. \'93Your lackwit sister gets herself raped by half of King\rquote s Landing, and Tanda thinks to honor the bastard with my lord father\rquote s name? I think not.\'94 
\par Falyse flinched back as if she\rquote d been slapped, but her husband only stroked his thick blond mustache with a thumb. \'93I told Lady Tanda as much. We shall find a more, ah . . . a more fitting name for Lollys\rquote s bastard, you have my word.\'94 

\par \'93See that you do.\'94 Cersei showed them a shoulder and moved away. Tommen had fallen into the clutche
s of Margaery Tyrell and her grandmother, she saw. The Queen of Thorns was so short that for an instant Cersei took her for another child. Before she could rescue her son from the roses, the press brought her face-to-face with her uncle. When the queen re
minded him of their meeting later, Ser Kevan gave a weary nod and begged leave to withdraw. But Lancel lingered, the very picture of a man with one foot in the grave. }{\cs28\i But is he climbing in or climbing out? }{
\par Cersei forced herself to smile. \'93Lancel, I am happy to see you looking so much stronger. Maester Ballabar brought us such dire reports, we feared for your life. But I would have thought you on your way to Darry by now, to take up your lordship.\'94
 Her father had made Lancel a lord after the Battle of the Blackwater, as a sop to his brother Kevan. 
\par \'93Not as yet. There are outlaws in my castle.\'94 Her cousin\rquote s voice was as wispy as the mustache on his upper lip. Though his hair had gone white, his mustache fuzz remained a sandy color. Cersei had often gazed up at
 it while the boy was inside her, pumping dutifully away. }{\cs28\i It looks like a smudge of dirt on his lip.}{ She used to threaten to scrub it off with a little spit. \'93The riverlands have need of a strong hand, my father says.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i A pity that they\rquote re getting yours,}{ she wanted to say. Instead she smiled. \'93And you are to be wed as well.\'94 
\par A gloomy look passed across the young knight\rquote s ravaged face. \'93A Frey girl, and not of my choosing. She is not even maiden. A widow, of Darry blood. My father says that will help me with the peasants, but the peasants are all dead.\'94
 He reached for her hand. \'93It is cruel, Cersei. Your Grace knows that I love\emdash \'94 
\par \'93\emdash House Lannister,\'94 she finished for him. \'93No one can doubt that, Lancel. May your wife give you strong sons.\'94 }{\cs28\i Best not let her lord grandfather host the wedding, though.}{ \'93I know you will do many noble deeds in Darry.\'94
 
\par Lancel nodded, plainly miserable. \'93When it seemed that I might die, my father brought the High Septon to pray for me. He is a good man.\'94 Her cousin\rquote s eyes were wet and shiny, a child\rquote s eyes in an old man\rquote s face. \'93
He says the Mother spared me for some holy purpose, so I might atone for my sins.\'94 
\par Cersei wondered how he intended to atone for her. }{\cs28\i Knighting him was a mistake, and bedding him a bigger one.}{ Lancel was a weak reed, and she liked his newfound piety not at all; he had been much more amusing when he was trying to be Jaime. }{
\cs28\i What has this mewling fool told the High Septon? And what will he tell his little Frey when they lie together in the dark?}{ If he confessed t
o bedding Cersei, well, she could weather that. Men were always lying about women; she would put it down as the braggadocio of a callow boy smitten by her beauty. }{\cs28\i If he sings of Robert and the strongwine, though . . . \'93}{
Atonement is best achieved through prayer,\'94 Cersei told him. \'93}{\cs28\i Silent}{ prayer.\'94 She left him to think about that and girded herself to face the Tyrell host. 
\par Margaery embraced her like a sister, which the queen found presumptuous, but this was not the place to reproach her. Lady Alerie and the cousins contented themselves with kissing fingers. Lady Graceford, who was large with child, asked the queen\rquote 
s leave to name it Tywin if it were a boy, or Lanna if it were a girl. }{\cs28\i Another one?}{ she almost groaned. }{\cs28\i The realm will drown in Tywins.}{ She gave consent as graciously as she could, feigning delight. 
\par It was Lady Merryweather who truly pleased her. \'93Your Grace,\'94 that one said, in her sultry Myrish tones, \'93I have sent word to my friends across the narrow sea, asking them to seize the Imp at once should he show his ugly face in the Free Cities.
\'94 
\par \'93Do you have many friends across the water?\'94 
\par \'93In Myr, many. In Lys as well, and Tyrosh. Men of power.\'94 
\par Cersei could well believe it. The Myrish woman was too beautiful by half; long-legged and full-breasted, with smooth olive skin, ripe lips, huge dark eyes, and thick black hair that always looked as if she\rquote d just come from bed. }{\cs28\i 
She even smells of sin, like some exotic lotus.}{ \'93Lord Merryweather and I wish only to serve Your Grace and the little king,\'94 the woman purred, with a look that was as pregnant as Lady Graceford. 
\par }{\cs28\i This one is ambitious, and her lord is proud but poor.}{ \'93We must speak again, my lady. Taena, is it? You are most kind. I know that we shall be great friends.\'94 
\par Then the Lord of Highgarden descended on her. 
\par Mace Tyrell was no more than ten years older than Cersei, yet she thought of him as her father\rquote s age, not her own. He was not quite so tall as Lord Tywin had been, but elsewise he was bigger, with a thick ches
t and a gut grown even thicker. His hair was chestnut-colored, but there were specks of white and grey in his beard. His face was often red. \'93Lord Tywin was a great man, an }{\cs28\i extraordinary}{ man,\'94
 he declared ponderously after he had kissed both her cheeks. \'93We shall never see his like again, I fear.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i You are looking at his like, fool,}{ Cersei thought. }{\cs28\i It is his daughter standing here before you.}{ But she needed Tyrell and the strength of Highgarden to keep Tommen on his throne, so all she said was, \'93He will be greatly missed.
\'94 
\par Tyrell put a hand upon her shoulder. \'93No man alive is fit to don Lord Tywin\rquote s armor, that is plain. Still, the realm goes on, and must be ruled. If there is aught that I might do to serve in this dark hour, Your Grace need only ask.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i If you want to be the King\rquote s Hand, my lord, have the courage to say it plainly.}{ The queen smiled. }{\cs28\i Let him read into that as much as he likes.}{ \'93Surely my lord is needed in the Reach?\'94 
