\par \'93Garth has served me well as Lord Seneschal, as he served my father before me,\'94 Tyrell was going on. \'93Littlefinger had a nose for gold, I grant you, but Garth\emdash \'94 
\par \'93My lord,\'94 Cersei broke in, \'93I fear there has been some misunderstanding. I have asked Lord Gyles Rosby to serve as our new master of coin, and he has done me the honor of accepting.\'94 
\par Mace gaped at her. \'93Rosby? That . . . }{\cs28\i cougher?}{ But . . . the matter was agreed, Your Grace. Garth is on his way to Oldtown.\'94 
\par \'93Best send a raven to Lord Hightower and ask him to make certain your uncle does not take ship. We would hate for Garth to brave an autumn sea for nought.\'94 She smiled pleasantly. 
\par A flush crept up Tyrell\rquote s thick neck. \'93This . . . your lord father assured me . . .\'94 He began to sputter. 
\par Then his mother appeared and slid her arm through his own. \'93It would seem that Lord Tywin did not share his plans with our regent, I can\rquote t }{\cs28\i imagine}{ why. Still, there \rquote 
tis, no use hectoring Her Grace. She is quite right, you must write Lord Leyton before Garth boards a ship. You know the sea will sicken him and make his farting worse.\'94 Lady Olenna gave Cersei a toothless smile. \'93Your council chambers will smell s
weeter with Lord Gyles, though I daresay that coughing would drive me to distraction. We all adore dear old uncle Garth, but the man is flatulent, that cannot be gainsaid. I do abhor foul smells.\'94 Her wrinkled face wrinkled up even more. \'93
I caught a whiff of something unpleasant in the holy sept, in truth. Mayhaps you smelled it too?\'94 
\par \'93No,\'94 Cersei said coldly. \'93A scent, you say?\'94 
\par \'93More like a stink.\'94 
\par \'93Perhaps you miss your autumn roses. We have kept you here too long.\'94 The sooner she rid the court of Lad
y Olenna the better. Lord Tyrell would doubtless dispatch a goodly number of knights to see his mother safely home, and the fewer Tyrell swords in the city, the more soundly the queen would sleep. 
\par \'93I do long for the fragrances of Highgarden, I confess it,\'94 said the old lady, \'93but of course I cannot leave until I have seen my sweet Margaery wed to your precious little Tommen.\'94 
\par \'93I await that day eagerly as well,\'94 Tyrell put in. \'93Lord Tywin and I were on the point of setting a date, as it happens. Perhaps you and I might take up that discussion, Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93Soon.\'94 
\par \'93Soon will serve,\'94 said Lady Olenna with a sniff. \'93Now come along, Mace, let Her Grace get on with her . . . grief.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I will see you dead, old woman,}{ Cersei promised herself as the Queen of Thorns tottered off between her towering guardsmen, a pair of seven-footers that it amused her to call Left and Right. }{\cs28\i We\rquote 
ll see how sweet a corpse you make.}{ The old woman was twice as clever as her lord son, that was plain. 
\par The queen rescued her son from Margaery and her cousins, and made for the doors. Outside, the rain had finally stopped. The autumn air smelled sweet and fresh. Tommen took his crown off. \'93Put that back on,\'94 Cersei commanded him. 
\par \'93It makes my neck hurt,\'94 the boy said, but he did as he was bid. \'93Will I be married soon? Margaery says that as soon as we\rquote re wed we can go to Highgarden.\'94 
\par \'93You are not going to Highgarden, but you can ride back to the castle.\'94 Cersei beckoned to Ser Meryn Trant. \'93Bring His Grace a mount, and ask Lord Gyles if he would do me the honor of sharing my litter.\'94
 Things were moving more quickly than she had anticipated; there was no time to be squandered. 
\par Tommen was happy at the prospect of a ride, and of course Lord Gyles was honored by her invitation . . . though when
 she asked him to be her master of coin, he began coughing so violently that she feared he might die right then and there. But the Mother was merciful, and Gyles eventually recovered sufficiently to accept, and even began coughing out the names of men he 
wanted to replace, customs officers and wool factors appointed by Littlefinger, even one of the keepers of the keys. 
\par \'93Name the cow what you will, so long as the milk flows. And should the question arise, you joined the council yesterday.\'94 
\par \'93Yester\emdash \'94 A fit of coughing bent him over. \'93Yesterday. To be sure.\'94 Lord Gyles coughed into a square of red silk, as if to hide the blood in his spittle. Cersei pretended not to notice. 
\par }{\cs28\i When he dies I will find someone else.}{ Perhaps she would recall Littlefinger. The que
en could not imagine that Petyr Baelish would be allowed to remain Lord Protector of the Vale for very long, with Lysa Arryn dead. The Vale lords were already stirring, if what Pycelle said was true. }{\cs28\i 
Once they take that wretched boy away from him, Lord Petyr will come crawling back. }{
\par \'93Your Grace?\'94 Lord Gyles coughed, and dabbed his mouth. \'93Might I . . .\'94 He coughed again. \'93. . . ask who . . .\'94 Another series of coughs racked him. \'93. . . who will be the King\rquote s Hand?\'94 
\par \'93My uncle,\'94 she replied absently. 
\par It was a relief to see the gates of the Red Keep looming large before her. She gave Tommen over to the charge of his squires and retired gratefully to her own chambers to rest. 
\par No sooner had she eased off her shoes than Jocelyn entered timidly to say that Qyburn was without and craved audience. \'93Send him in,\'94 the queen commanded. }{\cs28\i A ruler gets no rest.}{ 
\par Qyburn was old, but his hair still had more ash than snow in it, and the laugh lines around his mouth made him look like some little girl\rquote s favorite grandfather. }{\cs28\i A rather shabby grandfather, though.}{
 The collar of his robe was frayed, and one sleeve had been torn and badly sewn. \'93I must beg Your Grace\rquote s pardon for my appearance,\'94 he said. \'93I have been down in the dungeons making inquiries into the Imp\rquote s escape
, as you commanded.\'94 
\par \'93And what have you discovered?\'94 
\par \'93The night that Lord Varys and your brother disappeared, a third man also vanished.\'94 
\par \'93Yes, the gaoler. What of him?\'94 
\par \'93Rugen was the man\rquote s name. An undergaoler who had charge of the black cells. The c
hief undergaoler describes him as portly, unshaven, gruff of speech. He held his appointment of the old king, Aerys, and came and went as he pleased. The black cells have not oft been occupied in recent years. The other turnkeys were afraid of him, it see
ms, but none knew much about him. He had no friends, no kin. Nor did he drink or frequent brothels. His sleeping cell was damp and dreary, and the straw he slept upon was mildewed. His chamber pot was overflowing.\'94 
\par \'93I know all this.\'94 Jaime had examined Rugen\rquote s cell, and Ser Addam\rquote s gold cloaks had examined it again. 
\par \'93Aye, Your Grace,\'94 said Qyburn, \'93but did you know that under that stinking chamber pot was a loose stone, which opened on a small hollow? The sort of place where a man might hide valuables that he did not wish to be discovered?\'94 
\par \'93Valuables?\'94 This was new. \'93Coin, you mean?\'94 She had suspected all along that Tyrion had somehow bought this gaoler. 
\par \'93Beyond a doubt. To be sure, the hole was empty when I found it. No doubt Rugen took his ill-gotten treasure with him when he fled. But as I crouched over the hole with my torch, I saw something glitter, so I scratched in the dirt until I dug it out.
\'94 Qyburn opened his palm. \'93A gold coin.\'94 
