\par H
er uncle arrived promptly at sunset, wearing a quilted doublet of charcoal-colored wool as somber as his face. Like all the Lannisters, Ser Kevan was fair-skinned and blond, though at five-and-fifty he had lost most of his hair. No one would ever call him
 comely. Thick of waist, round of shoulder, with a square jutting chin that his close-cropped yellow beard did little to conceal, he reminded her of some old mastiff . . . but a faithful old mastiff was the very thing that she required. 
\par They ate a simple supper of beets and bread and bloody beef with a flagon of Dornish red to wash it all down. Ser Kevan said little and scarce touched his wine cup. }{\cs28\i He broods too much,}{ she decided. }{\cs28\i 
He needs to be put to work to get beyond his grief.}{ 
\par She said as much, when the last of the food had been cleared away and the servants had departed. \'93I know how much my father relied on you, Uncle. Now I must do the same.\'94 
\par \'93You need a Hand,\'94 he said, \'93and Jaime has refused you.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He is blunt. Very well.}{ \'93Jaime . . . I felt so lost with Father dead, I scarce knew what I was saying. Jaime is gallant, but a bit of a fool, let us be frank. Tommen needs a more seasoned man. Someone older . . .\'94 
\par \'93Mace Tyrell is older.\'94 
\par Her nostrils flared. \'93Never.\'94 Cersei pushed a lock of hair off her brow. \'93The Tyrells overreach themselves.\'94 
\par \'93You would be a fool to make Mace Tyrell your Hand,\'94 Ser Kevan admitted, \'93but a bigger fool to make him your foe. I\rquote ve heard what happened in the Hall of Lamps. Mace should have known better than to broach such m
atters in public, but even so, you were unwise to shame him in front of half the court.\'94 
\par \'93Better that than suffer another Tyrell on the council.\'94 His reproach annoyed her. \'93Rosby will make an adequate master of coin. You\rquote ve seen that litter of his, with i
ts carvings and silk draperies. His horses are better dressed than most knights. A man that rich should have no problem finding gold. As for Handship . . . who better to finish my father\rquote s work than the brother who shared all his counsels?\'94 

\par \'93Every man needs someone he can trust. Tywin had me, and once your mother.\'94 
\par \'93He loved her very much.\'94 Cersei refused to think about the dead whore in his bed. \'93I know they are together now.\'94 
\par \'93So I pray.\'94 Ser Kevan studied her face for a long moment before he replied. \'93You ask much of me, Cersei.\'94 
\par \'93No more than my father did.\'94 
\par \'93I am tired.\'94 Her uncle reached for his wine cup and took a swallow. \'93I have a wife I have not seen in two years, a dead son to mourn, another son about to marry and assume a lordship. Castle Da
rry must be made strong again, its lands protected, its burned fields plowed and planted anew. Lancel needs my help.\'94 
\par \'93As does Tommen.\'94 Cersei had not expected Kevan to require coaxing. }{\cs28\i He never played coy with Father.}{ \'93The realm needs you.\'94 
\par \'93The realm. Aye. And House Lannister.\'94 He sipped his wine again. \'93Very well. I will remain and serve His Grace . . .\'94 
\par \'93Very good,\'94 she started to say, but Ser Kevan raised his voice and bulled right over her. 
\par \'93. . . so long as you name me regent as well as Hand and take yourself back to Casterly Rock.\'94 
\par For half a heartbeat Cersei could only stare at him. \'93}{\cs28\i I}{ am the regent,\'94 she reminded him. 
\par \'93You were. Tywin did not intend that you continue in that role. He told me of his plans to send you back to the Rock and find a new husband for you.\'94 
\par Cersei could feel her anger rising. \'93He spoke of such, yes. And I told him it was not my wish to wed again.\'94 
\par Her uncle was unmoved. \'93If you are resolved against another marriage, I will not force it on you. As to the other, though . . . you are the Lady of Casterly Rock now. Your place is there.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i How dare you?}{ she wanted to scream. Instead, she said, \'93I am also the Queen Regent. My place is with my son.\'94 
\par \'93Your father thought not.\'94 
\par \'93My father is dead.\'94 
\par \'93To my grief, and the woe of all the realm. Open your eyes and look about you, Cersei. The kingdom is in ruins. Tywin might have been able to set matters aright, but . . .\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i I}{ shall set matters aright!\'94 Cersei softened her tone. \'93With your help, Uncle. If you will serve me as faithfully as you served my father\emdash \'94 
\par \'93You are not your father. And Tywin always regarded Jaime as his rightful heir.\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i Jaime}{ . . . Jaime has taken vows. Jaime never thinks, he laughs at everything and everyone and says whatever comes into his head. Jaime is a handsome fool.\'94 
\par \'93And yet he was your first choice to be the King\rquote s Hand. What does that make you, Cersei?\'94 
\par \'93I told you, I was sick with grief, I did not think\emdash \'94 
\par \'93No,\'94 Ser Kevan agreed. \'93Which is why you should return to Casterly Rock and leave the king with those who do.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93The king is my son!\'94}{ Cersei rose to her feet. 
\par \'93Aye,\'94 her uncle said, \'93and from what I saw of Joffrey, you are as unfit a mother as you are a ruler.\'94 
\par She threw the contents of her wine cup full in his face. 
\par Ser Kevan rose with a ponderous dignity. \'93Your Grace.\'94 Wine trickled down his cheeks and dripped from his close-cropped beard. \'93With your leave, might I withdraw?\'94 
\par \'93By what right do you presume to give }{\cs28\i me}{ terms? You are no more than one of my father\rquote s household knights.\'94 
\par \'93I hold no lands, that is true. But I have certain incomes, and chests of coin set aside. My own father forgot none of his children when he died, and Tywin knew how to reward good service. I feed two hundred knights and can double that number i
f need be. There are freeriders who will follow my banner, and I have the gold to hire sellswords. You would be wise not to take me lightly, Your Grace . . . and wiser still not to make of me a foe.\'94 
\par \'93Are you }{\cs28\i threatening}{ me?\'94 
\par \'93I am counseling you. If you will not yield the regency to me, name me your castellan for Casterly Rock and make either Mathis Rowan or Randyll Tarly the Hand of the King.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Tyrell bannermen, both of them.}{ The suggestion left her speechless. }{\cs28\i Is he bought?}{ she wondered. }{\cs28\i Has he taken Tyrell gold to betray House Lannister?}{ 
\par \'93Mathis Rowan is sensible, prudent, well liked,\'94 her uncle went on, oblivious. \'93Randyll Tarly is the finest soldier in the realm. A poor Hand for peacetime, but with Tywin dead there\rquote s no better man to finish this war
. Lord Tyrell cannot take offense if you choose one of his own bannermen as Hand. Both Tarly and Rowan are able men . . . and }{\cs28\i loyal}{
. Name either one, and you make him yours. You strengthen yourself and weaken Highgarden, yet Mace will likely thank you for it.\'94 He gave a shrug. \'93
That is my counsel, take it or no. You may make Moon Boy your Hand for all I care. My brother is dead, woman. I am going to take him home.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Traitor,}{ she thought. }{\cs28\i Turncloak.}{ She wondered how much Mace Tyrell had given him. \'93You would abandon your king when he needs you most,\'94 she told him. \'93You would abandon Tommen.\'94 
\par \'93Tommen has his mother.\'94 Ser Kevan\rquote s green eyes met her own, unblinking. A last drop of wine trembled wet and red beneath his chin, and finally fell. \'93Aye,\'94 he added softly, after a pause, \'93and his father too, I think.\'94
