\par Ser Jaime Lannister, all in white, stood beside his father\rquote s bier, five fingers curled about the hilt of a golden greatsword. 
\par At dusk, the interior of the Great Sept of Baelor turned dim and eerie. The last light of day slanted down through the high windows, washing the towering likenesses of the Seven in a red gloom. Around their altars, scented candles flickered wh
ilst deep shadows gathered in the transepts and crept silently across the marble floors. The echoes of the evensongs died away as the last mourners were departing. 
\par Balon Swann and Loras Tyrell remained when the rest had gone. \'93No man can stand a vigil for seven days and seven nights,\'94 Ser Balon said. \'93When did you last sleep, my lord?\'94 
\par \'93When my lord father was alive,\'94 said Jaime. 
\par \'93Allow me to stand tonight in your stead,\'94 Ser Loras offered. 
\par \'93He was not your father.\'94 }{\cs28\i You did not kill him. I did. Tyrion may have loosed the crossbow bolt that slew him, but I loosed Tyrion.}{ \'93Leave me.\'94 
\par \'93As my lord commands,\'94 said Swann. Ser Loras looked as if he might have argued further, but Ser Balon took his arm and drew him off. Jaim
e listened to the echoes of their footfalls die away. And then he was alone again with his lord father, amongst the candles and the crystals and the sickly sweet smell of death. His back ached from the weight of his armor, and his legs felt almost numb. H
e shifted his stance a bit and tightened his fingers around the golden greatsword. He could not wield a sword, but he could hold one. His missing hand was throbbing. That was almost funny. He had more feeling in the hand he\rquote 
d lost than in the rest of the body that remained to him. 
\par }{\cs28\i My hand is hungry for a sword. I need to kill someone. Varys, for a start, but first I\rquote d need to find the rock he\rquote s hiding under.}{ \'93I commanded the eunuch to take him to a ship, not to your bedchamber,\'94 he told the corpse. 
\'93The blood is on his hands as much as . . . as Tyrion\rquote s.\'94 }{\cs28\i The blood is on his hands as much as mine,}{ he meant to say, but the words stuck in his throat. }{\cs28\i Whatever Varys did, I made him do.}{ 
\par He had waited in the eunuch\rquote s chambers that night, when at last he had decided not to let his little brother die. As he waited, he had sharpened his dagger with one hand, taking a queer comfort from the }{\cs28\i scrape-scrape-scrape}{
 of steel on stone. At the sound of footsteps he stood beside the door. Varys entered in a wash of powder an
d lavender. Jaime stepped out behind him, kicked him in the back of the knee, knelt on his chest, and shoved the knife up under his soft white chin, forcing his head up. \'93Why, Lord Varys,\'94 he\rquote d said pleasantly, \'93fancy meeting you here.\'94
 
\par \'93Ser Jaime?\'94 Varys panted. \'93You frightened me.\'94 
\par \'93I meant to.\'94 When he twisted the dagger, a trickle of blood ran down the blade. \'93I was thinking you might help me pluck my brother from his cell before Ser Ilyn lops his head off. It is an ugly head, I grant you, but he only has the one.\'94 

\par \'93Yes . . . well . . . if you would . . . remove the blade . . . yes, gently, as it please my lord, gently, oh, I\rquote m pricked . . .\'94 The eunuch touched his neck and gaped at the blood on his fingers. \'93
I have always abhorred the sight of my own blood.\'94 
\par \'93You\rquote ll have more to abhor shortly, unless you help me.\'94 
\par Varys struggled to a sitting position. \'93Your brother . . . if the Imp should vanish unaccountably from his cell, q-questions would be asked. I would f-fear for my life . . .\'94 
\par \'93Your life is mine. I do not care what secrets you know. If Tyrion dies, you will not long outlive him, I promise you.\'94 
\par \'93Ah.\'94 The eunuch sucked the blood off his fingers. \'93You ask a dreadful thing . . . to loose the Imp who slew our lovely king. Or is it that you believe him innocent?\'94 
\par \'93Innocent or guilty,\'94 Jaime had said, like the fool he was, \'93a Lannister pays his debts.\'94 The words had come so easy. 
\par He had not slept since. He could see his brother now, the way the dwarf had grinned beneath the stub of his nose as the torchlight licked his face. \'93You poor stupid blind crippled fool,\'94 he\rquote d snarled, in a voice thick with malice. \'93
Cersei is a lying whore, she\rquote s been fucking Lancel and Osmund Kettleblack and probably Moon Boy for all I know. And I am the monster they all say I am. Yes, I killed your vile son.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He never said he meant to kill our father. If he had, I would have stopped him. Then I would be the kinslayer, not him.}{ 
\par Jaime wondered where Varys was hiding. Wisely, the master of whisperers had not returned to 
his own chambers, nor had a search of the Red Keep turned him up. It might be that the eunuch had taken ship with Tyrion, rather than remain to answer awkward questions. If so, the two of them were well out to sea by now, sharing a flagon of Arbor gold in
 the cabin of a galley. 
\par }{\cs28\i Unless my brother murdered Varys too, and left his corpse to rot beneath the castle.}{ Down there, it might be years before his bones were found. Jaime had led a dozen guards below, with torches and ropes and lanterns. For hours they 
had groped through twisting passages, narrow crawl spaces, hidden doors, secret steps, and shafts that plunged down into utter blackness. Seldom had he felt so utterly a cripple. A man takes much for granted when he has two hands. Ladders, for an instance
. Even crawling did not come easy; not for nought do they speak of }{\cs28\i hands}{ and knees. Nor could he hold a torch and climb, as others could. 
\par And all for naught. They found only darkness, dust, and rats. }{\cs28\i And dragons, lurking down below.}{ He remembered the sullen orange glow of the coals in the iron dragon\rquote 
s mouth. The brazier warmed a chamber at the bottom of a shaft where half a dozen tunnels met. On the floor he\rquote d found a scuffed mosaic of the three-headed dragon of House Targaryen done in tiles of black and red. }{\cs28\i I know you, Kingslayer,}
{ the beast seemed to be saying. }{\cs28\i I have been here all the time, waiting for you to come to me.}{ And it seemed to Jaime that he knew that voice, the iron tones that had once belonged to Rhaegar, Prince of Dragonstone. 
\par The day had been windy when he said farewell to Rhaegar, in the yard of the Red Keep. The prince had donned his night-black armor, with the three-headed dragon picked out in rubies on his breastplate. \'93Your Grace,\'94 Jaime had pleaded, \'93
let Darry stay to guard the king this once, or Ser Barristan. Their cloaks are as white as mine.\'94 
\par Prince Rhaegar shook his head. \'93My royal sire fears your father more than he does our cousin Robert. He wants you close, so Lord Tywin cannot harm him. I dare not take that crutch away from him at such an hour.\'94 
\par Jaime\rquote s anger had risen up in his throat. \'93I am not a crutch. I am a knight of the Kingsguard.\'94 
\par \'93Then guard the king,\'94 Ser Jon Darry snapped at him. \'93When you donned that cloak, you promised to obey.\'94 
\par Rhaegar had put his hand on Jaime\rquote s shoulder. \'93When this battle\rquote s done I mean to call a council. Changes will be made. I meant to do it long ago, but . . . well, it does no good to speak of roads not taken. We shall talk when I return.
\'94 
\par Those were the last words Rhaegar Targaryen ever spoke to him. Outside the gates an army had assembled, whilst another descended on the Trident. So the Prince of Dragonstone mounted up and donned his tall black helm, and rode forth to his doom. 
\par }{\cs28\i He was more right than he knew. When the battle was done, there were changes made.}{ \'93Aerys thought no harm could come to him if he kept me near,\'94 he told his father\rquote s corpse. \'93Isn\rquote t that amusing?\'94
 Lord Tywin seemed to think so; his smile was wider than before. }{\cs28\i He seems to enjoy being dead.}{ 
\par It was queer, but he felt no grief. }{\cs28\i Where are my tears? Where is my rage?}{ Jaime Lannister had never lacked for rage. \'93Father,\'94 he told the corpse, \'93
it was you who told me that tears were a mark of weakness in a man, so you cannot expect that I should cry for you.\'94 
\par A thousand lor
ds and ladies had come that morning to file past the bier, and several thousand smallfolk after noon. They wore somber clothes and solemn faces, but Jaime suspected that many and more were secretly delighted to see the great man brought low. Even in the w
est, Lord Tywin had been more respected than beloved, and King\rquote s Landing still remembered the Sack. 
\par Of all the mourners, Grand Maester Pycelle had seemed the most distraught. \'93I have served six kings,\'94 he told Jaime after the second service, whilst sniffing doubtfully about the corpse, \'93
but here before us lies the greatest man I ever knew. Lord Tywin wore no crown, yet he was all a king should be.\'94 
\par Without his beard, Pycelle looked not only old, but feeble. }{\cs28\i Shaving him was the cruelest thing Tyrion could have done,}{ thought Jaime, who knew what it was to lose a part of yourself, the part that made you who you were. Pycelle\rquote 
s beard had been magnificent, white as snow and soft as lambswool, a luxuriant growth th
at covered cheeks and chin and flowed down almost to his belt. The Grand Maester had been wont to stroke it when he pontificated. It had given him an air of wisdom, and concealed all manner of unsavory things: the loose skin dangling beneath the old man
\rquote s 
jaw, the small querulous mouth and missing teeth, warts and wrinkles and age spots too numerous to count. Though Pycelle was trying to regrow what he had lost, he was failing. Only wisps and tufts sprouted from his wrinkled cheeks and weak chin, so thin t
hat Jaime could see the splotchy pink skin beneath. 
\par \'93Ser Jaime, I have seen terrible things in my time,\'94 the old man said. \'93Wars, battles, murders most foul . . . I was a boy in Oldtown when the grey plague took half the city and three-quarters of the Cita
del. Lord Hightower burned every ship in port, closed the gates, and commanded his guards to slay all those who tried to flee, be they men, women, or babes in arms. They killed him when the plague had run its course. On the very day he reopened the port, 
they dragged him from his horse and slit his throat, and his young son\rquote 
s as well. To this day the ignorant in Oldtown will spit at the sound of his name, but Quenton Hightower did what was needed. Your father was that sort of man as well. A man who did what was needed.\'94 
\par \'93Is that why he looks so pleased with himself?\'94 
\par The vapors rising from the corpse were making Pycelle\rquote s eyes water. \'93The flesh . . . as the flesh dries, the muscles grow taut and pull his lips upward. That is no smile, only a . . . a }{\cs28\i drying,}{ that is all.\'94
 He blinked back tears. \'93You must excuse me. I am so very tired.\'94 Leaning heavily on his cane, Pycelle tottered slowly from the sept. }{\cs28\i That one is dying too,}{ Jaime realized. Small wonder Cersei called him useless. 
\par To be sure, his sweet sister seemed to think half the court was either useless or treasonous; Pycelle, the Kingsguard, the Tyrells, Jaime himself . . . even Ser Ilyn Payne, the silent knight who served as headsman. As King\rquote 
s Justice, the dungeons were his responsibility. Since he lacked a tongue, Payne had largely left the running of those dungeons to his underlings, but Cersei held him to blame for Tyrion\rquote s escape all the same. }{\cs28\i It was my work, not his,}{
 Jaime almost told her. Instead he had promised to find what answers he could from the chief undergaoler, a bentback old man named Rennifer Longwaters. 
\par \'93I see you wonder, what sort of name is that?\'94 the man had cackled when Jaime went to question him. \'93It is an old name, \rquote tis true. I am not one to boast, but 
there is royal blood in my veins. I am descended from a princess. My father told me the tale when I was a tad of a lad.\'94 Longwaters had not been a tad of a lad for many a year, to judge from his spotted head and the white hairs growing from his chin. 
\'93She was the fairest treasure of the Maidenvault. Lord Oakenfist the great admiral lost his heart to her, though he was married to another. She gave their son the bastard name of \lquote Waters\rquote 
 in honor of his father, and he grew to be a great knight, as did his own son, who put the \lquote Long\rquote  before the \lquote Waters\rquote  so men might know that he was not basely born himself. So I have a little dragon in me.\'94 
\par \'93Yes, I almost mistook you for Aegon the Conqueror,\'94 Jaime had answered. \'93Waters\'94 was a common bastard name about Blackwater Bay; old Longwaters was more like to be descended from some minor household knight than from a princess. \'93
As it matters, though, I have more pressing concerns than your lineage.\'94 
\par Longwaters inclined his head. \'93The lost prisoner.\'94 
\par \'93And the missing gaoler.\'94 
\par \'93Rugen,\'94 the old man supplied. \'93An undergaoler. He had charge of the third level, the black cells.\'94 
\par \'93Tell me of him,\'94 Jaime had to say. }{\cs28\i A bloody farce.}{ He knew who Rugen was, even if Longwaters did not. 
\par \'93Unkempt, unshaven, coarse of speech. I misliked the man, \rquote 
tis true, I do confess it. Rugen was here when I first came, twelve years past. He held his appointment from King Aerys. The man was seldom here, it must be said. I made note of it in my reports, my lord. I most suredly did, I give you my wor
d upon it, the word of a man with royal blood.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Mention that royal blood once more and I may spill some of it,}{ thought Jaime. \'93Who saw these reports?\'94 
\par \'93Certain of them went to the master of coin, others to the master of whisperers. All to the chief gaoler and the King\rquote s Justice. It has always been so in the dungeons.\'94 Longwaters scratched his nose. \'93
Rugen was here when need be, my lord. That must be said. The black cells are little used. Before your lordship\rquote s little brother was sent down, we had Grand Ma
ester Pycelle for a time, and before him Lord Stark the traitor. There were three others, common men, but Lord Stark gave them to the Night\rquote 
s Watch. I did not think it good to free those three, but the papers were in proper order. I made note of that in a report as well, you may be certain of it.\'94 
