\par Jaime\rquote s phantom fingers twitched as he said, \'93Get Osney and Osfryd down here and clean up this mess you\rquote ve made. And the next time my sweet sister commands you to kill a man, come to me first. Elsewise, stay out of my sight, ser.\'94 

\par The words echoed in his head in the dimness of Baelor\rquote 
s Sept. Above him, all the windows had gone black, and he could see the faint light of distant stars. The sun had set for good and all. The stench of death was growing stronger, despite the scented candles. The smell re
minded Jaime Lannister of the pass below the Golden Tooth, where he had won a glorious victory in the first days of the war. On the morning after the battle, the crows had feasted on victors and vanquished alike, as once they had feasted on Rhaegar Targar
yen after the Trident. }{\cs28\i How much can a crown be worth, when a crow can dine upon a king?}{ 
\par There were crows circling the seven towers and great dome of Baelor\rquote s Sept even now, Jaime suspected, their black wings beating against the night air as they searched for a way inside. }{\cs28\i 
Every crow in the Seven Kingdoms should pay homage to you, Father. From Castamere to the Blackwater, you fed them well.}{ That notion pleased Lord Tywin; his smile widened further. }{\cs28\i Bloody hell, he\rquote 
s grinning like a bridegroom at his bedding. }{
\par That was so grotesque it made Jaime laugh aloud. 
\par The sound echoed through the transepts and crypts and chapels, as if the dead interred within the walls were laughing too. }{\cs28\i Why not? This is more absurd than a mummer\rquote s farce, me standing vigil for a fathe
r I helped to slay, sending men forth to capture the brother I helped to free . . . }{He had commanded Ser Addam Marbrand to search the Street of Silk. \'93Look under every bed, you know how fond my brother is of brothels.\'94
 The gold cloaks would find more of interest beneath the whores\rquote  skirts than beneath their beds. He wondered how many bastard children would be born of the pointless search. 
\par Unbidden, his thoughts went to Brienne of Tarth. }{\cs28\i Stupid stubborn ugly wench.}{ He wondered where she was. }{\cs28\i Father, give her strength.}{
 Almost a prayer . . . but was it the god he was invoking, the Father Above whose towering gilded likeness glimmered in the candlelight across the sept? Or was he praying to the corpse that lay before him? }{\cs28\i Does it matter? They never listened, ei
ther one.}{ The Warrior had been Jaime\rquote 
s god since he was old enough to hold a sword. Other men might be fathers, sons, husbands, but never Jaime Lannister, whose sword was as golden as his hair. He was a warrior, and that was all he would ever be. 
\par }{\cs28\i I should tell Cersei the truth, admit that it was me who freed our little brother from his cell.}{ The truth had worked so splendidly with Tyrion, after all. }{\cs28\i I killed your vile son, and now I\rquote m off to kill your father too.}{
 Jaime could hear the Imp laughing in the gloom. He turned his head to look, but the sound was only his own laughter coming back at him. He closed his eyes, and just as quickly snapped them open. }{\cs28\i I must not sleep.}{
 If he slept, he might dream. Oh, how Tyrion was sniggering.}{\cs28\i  . . . a lying whore . . . fucking Lancel and Osmund Kettleblack . . . }{
\par At midnight the hinges on the Father\rquote s Doors gave a groan as several hundred septons filed in for their devotions. Some were clad in the cloth-of-silver vestments and crystal coronals that marked the Most Devout
; their humbler brethren wore their crystals on thongs about their necks and cinched white robes with seven-stranded belts, each plait a different color. Through the Mother\rquote 
s Doors marched white septas from their cloister, seven abreast and singing softly, while the silent sisters came single file down the Stranger\rquote s Steps. Death\rquote 
s handmaidens were garbed in soft grey, their faces hooded and shawled so only their eyes could be seen. A host of brothers appeared as well, in robes of brown and butternut and du
n and even undyed roughspun, belted with lengths of hempen rope. Some hung the iron hammer of the Smith about their necks, whilst others carried begging bowls. 
\par None of the devout paid Jaime any mind. They made a circuit of the sept, worshiping at each of 
the seven altars to honor the seven aspects of the deity. To each god they made sacrifice, to each they sang a hymn. Sweet and solemn rose their voices. Jaime closed his eyes to listen, but opened them again when he began to sway. }{\cs28\i 
I am more weary than I knew. }{
\par It had been years since his last vigil. }{\cs28\i And I was younger then, a boy of fifteen years.}{ He had worn no armor then, only a plain white tunic. The sept where he\rquote d spent the night was not a third as large as any of the Great Sept\rquote 
s seven transepts. Jaime had laid his sword across the Warrior\rquote s knees, piled his armor at his feet, and knelt upon the rough stone floor before the altar. When dawn came his knees were raw and bloody. \'93All knights must bleed, Jaime,\'94
 Ser Arthur Dayne had said, when he saw. \'93Blood is the seal of our devotion.\'94 With dawn he tapped him on the shoulder; the pale blade was so sharp that even that light touch cut through Jaime\rquote 
s tunic, so he bled anew. He never felt it. A boy knelt; a knight rose. }{\cs28\i The Young Lion, not the Kingslayer. }{
\par But that was long ago, and the boy was dead. 
\par He could not have said when the devotions ended. Perhaps he slept, still standing. When the devout had filed out, the Great Sept grew still once more. The candles were a wall of stars burning in the darkness, th
ough the air was rank with death. Jaime shifted his grip upon the golden greatsword. Perhaps he should have let Ser Loras relieve him after all. }{\cs28\i Cersei would have hated that.}{
 The Knight of Flowers was still half a boy, arrogant and vain, but he had it in him to be great, to perform deeds worthy of the White Book. 
\par The White Book would be waiting when this vigil was done, his page open in dumb reproach. }{\cs28\i I\rquote ll hack the bloody book to pieces before I\rquote ll fill it full of lies.}{ Yet if he would not lie, what could he write but truth? 
\par A woman stood before him. 
\par }{\cs28\i It is raining again,}{ he thought when he saw how wet she was. The water was trickling down her cloak to puddle round her feet. }{\cs28\i How did she get here? I never heard her enter.}{ She was dressed like a tavern wench
 in a heavy roughspun cloak, badly dyed in mottled browns and fraying at the hem. A hood concealed her face, but he could see the candles dancing in the green pools of her eyes, and when she moved he knew her. 
\par \'93Cersei.\'94 He spoke slowly, like a man waking from a dream, still wondering where he was. \'93What hour is it?\'94 
\par \'93The hour of the wolf.\'94 His sister lowered her hood, and made a face. \'93The drowned wolf, perhaps.\'94 She smiled for him, so sweetly. \'93Do you remember the first time I came to you like this? It w
as some dismal inn off Weasel Alley, and I put on servant\rquote s garb to get past Father\rquote s guards.\'94 
\par \'93I remember. It was Eel Alley.\'94 }{\cs28\i She wants something of me.}{ \'93Why are you here, at this hour? What would you have of me?\'94 His last word echoed up and down the sept, }{\cs28\i mememememememememememe,}{
 fading to a whisper. For a moment he dared to hope that all she wanted was the comfort of his arms. 
\par \'93Speak softly.\'94 Her voice sounded strange . . . breathless, almost frightened. \'93Jaime, Kevan has refused me. He will not serve as Hand, he . . . he knows about us. He said as much.\'94 
\par \'93Refused?\'94 That surprised him. \'93How could he know? He will have read what Stannis wrote, but there is no . . .\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i Tyrion}{ knew,\'94 she reminded him. \'93Who can say what tales that vile dwarf may have told, or to whom? Uncle Kevan is the least of it. The High Septon . . . Tyrion raised him to the crown, when the fat one died. He may know as well.\'94
 She moved closer. \'93You }{\cs28\i must}{ be Tommen\rquote s Hand. I do not trust Mace Tyrell. What if he had a hand in Father\rquote s death? He may have been conspiring with Tyrion. The Imp could be on his way to Highgarden . . .\'94 
\par \'93He\rquote s not.\'94 
\par \'93Be my Hand,\'94 she pleaded, \'93and we\rquote ll rule the Seven Kingdoms together, like a king and his queen.\'94 
\par \'93You were Robert\rquote s queen. And yet you won\rquote t be mine.\'94 
\par \'93I would, if I dared. But our son\emdash \'94 
\par \'93Tommen is no son of mine, no more than Joffrey was.\'94 His voice was hard. \'93You made them Robert\rquote s too.\'94 
\par His sister flinched. \'93You swore that you would always love me. It is not loving to make me beg.\'94 
\par Jaime could smell the fear on her, even through the rank stench of the corpse. He wanted to take her in his arms and kiss her, to bury his face in her golden curls and promise her that no one would ever hurt her . . . }{\cs28\i not here,}{ he thought, }{
\cs28\i not here in front of the gods, and Father.}{ \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93I cannot. Will not.\'94 
\par \'93I }{\cs28\i need}{ you. I need my other half.\'94 He could hear the rain pattering against the windows high above. \'93You are me, I am you. I need you with me. }{\cs28\i In}{ me. Please, Jaime. }{\cs28\i Please.}{\'94 
\par Jaime looked to make certain Lord Tywin was not rising from his bier in wrath, but his father lay still and cold, rotting. \'93I was made for a battlefield, not a council chamber. And now it may be that I am unfit even for that.\'94 
\par Cersei wiped her tears away on a ragged brown sleeve. \'93Very well. If it is battlefields you want, battlefields I shall give you.\'94 She jerked her hood up angrily. \'93I was a fool to come. I was a fool ever to love you.\'94
 Her footsteps echoed loudly in the quiet, and left damp splotches on the marble floor. 
\par Dawn caught Jaime almost unawares. As the glass in the dome began to lighten, suddenly there were rainbows shimmering off the walls and floors and pillars, bathing Lord Tywin\rquote s corpse in a haze of many-colored light. The King\rquote 
s Hand was rotting visib
ly. His face had taken on a greenish tinge, and his eyes were deeply sunken, two black pits. Fissures had opened in his cheeks, and a foul white fluid was seeping through the joints of his splendid gold-and-crimson armor to pool beneath his body. 
\par The sept
ons were the first to see, when they returned for their dawn devotions. They sang their songs and prayed their prayers and wrinkled up their noses, and one of the Most Devout grew so faint he had to be helped from the sept. Shortly after, a flock of novic
es came swinging censers, and the air grew so thick with incense that the bier seemed cloaked in smoke. All the rainbows vanished in that perfumed mist, yet the stench persisted, a sweet rotten smell that made Jaime want to gag. 
\par When the doors were opened the Tyrells were amongst the first to enter, as befit their rank. Margaery had brought a great bouquet of golden roses. She placed them ostentatiously at the foot of Lord Tywin\rquote 
s bier but kept one back and held it beneath her nose as she took her seat. }{\cs28\i So the girl is as clever as she is pretty. Tommen could do a deal worse for a queen. Others have.}{ Margaery\rquote s ladies followed her example. 
\par Cersei waited until the rest were in their places to make her entrance, with Tommen at her side. Ser Osmund Kettleblack paced beside them in his white enamel plate and white wool cloak. 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93. . . she\rquote s been fucking Lancel and Osmund Kettleblack and Moon Boy for all I know . . .\'94}{ 
\par Jaime had seen Kettleblack naked in the bathhouse, had seen the black hair on his chest, and the coarser thatch between his legs. He pictured that chest pressed against his sister\rquote s, that hair scratching the soft skin of her breasts. }{\cs28\i 
She would not do that. The Imp lied.}{ Spun gold and black wire tangled, sweaty. Kettleblack\rquote s narrow cheeks clenching each time he thrust. Jaime could hear his sister moan. }{\cs28\i No. A lie.}{ 
\par Red-eyed and pale, Cersei climbed the steps to kneel above their father, drawing Tommen down beside her. The boy recoiled at the sight, but his mother seized his wrist before he could pull away. }{\cs28\i \'93Pray,\'94}{
 she whispered, and Tommen tried. But he was only eight and Lord Tywin was a horror. One desperate breath of air, then the king began to sob. }{\cs28\i \'93Stop that!\'94}{ Cersei said. Tommen turned his head and
 doubled over, retching. His crown fell off and rolled across the marble floor. His mother pulled back in disgust, and all at once the king was running for the doors, as fast as his eight-year-old legs could carry him. 
\par \'93Ser Osmund, relieve me,\'94 Jaime said sharply, as Kettleblack turned to chase the crown. He handed the man the golden sword and went after his king. In the Hall of Lamps he caught him, beneath the eyes of two dozen startled septas. \'93I\rquote 
m sorry,\'94 Tommen wept. \'93I will do better on the morrow. Mother says a king must show the way, but the smell made me sick.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i This will not do. Too many eager ears and watching eyes.}{ \'93Best we go outside, Your Grace.\'94 Jaime led the boy out to where the air was as fresh and clean as King\rquote s Landing ever got. Twoscore 
gold cloaks had been posted around the plaza to guard the horses and the litters. He took the king off to the side, well away from everyone, and sat him down upon the marble steps. \'93I wasn\rquote t scared,\'94 the boy insisted. \'93
The smell made me sick. Didn\rquote t it make you sick? How could you bear it, Uncle, ser?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I have smelled my own hand rotting, when Vargo Hoat made me wear it for a pendant.}{ \'93A man can bear most anything, if he must,\'94 Jaime told his son. }{\cs28\i I have smelled a man roasting, as King Aerys cooked him in his own armor.}{ \'93
The world is full of horrors, Tommen. You can fight them, or laugh at them, or look without seeing . . . go away inside.\'94 
\par Tommen considered that. \'93I . . . I used to go away inside sometimes,\'94 he confessed, \'93when Joffy . . .\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93Joffrey.\'94}{ Cersei stood over them, the wind whipping her skirts around her legs. \'93Your brother\rquote s name was }{\cs28\i Joffrey.}{ He would never have shamed me so.\'94 
\par \'93I never meant to. I wasn\rquote t frightened, Mother. It was only that your lord father smelled so bad . . .\'94 
\par \'93Do you think he smelled any sweeter to me? I have a nose too.\'94 She caught his ear and pulled him to his feet. \'93Lord Tyrell has a nose. Did you see him retching in the holy sept? Did you see Lady Margaery bawling like a baby?\'94 
\par Jaime got to his feet. \'93Cersei, enough.\'94 
\par Her nostrils flared. \'93Ser? Why are you here? You swore to stand vigil over Father until the wake was done, as I recall.\'94 
\par \'93It }{\cs28\i is}{ done. Go look at him.\'94 
\par \'93No. Seven days and seven nights, you said. Surely the Lord Commander remembers how to count to seven. Take the number of your fingers, then add two.\'94 
\par Others had begun to stream out onto the plaza, fleeing the noxious odors in the sept. \'93Cersei, keep your voice down,\'94 Jaime warned. \'93Lord Tyrell is approaching.\'94 
\par That reached her. The queen drew Tommen to her side. Mace Tyrell bowed before them. \'93His Grace is not unwell, I hope?\'94 
\par \'93The king was overwhelmed by grief,\'94 said Cersei. 
\par \'93As are we all. If there is aught that I can do . . .\'94 
\par High above, a crow screamed loudly. He was perched on the statue of King Baelor, shitting on his holy head. \'93There is much and more you can do for Tommen, my lord,\'94 Jaime said. \'93
Perhaps you would do Her Grace the honor of supping with her, after the evening services?\'94 
\par Cersei threw him a withering look, but for once she had the sense to bite her tongue. 
\par \'93Sup?\'94 Tyrell seemed taken aback. \'93I suppose . . . of course, we should be honored. My lady wife and I.\'94 
\par The queen forced a smile and made pleasant noises. But when Tyrell had taken his leave and Tommen had been sent off with Ser Addam Marbrand, she turned on Jaime angrily. \'93
Are you drunk or dreaming, ser? Pray tell, why am I having supper with that grasping fool and his puerile wife?\'94 A gust of wind stirred her golden hair. \'93I will }{\cs28\i not}{ name him Hand, if that\rquote s what\emdash \'94 
\par \'93You need Tyrell,\'94 Jaime broke in, \'93but not }{\cs28\i here}{. Ask him to capture Storm\rquote s End for Tommen. Flatter him, and tell him you need him in the field, to replace Father. Mace fancies himself a m
ighty warrior. Either he will deliver Storm\rquote s End to you, or he will muck it up and look a fool. Either way, you win.\'94 
\par \'93Storm\rquote s End?\'94 Cersei looked thoughtful. \'93Yes, but . . . Lord Tyrell has made it tediously plain that he will not leave King\rquote s Landing till Tommen marries Margaery.\'94 
\par Jaime sighed. \'93Then let them wed. It will be years before Tommen is old enough to consummate the marriage. And until he does, the union can always be set aside. Give Tyrell his wedding and send him off to play at war.\'94 
\par A wary smile crept across his sister\rquote s face. \'93Even sieges have their dangers,\'94 she murmured. \'93Why, our Lord of Highgarden might even lose his life in such a venture.\'94 
\par \'93There is that risk,\'94 conceded Jaime. \'93Especially if his patience runs thin this time, and he elects to storm the gate.\'94 
\par Cersei gave him a lingering look. \'93You know,\'94 she said, \'93for a moment you sounded quite like Father.\'94
