\par THE KRAKEN\rquote S DAUGHTER
\par The hall was loud with drunken Harlaws, distant cousins all. Each lord had hung his banner behind the benches where his men were seated. }{\cs28\i Too few,}{ thought Asha Greyjoy, looking down from the gallery, }{\cs28\i too few by far.}{
 The benches were three-quarters empty. 
\par Qarl the Maid had said as much, when the }{\cs28\i Black Wind}{ was approaching from the sea. He had counted the longships moored beneath her uncle\rquote s castle, and his mouth had tightened. \'93They have not come,\'94 he observed, \'93
or not enough of them.\'94 He was not wrong, but Asha could not agree with him, out where her crew might hear. She did not doubt their devotion, but even ironborn will hesitate to give their lives for a cause that\rquote s plainly lost. 
\par }{\cs28\i Do I have so few friends as this?}{ Amongst the banners, she saw the silver fish of Botley, the stone tree of the Stonetrees, the black leviathan of Volmark, the nooses of the Myres. The rest were Harlaw scythes. Boremund
 placed his upon a pale blue field, Hotho\rquote s was girdled within an embattled border, and the Knight had quartered his with the gaudy peacock of his mother\rquote 
s House. Even Sigfryd Silverhair showed two scythes counterchanged on a field divided bendwise. Only }{\cs28\i the}{
 Lord Harlaw displayed the silver scythe plain upon a night-black field, as it had flown in the dawn of days: Rodrik, called the Reader, Lord of the Ten Towers, Lord of Harlaw, Harlaw of Harlaw . . . her favorite uncle. 
\par Lord Rodrik\rquote s high seat was vacan
t. Two scythes of beaten silver crossed above it, so huge that even a giant would have difficulty wielding them, but beneath were only empty cushions. Asha was not surprised. The feast was long concluded. Only bones and greasy platters remained upon the t
restle tables. The rest was drinking, and her uncle Rodrik had never been partial to the company of quarrelsome drunks. 
\par She turned to Three-Tooth, an old woman of fearful age who had been her uncle\rquote s steward since she was known as Twelve-Tooth. \'93My uncle is with his books?\'94 
\par \'93Aye, where else?\'94 The woman was so old that a septon had once said she must have nursed the Crone. That was when the Faith was still tolerated on the isles. Lord Rodrik had kept septons at Ten Towers, not for his soul\rquote s sake but for hi
s books. \'93With the books, and Botley. He was with him too.\'94 
\par Botley\rquote s standard hung in the hall, a shoal of silver fish upon a pale green field, though Asha had not seen his }{\cs28\i Swiftfin}{ amongst the other longships. \'93I had heard my nuncle Crow\rquote s Eye had old Sawane Botley drowned.\'94 

\par \'93Lord }{\cs28\i Tristifer}{ Botley, this one is.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Tris.}{ She wondered what had happened to Sawane\rquote s elder son, Harren. }{\cs28\i I will find out soon enough, no doubt. This should be awkward.}{ She had not seen Tris Botley since . . . no, she ought not dwell on it. \'93
And my lady mother?\'94 
\par \'93Abed,\'94 said Three-Tooth, \'93in the Widow\rquote s Tower.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Aye, where else?}{ The widow the tower was named after was her aunt. Lady Gwynesse had come home to mourn after her husband had died off Fair Isle during Balon Greyjoy\rquote s first rebellion. \'93I will only stay until my grief has passed,\'94
 she had told her brother, famously, \'93though by rights Ten Towers should be mine, for I am seven years your elder.\'94 Long years had passed since then, but still the widow lingered, grieving, and mutte
ring from time to time that the castle should be hers. }{\cs28\i And now Lord Rodrik has a second half-mad widowed sister beneath his roof,}{ Asha reflected. }{\cs28\i Small wonder if he seeks solace in his books.}{ 
\par Even now, it was hard to credit that frail, sickly Lady Alannys
 had outlived her husband Lord Balon, who had seemed so hard and strong. When Asha had sailed away to war, she had done so with a heavy heart, fearing that her mother might well die before she could return. Not once had she thought that her father might p
erish instead. }{\cs28\i The Drowned God plays savage japes upon us all, but men are crueler still.}{ A sudden storm and a broken rope had sent Balon Greyjoy to his death. }{\cs28\i Or so they claim.}{ 
\par Asha had last seen her mother when she stopped at Ten Towers to take on fresh 
water, on her way north to strike at Deepwood Motte. Alannys Harlaw never had the sort of beauty the singers cherished, but her daughter had loved her fierce strong face and the laughter in her eyes. On that last visit, though, she had found Lady Alannys 
in a window seat huddled beneath a pile of furs, staring out across the sea. }{\cs28\i Is this my mother, or her ghost?}{ she remembered thinking as she\rquote d kissed her cheek. 
\par Her mother\rquote s skin had been parchment thin, her long hair white. Some pride remained in the way she held her head, but her eyes were dim and cloudy, and her mouth had trembled when she asked after Theon. \'93Did you bring my baby boy?\'94
 she had asked. Theon had been ten years old when he was carried off to Winterfell a hostage, and so far as Lady Alannys was concerned he would always be ten years old, it seemed. \'93Theon could not come,\'94 Asha had to tell her. \'93
Father sent him reaving along the Stony Shore.\'94 Lady Alannys had naught to say to that. She only nodded slowly, yet it was plain to see how deep her daughter\rquote s words had cut her. 
\par }{\cs28\i And now I must tell her that Theon is dead, and drive yet another dagger through her heart.}{ There were two knives buried there already. On the blades were writ the words }{\cs28\i Rodrik}{ and }{\cs28\i Maron,}{
 and many a time they twisted cruelly in the night. }{\cs28\i I will see her on the morrow,}{ Asha vowed to herself. Her journey had been long and wearisome, she could not face her mother now. 
\par \'93I must speak with Lord Rodrik,\'94 she told Three-Tooth. \'93See to my crew, once they\rquote re done unloading }{\cs28\i Black Wind.}{ They\rquote ll bring captives. I want them to have warm beds and a hot meal.\'94 
\par \'93There\rquote s cold beef in the kitchens. And mustard in a big stone jar, from Oldtown.\'94 The thought of that mustard made the old woman smile. A single long brown tooth poked from her gums. 
\par \'93That will not serve. We had a rough crossing. I want something hot in their bellies.\'94 Asha hooked a thumb through the studded belt about her hips. \'93
Lady Glover and the children should not want for wood nor warmth. Put them in some tower, not the dungeons. The babe is sick.\'94 
\par \'93Babes are often sick. Most die, and folks are sorry. I shall ask my lord where to put these wolf folk.\'94 
\par She caught the woman\rquote s nose between thumb and forefinger and pinched. \'93You will do as I say. And if }{\cs28\i this}{ babe dies, no one will be sorrier than you.\'94
 Three-Tooth squealed and promised to obey, till Asha let her loose and went to find her uncle. 
\par It was good to walk these halls again. Ten Towers had always felt like home to Asha, more so than Pyke. }{\cs28\i Not one castle, ten castles squashed together,}{
 she had thought, the first time she had seen it. She remembered breathless races up and down the steps and along wallwalks and covered bridges, fishing off the Long Stone Quay, days and nights lost amongst her uncle\rquote s wealth of books. His gran
dfather\rquote 
s grandfather had raised the castle, the newest on the isles. Lord Theomore Harlaw had lost three sons in the cradle and laid the blame upon the flooded cellars, damp stones, and festering nitre of ancient Harlaw Hall. Ten Towers was airier, more c
omfortable, better sited . . . but Lord Theomore was a changeable man, as any of his wives might have testified. He\rquote d had six of those, as dissimilar as his ten towers. 
\par The Book Tower was the fattest of the ten, octagonal in shape and made with great blocks of hewn stone. The stair was built within the thickness of the walls. Asha climbed quickly, to the fifth story and the room where her uncle read. }{\cs28\i 
Not that there are any rooms where he does not read.}{ Lord Rodrik was seldom seen without a book in hand, be it in the privy, on the deck of his }{\cs28\i Sea Song,}{
 or whilst holding audience. Asha had oft seen him reading on his high seat beneath the silver scythes. He would listen to each case as it was laid before him, pronounce his judgment . . . and read a bit whilst
 his captain-of-guards went to bring in the next supplicant. 
\par She found him hunched over a table by a window, surrounded by parchment scrolls that might have come from Valyria before its Doom, and heavy leather-bound books with bronze-and-iron hasps. Beeswax candles as thick and tall as a man\rquote 
s arm burned on either s
ide of where he sat, on ornate iron holders. Lord Rodrik Harlaw was neither fat nor slim; neither tall nor short; neither ugly nor handsome. His hair was brown, as were his eyes, though the short, neat beard he favored had gone grey. All in all, he was an
 ordinary man, distinguished only by his love of written words, which so many ironborn found unmanly and perverse. 
\par \'93Nuncle.\'94 She closed the door behind her. \'93What reading was so urgent that you leave your guests without a host?\'94 
\par \'93Archmaester Marwyn\rquote s }{\cs28\i Book of Lost Books.}{\'94 He lifted his gaze from the page to study her. \'93Hotho brought me a copy from Oldtown. He has a daughter he would have me wed.\'94 Lord Rodrik tapped the book with a long nail. \'93
See here? Marwyn claims to have found three pages of }{\cs28\i Signs and Portents,}{ visions written down by the maiden daughter of Aenar Targaryen before the Doom came to Valyria. Does Lanny know that you are here?\'94 
\par \'93Not as yet.\'94 }{\cs28\i Lanny}{ was his pet name for her mother; only the Reader called her that. \'93Let her rest.\'94 Asha moved a stack of books off a stool and seated herself. \'93
Three-Tooth seems to have lost two more of her teeth. Do you call her One-Tooth now?\'94 
\par \'93I seldom call her at all. The woman frightens me. What hour is it?\'94 Lord Rodrik glanced out the window, at the moonlit sea. \'93Dark, so soon? I had not noticed. You come late. We looked for you some days ago.\'94 
\par \'93The winds were against us, and I had captives to concern me. Robett Glover\rquote s wife and children. The youngest is still at the breast, and Lady Glover\rquote s milk dried up during our crossing. I had no choice but to beach }{\cs28\i Black Wind}{
 upon the Stony Shore and send my men out to find a wet nurse. They found a goat instead. The girl does not thrive. Is there a nursing mother in the village? Deepwood is important to my plans.\'94 
\par \'93Your plans must change. You come too late.\'94 
\par \'93Late and hungry.\'94 She stretched her long legs out beneath the table and turned the pages of the nearest book, a septon\rquote s discourse on Maegor the Cruel\rquote s war against the Poor Fellows. \'93Oh, and thirsty too. A horn
 of ale would go down well, Nuncle.\'94 
\par Lord Rodrik pursed his lips. \'93You know I do not permit food nor drink in my library. The books\emdash \'94 
\par \'93\emdash might suffer harm.\'94 Asha laughed. 
\par Her uncle frowned. \'93You do like to provoke me.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, don\rquote t look so aggrieved. I have never met a man I didn\rquote t provoke, you should know that well enough by now. But enough of me. You are well?\'94 
\par He shrugged. \'93Well enough. My eyes grow weaker. I have sent to Myr for a lens to help me read.\'94 
\par \'93And how fares my aunt?\'94 
\par Lord Rodrik sighed. \'93Still seven years my elder, and convinced Ten Towers should be hers. Gwynesse grows forgetful, but }{\cs28\i that}{
 she does not forget. She mourns for her dead husband as deeply as she did the day he died, though she cannot always recall his name.\'94 
\par \'93I am not certain she ever knew his name.\'94 Asha closed the septon\rquote s book with a }{\cs28\i thump.}{ \'93Was my father murdered?\'94 
\par \'93So your mother believes.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i There were times when she would gladly have murdered him herself,}{ she thought. \'93And what does my nuncle believe?\'94 
\par \'93Balon fell to his death when a rope bridge broke beneath him. A storm was rising, and the bridge was swaying and twisting with each gust of wind.\'94 Rodrik shrugged. \'93Or so we are told. Your mother had a bird from Maester Wendamyr.\'94 
\par Asha slid her dirk out of its sheath and began to clean the dirt from beneath her fingernails. \'93Three years away, and the Crow\rquote s Eye returns the very day my father dies.\'94 
\par \'93The day after, we had heard. }{\cs28\i Silence}{ was still out to sea when Balon died, or so it is claimed. Even so, I will agree that Euron\rquote s return was . . . timely, shall we say?\'94 
\par \'93That is not how I would say it.\'94 Asha slammed the point of the dirk into the table. \'93}{\cs28\i Where are my ships?}{ I counted twoscore longships moored below, not near enough to throw the Crow\rquote s Eye off my father\rquote s chair.\'94 

\par \'93I sent the summons. In your name, for the love I bear you and your mother. House Harlaw has gathered. Stonetree as well, and Volmark. Some Myres . . .\'94 
\par \'93All from the isle of Harlaw . . . one isle out of seven. I saw one lonely Botley banner in the hall, from Pyke. Where are the ships from Saltcliffe, from Orkwood, from the Wyks?\'94 
\par \'93Baelor Blacktyde came from Blacktyde to consult with me, and just as soon set sail again.\'94 Lord Rodrik closed }{\cs28\i The Book of Lost Books.}{ \'93He is on Old Wyk by now.\'94 
\par \'93Old Wyk?\'94 Asha had feared he was about to say that they all had gone to Pyke, to do homage to the Crow\rquote s Eye. \'93Why Old Wyk?\'94 
\par \'93I thought you would have heard. Aeron Damphair has called a kingsmoot.\'94 
\par Asha threw back her head and laughed. \'93The Drowned God must have shoved a pricklefish up Uncle Aeron\rquote s arse. A }{\cs28\i kingsmoot?}{ Is this some jape, or does he mean it truly?\'94 
\par \'93The Damphair has not japed since he was drowned. And the other priests have taken up the call. Blind Beron Blacktyde, Tarle the Thrice-Drowned . . 
. even the Old Grey Gull has left that rock he lives on to preach this kingsmoot all across Harlaw. The captains are gathering on Old Wyk as we speak.\'94 
\par Asha was astonished. \'93Has the Crow\rquote s Eye agreed to attend this holy farce and abide by its decision?\'94 
\par \'93The Crow\rquote s Eye does not confide in me. Since he summoned me to Pyke to do him homage, I have had no word from Euron.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i A kingsmoot. This is something new . . . or rather, something very old.}{ \'93And my uncle Victarion? What does he make of the Damphair\rquote s notion?\'94 
\par \'93Victarion was sent word of your father\rquote s death. And of this kingsmoot too, I do not doubt. Beyond that, I cannot say.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Better a kingsmoot than a war.}{ \'93I believe I\rquote ll kiss the Damphair\rquote s smelly feet and pluck the seaweed from out between his toes.\'94 Asha wrenched loose her dirk and sheathed it once again. \'93A bloody }{\cs28\i kingsmoot!}{
\'94 
