\par The bride was fair and gay and beautiful, the groom still baby-faced and plump. He recited his vows in a high, childish voice, promising his love and devotion to Mace Tyrell\rquote s tw
ice-widowed daughter. Margaery wore the same gown she had worn to marry Joffrey, an airy confection of sheer ivory silk, Myrish lace, and seed pearls. Cersei herself was still in black, as a sign of mourning for her murdered firstborn. His widow might be 
pleased to laugh and drink and dance and put all memory of Joff aside, but his mother would not forget him so easily. 
\par }{\cs28\i This is wrong,}{ she thought. }{\cs28\i It is too soon. A year, two years, that would have been time enough. Highgarden should have been content with a betrothal.}{ Cersei stared back to where Mace Tyrell stood between his wife and mother. }{
\cs28\i You forced me into this travesty of a wedding, my lord, and I shall not soon forget it.}{ 
\par When it was time for the changing of the cloaks, the bride sank gracefully to h
er knees and Tommen covered her with the heavy cloth-of-gold monstrosity that Robert had cloaked Cersei in on their own wedding day, with the crowned stag of Baratheon worked upon its back in beads of onyx. Cersei had wanted to use the fine red silk cloak
 Joffrey had used. \'93It was the cloak my lord father used when he wed my lady mother,\'94 she explained to the Tyrells, but the Queen of Thorns had balked her in that as well. \'93That old thing?\'94 the crone had said. \'93
It looks a bit threadbare to me . . . and dare I say, unlucky? And wouldn\rquote t a }{\cs28\i stag}{ be more fitting for King Robert\rquote s trueborn son? In my day a bride donned her }{\cs28\i husband}{\rquote s colors, not his lady mother\rquote s.
\'94 
\par Thanks to Stannis and his filthy letter, there were already too many rumors concerning Tommen\rquote s par
entage. Cersei dared not fan the fires by insisting that he drape his bride in Lannister crimson, so she yielded as gracefully as she could. But the sight of all that gold and onyx still filled her with resentment. }{\cs28\i 
The more we give these Tyrells, the more they demand of us.}{ 
\par When all the vows were spoken, the king and his new queen stepped outside the sept to accept congratulations. \'93Westeros has two queens now, and the young one is as beautiful as the old one,\'94 boom
ed Lyle Crakehall, an oaf of a knight who oft reminded Cersei of her late and unlamented husband. She could have slapped him. Gyles Rosby made to kiss her hand, and only succeeded in coughing on her fingers. Lord Redwyne kissed her on one cheek and Mace T
yrell on both. Grand Maester Pycelle told Cersei that she had not lost a son, but rather gained a daughter. At least she was spared Lady Tanda\rquote s tearful embraces. None of the Stokeworth women had appeared, and for that much the queen was grateful. 

\par Amongst the last was Kevan Lannister. \'93I understand you mean to leave us for another wedding,\'94 the queen said to him. 
\par \'93Hardstone has cleared the broken men from Darry castle,\'94 he replied. \'93Lancel\rquote s bride awaits us there.\'94 
\par \'93Will your lady wife be joining you for the nuptials?\'94 
\par \'93The riverlands are still too dangerous. Vargo Hoat\rquote s scum remain abroad, and Beric Dondarrion has been hanging Freys. Is it true that Sandor Clegane has joined him?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i How does he know that?}{ \'93Some say. Reports are confused.\'94 The bird had co
me last night, from a septry on an island hard by the mouth of the Trident. The nearby town of Saltpans had been savagely raided by a band of outlaws, and some of the survivors claimed a roaring brute in a hound\rquote 
s head helm was amongst the raiders. Supposedly he\rquote d killed a dozen men and raped a girl of twelve. \'93No doubt Lancel will be eager to hunt down Clegane and Lord Beric both, to restore the king\rquote s peace to the riverlands.\'94 
\par Ser Kevan stared into her eyes for a moment. \'93My son is not the man to deal with Sandor Clegane.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i We agree on that much, at least.}{ \'93His father might be.\'94 
\par Her uncle\rquote s mouth grew hard. \'93If my service is not required at the Rock . . .\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Your service was required here.}{ Cersei had named her cousin Damion Lannister her castellan for the Rock, and another cousin, Ser Daven Lannister, the Warden of the West. }{\cs28\i Insolence has its price, Uncle.}{ \'93Bring us Sandor\rquote 
s head, and I know His Grace will be most grateful. Joff may have liked the man, but Tommen was always afraid of him . . . with good reason, it would seem.\'94 
\par \'93When a dog goes bad, the fault lies with his master,\'94 Ser Kevan said. Then he turned and walked away. 
\par Jaime escorted her to the Small Hall, where the feast was being readied. \'93I blame you for all this,\'94 she whispered as they walked. \'93}{\cs28\i Let them wed,}{
 you said. Margaery should be mourning Joffrey, not marrying his brother. She should be as sick with grief as I am. I do not believe she is a maid. Renly had a cock, didn\rquote t he? He was Robert\rquote s brother, he }{\cs28\i surely}{
 had a cock. If that disgusting old crone thinks that I will allow my son to\emdash \'94 
\par \'93You will be rid of Lady Olenna soon enough,\'94 Jaime broke in quietly. \'93She\rquote s returning to Highgarden on the morrow.\'94 
\par \'93So she says.\'94 Cersei did not trust any Tyrell promise. 
\par \'93She\rquote s leaving,\'94 he insisted. \'93Mace is taking half the Tyrell strength to Storm\rquote 
s End, and the other half will be going back to the Reach with Ser Garlan to make good his claim on Brightwater. A few more days, and the only roses left in King\rquote s Landing will be Margaery and her ladies and a few guardsmen.\'94 
\par \'93And Ser Loras. Or have you forgotten your }{\cs28\i Sworn Brother?}{\'94 
\par \'93Ser Loras is a knight of the Kingsguard.\'94 
\par \'93Ser Loras is so Tyrell he pisses rosewater. He should never have been given a white cloak.\'94 
\par \'93He would not have been my choice, I\rquote ll grant you. No one troubled to consult me. Loras will do well enough, I think. Once a man puts on that cloak, it changes him.\'94 
\par \'93It certainly changed }{\cs28\i you,}{ and not for the better.\'94 
\par \'93I love you too, sweet sister.\'94 He held the door for her, and walked her 
to the high table and her seat beside the king. Margaery was on the other side of Tommen, in the place of honor. When she entered, arm in arm with the little king, she made a point of stopping to kiss Cersei on the cheeks and throw her arms around her. 
\'93Your Grace,\'94 the girl said, bold as polished brass, \'93I feel as though I have a second mother now. I pray that we shall be very close, united by our love for your sweet son.\'94 
\par \'93I loved both my sons.\'94 
\par \'93Joffrey is in my prayers as well,\'94 said Margaery. \'93I loved him dearly, though I never had the chance to know him.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Liar,}{ the queen thought. }{\cs28\i If you had loved him even for an instant, you would not have been in such unseemly haste to wed his brother. His crown was all you ever wanted.}{ For half a groat she would h
ave slapped the blushing bride right there upon the dais, in view of half the court. 
\par Like the service, the wedding feast was modest. Lady Alerie had made all the arrangements; Cersei had not had the stomach to face that daunting task again, after the way Joffrey\rquote 
s wedding had ended. Only seven courses were served. Butterbumps and Moon Boy entertained the guests between dishes, and musicians played as they ate. They listened to pipers and fiddlers, a lute and a flute, a high harp. The only singer was some f
avorite of Lady Margaery\rquote s, a dashing young cock-a-whoop clad all in shades of azure who called himself the Blue Bard. He sang a few love songs and retired. \'93What a disappointment,\'94 Lady Olenna complained loudly. \'93I was hoping for \lquote 
The Rains of Castamere.\rquote \'94 
\par Whenever Cersei looked at the old crone, the face of Maggy the Frog seemed to float before her eyes, wrinkled and terrible and wise. }{\cs28\i All old women look alike,}{ she tried to tell herself, }{\cs28\i that\rquote s all it is.}{
 In truth, the bent-back sorceress had looked nothing like the Queen of Thorns, yet somehow the sight of Lady Olenna\rquote s nasty little smile was enough to put her back in Maggy\rquote 
s tent again. She could still remember the smell of it, redolent with queer eastern spices, and the softness of Maggy\rquote s gums as she sucked the blood from Cersei\rquote s finger. }{\cs28\i Queen you shall be,}{
 the old woman had promised, with her lips still wet and red and glistening, }{\cs28\i until there comes another, younger and more beautiful, to cast you down and take all that you hold dear.}{ 
\par Cersei glanced past Tommen, to where Margaery sat laughing with her father. }{\cs28\i She is pretty enough,}{ she had to admit, }{\cs28\i 
but most of that is youth. Even peasant girls are pretty at a certain age, when they are still fresh and innocent and unspoiled, and most of them have the 
same brown hair and brown eyes as she does. Only a fool would ever claim she was more beautiful than I.}{ The world was full of fools, however. So was her son\rquote s court. 
\par Her mood was not improved when Mace Tyrell arose to lead the toasts. He raised a golden goblet high, smiling at his pretty little daughter, and in a booming voice said, \'93To the king and queen!\'94 The other sheep all }{\cs28\i baaaaaa}{
ed along with him. }{\cs28\i \'93The king and queen!\'94}{ they cried, smashing their cups together. }{\cs28\i \'93The king and queen!\'94}{ She had no choice b
ut to drink along with them, all the time wishing that the guests had but a single face, so she could throw her wine into their eyes and remind them that }{\cs28\i she}{ was the true queen. The only one of Tyrell\rquote 
s lickspittles who seemed to remember her at all was Paxter Redwyne, who rose to make his own toast, swaying slightly. }{\cs28\i \'93To both our queens!\'94}{ he chirruped. }{\cs28\i \'93To the young queen and the old!\'94}{ 
\par Cersei drank several cups of wine and pushed her food around a golden plate. Jaime ate even less, and seldom deigned to occupy his seat upon the dais. }{\cs28\i He is as anxious as I am,}{
 the queen realized as she watched him prowl the hall, twitching aside the tapestries with his good hand to assure himself that no one was hiding behind them. There were Lannister spearmen posted aroun
d the building, she knew. Ser Osmund Kettleblack guarded one door, Ser Meryn Trant the other. Balon Swann stood behind the king\rquote s chair, Loras Tyrell behind the queen\rquote 
s. No swords had been allowed inside the feast save for those the white knights bore. 
\par }{\cs28\i My son is safe,}{ Cersei told herself. }{\cs28\i No harm can come to him, not here, not now.}{ Yet every time she looked at Tommen, she saw Joffrey clawing at his throat. And when the boy began to cough the queen\rquote 
s heart stopped beating for a moment. She knocked aside a serving girl in her haste to reach him. 
\par \'93Only a little wine that went down the wrong way,\'94 Margaery Tyrell assured her, smiling. She took Tommen\rquote s hand in her own and kissed his fingers. \'93My little love needs to take smaller sips. See, you scared your lady mother half to death.
\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote m sorry, Mother,\'94 Tommen said, abashed. 
\par It was more than Cersei could stand. }{\cs28\i I cannot let them see me cry,}{ she thought, when she felt the tears welling in her eyes. She walked past Ser Meryn Trant and out into the back passage.
 Alone beneath a tallow candle, she allowed herself a shuddering sob, then another. }{\cs28\i A woman may weep, but not a queen. }{
\par \'93Your Grace?\'94 said a voice behind her. \'93Do I intrude?\'94 
\par It was a woman\rquote s voice, flavored with the accents of the east. For an instant she feared that Maggy the Frog was speaking to her from the grave. But it was only Merryweather\rquote 
s wife, the sloe-eyed beauty Lord Orton had wed during his exile and fetched home with him to Longtable. \'93The Small Hall is so stuffy,\'94 Cersei heard herself say. \'93The smoke was making my eyes water.\'94 
\par \'93And mine, Your Grace.\'94 Lady Merryweather was as tall as the queen, but dark instead of fair, raven-haired and olive-skinned and younger by a decade. She offered the queen a pale blue handkerchief of silk and lace. \'93I
 have a son as well. I know that I shall weep rivers on the day he weds.\'94 
\par Cersei wiped her cheeks, furious that she had let her tears be seen. \'93My thanks,\'94 she said stiffly. 
\par \'93Your Grace, I . . .\'94 The Myrish woman lowered her voice. \'93There is something you must know. Your maid is bought and paid for. She tells Lady Margaery everything you do.\'94 
\par \'93Senelle?\'94 Sudden fury twisted in the queen\rquote s belly. Was there no one she could trust? \'93You are certain of this?\'94 
\par \'93Have her followed. Margaery never meets with her
 directly. Her cousins are her ravens, they bring her messages. Sometimes Elinor, sometimes Alla, sometimes Megga. All of them are as close to Margaery as sisters. They meet in the sept and pretend to pray. Put your own man in the gallery on the morrow, a
nd he will see Senelle whispering to Megga beneath the altar of the Maiden.\'94 
\par \'93If this is true, why tell me? You are one of Margaery\rquote s companions. Why would you betray her?\'94 Cersei had learned suspicion at her father\rquote s knee; this could well be some trap, a lie meant to sow discord between the lion and the rose. 

\par \'93Longtable may be sworn to Highgarden,\'94 the woman replied, with a toss of her black hair, \'93but I am of Myr, and my loyalty is to my husband and my son. I want all that is best for them.\'94 
\par \'93I see.\'94 In the closeness of the passage, the queen could smell the other woman\rquote s perfume, a musky scent that spoke of moss and earth and wildflowers. Under it, she smelled ambition. }{\cs28\i She gave testimony at Tyrion\rquote s trial,}{
 Cersei recalled suddenly. }{\cs28\i She saw the Imp put the poison in Joff\rquote s cup and was not afraid to say so.}{ \'93I shall look into this,\'94 she promised. \'93If what you say is true, you will be rewarded.\'94 }{\cs28\i And if you\rquote 
ve lied to me, I\rquote ll have your tongue, and your lord husband\rquote s lands and gold as well.}{ 
\par \'93Your Grace is kind. And beautiful.\'94 Lady Merryweather smiled. Her teeth were white, her lips full and dark. 
\par When the queen returned to the Small Hall, she found her brother pacing restlessly. \'93It was only a gulp of wine that went down the wrong way. Though it startled me as well.\'94 
\par \'93My belly is such a knot that I cannot eat,\'94 she growled at him. \'93The wine tastes of bile. This wedding was a mistake.\'94 
\par \'93This wedding was necessary. The boy is safe.\'94 
\par \'93Fool. No one who wears a crown is ever safe.\'94 She looked about the ha
ll. Mace Tyrell laughed amongst his knights. Lords Redwyne and Rowan were talking furtively. Ser Kevan sat brooding over his wine at the back of the hall, whilst Lancel whispered something to a septon. Senelle was moving down the table, filling the cups o
f the bride\rquote s cousins with wine as red as blood. Grand Maester Pycelle had fallen asleep. }{\cs28\i There is no one I can rely upon, not even Jaime,}{ she realized grimly. }{\cs28\i 
I will need to sweep them all away and surround the king with mine own people.}{ 
\par Later, after swee
ts and nuts and cheese had been served and cleared away, Margaery and Tommen began the dancing, looking more than a bit ridiculous as they whirled about the floor. The Tyrell girl stood a good foot and a half taller than her little husband, and Tommen was
 a clumsy dancer at best, with none of Joffrey\rquote 
s easy grace. He did his earnest best, though, and seemed oblivious to the spectacle he was making of himself. And no sooner was Maid Margaery done with him than her cousins swooped in, one after the other, ins
isting that His Grace must dance with them as well. }{\cs28\i They will have him stumbling and shuffling like a fool by the time they\rquote re done,}{ Cersei thought resentfully as she watched. }{\cs28\i 
Half the court will be laughing at him behind his back. }{
\par Whilst Alla, Elinor, an
d Megga took their turns with Tommen, Margaery took a turn around the floor with her father, then another with her brother Loras. The Knight of Flowers was in white silk, with a belt of golden roses about his waist and a jade rose fastening his cloak. }{
\cs28\i They could be twins,}{ Cersei thought as she watched them. Ser Loras was a year older than his sister, but they had the same big brown eyes, the same thick brown hair falling in lazy ringlets to their shoulders, the same smooth unblemished skin. }
{\cs28\i A ripe crop of pimples would teach them some humility.}{ Loras was taller and had a few wisps of soft brown fuzz on his face, and Margaery had a woman\rquote s shape, but elsewise they were more alike than she and Jaime. That annoyed her too. 

\par Her own twin interrupted her musings. \'93Would Your Grace honor her white knight with a dance?\'94 
\par She gave him a withering look. \'93And have you fumbling at me with that stump? No. I will let you fill my wine cup for me, though. If you think you can manage it without spilling.\'94 
\par \'93A cripple like me? Not likely.\'94 He moved away and made another circuit of the hall. She had to fill her own cup. 
\par Cersei refused Mace Tyrell as well, and later Lancel. The others took the hint, and no one else approached her. }{\cs28\i Our fast friends and loyal lords.}{ She could not even trust the westermen, her father\rquote 
s sworn swords and bannermen. Not if her own uncle was conspiring with her enemies . . . 
\par Margaery was dancing with her cousin Alla, Megga with Ser Tallad the Tall. The other cousin, Elinor, was sharing a cup of wine w
ith the handsome young Bastard of Driftmark, Aurane Waters. It was not the first time the queen had made note of Waters, a lean young man with grey-green eyes and long silver-gold hair. The first time she had seen him, for half a heartbeat she had almost 
thought Rhaegar Targaryen had returned from the ashes. }{\cs28\i It is his hair,}{ she told herself. }{\cs28\i He is not half as comely as Rhaegar was. His face is too narrow, and he has that cleft in his chin.}{
 The Velaryons came from old Valyrian stock, however, and some had the same silvery hair as the dragonkings of old. 
\par Tommen returned to his seat to nibble at an applecake. Her uncle\rquote s place was empty. The queen finally found him in a corner, talking intently with Mace Tyrell\rquote s son Garlan. }{\cs28\i What do they have to talk about?}{ Th
e Reach might call Ser Garlan gallant, but she trusted him no more than Margaery or Loras. She had not forgotten the gold coin that Qyburn had discovered beneath the gaoler\rquote s chamber pot. }{\cs28\i 
A golden hand from Highgarden. And Margaery is spying on me.}{ When Senelle appeared to fill her wine cup, the queen had to resist an urge to take her by the throat and throttle her. }{\cs28\i 
Do not presume to smile at me, you treacherous little bitch. You will be begging me for mercy before I\rquote m done with you. }{
\par \'93I think Her Grace has had enough wine for one night,\'94 she heard her brother Jaime say. 
\par }{\cs28\i No,}{ the queen thought. }{\cs28\i All the wine in the world would not be enough to see me through this wedding.}{ She rose so fast she almost fell. Jaime caught her by the arm and steadied her. She wren
ched free and clapped her hands together. The music died, the voices stilled. }{\cs28\i \'93Lords and ladies,\'94}{ Cersei called out loudly, \'93
if you will be so good as to come outside with me, we shall light a candle to celebrate the union of Highgarden and Casterly Rock, and a new age of peace and plenty for our Seven Kingdoms.\'94 
\par Dark and forlorn stood the Tower of the Hand, with only gaping holes where oaken doors and shuttered windows had once been. Yet even ruined and slighted, it loomed above the outer ward. As the wed
ding guests filed out of the Small Hall, they passed beneath its shadow. When Cersei looked up she saw the tower\rquote s crenellated battlements gnawing at a hunter\rquote 
s moon, and wondered for a moment how many Hands of how many kings had made their home there over the past three centuries. 
\par A hundred yards from the tower, she took a breath to stop her head from spinning. \'93Lord Hallyne! You may commence.\'94 
\par Hallyne the pyromancer said }{\cs28\i \'93Hmmmmmm\'94}{ and waved the torch he was holding, and the archers on the walls bent their bows and sent a dozen flaming arrows through the gaping windows. 
\par The tower went up with a }{\cs28\i whoosh.}{ In half a heartbeat its interior was alive with light, red, yellow, orange . . . and green, an ominous dark green, the color of bile and jade and pyromancer\rquote s piss. \'93The substance,\'94
 the alchemists named it, but common folk called it }{\cs28\i wildfire.}{ Fifty pots had been placed inside the Tower of the Hand, along with logs and casks of pitch and the greater part of the worldly possessions of a dwarf named Tyrion Lannister. 

\par The queen could feel the heat of those green flames. The pyromancers said that only three things burned hotter than their substance: dragonflame, the fires beneath the earth, and the summer sun. Some of the ladies gasped when the first flames appe
ared in the windows, licking up the outer walls like long green tongues. Others cheered, and made toasts. 
\par }{\cs28\i It is beautiful,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i as beautiful as Joffrey, when they laid him in my arms.}{ No man had ever made her feel as good as she had felt when he took her nipple in his mouth to nurse. 
\par Tommen stared wide-eyed at the fires, as fascinated as he was frightened, until Margaery whispered something in his ear that made him laugh. Some of the 
knights began to make wagers on how long it would be before the tower collapsed. Lord Hallyne stood humming to himself and rocking on his heels. 
\par Cersei thought of all the King\rquote s Hands that she had known through the years: Owen Merryweather, Jon Connington, Qarlton Chelsted, Jon Arryn, Eddard Stark, her brother Tyrion. And her father, Lord Tywin Lannister, her father most of all. }{\cs28\i 
All of them are burning now,}{ she told herself, savoring the thought. }{\cs28\i They are dead and burning, every one, with all their plots and schemes and betrayals. It is my day now. It is my castle and my kingdom.}{ 
\par The Tower of the Hand gave out a sudden groan, so loud that all the conversation stopped abruptly. Stone cracked and split, and part of the upper battlements fell away and landed 
with a crash that shook the hill, sending up a cloud of dust and smoke. As fresh air rushed in through the broken masonry, the fire surged upward. Green flames leapt into the sky and whirled around each other. Tommen shied away, till Margaery took his han
d and said, \'93Look, the flames are dancing. Just as we did, my love.\'94 
\par \'93They are.\'94 His voice was filled with wonder. \'93Mother, look, they\rquote re dancing.\'94 
\par \'93I see them. Lord Hallyne, how long will the fires burn?\'94 
\par \'93All night, Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93It makes a pretty candle, I grant you,\'94 said Lady Olenna Tyrell, leaning on her cane between Left and Right. \'93
Bright enough to see us safe to sleep, I think. Old bones grow weary, and these young ones have had enough excitement for one night. It is time the king and queen were put to bed.\'94 
\par \'93Yes.\'94 Cersei beckoned to Jaime. \'93Lord Commander, escort His Grace and his little queen to their pillows, if you would.\'94 
\par \'93As you command. And you as well?\'94 
\par \'93No need.\'94 Cersei felt too alive for sleep. The wildfire was cleansing her, burning away all her rage and fear, filling her with resolve. \'93The flames are so pretty. I want to watch them for a while.\'94 
\par Jaime hesitated. \'93You should not stay alone.\'94 
\par \'93I will not be alone. Ser Osmund can remain with me and keep me safe. Your Sworn Brother.\'94 
\par \'93If it please Your Grace,\'94 said Kettleblack. 
\par \'93It does.\'94 Cersei slid her arm through his, and side by side they watched the fire rage.
