\par BRIENNE
\par The stone wall was old and crumbling, but the sight of it across the field made the hairs on Brienne\rquote s neck stand up. 
\par }{\cs28\i That was where the archers hid and slew poor Cleos Frey,}{ she thought . . . but half a mile farther on she passed another wall tha
t looked much like the first and found herself uncertain. The rutted road turned and twisted, and the bare brown trees looked different from the green ones she remembered. Had she ridden past the place where Ser Jaime had snatched his cousin\rquote 
s sword from its scabbard? Where were the woods they\rquote d fought in? The stream where they\rquote d splashed and slashed at one another until they drew the Brave Companions down upon them? 
\par \'93My lady? Ser?\'94 Podrick never seemed certain what to call her. \'93What are you looking for?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Ghosts.}{ \'93A wall I rode by once. It does not matter.\'94 }{\cs28\i It was when Ser Jaime still had both his hands. How I loathed him, with all his taunts and smiles.}{ \'93Stay quiet, Podrick. There may still be outlaws in these woods.\'94 

\par The boy looked at the bare brown trees, the wet leaves, the muddy road ahead. \'93I have a longsword. I can fight.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Not well enough.}{ Brienne did not doubt the boy\rquote s courage, only his training. A squire he might be, in name at least, but the men he\rquote d squired for had served him ill. 
\par She had go
tten his story out of him in fits and starts on the road from Duskendale. His was a lesser branch of House Payne, an impoverished offshoot sprouted from the loins of a younger son. His father had spent his life squiring for richer cousins and had sired Po
drick upon a chandler\rquote s daughter he\rquote 
d wed before going off to die in the Greyjoy Rebellion. His mother had abandoned him with one of those cousins when he was four, so she could run after a wandering singer who had put another baby in her belly. Podrick did
 not remember what she looked like. Ser Cedric Payne had been the nearest thing to a parent the boy had ever known, though from his stammered stories it seemed to Brienne that cousin Cedric had treated Podrick more like a servant than a son. When Casterly
 Rock called its banners, the knight had taken him along to tend his horse and clean his mail. Then Ser Cedric had been slain in the riverlands whilst fighting in Lord Tywin\rquote s host. 
\par Far from home, alone, and penniless, the boy had attached himself to a fat hedge knight named Ser Lorimer the Belly, who was part of Lord Lefford\rquote s contingent, charged with protecting the baggage train. \'93
The boys who guard the foodstuffs always eat the best,\'94 Ser Lorimer liked to say, until he was discovered with a salted ham he\rquote d stolen from Lord Tywin\rquote 
s personal stores. Tywin Lannister chose to hang him as a lesson to other looters. Podrick had shared the ham and might have shared the rope as well, but his name had saved him. Ser Kevan Lannister took charge of him, and sometime
 later sent the boy to squire for his nephew Tyrion. 
\par Ser Cedric had taught Podrick how to groom a horse and check his shoes for stones, and Ser Lorimer had taught him how to steal, but neither had given him much training with a sword. The Imp at least had dispatched him to the Red Keep\rquote 
s master-at-arms when they came to court. But during the bread riots Ser Aron Santagar had been amongst those slain, and that had been the end of Podrick\rquote s training. 
\par Brienne cut two wooden swords from fallen branches to get a sense of Podrick\rquote 
s skills. The boy was slow of speech but not of hand, she was pleased to learn. Though fearless and attentive, he was also underfed and skinny, and not near strong enough. If he had survived the Battle of the Blackwater as he claimed, i
t could only be because no one thought him worth the killing. \'93You may call yourself a squire,\'94 she told him, \'93but I\rquote ve seen pages half your age who could have beat you bloody. If you stay with me, you\rquote 
ll go to sleep with blisters on your hands and bruises on your arms most every night, and you\rquote ll be so stiff and sore you\rquote ll hardly sleep. You don\rquote t want that.\'94 
\par \'93I do,\'94 the boy insisted. \'93I want that. The bruises and the blisters. I mean, I don\rquote t, but I do. Ser. My lady.\'94 
\par So far he had been true to his word, and Brienne had been true to hers. Podrick had not complained. Every time he raised a new blister on his sword hand, he felt the need to show it to her proudly. He took good care of their horses too. }{\cs28\i 
He is still no squire,}{ she reminded herself, }{\cs28\i but I am no knight, no matter how many times he calls me \'93ser.\'94}{
 She would have sent him on his way, but he had nowhere to go. Besides, though Podrick said he did not know where Sansa Stark had gone, it might be that he knew more than he realized. Some chance remark, half-remembered, might hold the key to Brienne
\rquote s quest. 
\par \'93Ser? My lady?\'94 Podrick pointed. \'93There\rquote s a cart ahead.\'94 
\par Brienne saw it: a wooden oxcart, two-wheeled and high-sided. A man and a woman were laboring in the traces, pulling the cart along the ruts toward Maidenpool. }{\cs28\i Farm folk, by the look of them.}{ \'93Slowly now,\'94 she told the boy. \'93
They may take us for outlaws. Say no more than you must and be courteous.\'94 
\par \'93I will, ser. Be courteous. My lady.\'94 The boy seemed almost pleased by the prospect of being taken for an outlaw. 
\par The farm folk watched them warily as they came trotting up, but once Brienne made it plain that she meant them no harm, they let her ride beside them. \'93We used to have an ox,\'94 the old man told her as they made their way through the weed
-choked fields, lakes of soft mud, and burnt and blackened trees, \'93but the wolves made off with him.\'94 His face was red from the effort of pulling the cart. \'93
They took off our daughter too and had their way with her, but she come wandering back after the battle down at Duskendale. The ox never did. The wolves ate him, I expect.\'94 
\par The woman had little to add. She was younger than the man by twenty years, but never spoke a word, only looked at Brienne the same way she might have looked at a two-headed calf. Th
e Maid of Tarth had seen such eyes before. Lady Stark had been kind to her, but most women were just as cruel as men. She could not have said which she found most hurtful, the pretty girls with their waspish tongues and brittle laughter or the cold-eyed l
adies who hid their disdain behind a mask of courtesy. And common women could be worse than either. \'93Maidenpool was all in ruins when last I saw it,\'94 she said. \'93The gates were broken and half the town was burned.\'94 
\par \'93They rebuilt it some. This Tarly, he\rquote s a hard man, but a braver lord than Mooton. There\rquote s still outlaws in the woods, but not so many as there was. Tarly hunted down the worst o\rquote  them and shortened them with that big sword o
\rquote  his.\'94 He turned his head and spat. \'93You\rquote ve seen no outlaws on the road?\'94 
\par \'93None.\'94 }{\cs28\i Not this time.}{ The farther they had come from Duskendale, the emptier the road had been. The only travelers they\rquote 
d glimpsed had melted away into the woods before they reached them, save for a big, bearded septon they met walking south with twosc
ore footsore followers. Such inns as they passed had either been sacked and abandoned or turned into armed camps. Yesterday they had encountered one of Lord Randyll\rquote 
s patrols, bristling with longbows and lances. The horsemen had surrounded them while their captain questioned Brienne, but in the end he\rquote d let them continue on their way. \'93
Be wary, woman. The next men you meet may not be as honest as my lads. The Hound has crossed the Trident with a hundred outlaws, and it\rquote s said they\rquote re raping every wench they come upon and cutting off their teats for trophies.\'94 
\par Brienne felt obligated to pass along that warning to the farmer and his wife. The man nodded as she told him, but when she was done he spat again and said, \'93Dogs and wolves and lions, may the Others take them all. These outlaws won\rquote 
t dare come too near to Maidenpool. Not so long as Lord Tarly has the rule there.\'94 
\par Brienne knew Lord Randyll Tarly from her time with King Renly\rquote s host. Though she could not find it in herself to like the man, she could not forget the debt she owed him either. }{\cs28\i 
If the gods are good, we will pass Maidenpool before he knows that I am there.}{ \'93The town will be restored to Lord Mooton once the fighting\rquote s done,\'94 she told the farmer. \'93His lordship has been pardoned by the king.\'94 
\par \'93Pardoned?\'94 The old man laughed. \'93
For what? Sitting on his arse in his bloody castle? He sent men off to Riverrun to fight but never went himself. Lions sacked his town, then wolves, then sellswords, and his lordship just sat safe behind his walls. His brother \rquote 
ud never have hid like that. Ser Myles was bold as brass till that Robert killed him.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i More ghosts,}{ Brienne thought. \'93I am looking for my sister, a fair maid of three-and-ten. Perhaps you\rquote ve seen her?\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote ve not seen no maids, fair nor foul.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i No one has.}{ But she had to keep asking. 
\par \'93Mooton\rquote s daughter, she\rquote s a maid,\'94 the man went on. \'93Till the bedding, anyways. These eggs, they\rquote re for her wedding. Her and Tarly\rquote s son. The cooks will need eggs for cakes.\'94 
\par \'93They will.\'94 }{\cs28\i Lord Tarly\rquote s son. Young Dickon\rquote s to be wed.}{ She tried to recall how old he was; eight or ten, she thought. Brienne had been betrothed at seven, to a boy three years her senior, Lord Caron\rquote 
s younger son, a shy boy with a mole above his lip. They had only met the once, on the occasio
n of their betrothal. Two years later he was dead, carried off by the same chill that took Lord and Lady Caron and their daughters. Had he lived, they would have been wed within a year of her first flowering, and her whole life would have been different. 
She would not be here now, dressed in man\rquote s mail and carrying a sword, hunting for a dead woman\rquote s child. More like she\rquote 
d be at Nightsong, swaddling a child of her own and nursing another. It was not a new thought for Brienne. It always made her feel a little sad, but a little relieved as well. 
\par The sun was half-hidden behind a bank of clouds when they emerged from the blackened trees to find Maidenpool before them, with the deep waters of the bay beyond. The town\rquote s gates had been rebuilt and strengthened, Br
ienne saw at once, and crossbowmen walked its pink stone walls once more. Above the gatehouse floated King Tommen\rquote 
s royal banner, a black stag and golden lion combatant on a field divided gold and crimson. Other banners displayed the Tarly huntsman, but the red salmon of House Mooton flew only from their castle on its hill. 
\par At the portcullis they came upon a dozen guards armed with halberds. Their badges marked them for soldiers of Lord Tarly\rquote s host, though none was Tarly\rquote s own. She saw two centaurs, a thu
nderbolt, a blue beetle and a green arrow, but not the striding huntsman of Horn Hill. Their serjeant had a peacock on his breast, its bright tail faded by the sun. When the farmers drew their cart up he gave a whistle. \'93What\rquote s this now? Eggs?
\'94 He tossed one up, caught it, and grinned. \'93We\rquote ll take them.\'94 
\par The old man squawked. \'93Our eggs is for Lord Mooton. For the wedding cakes and such.\'94 
\par \'93Have your hens lay more. I haven\rquote t had an egg in half a year. Here, don\rquote t say you weren\rquote t paid.\'94 He flung a handful of pennies at the old man\rquote s feet. 
\par The farmer\rquote s wife spoke up. \'93That\rquote s not enough,\'94 she said. \'93Not near enough.\'94 
\par \'93I say it is,\'94 said the serjeant. \'93For them eggs, and you as well. Bring her here, boys. She\rquote s too young for that old man.\'94 Two of the guards le
aned their halberds against the wall and pulled the woman away from the cart, struggling. The farmer watched grey-faced, but dared not move. 
\par Brienne spurred her mare forward. \'93Release her.\'94 
\par Her voice made the guards hesitate long enough for the farmer\rquote s wife to wrench free of their grasp. \'93This is none of your concern,\'94 one man said. \'93You mind your mouth, wench.\'94 
\par Brienne drew her sword instead. 
\par \'93Well now,\'94 the serjeant said, \'93naked steel. Seems to me I smell an outlaw. You know what Lord Tarly does with outlaws?\'94 He still held the egg he\rquote d taken from the cart. His hand closed, and the yolk oozed through his fingers. 
\par \'93I know what Lord Randyll does with outlaws,\'94 Brienne said. \'93I know what he does with rapers too.\'94 
\par She had hoped the name might cow them, but the serjeant only flicked egg off his fingers and signaled to his men to spread out. Brienne found herself surrounded by steel points. \'93
What was it you was saying, wench? What is it that Lord Tarly does to . . .\'94 
\par \'93. . . rapers,\'94 a deeper voice finished. \'93He gelds them or sends them to the Wall. Sometimes both. And he cuts fingers off thieves.\'94
 A languid young man stepped from the gatehouse, a swordbelt buckled at his waist. The surcoat he wore above his steel had once been white, and here and there sti
ll was, beneath the grass stains and dried blood. His sigil was displayed across his chest: a brown deer, dead and bound and slung beneath a pole. 
\par }{\cs28\i Him.}{ His voice was a punch in her stomach, his face a blade in her bowels. \'93Ser Hyle,\'94 she said stiffly. 
\par \'93Best let her by, lads,\'94 warned Ser Hyle Hunt. \'93This is Brienne the Beauty, the Maid of Tarth, who slew King Renly and half his Rainbow Guard. She\rquote s as mean as she is ugly, and there\rquote 
s no one uglier . . . except perhaps for you, Pisspot, but your father was the rear end of an aurochs, so you have a good excuse. }{\cs28\i Her}{ father is the Evenstar of Tarth.\'94 
\par The guards laughed, but the halberds parted. \'93Shouldn\rquote t we seize her, ser?\'94 the serjeant asked. \'93For killing Renly?\'94 
\par \'93Why? Renly was a rebel. So were we all, rebels to a man, but now we\rquote re Tommen\rquote s loyal lads.\'94 The knight waved the farm folk through the gate. \'93His lordship\rquote s steward will be pleased to see those eggs. You\rquote 
ll find him in the market.\'94 
\par The old man knuckled his forehead. \'93My thanks, m\rquote lord. You\rquote re a true knight, it\rquote s plain to see. Come, wife.\'94 They put their shoulders to the cart again and rumbled through the gate. 
\par Brienne trotted after them, with Podrick at her heels. }{\cs28\i A true knight,}{ she thought, frowning. Inside the town she reined up. The ruins of a
 stable could be seen off to her left, fronting on a muddy alley. Across from it three half-dressed whores stood on the balcony of a brothel, whispering to one another. One looked a bit like a camp follower who had once come up to Brienne to ask if she ha
d a cunt or a cock inside her breeches. 
\par \'93That rounsey may be the most hideous horse I\rquote ve ever seen,\'94 said Ser Hyle of Podrick\rquote s mount. \'93I am surprised that you\rquote re not riding it, my lady. Do you plan to thank me for my help?\'94 
\par Brienne swung down off her mare. She stood a head taller than Ser Hyle. \'93One day I\rquote ll thank you in a m\'eal\'e9e, ser.\'94 
\par \'93The way you thanked Red Ronnet?\'94 Hunt laughed. He had a full, rich laugh, though his face was plain. An honest face, she\rquote d thought once, before she learned better; shaggy
 brown hair, hazel eyes, a little scar by his left ear. His chin had a cleft and his nose was crooked, but he did laugh well, and often. 
\par \'93Shouldn\rquote t you be watching your gate?\'94 
\par He made a wry face at her. \'93My cousin Alyn is off hunting outlaws. Doubtless he\rquote ll return with the Hound\rquote s head, gloating and covered in glory. Meanwhile, I am condemned to guard this gate, thanks to you. I hope you\rquote 
re pleased, my beauty. What is it that you\rquote re looking for?\'94 
\par \'93A stable.\'94 
\par \'93Over by the east gate. This one burned.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I can see that.}{ \'93What you said to those men . . . I was with King Renly when he died, but it was some sorcery that slew him, ser. I swear it on my sword.\'94
 She put her hand upon her hilt, ready to fight if Hunt named her a liar to her face. 
\par \'93Aye, and it wa
s the Knight of Flowers who carved up the Rainbow Guard. On a good day you might have been able to defeat Ser Emmon. He was a rash fighter, and he tired easily. Royce, though? No. Ser Robar was twice the swordsman that you are . . . though you\rquote re }
{\cs28\i not}{ a swordsman, are you? Is there such a word as swordswench? What quest brings the Maid to Maidenpool, I wonder?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Searching for my sister, a maid of three-and-ten,}{ she almost said, but Ser Hyle would know she had no sisters. \'93There\rquote s a man I seek, at a place called the Stinking Goose.\'94 
\par \'93I thought Brienne the Beauty had no use for men.\'94 There was a cruel edge to his smile. \'93The Stinking Goose. An apt name, that . . . the stinking part, at least. It\rquote s by the harbor. First you will come with me to see his lordship.\'94 

\par Brienne did not fear Ser Hyle, but he was one of Randyll Tarly\rquote s captains. A whistle, and a hundred men would come running to defend him. \'93Am I to be arrested?\'94 
\par \'93What, for Renly? Who was he? We\rquote ve changed kings since then, some of us twice. No one cares, no one remembers.\'94 He laid a hand lightly on her arm. \'93This way, if you please.\'94 
\par She wrenched away. \'93I would thank you not to touch me.\'94 
\par \'93Thanks at last,\'94 he said, with a wry smile. 
\par When last she had seen Maidenpool, the town had been a desolation, a
 grim place of empty streets and burned homes. Now the streets were full of pigs and children, and most of the burned buildings had been pulled down. Vegetables had been planted in the lots where some once stood; merchant\rquote s tents and knight\rquote 
s pavilions too
k the place of others. Brienne saw new houses going up, a stone inn rising where a wooden inn had burned, a new slate roof on the town sept. The cool autumn air rang to the sounds of saw and hammer. Men carried timber through the streets, and quarrymen dr
ove their wagons down muddy lanes. Many wore the striding huntsman on their breasts. \'93The soldiers are rebuilding the town,\'94 she said, surprised. 
\par \'93They would sooner be dicing, drinking, and fucking, I don\rquote t doubt, but Lord Randyll believes in putting idle men to work.\'94 
\par She had expected to be taken to the castle. Instead, Hunt led them toward the busy harbor. The traders had returned to Maidenpool, she was pleased to see. A galley, a galleas, and a big two-masted cog were in port, along with a score of litt
le fishing boats. More fishermen were visible out on the bay. }{\cs28\i If the Stinking Goose yields nothing, I will take passage on a ship,}{
 she decided. Gulltown was only a short voyage away. From there she could make her way to the Eyrie easily enough. 
\par They found Lord Tarly in the fishmarket, doing justice. 
\par A platform had been thrown up beside the water, from which his lordship could look down upon the men accused of crimes. To his left stood a long gallows, with ropes enough for twenty men. Four corpses swung be
neath it. One looked fresh, but the other three had plainly been there for some time. A crow was pulling strips of flesh from the ripe ruins of one of the dead men. The other crows had scattered, wary of the crowd of townsfolk who\rquote 
d gathered in hopes of someone\rquote s being hanged. 
\par Lord Randyll shared the platform with Lord Mooton, a pale, soft, fleshy man in a white doublet and red breeches, his ermine cloak pinned at the shoulder by a red-gold brooch in the shape of a salmon. Tarly wore mail and boiled leathe
r, and a breastplate of grey steel. The hilt of a greatsword poked up above his left shoulder. }{\cs28\i Heartsbane,}{ it was named, the pride of his House. 
\par A stripling in a roughspun cloak and soiled jerkin was being heard when they came up. \'93I never hurt no one, m\rquote lord,\'94 Brienne heard him say. \'93I only took what the septons left when they run off. If you got to take my finger for that, do it.
\'94 
\par \'93It is customary to take a finger from a thief,\'94 Lord Tarly replied in a hard voice, \'93but a man who steals from a sept is stealing from the gods.\'94 He turned to his captain of guards. \'93Seven fingers. Leave his thumbs.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93Seven?\'94}{ The thief paled. When the guards seized hold of him he tried to fight, but feebly, as if he were already maimed. Watching him, Brienne could not help think of Ser Jaime, and the way he\rquote d screamed when Zollo\rquote s }{
\cs28\i arakh}{ came flashing down. 
\par The next man was a baker, accused of mixing sawdust in his flour. Lord Randyll fined him fifty silver stags. When the baker swore he did not have that much silver, his lord
ship declared that he could have a lash for every stag that he was short. He was followed by a haggard grey-faced whore, accused of giving the pox to four of Tarly\rquote s soldiers. \'93Wash out her private parts with lye and throw her in a dungeon,\'94
 Tarly commanded. As the whore was dragged off sobbing, his lordship saw Brienne on the edge of the crowd, standing between Podrick and Ser Hyle. He frowned at her, but his eyes betrayed not a flicker of recognition. 
\par A sailor off the galleas came next. His accuser was an archer of Lord Mooton\rquote s garrison, with a bandaged hand and a salmon on his breast. \'93If it please m\rquote 
lord, this bastid put his dagger through my hand. He said I was cheating him at dice.\'94 
\par Lord Tarly took his gaze away from Brienne to consider the men before him. \'93Were you?\'94 
\par \'93No, m\rquote lord. I never.\'94 
\par \'93For theft, I will take a finger. Lie to me and I will hang you. Shall I ask to see these dice?\'94 
\par \'93The dice?\'94 The archer looked to Mooton, but his lordship was gazing at the fishing boats. The bowman swallowed. \'93Might be I . . . them dice, they\rquote re lucky for me, \rquote s true, but I . . .\'94 
\par Tarly had heard enough. \'93Take his little finger. He can choose which hand. A nail through the palm for the other.\'94 He stood. \'93We\rquote re done. March the rest of them back to the dungeon, I\rquote ll deal with them on the morrow.\'94
 He turned to beckon Ser Hyle forward. Brienne followed. \'93My lord,\'94 she said, when she stood before him. She felt eight years old again. 
\par \'93My lady. To what do we owe this . . . honor?\'94 
\par \'93I have been sent to look for . . . for . . .\'94 She hesitated. 
\par \'93How will you find him if you do not know his name? Did you slay Lord Renly?\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 
\par Tarly weighed the word. }{\cs28\i He is judging me, as he judged those others.}{ \'93No,\'94 he said at last, \'93you only let him die.\'94 
\par He had died in her arms, his life\rquote s blood drenching her. Brienne flinched. \'93It was sorcery. I never . . .\'94 
\par \'93You }{\cs28\i never?}{\'94 His voice became a whip. \'93Aye. You never should have donned mail, nor buckled on a sword. You never should have left your father\rquote s hall
. This is a war, not a harvest ball. By all the gods, I ought to ship you back to Tarth.\'94 
\par \'93Do that and answer to the throne.\'94 Her voice sounded high and girlish, when she wanted to sound fearless. \'93Podrick. In my bag you\rquote ll find a parchment. Bring it to his lordship.\'94 
\par Tarly took the letter and unrolled it, scowling. His lips moved as he read. \'93The king\rquote s business. What sort of business?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Lie to me and I will hang you.}{ \'93S-sansa Stark.\'94 
\par \'93If the Stark girl were here, I\rquote d know it. She\rquote s run back north, I\rquote ll wager. Hoping to find refuge with one of her father\rquote s bannermen. She had best hope she chooses the right one.\'94 
\par \'93She might have gone to the Vale instead,\'94 Brienne heard herself blurt out, \'93to her mother\rquote s sister.\'94 
\par Lord Randyll gave her a contemptuous look. \'93
Lady Lysa is dead. Some singer pushed her off a mountain. Littlefinger holds the Eyrie now . . . though not for long. The lords of the Vale are not the sort to bend their knees to some upjumped jackanapes whose only skill is counting coppers.\'94 He hande
d her back her letter. \'93Go where you want and do as you will . . . but when you\rquote re raped don\rquote t look to me for justice. You will have earned it with your folly.\'94 He glanced at Ser Hyle. \'93
And you, ser, should be at your gate. I gave you the command there, did I not?\'94 
\par \'93You did, my lord,\'94 said Hyle Hunt, \'93but I thought\emdash \'94 
