\par \'93The boy needs a bit of seasoning, that\rquote s all,\'94 his father had told Lord Redwyne that night, but Redwyne\rquote s fool rattled his rattle and replied, \'93Aye, a pinch of pepper, a few nice cloves, and an apple in his mouth.\'94
 Thereafter, Lord Randyll forbade Sam to eat apples so long as they remained beneath Paxter Redwyne\rquote s roof. He had been seasick on their voyage ho
me as well, but so relieved to be going that he almost welcomed the taste of vomit at the back of his throat. It was not until they were back at Horn Hill that his mother told Sam that his father had never meant for him to return. \'93
Horas was to come with us in your place, whilst you remained on the Arbor as Lord Paxter\rquote s page and cupbearer. If you had pleased him, you would have been betrothed to his daughter.\'94 Sam could still recall the soft touch of his mother\rquote 
s hand as she washed the tears off his face with a bit of lace, dampened with her spit. \'93My poor Sam,\'94 she murmured. \'93My poor poor Sam.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i It will be good to see her again,}{ he thought, as he clung to }{\cs28\i Blackbird}{\rquote s rail and watched waves breaking on the stony shore. }{\cs28\i If she saw me in my blacks, it might even make her proud. \'93I am a man now, Mother,\'94
 I could tell her, \'93a steward, and a man of the Night\rquote s Watch. My brothers call me Sam the Slayer sometimes.\'94}{ He would see his brother Dickon too, and his sisters. }{\cs28\i \'93See,\'94 I could tell them, \'93see, I was good for 
something after all.\'94}{ 
\par If he went to Horn Hill, though, his father might be there. 
\par The thought made his belly heave again. Sam bent over the gunwale and retched, but not into the wind. He had gone to the right rail this time. He was getting good at retching. 
\par Or so he thought, until }{\cs28\i Blackbird}{ left the land behind and struck east across the bay for the shores of Skagos. 
\par The island sat at the mouth of the Bay of Seals, massive and mountainous, a stark and forbidding land peopled by savages. They lived in caves and grim mountain fastnesses, Sam had read, and rode great shaggy unicorns to war. }{\cs28\i Skagos}{ meant \'93
stone\'94 in the Old Tongue. The Skagosi named themselves the stoneborn, but their fellow northmen called them Skaggs and liked them little. Only a hundred ye
ars ago Skagos had risen in rebellion. Their revolt had taken years to quell and claimed the life of the Lord of Winterfell and hundreds of his sworn swords. Some songs said the Skaggs were cannibals; supposedly their warriors ate the hearts and livers of
 the men they slew. In ancient days, the Skagosi had sailed to the nearby isle of Skane, seized its women, slaughtered its men, and ate them on a pebbled beach in a feast that lasted for a fortnight. Skane remained unpeopled to this day. 
\par Dareon knew the songs as well. When the bleak grey peaks of Skagos rose up from the sea, he joined Sam at }{\cs28\i Blackbird}{\rquote s prow, and said, \'93If the gods are good, we may catch a glimpse of a unicorn.\'94 
\par \'93If the captain is good, we won\rquote t come that close. The currents are treacherous around Skagos, and there are rocks that can crack a ship\rquote s hull like an egg. But don\rquote t you mention that to Gilly. She\rquote s scared enough.\'94 

\par \'93Her and that squalling whelp of hers. I don\rquote t know which of them is noisier. The only time he ever stops crying is when she shoves a nipple in his mouth, and then }{\cs28\i she}{ starts to sob.\'94 
\par Sam had noticed that as well. \'93Maybe the babe is hurting her,\'94 he said, feebly. \'93If his teeth are coming in . . .\'94 
\par Dareon plucked at his lute with one finger, sending up a derisive note. \'93I\rquote d heard that wildlings were braver than that.\'94 
\par \'93She }{\cs28\i is}{ brave,\'94 Sam insisted, though even he had to admit that he had never seen Gilly in such a wretched state. Though she hid her face more oft than not and kept the cabin dark, he could see that her eye
s were always red, her cheeks wet with tears. When he asked her what was wrong, though, she only shook her head, leaving him to find answers of his own. \'93The sea scares her, that\rquote s all,\'94 he told Dareon. \'93
Before she came to the Wall, all she knew was Craster\rquote s Keep and the woods around it. I don\rquote 
t know that she went more than half a league from the place that she was born. She knows streams and rivers, but she had never seen a lake until we came on one, and the sea . . . the sea is a scary thing.\'94 
\par \'93We\rquote ve never been out of sight of land.\'94 
\par \'93We will be.\'94 Sam did not relish that part himself. 
\par \'93Surely a little water does not frighten the Slayer.\'94 
\par \'93No,\'94 Sam lied, \'93not me. But Gilly . . . maybe if you played some lullabies for them, it would help the babe to sleep.\'94 
\par Dareon\rquote s mouth twisted in disgust. \'93Only if she shoves a plug up his arse. I cannot abide the smell.\'94 
\par The next day the rains began, and the seas grew rougher. \'93We had best go below, where it\rquote s dry,\'94 Sam said to Aemon, but the old maester only smiled, and said, \'93
The rain feels good against my face, Sam. It feels like tears. Let me stay a while longer, I pray you. It has been a long time since last I wept.\'94 
\par If Maester Aemon meant to stay on deck, old and frail as he was, Sam had no choice but to do the same. He stayed beside the old man for nigh unto an hour, huddled in his cloak as a soft, steady rain soaked him to his skin. Aemon hardly seemed to feel it. 
He sighed and closed his eyes, and Sam moved closer to him, to shield him from the worst of the wind. }{\cs28\i He will ask me to help him to the cabin soon,}{ he told himself. }{\cs28\i He must.}{
 But he never did, and finally thunder began to rumble in the distance, off to the east. \'93We }{\cs28\i have}{ to get below,\'94 Sam said, shivering. Maester Aemon did not reply. It was only then that Sam realized the old man had gone to sleep. \'93
Maester,\'94 he said, shaking him gently by one shoulder. \'93Maester Aemon, wake up.\'94 
\par Aemon\rquote s blind white eyes came open. \'93Egg?\'94 he said, as the rain streamed down his cheeks. \'93Egg, I dreamed that I was old.\'94 
\par Sam did not know what to do. He knelt and scooped the old man up and carried him below. No one had ever called him strong, and the rain had soaked through Maester Aemon\rquote 
s blacks and made him twice as heavy, but even so, he weighed no more than a child. 
\par When he shoved into the cabin with Aemon in his arms, he found that Gilly had let all the candles gutter out. The babe was asleep and she was curled up in a corner, sobbing softly in the folds of the big black cloak that Sam had given her. \'93Help me,
\'94 he said urgently. \'93Help me dry him off and get him warm.\'94 
\par She rose at once, and together they got the old maester out of his wet clothes and buried him beneath a pile of furs. His skin was damp and cold, though, clammy to the touch. \'93You get in with him,\'94 Sam told Gilly. \'93
Hold him. Warm him with your body. We have to warm him up.\'94 She did that too, never saying a word, all the while still sniffling. \'93Where\rquote s Dareon?\'94 asked Sam. \'93We\rquote d all be warmer if we were together. He needs to be here too.\'94
 He was headed back up top to find the singer when the deck rose up beneath him, then fell away beneath his feet. Gilly wailed, Sam slammed down hard and lost his legs, and the babe woke screaming. 
\par The next roll of the ship came as he was struggling back to his feet. It threw Gilly into his arms, and the wildling girl clung to him so fiercely that Sam could hardly breathe. \'93Don\rquote t you be frightened,\'94 he told her. \'93This is just an ad
venture. One day you\rquote ll tell your son this tale.\'94 That only made her dig her nails into his arm. She shuddered, her whole body shaking with the violence of her sobs. }{\cs28\i Whatever I say just makes her worse.}{
 He held her tightly, uncomfortably aware of her breasts pressing up against him. As frightened as he was, somehow that was enough to make him stiff. }{\cs28\i She\rquote ll feel it,}{
 he thought, ashamed, but if she did, she gave no sign, only clung to him the harder. 
\par The days ran together after that. They never saw the sun. 
The days were grey and the nights black, except when lightning lit the sky above the peaks of Skagos. All of them were starved yet none could eat. The captain broached a cask of firewine to fortify the oarsmen. Sam tried a cup and sighed as hot snakes wri
ggled down his throat and through his chest. Dareon took a liking to the drink as well, and was seldom sober thereafter. 
\par The sails went up, the sails came down, and one ripped free of the mast and flew away like a great grey bird. As }{\cs28\i Blackbird}{ rounded the 
south coast of Skagos, they spotted the wreckage of a galley on the rocks. Some of her crew had washed up on the shore, and the rooks and crabs had gathered to pay them homage. \'93Too bloody close,\'94 grumbled Old Tattersalt when he saw. \'93
One good blow, and we\rquote ll be breaking up aside them.\'94
 Exhausted as they were, his rowers bent to their oars again, and the ship clawed south toward the narrow sea, till Skagos dwindled to no more than a few dark shapes in the sky that might have been thunderheads, or the tops o
f tall black mountains, or both. After that, they had eight days and seven nights of clear, smooth sailing. 
\par Then came more storms, worse than before. 
\par Was it three storms, or only one, broken up by lulls? Sam never knew, though he tried desperately to care. }{\cs28\i \'93What does it matter?\'94}{ Dareon screamed at him once, when all of them were huddled in the cabin. }{\cs28\i It doesn\rquote t,}{
 Sam wanted to tell him, }{\cs28\i but so long as I\rquote m thinking about that I\rquote m not thinking about drowning or being sick or Maester Aemon\rquote s shivering.}{ \'93It doesn\rquote t,\'94
 he managed to squeak, but the thunder drowned out all the rest of it, and the deck lurched and knocked him sideways. Gilly was sobbing. The babe was shrieking. And up top he could hear Old Tattersalt bellowing at his crew, the ragged captain who ne
ver spoke at all. 
\par }{\cs28\i I hate the sea,}{ Sam thought, }{\cs28\i I hate the sea, I hate the sea, I hate the sea.}{ The next lightning flash was so bright it lit the cabin through the seams in the planking overhead. }{\cs28\i 
This is a good sound ship, a good sound ship, a good ship,}{ he told himself. }{\cs28\i It will not sink. I am not afraid.}{ 
\par During one of the lulls between the gales, as Sam clung white-knuckled to the rail wanting desperately to retch, he heard some of the crew muttering that this was what came of bringing a woman aboard ship, and a wildling woman at that. \'93
Fucked her own father,\'94 Sam heard one man say, as the wind was rising once again. \'93Worse than whoring, that. Worse than }{\cs28\i anything.}{ We\rquote ll all drown unless we get rid of her, and that abomination that she whelped.\'94 
\par Sam dared not confront them. They were older men, hard and sinewy, their arms and shoulders thickened by years at the oars. But he made certain that his knife was sharp, and whenever Gilly left the cabin to make water, he went with her. 
\par Even Dareon had no good to say about the wildling girl. Once, at Sam\rquote s urging, the singer played a lullaby to soothe the babe, but partway through the first verse Gilly began to sob inconsolably. \'93Seven bloody hells,\'94 Dareon snapped, \'93can
\rquote t you even stop weeping long enough to hear a }{\cs28\i song}{?\'94 
\par \'93Just play,\'94 Sam pleaded, \'93just sing the song for her.\'94 
\par \'93She doesn\rquote t need a song,\'94 said Dareon. \'93She needs a good spanking, or maybe a hard fuck. Get out of my way, Slayer.\'94 He shoved Sam aside and went from the cabin to find some solace in a c
up of firewine and the rough brotherhood of the oars. 
\par Sam was at his wit\rquote s end by then. He had almost gotten used to the smells, but between the storms and Gilly\rquote s sobbing he had not slept for days. \'93Isn\rquote t there something you can give her?\'94 he asked Maest
er Aemon very softly, when he saw that the old man was awake. \'93Some herb or potion, so she won\rquote t be so afraid?\'94 
\par \'93It is not fear you hear,\'94 the old man told him. \'93That is the sound of grief, and there is no potion for that. Let her tears run their course, Sam. You cannot stem the flow.\'94 
\par Sam had not understood. \'93She\rquote s going to a safe place. A }{\cs28\i warm}{ place. Why should she be grieving?\'94 
\par \'93Sam,\'94 the old man whispered, \'93you have two good eyes, and yet you do not see. She is a mother grieving for her child.\'94 
\par \'93He\rquote s greensick, that\rquote s all. We\rquote re all greensick. Once we make port in Braavos . . .\'94 
\par \'93. . . the babe will still be Dalla\rquote s son, and not the child of her body.\'94 
\par It took Sam a moment to grasp what Aemon was suggesting. \'93That couldn\rquote t . . . she wouldn\rquote t . . . of course he\rquote s hers. Gilly would never have left the Wall without her }{\cs28\i son}{. She loves him.\'94 
\par \'93She nursed them both and loved them both,\'94 said Aemon, \'93but not alike. No mother loves all her children the same, not even the Mother Above. Gilly did not leave th
e child willingly, I am certain. What threats the Lord Commander made, what promises, I can only guess . . . but threats and promises there surely were.\'94 
\par \'93No. No, that\rquote s wrong. Jon would never . . .\'94 
\par \'93Jon would never. Lord Snow did. Sometimes there is no happy choice, Sam, only one less grievous than the others.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i No happy choice.}{ Sam thought of all the trials that he and Gilly suffered, Craster\rquote s Keep and the death of the Old Bear, snow and ice and freezing winds, days and days and days of walking, the w
ights at Whitetree, Coldhands and the tree of ravens, the Wall, the Wall, the Wall, the Black Gate beneath the earth. What had it all been for? }{\cs28\i No happy choices and no happy endings. }{
\par He wanted to scream. He wanted to howl and sob and shake and curl up in a little ball and whimper. }{\cs28\i He switched the babes,}{ he told himself. }{\cs28\i He switched the babes to protect the little prince, to keep him away from Lady Melisandre
\rquote s fires, away from her red god. If she burns Gilly\rquote s boy, who will care? No one but Gilly. He was only Craster\rquote s whelp, an abomination born of incest, not the son of the King-beyond-the-Wall. He\rquote 
s no good for a hostage, no good for a sacrifice, no good for anything, he doesn\rquote t even have a name.}{ 
\par Wordless, Sam staggered up onto the deck to retch, but the
re was nothing in his belly to bring up. Night had come upon them, a strange still night such as they had not seen for many days. The sea was black as glass. At the oars, the rowers rested. One or two were sleeping where they sat. The wind was in the sail
s, and to the north Sam could even see a scattering of stars, and the red wanderer the free folk called the Thief. }{\cs28\i That ought to be my star,}{ Sam thought miserably. }{\cs28\i 
I helped to make Jon Lord Commander, and I brought him Gilly and the babe. There are no happy endings.}{ 
\par \'93Slayer.\'94 Dareon appeared beside him, oblivious to Sam\rquote s pain. \'93A sweet night, for once. Look, the stars are coming out. We might even get a bit of moon. Might be the worst is done.\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 Sam wiped his nose, and pointed south with a fat finger, toward the gathering darkness. \'93There,\'94
 he said. No sooner had he spoken than lightning flashed, sudden and silent and blinding bright. The distant clouds glowed for half a heartbeat, mountains heaped on mountains, purple and red and yellow, taller than the world. \'93The worst isn\rquote 
t done. The worst is just beginning, and there are no happy endings.\'94 
\par \'93Gods be good,\'94 said Dareon, laughing. \'93Slayer, you are }{\cs28\i such}{ a craven.\'94
