\par JAIME
\par Lord Tywin Lannister had entered the city on a stallion, his enameled crimson armor polished and gleaming, bright with gems and goldwork. He left it in a tall wagon draped with crimson banners, with six silent sisters riding attendance on his bones. 

\par The funeral procession departed King\rquote s Landing through the Gate of the Gods, wider and more splendid than the Lion Gate. The choice felt wrong to Jaime. His father had been a lion, that no one could den
y, but even Lord Tywin never claimed to be a god. 
\par An honor guard of fifty knights surrounded Lord Tywin\rquote s wagon, crimson pennons fluttering from their lances. The lords of the west followed close behind them. The winds snapped at their banners, making the
ir charges dance and flutter. As he trotted up the column, Jaime passed boars, badgers, and beetles, a green arrow and a red ox, crossed halberds, crossed spears, a treecat, a strawberry, a maunch, four sunbursts counterchanged. 
\par Lord Brax was wearing a pale grey doublet slashed with cloth-of-silver, an amethyst unicorn pinned above his heart. Lord Jast was armored in black steel, three gold lion\rquote 
s heads inlaid on his breastplate. The rumors of his death had not been far wrong, to look at him; wounds and imprisonment had left him a shadow of the man he\rquote 
d been. Lord Banefort had weathered battle better, and looked ready to return to war at once. Plumm wore purple, Prester ermine, Moreland russet and green, but each had donned a cloak of crimson silk, in honor of the man they were escorting home. 
\par Behind the lords came a hundred crossbowmen and three hundred men-at-arms, and crimson flowed from their shoulders as well. In his white cloak and white scale armor, Jaime felt out of place amongst that river of red. 
\par Nor did his uncle make him more at ease. \'93Lord Commander,\'94 Ser Kevan said, when Jaime trotted up beside him at the head of the column. \'93Does Her Grace have some last command for me?\'94 
\par \'93I am not here for Cersei.\'94 A drum began to beat behind them, slow, measured, funereal. }{\cs28\i Dead,}{ it seemed to say, }{\cs28\i dead, dead.}{ \'93I came to make my farewells. He was my father.\'94 
\par \'93And hers.\'94 
\par \'93I am not Cersei. I have a beard, and she has breasts. If you are still confused, nuncle, count our hands. Cersei has two.\'94 
\par \'93Both of you have a taste for mockery,\'94 his uncle said. \'93Spare me your japes, ser, I have no taste for them.\'94 
\par \'93As you will.\'94 }{\cs28\i This is not going as well as I might have hoped.}{ \'93Cersei would have wanted to see you off, but she has many pressing duties.\'94 
\par Ser Kevan snorted. \'93So do we all. How fares your king?\'94 His tone made the question a reproach. 
\par \'93Well enough,\'94 Jaime said defensively. \'93Balon Swann is with him during the mornings. A good and valiant knight.\'94 
\par \'93Once that went without saying when men spoke of those who wore the white cloak.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i No man can choose his brothers,}{ Jaime thought. }{\cs28\i Give me leave to pick my own men, and the Kingsguard will be great again.}{ Put that baldly, though, it sounded feeble; an empty boast from a man the realm called Kingslayer. }{\cs28\i 
A man with shit for honor.}{ Jaime let it go. He had not come to argue with his uncle. \'93Ser,\'94 he said, \'93you need to make your peace with Cersei.\'94 
\par \'93Are we at war? No one told me.\'94 
\par Jaime ignored that. \'93Strife between Lannister and Lannister can only help the enemies of our House.\'94 
\par \'93If there is strife, it will not be my doing. Cersei wants to rule. Well and good. The realm is hers. All I ask is to be left in peace. My place is at Darry with my son. The castle must needs be restored, the lands planted and protected.\'94 He gave a
 bark of bitter laughter. \'93And your sister has left me little else to occupy my time. I had as well see Lancel wed. His bride has grown impatient waiting for us to make our way to Darry.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i His widow from the Twins.}{ His cousin Lancel was riding ten yards behind them. With his hollow eyes and dry white hair, he looked older than Lord Jast. Jaime could feel his phantom fingers itching at the sight of him. }{\cs28\i 
. . . fucking Lancel and Osmund Kettleblack and Moon Boy for all I know . . . }{He had tried to speak with Lancel more times than he could count, but never found him alone. If his father was not with him, some septon was. }{\cs28\i He may be Kevan\rquote 
s son, but he has milk in his veins. Tyrion was lying to me. His words were meant to wound.}{ 
\par Jaime put his cousin from his thoughts and turned back to his uncle. \'93Will you remain at Darry after the wedding?\'94 
\par \'93For a while, mayhaps. Sandor Clegane is raiding along the Trident, it would seem. Your sister wants his head. It may be that he has joined Dondarrion.\'94 
\par Jaime had heard about Saltpans. By now half the realm had heard. The raid had been exceptionally savage. Women raped and mutilated, children butchered in their mothers\rquote  arms, half the town put to the torch. \'93
Randyll Tarly is at Maidenpool. Let him deal with the outlaws. I would sooner have you go to Riverrun.\'94 
\par \'93Ser Daven has command there. The Warden of the West. He has no need of me. Lancel does.\'94 
\par \'93As you say, uncle.\'94 Jaime\rquote s head was pounding to the same beat as the drum. }{\cs28\i Dead, dead, dead.}{ \'93You would do well to keep your knights around you.\'94 
\par His uncle gave him a cool stare. \'93Is that a threat, ser?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i A threat?}{ The suggestion took him aback. \'93A caution. I only meant . . . Sandor is dangerous.\'94 
\par \'93I was hanging outlaws and robber knights when you were still shitting in your swaddling clothes. I am not like to go off and face Clegane and Dondarrion by myself, if that is what you fear, ser. Not every Lannister is a fool for glory.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Why, nuncle, I believe you are talking about me.}{ \'93Addam Marbrand could deal with these outlaws just as well as you. So could Brax, Banefort, Plumm, any of these others. But none would make a good King\rquote s Hand.\'94 
\par \'93Your sister knows my terms. They have not changed. Tell her that, the next time you are in her bedchamber.\'94 Ser Kevan put his heels into his courser and galloped ahead, putting an abrupt end to their conversation. 
\par Jaime let him go, his missing sword hand twitching. He had hoped against hope that Cersei had somehow misunderstood, but plainly that was wrong. }{\cs28\i He knows about the two of us. About Tommen and Myrcella. And Cersei knows he knows.}{
 Ser Kevan was a Lannister of Casterly Rock. He could not believe that she would ever do him harm, but . . . }{\cs28\i I was wrong about Tyrion, why not about Cersei?}{ When sons were killing
 fathers, what was there to stop a niece from ordering an uncle slain? }{\cs28\i An inconvenient uncle, who knows too much.}{
 Though perhaps Cersei was hoping that the Hound might do her work for her. If Sandor Clegane cut down Ser Kevan, she would not need to bloody her own hands. }{\cs28\i And he will, if they should meet.}{
 Kevan Lannister had once been a stout man with a sword, but he was no longer young, and the Hound . . . 
\par The column had caught up to him. As his cousin rode past, flanked by his two septons, Jaime called out to him. \'93Lancel. Coz. I wanted to congratulate you upon your marriage. I only regret that my duties do not permit me to attend.\'94 
\par \'93His Grace must be protected.\'94 
\par \'93And will be. Still, I hate to miss your bedding. It is your first marriage and her second, I understand. I\rquote m sure my lady will be pleased to show you what goes where.\'94 
\par The bawdy remark drew a laugh from several nearby lords and a disapproving look from Lancel\rquote s septons. His cousin squirmed uncomfortably in the saddle. \'93I know enough to do my duty as a husband, ser.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s just the thing a bride wants on her wedding night,\'94 said Jaime. \'93A husband who knows how to do his }{\cs28\i duty.}{\'94 
\par A flush crept up Lancel\rquote s cheeks. \'93I pray for you, cousin. And for Her Grace the queen. May the Crone lead her to her wisdom and the Warrior defend her.\'94 
\par \'93Why would Cersei need the Warrior? She has me.\'94 Jaime turned his horse about, his white cloak snapping in the wind. }{\cs28\i The Imp was lying. Cersei would sooner have Robert\rquote s corpse between her legs than a pious fool like La
ncel. Tyrion, you evil bastard, you should have lied about someone more likely.}{ He galloped past his lord father\rquote s funeral wayn toward the city in the distance. 
\par The streets of King\rquote s Landing seemed almost deserted as Jaime Lannister made his way back to the Red Keep atop Aegon\rquote s High Hill. The soldiers who had crowded the city\rquote 
s gambling dens and pot shops were largely gone now. Garlan the Gallant had taken half the Tyrell strength back to Highgarden, and his lady mother and grandmother had gone with him. 
The other half had marched south with Mace Tyrell and Mathis Rowan to invest Storm\rquote s End. 
\par As for the Lannister host, two thousand seasoned veterans remained encamped outside the city walls, awaiting the arrival of Paxter Redwyne\rquote s fleet to carry them acro
ss Blackwater Bay to Dragonstone. Lord Stannis appeared to have left only a small garrison behind him when he sailed north, so two thousand men would be more than sufficient, Cersei had judged. 
\par The rest of the westermen had gone back to their wives and ch
ildren, to rebuild their homes, plant their fields, and bring in one last harvest. Cersei had taken Tommen round their camps before they marched, to let them cheer their little king. She had never looked more beautiful than she did that day, with a smile 
on her lips and the autumn sunlight shining on her golden hair. Whatever else one might say about his sister, she did know how to make men love her when she cared enough to try. 
\par As Jaime trotted through the castle gates, he came upon two dozen knights riding at a quintain in the outer yard. }{\cs28\i Something else I can no longer do,}{
 he thought. A lance was heavier and more cumbersome than a sword, and swords were proving trial enough. He supposed he might try holding the lance with his left hand, but that would mean shifting his shield to his right arm. In a tilt, a man\rquote 
s foe was always to the left. A shield on his right arm would prove about as useful as nipples on his breastplate. }{\cs28\i No, my jousting days are done,}{ he thought as he dismounted . . . but all the same, he stopped to watch a while. 
\par Ser Tallad the Tall lost his mount when the sandbag came around and thumped him in the head. Strongboar struck the shield so hard he cracked it. Kennos of Kayce finished the destruction. A new shield was hung for Ser Dermot of 
the Rainwood. Lambert Turnberry only struck a glancing blow, but Beardless Jon Bettley, Humfrey Swyft, and Alyn Stackspear all scored solid hits, and Red Ronnet Connington broke his lance clean. Then the Knight of Flowers mounted up and put the others all
 to shame. 
\par Jousting was three-quarters horsemanship, Jaime had always believed. Ser Loras rode superbly, and handled a lance as if he\rquote d been born holding one . . . which no doubt accounted for his mother\rquote s pinched expression. }{\cs28\i 
He puts the point just where he means to put it, and seems to have the balance of a cat. Perhaps it was not such a fluke that he unhorsed me.}{ It was a shame that he would never have the chance to try the boy again. He left the whole men to their sport. 

\par Cersei was in her solar in Maegor\rquote s Holdfast, with Tommen and Lord Merryweather\rquote s dark-haired Myrish wife. The three of them were laughing at Grand Maester Pycelle. \'93Did I miss some clever jape?\'94
 Jaime said, as he shoved through the door. 
\par \'93Oh, look,\'94 purred Lady Merryweather, \'93your brave brother has returned, Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93Most of him.\'94 The queen was in her cups, Jaime realized. Of late, Cersei always seemed to have a flagon of wine to hand, she who had once scorned Robert Baratheon for his drinking. He misliked that, but these days he 
seemed to mislike everything his sister did. \'93Grand Maester,\'94 she said, \'93share the tidings with the Lord Commander, if you would.\'94 
\par Pycelle looked desperately uncomfortable. \'93There has been a bird,\'94 he said. \'93From Stokeworth. Lady Tanda sends word that her daughter Lollys has been delivered of a strong, healthy son.\'94 
