\par \'93You are, ser.\'94 She kissed him, and let him have a little taste of tongue before she broke away. \'93Enough for now. The rest must wait. Will you dream of me tonight?\'94 
\par \'93Aye.\'94 His voice was hoarse. 
\par \'93And when you\rquote re abed with our Maid Margaery?\'94 she asked him, teasing. \'93When you\rquote re in her, will you dream of me then?\'94 
\par \'93I will,\'94 swore Osney Kettleblack. 
\par \'93Good.\'94 
\par After he was gone, Cersei summoned Jocelyn to brush her hair out whilst she slipped off her shoes and stretched like a cat. }{\cs28\i I was made for this,}{
 she told herself. It was the sheer elegance of it that pleased her most. Even Mace Tyrell would not dare defend his darling daughter if she was caught in the act with the likes of Osney Kettleblack, and neither Stannis Baratheon nor Jon Snow would have c
ause to wonder why Osney was being sent to the Wall. She would see to it that Ser Osmund was the one to discover his brother with the little queen; that way the loyalty of the other two Kettleblacks need not be impugned. }{\cs28\i 
If Father could only see me now, he would not be so quick to speak of marrying me off again. A pity he\rquote s so dead. Him and Robert, Jon Arryn, Ned Stark, Renly Baratheon, all dead. Only Tyrion remains, and not for long. }{
\par That night the queen summoned Lady Merryweather to her bedchamber. \'93Will you take a cup of wine?\'94 she asked her. 
\par \'93A small one.\'94 The Myrish woman laughed. \'93A big one.\'94 
\par \'93On the morrow I want you to pay a call on my good-daughter,\'94 Cersei said as Dorcas was dressing her for bed. 
\par \'93Lady Margaery is always happy to see me.\'94 
\par \'93I know.\'94 The queen did not fail to note the style that Taena used when referring to Tommen\rquote s little wife. \'93Tell her I\rquote ve sent seven beeswax candles to the Baelor\rquote s Sept in memory of our dear High Septon.\'94 
\par Taena laughed. \'93If so, she will send seven-and-seventy candles of her own, so as not to be outmourned.\'94 
\par \'93I will be very cross if she does not,\'94 the queen said, smiling. \'93Tell her also that she has a secret admirer, a knight so smitten with her beauty that he cannot sleep at night.\'94 
\par \'93Might I ask Your Grace which knight?\'94 Mischief sparkled in Taena\rquote s big dark eyes. \'93Could it be Ser Osney?\'94 
\par \'93It could be,\'94 the queen said, \'93but do not offer up that name freely. Make her worm it out of you. Will you do that?\'94 
\par \'93If it please you. That is all I wish, Your Grace.\'94 
\par Outside a cold wind was rising. They stayed up late into the morning, drinking Arbor gold and telling one another tales. Taena got quite drunk and Cersei pried the name of her secret lover from her. He was a Myrish sea captain, half a pirate, with black h
air to the shoulders and a scar that ran across his face from chin to ear. \'93A hundred times I told him no, and he said yes,\'94 the other woman told her, \'93until finally I was saying yes as well. He was not the sort of man to be denied.\'94 
\par \'93I know the sort,\'94 the queen said with a wry smile. 
\par \'93Has Your Grace ever known a man like that, I wonder?\'94 
\par \'93Robert,\'94 she lied, thinking of Jaime. 
\par Yet when she closed her eyes, it was the other brother that she dreamt of, and the three wretched fools with whom she had begun her day. In the dream it was Tyrion\rquote 
s head they brought her in their sack. She had it bronzed, and kept it in her chamber pot.
