\par BRIENNE
\par East of Maidenpool the hills rose wild, and the pines closed in about them like a host of silent grey-green soldiers. 
\par Nimble Dick said the coast road was the shortest way, and the easiest, so they were seldom out of sight of the bay. The towns and villages along t
he shore grew smaller as they went, and less frequent. At nightfall they would seek an inn. Crabb would share the common bed with other travelers, whilst Brienne took a room for her and Podrick. \'93Cheaper if we all shared the same bed, m\rquote lady,
\'94 Nimble Dick would say. \'93You could lay your sword between us. Old Dick\rquote s a harmless fellow. Chivalrous as a knight, and honest as the day is long.\'94 
\par \'93The days are growing shorter,\'94 Brienne pointed out. 
\par \'93Well, that may be. If you don\rquote t trust me in the bed, I could just curl up on the floor, m\rquote lady.\'94 
\par \'93Not on my floor.\'94 
\par \'93A man might think you don\rquote t trust me none.\'94 
\par \'93Trust is earned. Like gold.\'94 
\par \'93As you say, m\rquote lady,\'94 said Crabb, \'93but up north where the road gives out, you\rquote ll need t\rquote  trust Dick then. If I wanted t\rquote  take your gold at swordpoint, who\rquote s to stop me?\'94 
\par \'93You don\rquote t own a sword. I do.\'94 
\par She shut the door between them and stood there listening until she was certain he had moved away. However nimble he might be, Dick Crabb was no Jaime Lannister, no Mad Mouse,
 not even a Humfrey Wagstaff. He was scrawny and ill fed, his only armor a dinted halfhelm spotted with rust. In place of a sword, he carried an old, nicked dagger. So long as she was awake, he posed no danger to her. \'93Podrick,\'94 she said, \'93
there will come a time when there are no more inns to shelter us. I do not trust our guide. When we make camp, can you watch over me as I sleep?\'94 
\par \'93Stay awake, my lady? Ser.\'94 He thought. \'93I have a sword. If Crabb tries to hurt you, I could kill him.\'94 
\par \'93No,\'94 she said sternly. \'93You are not to try and fight him. All I ask is that you watch him as I sleep, and wake me if he does anything suspicious. I wake quickly, you will find.\'94 
\par Crabb showed his true colors the next day, when they stopped to water the horses. Brienne had to step behind some bushes to empty her bladder. As she was squatting, she heard Podrick say, \'93What are you doing? You get away from there.\'94
 She finished her business, hiked up her breeches, and returned to the road to find Nimble Dick wiping flour off his fingers. \'93You won\rquote t find any dragons in my saddlebags,\'94 she told him. \'93I keep my gold upon my person.\'94
 Some of it was in the pouch at her belt, the rest hidden in a pair of pockets sewn inside her clothing. The fat purse inside her saddlebag was filled with
 coppers large and small, pennies and halfpennies, groats and stars . . . and fine white flour, to make it fatter still. She had bought the flour from the cook at the Seven Swords the morning she rode out from Duskendale. 
\par \'93Dick meant no harm, m\rquote lady.\'94 He wriggled his flour-spotted fingers to show he held no weapon. \'93I was only looking to see if you had these dragons what you promised me. The world\rquote s full o\rquote 
 liars, ready to cheat an honest man. Not that }{\cs28\i you\rquote re}{ one.\'94 
\par Brienne hoped he was a better guide than he was a thief. \'93We had best be going.\'94 She mounted up again. 
\par Dick would oft sing as they rode along together; never a whole song, only a snatch of this and a verse of that. She suspected that he meant to charm her, to put her off her guard. Sometimes he
 would try to get her and Podrick to sing along with him, to no avail. The boy was too shy and tongue-tied, and Brienne did not sing. }{\cs28\i Did you sing for your father?}{ Lady Stark had asked her once, at Riverrun. }{\cs28\i Did you sing for Renly?}{
 She had not, not ever, though she had wanted . . . she had wanted . . . 
\par When he was not singing, Nimble Dick would talk, regaling them with tales of Crackclaw Point. Every gloomy valley had its lord, he said, the lot of them united only by their mistrust of outsiders. In their v
eins the blood of the First Men ran dark and strong. \'93The Andals tried t\rquote  take Crackclaw, but we bled them in the valleys and drowned them in the bogs. Only what their sons couldn\rquote 
t win with swords, their pretty daughters won with kisses. They married into the houses they couldn\rquote t conquer, aye.\'94 
\par The Darklyn kings of Duskendale had tried to impose their rule on Crackclaw Point; the Mootons of Maidenpool had tried as well, and later the haughty Celtigars of Crab Isle. But the Crackclaws knew their bogs and f
orests as no outsider could, and if hard pressed would vanish into the caverns that honeycombed their hills. When not fighting would-be conquerors, they fought each other. Their blood feuds were as deep and dark as the bogs between their hills. From time 
t
o time some champion would bring peace to the Point, but it never lasted longer than his lifetime. Lord Lucifer Hardy, he was a great one, and the Brothers Brune as well. Old Crackbones even more so, but the Crabbs were the mightiest of all. Dick still re
fused to believe that Brienne had never heard of Ser Clarence Crabb and his exploits. 
\par \'93Why would I lie?\'94 she asked him. \'93Every place has its local heroes. Where I come from, the singers sing of Ser Galladon of Morne, the Perfect Knight.\'94 
\par \'93Ser Gallawho of What?\'94 He snorted. \'93Never heard o\rquote  him. Why was he so bloody perfect?\'94 
\par \'93Ser Galladon was a champion of such valor that the Maiden herself lost her heart to him. She gave him an enchanted sword as a token of her love. The Just Maid, it was called. No commo
n sword could check her, nor any shield withstand her kiss. Ser Galladon bore the Just Maid proudly, but only thrice did he unsheathe her. He would not use the Maid against a mortal man, for she was so potent as to make any fight unfair.\'94 
\par Crabb thought that was hilarious. \'93The Perfect Knight? The Perfect Fool, he sounds like. What\rquote s the point o\rquote  having some magic sword if you don\rquote t bloody well use it?\'94 
\par \'93Honor,\'94 she said. \'93The point is honor.\'94 
\par That only made him laugh the louder. \'93Ser Clarence Crabb would have wiped his hairy arse with your Perfect Knight, m\rquote lady. If they\rquote d ever have met, there\rquote d be one more bloody head sitting on the shelf at the Whispers, you ask me. 
\lquote I should have used the magic sword,\rquote  it\rquote d be saying to all the other heads. \lquote I should have used the bloody sword.\rquote \'94 
\par Brienne could not help but smile. \'93Perhaps,\'94 she allowed, \'93but Ser Galladon was no fool. Against a foe eight feet tall mounted on an aurochs, he might well have unsheathed the Just Maid. He used her once to slay a dragon, they say.\'94 
\par Nimble Dick was unimpressed. \'93Crackbones fought a dragon too, but he didn\rquote t need no magic sword. He just tied its neck in a knot, so every time it breathed fire it roasted its own arse.\'94 
\par \'93And what did Crackbones do when Aegon and his sisters came?\'94 Brienne asked him. 
\par \'93He was dead. M\rquote lady must know that.\'94 Crabb gave her a sideways look. \'93Aegon sent his sister up to Crackclaw, that Visenya. The lords had heard o\rquote  Harren\rquote 
s end. Being no fools, they laid their swords at her feet. The queen took them as her own men, and said they\rquote d owe no fealty to Maidenpool, Crab Isle, or Duskendale. Don\rquote t stop them bloody Celtigars from sending men to t\rquote 
 eastern shore to collect his taxes. If he sends enough, a few come back to him . . . elsewise, we bow only to our own lords, and the king. The }{\cs28\i true}{ king, not Robert and his ilk.\'94 He spat. \'93
There was Crabbs and Brunes and Boggses with Prince Rhaegar on the Trident, and in the Kingsguard too. A Hardy, a Cave, a Pyne, and }{\cs28\i three}{ Crabbs, Clement and Rupert and Clarence the Short. Six foot tall, he was, but short compared to the }{
\cs28\i real}{ Ser Clarence. We\rquote re all good dragon men, up Crackclaw way.\'94 
\par The traffic continued to dwindle as they moved north and east, until finally there were n
o inns to be found. By then the bayside road was more weeds than ruts. That night they took shelter in a fishing village. Brienne paid the villagers a few coppers to allow them to bed down in a hay barn. She claimed the loft for Podrick and herself, and p
ulled the ladder up after them. 
\par \'93You leave me down here alone, I could bloody well steal your horses,\'94 Crabb called up from below. \'93Best you get them up the ladder too, m\rquote lady.\'94 When she ignored him, he went on to say, \'93It\rquote s going to rain tonight. A cold h
ard rain. You and Pods will sleep all snug and warm, and poor old Dick will be shivering down here by myself.\'94 He shook his head, muttering, as he made a bed on a pile of hay. \'93I never knew such a mistrustful maid as you.\'94 
\par Brienne curled up beneath her cloak, with Podrick yawning at her side. }{\cs28\i I was not always wary,}{ she might have shouted down at Crabb. }{\cs28\i When I was a little girl I believed that all men were as noble as my father.}{
 Even the men who told her what a pretty girl she was, how tall and bright and clever, how graceful when she danced. It was Septa Roelle who had lifted the scales from her eyes. \'93They only say those things to win your lord father\rquote s favor,\'94
 the woman had said. \'93You\rquote ll find truth in your looking glass, not on the tongues of men.\'94 It was a harsh lesson, one that left her weeping, but it had stood her in good stead at Harrenhal when Ser Hyle and his friends had played their game. 
}{\cs28\i A maid has to be mistrustful in this world, or she will not be a maid for long,}{ she was thinking, as the rain began to fall. 
\par In the m\'eal\'e9e at Bitterbridge she had sought out her suitors and battered them one by one, Farrow and Ambrose and Bushy, Mark Mullendore and Raymond Nayland and Will the Stork. She had ridden over Harry Sawyer and broken Robin Potter\rquote s helm, 
giving him a nasty scar. And when the last of them had fallen, the Mother had delivered Connington to her. This time Ser Ronnet held a sword and not a rose. Every blow she dealt him was sweeter than a kiss. 
\par Loras Tyrell had been the last to face her wroth that day. He\rquote 
d never courted her, had hardly looked at her at all, but he bore three golden roses on his shield that day, and Brienne hated roses. The sight of them had given her a furious strength. She went to sleep dreaming of the fight they\rquote d had, and 
of Ser Jaime fastening a rainbow cloak about her shoulders. 
\par It was still raining the next morning. As they broke their fast, Nimble Dick suggested that they wait for it to stop. 
\par \'93When will that be? On the morrow? In a fortnight? When summer comes again? No. We have cloaks, and leagues to ride.\'94 
\par It rained all that day. The narrow track they followed soon turned to mud beneath them. What trees they saw were naked, and the steady rain had turned their fallen leaves into a sodden brown mat. Despite its squirrel-skin lining, Dick\rquote 
s cloak soaked through, and she could see him shivering. Brienne felt a moment\rquote s pity for the man. }{\cs28\i He has not eaten well, that\rquote s plain.}{ She wondered if there truly was a smugglers\rquote 
 cove, or a ruined castle called the Whispers. Hungry men do desperate things. This all might be some ploy to cozen her. Suspicion soured her stomach. 
\par For a time it seemed as though the steady wash of rain was the only sound in the wo
rld. Nimble Dick plowed on, heedless. She watched closely, noting how he bent his back, as if huddling low in the saddle would keep him dry. This time there was no village close at hand when darkness came upon them. Nor were there any trees to give them s
helter. They were forced to camp amongst some rocks, fifty yards above the tideline. The rocks at least would keep the wind off. \'93Best we keep a watch tonight, m\rquote lady,\'94 Crabb told her, as she was struggling to get a driftwood fire lit. \'93
A place like this, there might be squishers.\'94 
\par \'93Squishers?\'94 Brienne gave him a suspicious look. 
\par \'93Monsters,\'94 Nimble Dick said, with relish. \'93They look like men till you get close, but their heads is too big, and they got scales where a proper man\rquote s got hair. Fish-belly white they are, with webs between their fingers. They\rquote 
re always damp and fishy-smelling, but behind these blubbery lips they got rows of green teeth sharp as needles. Some say the First Men killed them all, but don\rquote t you believe it. They come by night and steal 
bad little children, padding along on them webbed feet with a little }{\cs28\i squish-squish}{ sound. The girls they keep to breed with, but the boys they eat, tearing at them with those sharp green teeth.\'94 He grinned at Podrick. \'93They\rquote 
d eat you, boy. They\rquote d eat you }{\cs28\i raw.}{\'94 
\par \'93If they try, I\rquote ll kill them.\'94 Podrick touched his sword. 
\par \'93You try that. You just try. Squishers don\rquote t die easy.\'94 He winked at Brienne. \'93You a bad little girl, m\rquote lady?\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 }{\cs28\i Just a fool.}{ The wood was too damp to light, no matter how many sparks Br
ienne struck off her flint and steel. The kindling sent up some smoke, but that was all. Disgusted, she settled down with her back to a rock, pulled her cloak over herself, and resigned herself to a cold, wet night. Dreaming of a hot meal, she gnawed on a
 strip of hard salt beef whilst Nimble Dick talked about the time Ser Clarence Crabb had fought the squisher king. }{\cs28\i He tells a lively tale,}{ she had to admit, }{\cs28\i but Mark Mullendore was amusing too, with his little monkey.}{ 
\par It was too wet to see the sun go down, too grey to see the moon come up. The night was black and starless. Crabb ran out of tales and went to sleep. Podrick was soon snoring too. Brienne sat with her back to the rock, listening to the waves. }{\cs28\i 
Are you near the sea, Sansa? }{she wondered. }{\cs28\i Are you waiting at the Whispers for a ship that will never come? Who do you have with you? Passage for three, he said. Has the Imp joined you and Ser Dontos, or did you find your little sister?}{ 

\par The day had been a long one, and Brienne was tired. Even sitting up ag
ainst the rock, with rain pattering softly all around her, she found her eyelids growing heavy. Twice she dozed. The second time she woke all at once, heart pounding, convinced that someone was looming over her. Her limbs were stiff, and her cloak had got
ten tangled round her ankles. She kicked free of it and stood. Nimble Dick was curled against a rock, half-buried in wet, heavy sand, asleep. }{\cs28\i A dream. It was a dream. }{
\par Perhaps she had made a mistake in abandoning Ser Creighton and Ser Illifer. They had seemed like honest men. }{\cs28\i Would that Jaime had come with me,}{
 she thought . . . but he was a knight of the Kingsguard, his rightful place was with his king. Besides, it was Renly that she wanted. }{\cs28\i I swore I would protect him, and I failed. Then I swore I would ave
