\par Beneath the burning sun of Dorne, wealth was measured as much in water as in gold, so every well was zealously guarded. The well at Shandystone had gone dry a hundred years before, howev
er, and its guardians had departed for some wetter place, abandoning their modest holdfast with its fluted columns and triple arches. Afterward the sands had crept back in to reclaim their own. 
\par Arianne Martell arrived with Drey and Sylva just as the sun w
as going down, with the west a tapestry of gold and purple and the clouds all glowing crimson. The ruins seemed aglow as well; the fallen columns glimmered pinkly, red shadows crept across the cracked stone floors, and the sands themselves turned from gol
d to orange to purple as the light faded. Garin had arrived a few hours earlier, and the knight called Darkstar the day before. 
\par \'93It is lovely here,\'94 Drey observed as he was helping Garin water the horses. They had carried their own water with them. The san
d steeds of Dorne were swift and tireless, and would keep going for long leagues after other horses had given out, but even such as they could not run dry. \'93How did you know of this place?\'94 
\par \'93My uncle brought me here, with Tyene and Sarella.\'94 The memory made Arianne smile. \'93
He caught some vipers and showed Tyene the safest way to milk them for their venom. Sarella turned over rocks, brushed sand off the mosaics, and wanted to know everything there was to know about the people who had lived here.\'94 
\par \'93And what did you do, princess?\'94 asked Spotted Sylva. 
\par }{\cs28\i I sat beside the well and pretended that some robber knight had brought me here to have his way with me,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i a tall hard man with black eyes and a widow\rquote s peak.}{ The memory made her uneasy. \'93I dreamed,\'94
 she said, \'93and when the sun went down I sat cross-legged at my uncle\rquote s feet and begged him for a story.\'94 
\par \'93Prince Oberyn was full of stories.\'94 Garin had been with them as well that day; he was Arianne\rquote s milk brother, and they had been inseparable since before they learned to walk. \'93
He told about Prince Garin, I remember, the one that I was named for.\'94 
\par \'93Garin the Great,\'94 offered Drey, \'93the wonder of the Rhoyne.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s the one. He made Valyria tremble.\'94 
\par \'93They trembled,\'94 said Ser Gerold, \'93then they killed him. If I led a quarter of a million men to death, would they call me Gerold the Great?\'94 He snorted. \'93I shall remain Darkstar, I think. At least it is mine own.\'94
 He unsheathed his longsword, sat upon the lip of the dry well, and began to hone the blade with an oilstone. 
\par Arianne watched him warily. }{\cs28\i He is highborn enough to make a worthy consort,}{ she thought. }{\cs28\i Father would question my good sense, but our children would be as beautiful as dragonlords.}{
 If there was a handsomer man in Dorne, she did not know h
im. Ser Gerold Dayne had an aquiline nose, high cheekbones, a strong jaw. He kept his face clean-shaven, but his thick hair fell to his collar like a silver glacier, divided by a streak of midnight black. }{\cs28\i 
He has a cruel mouth, though, and a crueler tongue.}{ His eyes seemed black as he sat outlined against the dying sun, sharpening his steel, but she had looked at them from a closer vantage and she knew that they were purple. }{\cs28\i 
Dark purple. Dark and angry. }{
\par He must have felt her gaze upon him, for he looked up from his sword, met her eyes, and smiled. Arianne felt heat rushing to her face. }{\cs28\i I should never have brought him. If he gives me such a look when Arys is here, we will have blood on the sand.
}{ Whose, she could not say. By tradition the Kingsguard were the finest knights in all the Seven Kingdoms . . . but Darkstar was Darkstar. 
\par The Dornish nights grow cold out upon the sands. Garin gathered wood for them, bleached white branches from trees that had withered up and died a hundred years ago. Drey built a fire, whistling as he struck sparks off his flint. 
\par Once the kindling caught, they sat around the flames and passed a skin of summerwine from hand to hand . . . all but Darkstar, who preferred to drink unsweetened lemonwater. Garin was in a lively mood and ent
ertained them with the latest tales from the Planky Town at the mouth of the Greenblood, where the orphans of the river came to trade with the carracks, cogs, and galleys from across the narrow sea. If the sailors could be believed, the east was seething 
w
ith wonders and terrors: a slave revolt in Astapor, dragons in Qarth, grey plague in Yi Ti. A new corsair king had risen in the Basilisk Isles and raided Tall Trees Town, and in Qohor followers of the red priests had rioted and tried to burn down the Blac
k Goat. \'93And the Golden Company broke its contract with Myr, just as the Myrmen were about to go to war with Lys.\'94 
\par \'93The Lyseni bought them off,\'94 suggested Sylva. 
\par \'93Clever Lyseni,\'94 Drey said. \'93Clever, craven Lyseni.\'94 
\par Arianne knew better. }{\cs28\i If Quentyn has the Golden Company behind him . . . }{\'93Beneath the gold the bitter steel,\'94 was their cry. }{\cs28\i You will need bitter steel and more, brother, if you think to set me aside.}{
 Arianne was loved in Dorne, Quentyn little known. No company of sellswords could change that. 
\par Ser Gerold rose. \'93I believe I\rquote ll have a piss.\'94 
\par \'93Watch where you set your feet,\'94 Drey cautioned. \'93It has been a while since Prince Oberyn milked the local vipers.\'94 
\par \'93I was weaned on venom, Dalt. Any viper takes a bite of me will rue it.\'94 Ser Gerold vanished through a broken arch. 
\par When he was gone, the others exchanged glances. \'93Forgive me, princess,\'94 said Garin softly, \'93but I do not like that man.\'94 
\par \'93A pity,\'94 Drey said. \'93I believe he\rquote s half in love with you.\'94 
\par \'93We need him,\'94 Arianne reminded them. \'93It may be that we will need his sword, and we will surely need his castle.\'94 
\par \'93High Hermitage is not the only castle in Dorne,\'94 Spotted Sylva pointed out, \'93and you have other knights who love you well. Drey is a knight.\'94 
\par \'93I am,\'94 he affirmed. \'93I have a wonderful horse and a very fine sword, and my valor is second to . . . well, several, actually.\'94 
\par \'93More like several hundred, ser,\'94 said Garin. 
\par Arianne left them to their banter. Drey and Spotted Sylva were her dearest friends, aside from her cousin Tyene, and Garin had been teasing her since both of them were drinking from his mother\rquote 
s teats, but just now she was in no mood for japery. The sun was gone, and the sky was full of stars. }{\cs28\i So many.}{ She leaned her back against a fluted pillar and wondered
 if her brother was looking at the same stars tonight, wherever he might be. }{\cs28\i Do you see the white one, Quentyn? That is Nymeria\rquote 
s star, burning bright, and that milky band behind her, those are ten thousand ships. She burned as bright as any man, and so shall I. You will not rob me of my birthright!}{ 
\par Quentyn had been very young when he was sent to Yronwood; too young, according to their mother. Norvoshi did not foster out their children, and Lady Mellario had never forgiven Prince Doran for taking her son away from her. \'93
I like it no more than you do,\'94 Arianne had overheard her father say, \'93but there is a blood debt, and Quentyn is the only coin Lord Ormond will accept.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93Coin?\'94}{ her mother had screamed. \'93He is your }{\cs28\i son.}{ What sort of father uses his own flesh and blood to pay his debts?\'94 
\par \'93The princely sort,\'94 Doran Martell had answered. 
\par Prince Doran was still pretending that her brother was with Lord Yronwood, but Garin\rquote s mother had seen him at the Planky Town, posing as a merchant. One of his companions had a lazy eye, the same as Cletus Yronwood, Lord Anders\rquote 
s randy son. A maester traveled with them too, a maester skilled in tongues. }{\cs28\i My brother is not as clever as he thinks. A clever man would have left from Oldtown, even if it meant a longer voyage. In Oldtown he might have gone unrecognized.}{
 Arianne had friends amongst the orphans of the Planky Town, and some had grown curious as to why a prince and a lord\rquote s son might be traveling under false names and seeking passage across the narrow sea. One of them had
 crept through a window of a night, tickled the lock on Quentyn\rquote s little strongbox, and found the scrolls within. 
\par Arianne would have given much and more to know that this secret trip across the narrow sea was Quentyn\rquote s own doing, and his alone . . . but parchments he had carried had been sealed with the sun and spear of Dorne. Garin\rquote 
s cousin had not dared break the seal to read them, but . . . 
\par \'93Princess.\'94 Ser Gerold Dayne stood behind her, half in starlight and half in shadow. 
\par \'93How was your piss?\'94 Arianne inquired archly. 
\par \'93The sands were duly grateful.\'94 Dayne put a foot upon the head of a statue that might have been the Maiden till the sands had scoured her face away. \'93It occurred to me as I was pissing that this plan of yours may not yield you what you want.\'94 

\par \'93And what is it I want, ser?\'94 
\par \'93The Sand Snakes freed. Vengeance for Oberyn and Elia. Do I know the song? You want a little taste of lion blood.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i That, and my birthright. I want Sunspear, and my father\rquote s seat. I want Dorne.}{ \'93I want justice.\'94 
\par \'93Call it what you will. Crowning the Lannister girl is a hollow gesture. She will never sit the Iron Throne. Nor will you get the war you want. The lion is not so easily provoked.\'94 
\par \'93The lion\rquote s dead. Who knows which cub the lioness prefers?\'94 
\par \'93The one in her own den.\'94 Ser Gerold drew his sword. It glimmered in the starlight, sharp as lies. \'93This is how you start a war. Not with a crown of gold, but with a blade of steel.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I am no murderer of children.}{ \'93Put that away. Myrcella is under my protection. And Ser Arys will permit no harm to come to his precious princess, you know that.\'94 
\par \'93No, my lady. What I know is that Daynes have been killing Oakhearts for several thousand years.\'94 
\par His arrogance took her breath away. \'93It seems to me that Oakhearts have been killing Daynes for just as long.\'94 
\par \'93We all have our family traditions.\'94 Darkstar sheathed his sword. \'93The moon is rising, and I see your paragon approaching.\'94 
\par His eyes were sharp. The horseman on the tall grey palfrey did indeed prove to be Ser Arys, white cloak fluttering bravely as he spurred across the sand. Princess Myrcella rode pillion behind him, swaddled in a cowled robe that hid her golden curls. 

\par As Ser Arys helped her from the saddle, Drey went to one knee before her. \'93Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93My lady liege.\'94 Spotted Sylva knelt beside him. 
\par \'93My queen, I am your man.\'94 Garin dropped to both knees. 
