\par Arianne drew the child away. \'93You must be hungry. We have dates and cheese
 and olives, and lemonsweet to drink. You ought not eat or drink too much, though. After a little rest, we must ride. Out here on the sands it is always best to travel by night, before the sun ascends the sky. It is kinder to the horses.\'94 
\par \'93And the riders,\'94 Spotted Sylva said. \'93Come, Your Grace, warm yourself. I should be honored if you\rquote d let me serve you.\'94 
\par As she led the princess to the fire, Arianne found Ser Gerold behind her. \'93My House goes back ten thousand years, unto the dawn of days,\'94 he complained. \'93Why is it that my cousin is the only Dayne that anyone remembers?\'94 
\par \'93He was a great knight,\'94 Ser Arys Oakheart put in. 
\par \'93He had a great sword,\'94 Darkstar said. 
\par \'93And a great heart.\'94 Ser Arys took Arianne by the arm. \'93Princess, I beg a moment\rquote s word.\'94 
\par \'93Come.\'94
 She led Ser Arys deeper into the ruins. Beneath his cloak, the knight wore a cloth-of-gold doublet embroidered with the three green oak leaves of his House. On his head was a light steel helm topped by a jagged spike, wound about with a yellow scarf 
in the Dornish fashion. He might have passed for any knight, but for the cloak. Of shimmering white silk it was, pale as moonlight and airy as a breeze. }{\cs28\i A Kingsguard cloak beyond all doubt, the gallant fool.}{ \'93How much does the child know?
\'94 
\par \'93Little enough. Before we left King\rquote 
s Landing, her uncle reminded her that I was her protector and that any commands that I might give her were meant to keep her safe. She has heard them in the streets as well, shouting out for vengeance. She knew this was no game. The g
irl is brave, and wise beyond her years. She did all I asked of her, and never asked a question.\'94 The knight took her arm, glanced about, lowered his voice. \'93There are other tidings you should hear. Tywin Lannister is dead.\'94 
