s blood is in me, along with that of Mors Martell, the Dornish lord she married. On the day they wed, Nymeria fired her ships, so her people would understand that there could be no going back. Most were glad to see those flames, for their voyagings had be
en long and terrible before they came to Dorne, and many and more had been lost to storm, disease, and slavery. There were a few who mourned, however. They did not love this dry red land or its seven-faced god, so they clung to their old ways, hammered bo
ats together from the hulks of the burned ships, and became the orphans of the Greenblood. The Mother in their songs is not }{\cs28\i our}{ Mother, but Mother Rhoyne, whose waters nourished them from the dawn of days.\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote d heard the Rhoynar had some turtle god,\'94 said Ser Arys. 
\par \'93The Old Man of the River is a lesser god,\'94 said Garin. \'93He was born from Mother River too, and fought the Crab King to win dominion over all who dwell beneath the flowing waters.\'94 
\par \'93Oh,\'94 said Myrcella. 
\par \'93I understand you\rquote ve fought some mighty battles too, Your Grace,\'94 said Drey in his most cheerful voice. \'93It is said you show our brave Prince Trystane no mercy at the }{\cs28\i cyvasse}{ table.\'94 
\par \'93He always sets his squares up the same way, with all the mountains in the front and his elephants in the passes,\'94 said Myrcella. \'93So I send my dragon through to eat his elephants.\'94 
\par \'93Does your handmaid play the game as well?\'94 asked Drey. 
\par \'93Rosamund?\'94 asked Myrcella. \'93No. I tried to teach her, but she said the rules were too hard.\'94 
\par \'93She is a Lannister as well?\'94 said Lady Sylva. 
\par \'93A Lannister of }{\cs28\i Lannisport,}{ not a Lannister of Casterly Rock. Her hair is the same color as mine, but straight instead of curly. Rosamund doesn\rquote t truly favor me, but when she dresses up in my clothes people who don\rquote t kn
ow us think she\rquote s me.\'94 
\par \'93You have done this before, then?\'94 
\par \'93Oh, yes. We traded places on the }{\cs28\i Seaswift,}{ on the way to Braavos. Septa Eglantine put brown dye in my hair. She said we were doing it as a game, but it was meant to keep me safe in case the ship was taken by my uncle Stannis.\'94 
\par The girl was plainly growing tired, so Arianne called a halt. They watered the horses once again, rested for a bit, and had some cheese and fruit. Myrcella split an orange with Spotted Sylva, whilst Garin ate olives and spit the stones at Drey. 
\par Arianne had hoped to reach the river before the sun came up, but they had started much later than she\rquote d planned, so they were still in the saddle when the eastern sky turned red. Darkstar cantered up beside her. \'93Princess,\'94 he said, \'93I
\rquote d set a faster pace, unless you mean to kill the child after all. We have no tents, and by day the sands are cruel.\'94 
\par \'93I know the sands as well as you do, ser,\'94 she told him. All the same, she did as he suggested. It was hard on their mounts, but better she should lose six horses than one princess. 
\par Soon enough the wind came gusting from the west, hot and dry and full of grit. Arianne drew her veil across her face. It was made of shimmering silk, pale green above and yellow below, the colors blending int
o one another. Small green pearls gave it weight, and rattled softly against each other as she rode. 
\par \'93I know why my princess wears a veil,\'94 Ser Arys said as she was fastening it to the temples of her copper helm. \'93Elsewise her beauty would outshine the sun above.\'94 
\par She had to laugh. \'93No, your princess wears a veil to keep the glare out of her eyes and the sand out of her mouth. You should do the same, ser.\'94 She wondered how long her white knight had been polishing his ponderous gallantry. Ser Arys was plea
sant company abed, but wit and he were strangers. 
\par Her Dornishmen covered their faces as she did, and Spotted Sylva helped veil the little princess from the sun, but Ser Arys stayed stubborn. Before long the sweat was running down his face, and his cheeks had taken on a rosy blush. }{\cs28\i 
Much longer and he will cook in those heavy clothes,}{ she reflected. He would not be the first. In centuries past, many a host had come down from the Prince\rquote s Pass with banners streaming, only to wither and broil on the hot red Dornish sands. \'93
The arms of House Martell display the sun and spear, the Dornishman\rquote s two favored weapons,\'94 the Young Dragon had once written in his boastful }{\cs28\i Conquest of Dorne}{, \'93but of the two, the sun is the more deadly.\'94 
\par Thankfully, they did not need to c
ross the deep sands but only a sliver of the drylands. When Arianne spied a hawk wheeling high above them against a cloudless sky, she knew the worst was behind them. Soon they came upon a tree. It was a gnarled and twisted thing with as many thorns as le
aves, of the sort called sandbeggars, but it meant that they were not far from water. 
\par \'93We\rquote re almost there, Your Grace,\'94 Garin told Myrcella cheerfully when they spied more sandbeggars up ahead, a thicket of them growing all around the dry bed of a stream. 
The sun was beating down like a fiery hammer, but it did not matter with their journey at its end. They stopped to water the horses again, drank deep from their skins and wet their veils, then mounted for the last push. Within half a league they were ridi
ng over devilgrass and past olive groves. Beyond a line of stony hills the grass grew greener and more lush, and there were lemon orchards watered by a spider\rquote 
s web of old canals. Garin was the first to spy the river glimmering green. He gave a shout and raced ahead. 
\par Arianne Martell had crossed the Mander once, when she had gone with three of the Sand Snakes to visit Tyene\rquote s mother. Compared to that mighty waterway, the Greenblood was scarce worthy of the name of river, yet it remained the life of Dorne. It
 took its name from the murky green of its sluggish waters; but as they approached, the sunlight seemed to turn those waters gold. She had seldom seen a sweeter sight. }{\cs28\i The next part should be slow and simple,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i 
up the Greenblood and onto the Vaith, as far as a poleboat can go.}{
 That would give her time enough to prepare Myrcella for all that was to come. Beyond Vaith the deep sands waited. They would need help from Sandstone and the Hellholt to make that crossing, but she did not doubt that it wou
ld be forthcoming. The Red Viper had been fostered at Sandstone, and Prince Oberyn\rquote s paramour Ellaria Sand was Lord Uller\rquote s natural daughter; four of the Sand Snakes were his granddaughters. }{\cs28\i 
I will crown Myrcella at the Hellholt and raise my banners there.}{ 
\par They found the boat half a league downstream, hidden beneath the drooping branches of a great green willow. Low of roof and wide abeam, the poleboats had hardly any draft to speak of; the Young Dragon had disparaged them as \'93hovels built on rafts,\'94
 but t
hat was hardly fair. All but the poorest orphan boats were wonderfully carved and painted. This one was done in shades of green, with a curved wooden tiller shaped like a mermaid, and fish faces peering through her rails. Poles and ropes and jars of olive
 oil cluttered her decks, and iron lanterns swung fore and aft. Arianne saw no orphans. }{\cs28\i Where is her crew?}{ she wondered. 
\par Garin reined up beneath the willow. \'93Wake up, you fish-eyed lagabeds,\'94 he called as he leapt down from the saddle. \'93Your }{\cs28\i queen}{ is here, and wants her royal welcome. Come up, come out, we\rquote 
ll have some songs and sweetwine. My mouth is set for\emdash \'94 
\par The door on the poleboat slammed open. Out into the sunlight stepped Areo Hotah, longaxe in hand. 
\par Garin jerked to a halt. Arianne felt as though an axe had caught her in the belly. }{\cs28\i It was not supposed to end this way. This was not supposed to happen.}{ When she heard Drey say, \'93There\rquote s the last face I\rquote d hoped to see,\'94
 she knew she had to act. }{\cs28\i \'93Away!\'94}{ she cried, vaulting back into the saddle. \'93Arys, protect the princess\emdash \'94 
\par Hotah thumped the butt of his longaxe upon the deck. Behind the ornate rails of the poleboat, a dozen guardsmen rose, armed with throwing spears or crossbows. Still more appeared atop the cabin. \'93Yield, my princess,\'94 the captain called, \'93
else we must slay all but the child and yourself, by your father\rquote s word.\'94 
\par Princess Myrcella sat motionless upon her mount. Garin backed slowly from the poleboat, his hands in the air. Drey unbuckled his swordbelt. \'93Yielding seems the wisest course,\'94 he called to Arianne, as his sword thumped to the ground. 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93No!\'94}{ Ser Arys Oakheart put his horse between Arianne and the crossbows, his blade shining silver in his hand. He had unslung his shield and slipped his left arm through the straps. \'93You will not take her whilst I still draw breath.
\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i You reckless fool,}{ was all that Arianne had time to think, }{\cs28\i what do you think you\rquote re doing? }{
\par Darkstar\rquote s laughter rang out. \'93Are you blind or stupid, Oakheart? There are too many. Put up your sword.\'94 
\par \'93Do as he says, Ser Arys,\'94 Drey urged. 
\par }{\cs28\i We are taken, ser,}{ Arianne might have called out. }{\cs28\i Your death will not free us. If you love your princess, yield.}{ But when she tried to speak, the words caught in her throat. 
\par Ser Arys Oakheart gave her one last longing look, then put his golden spurs into his horse and charged. 
\par He rode headlong for the poleboat, his white cloak streaming behind him. Arianne Martell had never seen anything half so gallant, or half so stupid. }{\cs28\i \'93Noooo,\'94}{ she shrieked, but she had found her tongue too late. A crossbow }{\cs28\i 
thrumm}{ed, then another. Hotah bellowed a command. At such close range, the white knight\rquote s armor had as well been made of parchment. The first bolt punched right through his heavy oaken 
shield, pinning it to his shoulder. The second grazed his temple. A thrown spear took Ser Arys\rquote s mount in the flank, yet still the horse came on, staggering as he hit the gangplank. }{\cs28\i \'93No,\'94}{
 some girl was shouting, some foolish little girl, }{\cs28\i \'93no, please, this was not supposed to happen.\'94}{ She could hear Myrcella shrieking too, her voice shrill with fear. 
\par Ser Arys\rquote s longsword slashed right and left, and two spearmen went down. His horse reared, and kicked a crossbowman in the face as he was trying to reload, but
 the other crossbows were firing, feathering the big courser with their quarrels. The bolts hit home so hard they knocked the horse sideways. His legs went out from under him and sent him crashing down the deck. Somehow Arys Oakheart leapt free. He even m
anaged to keep hold of his sword. He struggled to his knees beside his dying horse . . . 
\par . . . and found Areo Hotah standing over him. 
\par The white knight raised his blade, too slowly. Hotah\rquote s longaxe took his right arm off at the shoulder, spun away sprayin
g blood, and came flashing back again in a terrible two-handed slash that removed the head of Arys Oakheart and sent it spinning through the air. It landed amongst the reeds, and the Greenblood swallowed the red with a soft splash. 
\par Arianne did not remember climbing from her horse. Perhaps she\rquote d fallen. She did not remember that either. Yet she found herself on her hands and feet in the sand, shaking and sobbing and retching up her supper. }{\cs28\i No,}{
 was all that she could think, }{\cs28\i no, no one was to be hurt, it was all planned, I was so careful.}{ She heard Areo Hotah roar, \'93After him. He must not escape. }{\cs28\i After him!}{\'94
 Myrcella was on the ground, wailing, shaking, her pale face in her hands, blood streaming through her fingers. Arianne did not understand. Men were scramb
ling onto horses whilst others swarmed over her and her companions, but none of it made sense. She had fallen into a dream, some terrible red nightmare. }{\cs28\i This cannot be real. I will wake soon, and laugh at my night terrors.}{ 
\par When they sought to bind her hands behind her back, she did not resist. One of the guardsmen jerked her to her feet. He wore her father\rquote s colors. Another bent and seized the throwing knife inside her boot, a gift from her cousin Lady Nym. 
\par Areo Hotah took it from the man and frowned at it. \'93The prince said I must bring you back to Sunspear,\'94 he announced. His cheeks and brow were freckled with the blood of Arys Oakheart. \'93I am sorry, little princess.\'94 
\par Arianne raised a tear-streaked face. \'93How could he know?\'94 she asked the captain. \'93I was so careful. How could he know?\'94 
\par \'93Someone told.\'94 Hotah shrugged. \'93Someone always tells.\'94
