\par As the rising sun came streaming through the windows, Alayne sat up in bed and stretched. Gretchel heard her stir and rose at once to fetch her bedrobe. The rooms had grown chilly during the night. }{\cs28\i It will be worse when winte
r has us in its grip,}{ she thought. }{\cs28\i Winter will make this place as cold as any tomb.}{ Alayne slipped into the robe and belted it about her waist. \'93The fire\rquote s almost out,\'94 she observed. \'93Put another log on, if you would.\'94 

\par \'93As my lady wishes,\'94 the old woman said. 
\par Alayne\rquote s apartments in the Maiden\rquote s Tower were larger and more lavish than the little bedchamber where she\rquote 
d been kept when Lady Lysa was alive. She had a dressing room and a privy of her own now, and a balcony of carved white stone that looked off a
cross the Vale. While Gretchel was tending to the fire, Alayne padded barefoot across the room and slipped outside. The stone was cold beneath her feet, and the wind was blowing fiercely, as it always did up here, but the view made her forget all that for
 half a heartbeat. Maiden\rquote s was the easternmost of the Eyrie\rquote 
s seven slender towers, so she had the Vale before her, its forests and rivers and fields all hazy in the morning light. The way the sun was hitting the mountains made them look like solid gold. 
\par }{\cs28\i So lovely.}{ The snow-clad summit of the Giant\rquote s Lance loomed above her, an immensity of stone and ice that dwarfed the castle perched upon its shoulder. Icicles twenty feet long draped the lip of the precipice where Alyssa\rquote 
s Tears fell in summer. A falcon soared above the frozen waterfall, blue wings spread wide against the morning sky. }{\cs28\i Would that I had wings as well. }{
\par She rested her hands on the carved stone balustrade and made herself peer over the edge. She could see Sky six hundred feet below, and the st
one steps carved into the mountain, the winding way that led past Snow and Stone all the way down to the valley floor. She could see the towers and keeps of the Gates of the Moon, as small as a child\rquote 
s toys. Around the walls the hosts of Lords Declarant were stirring, emerging from their tents like ants from an anthill. }{\cs28\i If only they were truly ants,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i we could step on them and crush them. }{
\par Young Lord Hunter and his levies had joined the others two days past. Nestor Royce had closed the Gates agai
nst them, but he had fewer than three hundred men in his garrison. Each of the Lords Declarant had brought a thousand, and there were six of them. Alayne knew their names as well as her own. Benedar Belmore, Lord of Strongsong. Symond Templeton, the Knigh
t
 of Ninestars. Horton Redfort, Lord of Redfort. Anya Waynwood, Lady of Ironoaks. Gilwood Hunter, called Young Lord Hunter by all and sundry, Lord of Longbow Hall. And Yohn Royce, mightiest of them all, the redoubtable Bronze Yohn, Lord of Runestone, Nesto
r\rquote s cousin and the chief of the senior branch of House Royce. The six had gathered at Runestone after Lysa Arryn\rquote 
s fall, and there made a pact together, vowing to defend Lord Robert, the Vale, and one another. Their declaration made no mention of the Lord Protector, but spoke of \'93misrule\'94 that must be ended, and of \'93false friends and evil counselors\'94
 as well. 
\par A cold gust of wind blew up her legs. She went inside to choose a gown to break her fast in. Petyr had given her his late wife\rquote s wardrobe, a wealth of
 silks, satins, velvets, and furs far beyond anything she had ever dreamed, though the great bulk of it was far too large for her; Lady Lysa had grown very stout during her long succession of pregnancies, stillbirths, and miscarriages. A few of the oldest
 gowns had been made for young Lysa Tully of Riverrun, however, and others Gretchel had been able to alter to fit Alayne, who was almost as long of leg at three-and-ten as her aunt had been at twenty. 
\par This morning her eye was caught by a parti-colored gown
 of Tully red and blue, lined with vair. Gretchel helped her slide her arms into the belled sleeves and laced her back, then brushed and pinned her hair. Alayne had darkened it again last night before she went to bed. The wash her aunt had given her chang
ed her own rich auburn into Alayne\rquote s burnt brown, but it was seldom long before the red began creeping back at the roots. }{\cs28\i And what must I do when the dye runs out?}{ The wash had come from Tyrosh, across the narrow sea. 
\par As she went down to break her fast, Al
ayne was struck again by the stillness of the Eyrie. There was no quieter castle in all the Seven Kingdoms. The servants here were few and old and kept their voices down so as not to excite the young lord. There were no horses on the mountain, no hounds t
o
 bark and growl, no knights training in the yard. Even the footsteps of the guards seemed strangely muffled as they walked the pale stone halls. She could hear the wind moaning and sighing round the towers, but that was all. When she had first come to Eyr
ie, there had been the murmur of Alyssa\rquote s Tears as well, but the waterfall was frozen now. Gretchel said it would stay silent till the spring. 
\par She found Lord Robert alone in the Morning Hall above the kitchens, pushing a wooden spoon listlessly through a big bowl of porridge and honey. \'93I wanted eggs,\'94 he complained when he saw her. \'93I wanted }{\cs28\i three}{
