\par Forty knights and as many esquires awaited him outside the Red Keep\rquote s stables. Half were westermen sworn to House Lannister, the others recent foes turned doubtful friends. Ser Dermot of the Rainwood would carry Tommen\rquote 
s standard, Red Ronnet Connington the white banner of the Kingsguard. A Paege, a Piper, and a Peckledon would share the honor of squiring for the Lord Commander. \'93Keep friends at your back and foes where you can see them,\'94
 Sumner Crakehall had once counseled him. Or had that been Father? 
\par His palfrey was a blood bay, his destrier a magnificent grey stallion. It had been long years since Jaime had named any of his horses; he had seen too many die in battle, and that was harder when you named them. But whe
n the Piper boy started calling them Honor and Glory, he laughed and let the names stand. Glory wore trappings of Lannister crimson; Honor was barded in Kingsguard white. Josmyn Peckledon held the palfrey\rquote 
s reins as Ser Jaime mounted. The squire was skinny
 as a spear, with long arms and legs, greasy mouse-brown hair, and cheeks soft with peach fuzz. His cloak was Lannister crimson, but his surcoat showed the ten purple mullets of his own House arrayed upon a yellow field. \'93My lord,\'94 the lad asked, 
\'93will you be wanting your new hand?\'94 
\par \'93Wear it, Jaime,\'94 urged Ser Kennos of Kayce. \'93Wave at the smallfolk and give them a tale to tell their children.\'94 
\par \'93I think not.\'94 Jaime would not show the crowds a golden lie. }{\cs28\i Let them see the stump. Let them see the cripple.}{ \'93But feel free to make up for my lack, Ser Kennos. Wave with both hands, and waggle your feet if it please you.\'94
 He gathered the reins in his left hand and wheeled his horse around. \'93Payne,\'94 he called as the rest were forming up, \'93you\rquote ll ride be- side me.\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn Payne made his way to Jaime\rquote 
s side, looking like the beggar at the ball. His ringmail was old and rusted, worn over a stained jack of boiled leather. Neither the man nor his mount showed any heraldry; his shield was so hacked and battered it was 
hard to say what color paint might once have covered it. With his grim face and deep-sunk hollow eyes, Ser Ilyn might have passed for death himself . . . as he had, for years. 
\par }{\cs28\i No longer, though.}{ Ser Ilyn had been half of Jaime\rquote s price, for swallowing his boy king\rquote s command like a good little Lord Commander. The other half had been Ser Addam Marbrand. \'93I need them,\'94
 he had told his sister, and Cersei had not put up a fight. }{\cs28\i Most like she\rquote s pleased to rid herself of them.}{ Ser Addam was a boyhood friend of Jaime\rquote 
s, and the silent headsman had belonged to their father, if he belonged to anyone. Payne had been the captain of the Hand\rquote 
s guard when he had been heard boasting that it was Lord Tywin who ruled the Seven Kingdoms and told King Aerys what to do. Aerys Targaryen took his tongue for that. 
\par \'93Open the gates,\'94 said Jaime, and Strongboar, in his booming voice, called out, }{\cs28\i \'93OPEN THE GATES!\'94 }{
\par When Mace Tyrell had marched out through the Mud Gate to the sound of drums and fiddles, thousands lined the streets to 
cheer him off. Little boys had joined the march, striding along beside the Tyrell soldiers with heads held high and legs pumping, whilst their sisters threw down kisses from the windows. 
\par Not so today. A few whores called out invitations as they passed, and a meat pie man cried his wares. In Cobbler\rquote 
s Square two threadbare sparrows were haranguing several hundred smallfolk, crying doom upon the heads of godless men and demon worshipers. The crowd parted for the column. Sparrows and cobblers alike looked on with dull eyes. \'93
They like the smell of roses but have no love for lions,\'94 Jaime observed. \'93My sister would be wise to take note of that.\'94 Ser Ilyn made no reply. }{\cs28\i The perfect companion for a long ride. I will enjoy his conversation.}{ 
\par The greater part of his command awaited him beyond the city walls; Ser Addam Marbrand with his outriders, Ser Steffon Swyft and the baggage train, the Holy Hundred of old Ser Bonifer the Good, Sarsfield\rquote 
s mounted archers, Maester Gulian with four cages full of ravens, two hundr
ed heavy horse under Ser Flement Brax. Not a great host, all in all; fewer than a thousand men in total. Numbers were the last thing needed at Riverrun. A Lannister army already invested the castle, and an even larger force of Freys; the last bird they
\rquote d received suggested that the besiegers were having difficulty keeping themselves fed. Brynden Tully had scoured the land clean before retiring behind his walls. 
\par }{\cs28\i Not that it required much scouring.}{ From what Jaime had seen of the riverlands, scarce a field remained unburnt, a town unsacked, a maiden undespoiled. }{\cs28\i 
And now my sweet sister sends me to finish the work that Amory Lorch and Gregor Clegane began.}{ It left a bitter taste in his mouth. 
\par This near to King\rquote s Landing, the kingsroad was as safe as any road could be in such times, yet Jaime sent Marbrand and his outriders ahead to scout. \'93Robb Stark took me unawares in the Whispering Wood,\'94 he said. \'93
That will never happen again.\'94 
\par \'93You have my word on it.\'94 Marbrand seemed visibly relieved to be ahorse again, wearing the smoke-grey cloak of his own House instead of the gold wool of the City Watch. \'93
If any foe should come within a dozen leagues, you will know of them beforehand.\'94 
\par Jaime had given stern commands that no man was to depart the column without his l
eave. Elsewise, he knew he would have bored young lordlings racing through the fields, scattering livestock and trampling down the crops. There were still cows and sheep to be seen near the city; apples on the trees and berries in the brush, stands of bar
leycorn and oats and winter wheat, wayns and oxcarts on the road. Farther afield, things would not be so rosy. 
\par Riding at the front of the host with Ser Ilyn silent by his side, Jaime felt almost content. The sun was warm on his back and the wind riffled through his hair like a woman\rquote 
s fingers. When Little Lew Piper came galloping up with a helm full of blackberries, Jaime ate a handful and told the boy to share the rest with his fellow squires and Ser Ilyn Payne. 
\par Payne seemed as comfortable in his silence as in his rusted ringmail and boiled leather. The clop of his gelding\rquote 
s hooves and the rattle of sword in scabbard whenever he shifted his seat were the only sounds he made. Though his pox-scarred face was grim and his eyes as cold as ice on a winter lake, Jaime sensed that he was glad he\rquote d come. }{\cs28\i 
I gave the man a choice,}{ he reminded himself. }{\cs28\i He could have refused me and remained King\rquote s Justice. }{
\par Ser Ilyn\rquote s appointment had been a wedding gift from Robert Baratheon to the father of his bride, a sinecure to compensate Payne for the tongue he\rquote 
d lost in the service of House Lannister. He made a splendid headsman. He had never botched an execution, and seldom required as much as a second stroke. And there was something about his silence that inspired terror. Seldom had a King\rquote 
s Justice seemed so well fitted for his office. 
\par When Jaime decided to take him, he had sought out Ser Ilyn\rquote s chambers at the end of Traitor\rquote s Walk. The upper floor of the squat, half-round tower was divided into cells for prisoners who requir
ed some measure of comfort, captive knights or lordlings awaiting ransom or exchange. The entrance to the dungeons proper was at ground level, behind a door of hammered iron and a second of splintery grey wood. On the floors between were rooms set aside f
or the use of the Chief Gaoler, the Lord Confessor, and the King\rquote s Justice. The Justice was a headsman, but by tradition he also had charge of the dungeons and the men who kept them. 
\par And for that task, Ser Ilyn Payne was singularly ill suited. As he could neither read, nor write, nor speak, Ser Ilyn had left the running of the dungeons to his underlings, such as they were. The realm had not had a Lord Confessor since the second Daeron
, however, and the last Chief Gaoler had been a cloth merchant who purchased the office from Littlefinger during Robert\rquote s reign. No doubt he\rquote 
d had good profit from it for a few years, until he made the error of conspiring with some other rich fools to give the Iron Throne to Stannis. They called themselves \'93Antler Men,\'94
