 in him, to unlock the dungeon doors for Jaime and conduct him up the narrow steps inside the walls to the place where Ilyn Payne had lived for fifteen years. 
\par The chambers stank of rotted food, and the rushes were crawling with vermin. As Jaime entered, he almost trod upon a rat. Payne\rquote 
s greatsword rested on a trestle table, beside a whetstone and a greasy oilcloth. The steel was immaculate, the edge glimmering blue in the pale light, but elsewhere piles of soiled clothi
ng were strewn about the floors, and the bits of mail and armor scattered here and there were red with rust. Jaime could not count the broken wine jars. }{\cs28\i The man cares for naught but killing,}{
 he thought, as Ser Ilyn emerged from a bedchamber that reeked of overflowing chamber pots. \'93His Grace bids me win back his riverlands,\'94 Jaime told him. \'93I would have you with me . . . if you can bear to give up all of this.\'94 
\par Silence was his answer, and a long, unblinking stare. But just as he was about to turn and take his leave, Payne had given him a nod. }{\cs28\i And here he rides.}{ Jaime glanced at his companion. }{\cs28\i Perhaps there is yet hope for the both of us. }{

\par That night they made camp beneath the hilltop castle of the Hayfords. As the sun went down, a hundred tents sprouted be
neath the hill, along the banks of the stream that ran beside it. Jaime set the sentries himself. He did not expect trouble this close to the city, but his uncle Stafford had once thought himself safe on the Oxcross too. It was best to take no chances. 

\par When the invitation came down from the castle for him to sup with Lady Hayford\rquote s castellan, Jaime took Ser Ilyn with him, along with Ser Addam Marbrand, Ser Bonifer Hasty, Red Ronnet Connington, Strongboar, and a dozen other knights and lordlings. 
\'93I suppose I ought to wear the hand,\'94 he said to Peck before making his ascent. 
\par The lad fetched it straightaway. The hand was wrought of gold, very lifelike, with inlaid nails of mother-of-pearl, its fingers and thumb half closed so as to slip around a goblet\rquote s stem. }{\cs28\i I cannot fight, but I can drink,}{
 Jaime reflected as the lad was tightening the straps that bound it to his stump. \'93Men shall name you Goldenhand from this day forth, my lord,\'94 the armorer had assured him the first time he\rquote d fitted it onto Jaime\rquote s wrist. }{\cs28\i 
He was wrong. I shall be the Kingslayer till I die.}{ 
\par The golden hand was the occasion for much admiring comment over supper, at least until Jaime knocked over a goblet of wine. Then his temper got the best of him. \'93If you admire the bloody thing so much, lop off your own sword hand and you can have it,
\'94 he told Flement Brax. After that there was no more talk about his hand, and he managed to drink some wine in peace. 
\par The lady of the castle was a Lannister by marriage, a plump toddler who had been wed to h
is cousin Tyrek before she was a year old. Lady Ermesande was duly trotted out for their approval, all trussed up in a little gown of cloth-of-gold, with the green fretty and green pale wavy of House Hayford rendered in tiny beads of jade. But soon enough
 the girl began to squall, whereupon she was promptly whisked off to bed by her wet nurse. 
\par \'93Has there been no word of our Lord Tyrek?\'94 her castellan asked as a course of trout was served. 
\par \'93None.\'94 Tyrek Lannister had vanished during the riots in King\rquote s Landing whilst Jaime himself was still captive at Riverrun. The boy would be fourteen by now, assuming he was still alive. 
\par \'93I led a search myself, at Lord Tywin\rquote s command,\'94 offered Addam Marbrand as he boned his fish, \'93but I found no more than Bywater had be
fore me. The boy was last seen ahorse, when the press of the mob broke the line of gold cloaks. Afterward . . . well, his palfrey was found, but not the rider. Most like they pulled him down and slew him. But if that\rquote 
s so, where is his body? The mob let the other corpses lie, why not his?\'94 
\par \'93He would be of more value alive,\'94 suggested Strongboar. \'93Any Lannister would bring a hefty ransom.\'94 
\par \'93No doubt,\'94 Marbrand agreed, \'93yet no ransom demand was ever made. The boy is simply gone.\'94 
\par \'93The boy is dead.\'94 Jaime had drunk three cups of wine, and his golden hand seemed to be growing heavier and clumsier by the moment. }{\cs28\i A hook would serve me just as well.}{ \'93If they realized whom they\rquote 
d killed, no doubt they threw him in the river for fear of my father\rquote s wrath. They know the taste of that in King\rquote s Landing. Lord Tywin always paid his debts.\'94 
\par \'93Always,\'94 Strongboar agreed, and that was the end of that. 
\par Yet afterward, alone in the tower room he had been offered for the night, Jaime found himself wondering. Tyrek had served
 King Robert as a squire, side by side with Lancel. Knowledge could be more valuable than gold, more deadly than a dagger. It was Varys he thought of then, smiling and smelling of lavender. The eunuch had agents and informers all over the city. It would h
ave been a simple matter for him to arrange to have Tyrek snatched during the confusion . . . provided he knew beforehand that the mob was like to riot. }{\cs28\i 
And Varys knew all, or so he would have us believe. Yet he gave Cersei no warning of that riot. Nor did he ride down to the ships to see Myrcella off.}{ 
\par He opened the shutters. The night was growing cold, and a horned moon rode the sky. His hand shone dully in its light. }{\cs28\i No good for throttling eunuchs, but heavy enough to smash that slimy smile into a fine red ruin.}{ He wanted to hit someone. 

\par Jaime found Ser Ilyn honing his greatsword. \'93It\rquote s time,\'94 he told the man. The headsman rose and followed, his cracked leather boots scraping against the steep stone steps as they went down the stair. A small courtyard ope
ned off the armory. Jaime found two shields there, two halfhelms, and a pair of blunted tourney swords. He offered one to Payne and took the other in his left hand as he slid his right through the loops of the shield. His golden fingers were curved enough
 to hook, but could not grasp, so his hold upon the shield was loose. \'93You were a knight once, ser,\'94 Jaime said. \'93So was I. Let us see what we are now.\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn raised his blade in reply, and Jaime moved at once to the attack. Payne was as rusty as his ri
ngmail, and not so strong as Brienne, yet he met every cut with his own blade, or interposed his shield. They danced beneath the horned moon as the blunted swords sang their steely song. The silent knight was content to let Jaime lead the dance for a whil
e
, but finally he began to answer stroke for stroke. Once he shifted to the attack, he caught Jaime on the thigh, on the shoulder, on the forearm. Thrice he made his head ring with cuts to the helm. One slash ripped the shield off his right arm, and almost
 burst the straps that bound his golden hand to his stump. By the time they lowered their swords he was bruised and battered, but the wine had burned away and his head was clear. \'93We will dance again,\'94 he promised Ser Ilyn. \'93
On the morrow, and the morrow. Every day we\rquote ll dance, till I am as good with my left hand as ever I was with the right.\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn opened his mouth and made a clacking sound. }{\cs28\i A laugh,}{ Jaime realized. Something twisted in his gut. 
\par Come morning, none of the others was so bold as to make m
ention of his bruises. Not one of them had heard the sound of swordplay in the night, it would seem. Yet when they climbed back down to camp, Little Lew Piper voiced the question the knights and lordlings dared not ask. Jaime grinned at him. \'93
They have lusty wenches in House Hayford. These are love bites, lad.\'94 
\par Another bright and blustery day was followed by a cloudy one, then three days of rain. Wind and water made no matter. The column kept its pace, north along the kingsroad, and each night Jaime found 
some private place to win himself more love bites. They fought inside a stable as a one-eyed mule looked on, and in the cellar of an inn amongst the casks of wine and ale. They fought in the blackened shell of a big stone barn, on a wooded island in a sha
llow stream, and in an open field as the rain pattered softly against their helms and shields. 
\par Jaime made excuses for his nightly forays, but he was not so foolish as to think that they were believed. Addam Marbrand knew what he was about, surely, and some
 of his other captains must have suspected. But no one spoke of it in his hearing . . . and since the only witness lacked a tongue, he need not fear anyone learning just how inept a swordsman the Kingslayer had become. 
\par Soon the signs of war could be seen on every hand. Weeds and thorns and brushy trees grew high as a horse\rquote 
s head in fields where autumn wheat should be ripening, the kingsroad was bereft of travelers, and wolves ruled the weary world from dusk till dawn. Most of the animals were wary enough to keep their distance, but one of Marbrand\rquote 
s outriders had his horse run off and killed when he dismounted for a piss. \'93No beast would be so bold,\'94 declared Ser Bonifer the Good, of the stern sad face. \'93These are demons in the skins of wolves, sent to chastise us for our sins.\'94 
\par \'93This must have been an uncommonly sinful horse,\'94 Jaime said, standing over what remained of the poor animal. He gave orders for the rest of the carcass to be cut apart and salted down; it might be they would need the meat. 
\par At a place called Sow\rquote 
s Horn they found a tough old knight named Ser Roger Hogg squatting stubbornly in his towerhouse with six men-at-arms, four crossbowmen, and a score of peasants. Ser Roger was as big and bristly as his name and Ser Kennos suggested that he 
might be some lost Crakehall, since their sigil was a brindled boar. Strongboar seemed to believe it and spent an earnest hour questioning Ser Roger about his ancestors. 
\par Jaime was more interested in what Hogg had to say of wolves. \'93We had some trouble with a band of them white star wolves,\'94 the old knight told him. \'93
They come round sniffing after you, my lord, but we saw them off, and buried three down by the turnips. Before them there was a pack of bloody lions, begging your pardon. The one who led them had a manticore on his shield.\'94 
\par \'93Ser Amory Lorch,\'94 Jaime offered. \'93My lord father commanded him to harry the riverlands.\'94 
\par \'93Which we\rquote re no part of,\'94 Ser Roger Hogg said stoutly. \'93My fealty\rquote s owed to House Hayford, and Lady Ermesande bends her little knee at King\rquote s Landing, or will when she\rquote 
s old enough to walk. I told him that, but this Lorch wasn\rquote t much for listening. He slaughtered half my sheep and three good milk goats, and tried to roast me in my tower. My walls are solid stone and eight feet thick, th
ough, so after his fire burned out he rode off bored. The wolves come later, the ones on four legs. They ate the sheep the manticore left me. I got a few good pelts in recompense, but fur don\rquote t fill your belly. What should we do, my lord?\'94 

\par \'93Plant,\'94 said Jaime, \'93and pray for one last harvest.\'94 It was not a hopeful answer, but it was the only one he had. 
\par The next day, the column crossed the stream that formed the boundary between the lands that did fealty to King\rquote s Landing and those beholden to Riverr
un. Maester Gulian consulted a map and announced that these hills were held by the brothers Wode, a pair of landed knights sworn to Harrenhal . . . but }{\cs28\i their}{ halls had been earth and timber, and only blackened beams remained of them. 
\par No Wodes appeared, nor any of their smallfolk, though some outlaws had taken shelter in the root cellar beneath the second brother\rquote 
s keep. One of them wore the ruins of a crimson cloak, but Jaime hanged him with the rest. It felt good. This was justice. }{\cs28\i Make a habit of it, Lannister, and one day men might call you Goldenhand after all. Goldenhand the Just.}{ 
\par The world grew ever greyer as they drew near to Harrenhal. They rode beneath slate skies, beside waters that shone old and cold as a sheet of beaten steel. Jaime found himself wondering if Brienne might have passed this way before him. }{\cs28\i 
If she thought that Sansa Stark had made for Riverrun . . . }{Had they encountered other travelers, he might have stopped to ask if any of them had chance to see a pretty maid with auburn hair, o
r a big ugly one with a face that would curdle milk. But there was no one on the roads but wolves, and their howling held no answers. 
\par Across the pewter waters of the lake the towers of Black Harren\rquote s folly appeared at last, five twisted fingers of black, 
misshapen stone grasping for the sky. Though Littlefinger had been named the Lord of Harrenhal, he seemed in no great haste to occupy his new seat, so it had fallen to Jaime Lannister to \'93sort out\'94 Harrenhal on his way to Riverrun. 
\par That it needed sorting out he did not doubt. Gregor Clegane had wrested the immense, gloomy castle away from the Bloody Mummers before Cersei recalled him to King\rquote s Landing. No doubt the Mountain\rquote 
s men were still rattling around inside like so many dried peas in a suit of plate, but they were not ideally suited to restore the king\rquote s peace to the Trident. The only peace Ser Gregor\rquote 
s lot had ever given anyone was the peace of the grave. 
\par Ser Addam\rquote s outriders had reported that the gates of Harrenhal were closed and barred. Jaime drew his men up before them and commanded Ser Kennos of Kayce to sound the Horn of Herrock, black and twisted and banded in old gold. 
\par When three blasts had echoed off the walls, they heard the groan of iron hinges and the gates swung slowly open. So thick were the walls of Black Harren\rquote 
s folly that Jaime passed beneath a dozen murder holes before emerging into sudden sunlight in the yard where he\rquote d bid farewell to the Bloody Mummers, not so long ago. Weeds were sprouting from the hard-packed earth, and flies
 buzzed about the carcass of a horse. 
\par A handful of Ser Gregor\rquote s men emerged from the towers to watch him dismount; hard-eyed, hard-mouthed men, the lot of them. }{\cs28\i They would have to be, to ride beside the Mountain.}{ About the best that could be said for Gregor\rquote 
s men was that they were not quite as vile and violent a bunch as the Brave Companions. \'93Fuck me, Jaime Lannister,\'94 blurted one grey and grizzled man-at-arms. \'93It\rquote s the bleeding Kingslayer, boys. Fuck me with a spear!\'94 
\par \'93Who might you be?\'94 Jaime asked. 
\par \'93Ser used to call me Shitmouth, if it please m\rquote lord.\'94 He spit in his hands and wiped his cheeks with them, as if that would somehow make him more presentable. 
\par \'93Charming. Do you command here?\'94 
\par \'93Me? Shit, no. M\rquote lord. Bugger me with a bloody spear.\'94 Shitmouth had enough crumbs in his beard to feed the garrison. Jaime had to laugh. The man took that for encouragement. \'93Bugger me with a bloody spear,\'94
 he said again, and started laughing too. 
\par \'93You heard the man,\'94 Jaime said to Ilyn Payne. \'93Find a nice long spear, and shove it up his arse.\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn did not have a spear, but Beardless Jon Bettley was glad to toss him one. Shitmouth\rquote s drunken laughter stopped abruptly. \'93You keep that bloody thing away from me.\'94 
\par \'93Make up your mind,\'94 said Jaime. \'93Who has the command here? Did Ser Gregor name a castellan?\'94 
\par \'93Polliver,\'94 another man said, \'93only the Hound killed him, m\rquote lord. Him and the Tickler both, and that Sarsfield boy.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i The Hound again.}{ \'93You know it was Sandor? You saw him?\'94 
\par \'93Not us, m\rquote lord. That innkeep told us.\'94 
\par \'93It happened at the crossroads inn, my lord.\'94
 The speaker was a younger man with a mop of sandy hair. He wore the chain of coins that had once belonged to Vargo Hoat; coins from half a hundred distant cities, silver and gold, copper and bronze, squar
e coins and round coins, triangles and rings and bits of bone. \'93
The innkeep swore the man had one side of his face all burned. His whores told the same tale. Sandor had some boy with him, a ragged peasant lad. They hacked Polly and the Tickler to bloody bits and rode off down the Trident, we were told.\'94 
\par \'93Did you send men after them?\'94 
\par Shitmouth frowned, as if the thought were painful. \'93No, m\rquote lord. Fuck us all, we never did.\'94 
\par \'93When a dog goes mad you cut his throat.\'94 
\par \'93Well,\'94 the man said, rubbing his mouth, \'93I never much liked Polly, that shit, and the dog, he were Ser\rquote s brother, so . . .\'94 
\par \'93We\rquote re bad, m\rquote lord,\'94 broke in the man who wore the coins, \'93but you\rquote d need to be mad to face the Hound.\'94 
\par Jaime looked him over. }{\cs28\i Bolder than the rest, and not as drunk as Shitmouth.}{ \'93You were afraid of him.\'94 
\par \'93I wouldn\rquote t say }{\cs28\i afraid,}{ m\rquote lord. I\rquote d say we was leaving him for our betters. Someone like Ser. Or you.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Me, when I had two hands.}{ Jaime did not delude himself. Sandor would make short work of him now. \'93You have a name?\'94 
\par \'93Rafford, if it pleases. Most call me Raff.\'94 
\par \'93Raff, gather the garrison together in the Hall of a Hundred Hearths. Your captives as well. I\rquote ll want to see them. Those whores from the crossroads too. Oh, and Hoat. I was distraught to hear that he had died. I\rquote 
d like to look upon his head.\'94 
\par When they brought it to him, he found that the Goat\rquote s lips had been sliced off, along with his ears and most of his nose. The crows had supped up
on his eyes. It was still recognizably Hoat, however. Jaime would have known his beard anywhere; an absurd rope of hair two feet long, dangling from a pointed chin. Elsewise, only a few leathery strips of flesh still clung to the Qohorik\rquote s skull. 
\'93Where is the rest of him?\'94 he asked. 
\par No one wanted to tell him. Finally, Shitmouth lowered his eyes, and muttered, \'93Rotted, ser. And et.\'94 
\par \'93One of the captives was always begging food,\'94 Rafford admitted, \'93so Ser said to give him roast goat. The Qohorik didn\rquote t have much meat on him, though. Ser took his hands and feet first, then his arms and legs.\'94 
\par \'93The fat bugger got most, m\rquote lord,\'94 Shitmouth offered, \'93but Ser, he said to see that all the captives had a taste. And Hoat too, his own self. That whoreson \rquote ud slobber when we fed him, and the grease\rquote 
d run down into that skinny beard o\rquote  his.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Father,}{ Jaime thought, }{\cs28\i your dogs have both gone mad.}{ He found himself remembering tales he had first heard as a child at Casterly Rock, of mad Lady Lothston who bathed in tubs of 
blood and presided over feasts of human flesh within these very walls. 
\par Somehow revenge had lost its savor. \'93Take this and throw it in the lake.\'94 Jaime tossed Hoat\rquote s head to Peck, and turned to address the garrison. \'93Until such time as Lord Petyr arrives t
o claim his seat, Ser Bonifer Hasty shall hold Harrenhal in the name of the crown. Those of you who wish may join him, if he\rquote ll have you. The rest will ride with me to Riverrun.\'94 
\par The Mountain\rquote s men looked at one another. \'93We\rquote re owed,\'94 said one. \'93Ser promised us. Rich rewards, he said.\'94 
\par \'93His very words,\'94 Shitmouth agreed. }{\cs28\i \'93Rich rewards, for them as rides with me.\'94}{ A dozen others began to yammer their assent. 
\par Ser Bonifer raised a gloved hand. \'93Any man who remains with me shall have a hide of land to work, a second hide when he takes a wife, a third at the birth of his first child.\'94 
\par \'93Land, ser?\'94 Shitmouth spat. \'93Piss on that. If we wanted to grub in the bloody dirt, we could have bloody well stayed home, begging your pardon, ser. }{\cs28\i Rich rewards,}{ Ser said. Meaning gold.\'94 
\par \'93If you have a grievance, go to King\rquote s Landing and take it up with my sweet sister.\'94 Jaime turned to Rafford. \'93I\rquote ll see those captives now. Starting with Ser Wylis Manderly.\'94 
\par \'93He the fat one?\'94 asked Rafford. 
\par \'93I devoutly hope so. And tell me no sad stories of how he died, or the lot of you are apt to do the same.\'94 
\par Any hopes he might have nursed of finding Shagwell, Pyg, or Zollo languishing in the dungeons were sadly disappointed. The Brave Companions had abandoned Vargo Hoat to a man, it would seem. Of Lady Whent\rquote s people, only three remained\emdash 
the cook who had opened the postern gate for Ser Gregor, a bent-back armorer called Ben Blackthumb, and a girl named Pia, who was not near as pretty as she had been when Jaime saw her last. Someone had b
roken her nose and knocked out half her teeth. The girl fell at Jaime\rquote s feet when she saw him, sobbing and clinging to his leg with hysterical strength till Strongboar pulled her off. \'93No one will hurt you now,\'94
 he told her, but that only made her sob the louder. 
\par The other captives had been better treated. Ser Wylis Manderly was amongst them, along with several other highborn northmen taken prisoner by the Mountain That Rides in the fighting at the fords of the Trident. Useful hostages, all worth a goodly 
ransom. They were ragged, filthy, and shaggy to a man, and some had fresh bruises, cracked teeth, and missing fingers, but their wounds had been washed and bandaged, and none of them had gone hungry. Jaime wondered if they had any inkling what they
\rquote d been eating, and decided it was better not to inquire. 
\par None had any defiance left; especially not Ser Wylis, a bushy-faced tub of suet with dull eyes and sallow, sagging jowls. When Jaime told him that he would be escorted to Maidenpool and there put on a ship
 for White Harbor, Ser Wylis collapsed into a puddle on the floor and sobbed longer and louder than Pia had. It took four men to lift him back onto his feet. }{\cs28\i Too much roast goat,}{ Jaime reflected. }{\cs28\i Gods, but I hate this bloody castle.}
{ Harrenhal had seen more horror in its three hundred years than Casterly Rock had witnessed in three thousand. 
\par Jaime commanded that fires be lit in the Hall of a Hundred Hearths and sent the cook hobbling back to the kitchens to prepare a hot meal for the men of his column. \'93Anything but goat.\'94 
\par He took his own supper in Hunter\rquote s Hall with Ser Bonifer Hasty, a solemn stork of a man prone to salting his speech with appeals to the Seven. \'93I want none of Ser Gregor\rquote s followers,\'94
 he declared as he was cutting up a pear as withered as he was, so as to make certain that its nonexistent juice did not stain his pristine purple doublet, embroidered with the white bend cotised of his House. \'93
I will not have such sinners in my service.\'94 
\par \'93My septon used to say all men were sinners.\'94 
\par \'93He was not wrong,\'94 Ser Bonifer allowed, \'93but some sins are blacker than others, and fouler in the nostrils of the Seven.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i And you have no more nose than my little brother, or my own sins would have you choking on that pear.}{ \'93Very well. I\rquote ll take Gregor\rquote s lot off your hands.\'94
 He could always find a use for fighters. If nothing else, he could send them up the ladders first, should he need to storm the walls of Riverrun. 
\par \'93Take the whore as well,\'94 Ser Bonifer urged. \'93You know the one. The girl from the dungeons.\'94 
\par \'93Pia.\'94 The last time he had been here, Qyburn had sent the girl to his bed, thinking that would please him. But the Pia they had brought up from the dungeons was a different creature from the sweet, simple, giggly creature who\rquote 
d crawled beneath his blanket
s. She had made the mistake of speaking when Ser Gregor wanted quiet, so the Mountain had smashed her teeth to splinters with a mailed fist and broken her pretty little nose as well. He would have done worse, no doubt, if Cersei had not called him down to
 King\rquote s Landing to face the Red Viper\rquote s spear. Jaime would not mourn him. \'93Pia was born in this castle,\'94 he told Ser Bonifer. \'93It is the only home she has ever known.\'94 
\par \'93She is a font of corruption,\'94 said Ser Bonifer. \'93I won\rquote t have her near my men, flaunting her . . . parts.\'94 
\par \'93I expect her flaunting days are done,\'94 he said, \'93but if you find her that objectionable, I\rquote ll take her.\'94 He could make her a washerwoman, he supposed. His squires did not mind raising his tent, grooming his horse, or cleaning his armo
r, but the task of caring for his clothes struck them as unmanly. \'93Can you hold Harrenhal with just your Holy Hundred?\'94
 Jaime asked. They should actually be called the Holy Eighty-Six, having lost fourteen men upon the Blackwater, but no doubt Ser Bonifer would fill up his ranks again as soon as he found some sufficiently pious recruits. 
\par \'93I anticipate no difficulty. The Crone will light our way, and the Warrior will give strength to our arms.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Or else the Stranger will turn up for the whole holy lot of you.}{
 Jaime could not be certain who had convinced his sister that Ser Bonifer should be named castellan of Harrenhal, but the appointment smelled of Orton Merryweather. Hasty had once served Merryweather\rquote 
s grandsire, he seemed to recall dimly. And the carrot-haired justiciar was just the sort of simpleminded fool to assume that someone called \'93the Good\'94
 was the very potion the riverlands required to heal the wounds left by Roose Bolton, Vargo Hoat, and Gregor Clegane. 
\par }{\cs28\i But he might not be wrong.}{ Hasty hailed 
from the stormlands, so had neither friends nor foes along the Trident; no blood feuds, no debts to pay, no cronies to reward. He was sober, just, and dutiful, and his Holy Eighty-Six were as well disciplined as any soldiers in the Seven Kingdoms, and mad
e a lovely sight as they wheeled and pranced their tall grey geldings. Littlefinger had once quipped that Ser Bonifer must have gelded the riders too, so spotless was their repute. 
\par All the same, Jaime wondered about any soldiers who were better known for their lovely horses than for the foes they\rquote d slain. }{\cs28\i They pray well, I suppose, but can they fight?}{
 They had not disgraced themselves on the Blackwater, so far as he knew, but they ha
d not distinguished themselves either. Ser Bonifer himself had been a promising knight in his youth, but something had happened to him, a defeat or a disgrace or a near brush with death, and afterward he had decided that jousting was an empty vanity and p
ut away his lance for good and all. 
\par }{\cs28\i Harrenhal must be held, though, and Baelor Butthole here is the man that Cersei chose to hold it.}{ \'93This castle has an ill repute,\'94 he warned him, \'93and one that\rquote s well deserved. It\rquote s said that Harren and his sons still wa
lk the halls by night, afire. Those who look upon them burst into flame.\'94 
\par \'93I fear no shade, ser. It is written in }{\cs28\i The Seven-Pointed Star}{ that spirits, wights, and revenants cannot harm a pious man, so long as he is armored in his faith.\'94 
\par \'93Then armor yourself in faith, by all means, but wear a suit of mail and plate as well. Every man who holds this castle seems to come to a bad end. The Mountain, the Goat, even my father . . .\'94 
\par \'93If you will forgive my saying so, they were not godly men, as we are. The Wa
rrior defends us, and help is always near, if some dread foe should threaten. Maester Gulian will be remaining with his ravens, Lord Lancel is nearby at Darry with his garrison, and Lord Randyll holds Maidenpool. Together we three shall hunt down and dest
roy whatever outlaws prowl these parts. Once that is done, the Seven will guide the goodfolk back to their villages to plow and plant and build anew.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i The ones the Goat didn\rquote t kill, at least.}{ Jaime hooked his golden fingers round the stem of his wine goblet. \'93If any of Hoat\rquote s Brave Companions fall into your hands, send word to me at once.\'94
 The Stranger might have made off with the Goat before Jaime could get around to him, but fat Zollo was still out there, with Shagwell, Rorge, Faithful Urswyck, and the rest. 
\par \'93So you can torture them and kill them?\'94 
\par \'93I suppose you would forgive them, in my place?\'94 
\par \'93If they made sincere repentance for their sins . . . yes, I would embrace them all as brothers and pray with them before I sent them to the block. Sins may be forgiven. Crimes require punishment.\'94
 Hasty folded his hands before him like a steeple, in a way that reminded Jaime uncomfortably of his father. \'93If it is Sandor Clegane that we encounter, what would you have me do?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Pray hard,}{ Jaime thought, }{\cs28\i and run.}{ \'93Send him to join his beloved brother and be glad the gods made seven hells. One would never be enough to hold both of the Cleganes.\'94 He pushed himself awkwardly to his feet. \'93
Beric Dondarrion is a different matter. Should you capture him, hold him for my return. I\rquote ll want to march him back to King\rquote s Landing with a rope about his neck, and have Ser Ilyn take his head off where half the realm can see.\'94 
\par \'93And this Myrish priest who runs with him? It is said he spreads his false faith everywhere.\'94 
\par \'93Kill him, kiss him, or pray with him, as you please.\'94 
\par \'93I have no wish to kiss the man, my lord.\'94 
\par \'93No doubt he\rquote d say the same of you.\'94 Jaime\rquote s smile turned into a yawn. \'93My pardons. I shall take my leave of you, if you have no objections.\'94 
\par \'93None, my lord,\'94 said Hasty. No doubt he wished to pray. 
\par Jaime wished to fight. He took the steps two at a time, out to where the night air was cold and crisp. In the torchlit yard Strongboar and Ser Flement Brax were having at each other whilst a ring of men-at-arms cheered them on. }{\cs28\i 
Ser Lyle will have the best of that one,}{ he knew. }{\cs28\i I need to find Ser Ilyn.}{
 His fingers had the itch again. His footsteps took him away from the noise and the light. He passed beneath the covered bridge and through the Flowstone Yard before he realized where he was headed. 
\par As he neared the bear pit, he saw the glow of a lantern, its pale wintry light washing over the tiers of steep stone seats. }{\cs28\i Someone has come before me, it would seem.}{ The pit would be a fine place to dance; perhaps Ser Ilyn had antic
ipated him. 
