\par }{\cs28\i A pity.}{ Still, the absence of a bloody sheet meant little, by itself. Common peasant girls bled like pigs upon their wedding nights, she had heard, but that was less true of highborn maids like Margaery Tyrell. A lord\rquote 
s daughter was more like to give her maidenhead to a horse than a husband, it was said, and Margaery had been riding since she was old enough to walk. \'93I understand the little queen has many a
dmirers amongst our household knights. The Redwyne twins, Ser Tallad . . . who else, pray tell?\'94 
\par Lady Merryweather gave a shrug. \'93Ser Lambert, the fool who hides a good eye behind a patch. Bayard Norcross. Courtenay Greenhill. The brothers Woodwright, sometimes Portifer and often Lucantine. Oh, and Grand Maester Pycelle is a frequent visitor.\'94 

\par \'93Pycelle? Truly?\'94 Had that doddering old worm forsaken the lion for the rose? }{\cs28\i If so, he will regret it.}{ \'93Who else?\'94 
\par \'93The Summer Islander in his feathered cloak. Ho
w could I have forgotten him, with his skin as black as ink? Others come to pay court to her cousins. Elinor is promised to the Ambrose boy, but loves to flirt, and Megga has a new suitor every fortnight. Once she kissed a potboy in the kitchen. I have he
ard talk of her marrying Lady Bulwer\rquote s brother, but if Megga were to choose for herself, she would sooner have Mark Mullendore, I am certain.\'94 
