Aurane suggested that men might not want to serve on a ship named for a fool had the boy reluctantly agreed to honor his sister instead. 
\par \'93If this ragged septon thinks to make me }{\cs28\i buy}{ Tommen\rquote s blessing, he will soon learn better,\'94 she told Taena. The queen did not intend to truckle to a pack of priests. 
\par The litter halted yet again, so suddenly that Cersei jerked. \'93Oh, this is infuriating.\'94 She leaned out once more, and saw that they had reached the top of Visenya\rquote s Hill. Ahead loomed the Great Sept of Baelo
r, with its magnificent dome and seven shining towers, but between her and the marble steps lay a sullen sea of humanity, brown and ragged and unwashed. }{\cs28\i Sparrows,}{ she thought, sniffing, though no sparrows had ever smelled so rank. 
\par Cersei was appalled. Qyb
urn had brought her reports of their numbers, but hearing about them was one thing and seeing them another. Hundreds were encamped upon the plaza, hundreds more in the gardens. Their cookfires filled the air with smoke and stinks. Roughspun tents and mise
rable hovels made of mud and scrap wood besmirched the pristine white marble. They were even huddled on the steps, beneath the Great Sept\rquote s towering doors. 
\par Ser Osmund came trotting back to her. Beside him rode Ser Osfryd, mounted on a stallion as golden as his cloak. Osfryd was the middle Kettleblack, quieter than his siblings, more apt to scowl than smile. }{\cs28\i 
And crueler as well, if the tales are true. Perhaps I should have sent him to the Wall.}{ 
\par Grand Maester Pycelle had wanted an older man \'93more seasoned in the ways of war\'94 to command the gold cloaks, and several of her other councillors had agreed with him. \'93Ser Osfryd is seasoned quite sufficiently,\'94
 she had told them, but even that did not shut them up. }{\cs28\i They yap at me like a pack of small, annoying dogs.}{
 Her patience with Pycelle had all but run its course. He had even had the temerity to object to her sending to Dorne for a master-at-arms, on the grounds that it might offend the Tyrells. \'93Why do you think I\rquote m }{\cs28\i doing}{ it?\'94
 she had asked him scornfully. 
\par \'93Beg pardon, Your Grace,\'94 said Ser Osmund. \'93My brother\rquote s summoning more gold cloaks. We\rquote ll clear a path, never fear.\'94 
\par \'93I do not have the time. I will continue on afoot.\'94 
\par \'93Please, Your Grace.\'94 Taena caught her arm. \'93They frighten me. There are hundreds of them, and so dirty.\'94 
\par Cersei kissed her cheek. \'93The lion does not fear the sparrow . . . but it is good of you to care. I know you love me well, my lady. Ser Osmund, kindly help me down.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i If I had known I was going to have to walk, I would have dressed for it.}{
 She wore a white gown slashed with cloth-of-gold, lacy but demure. It had been several years since the last time she had donned it, and the queen found it uncomfortably tight about the middle. \'93Ser Osmund, Ser Meryn, you will accompany me.
 Ser Osfryd, see that my litter comes to no harm.\'94 Some of the sparrows looked gaunt and hollow-eyed enough to eat her horses. 
\par As she made her way through the ragged throng, past their cookfires, wagons, and crude shelters, the queen found herself remembe
ring another crowd that had once gathered on this plaza. The day she wed Robert Baratheon, thousands had turned out to cheer for them. All the women wore their best, and half the men had children on their shoulders. When she had emerged from inside the se
pt, hand in hand with the young king, the crowd sent up a roar so loud it could be heard in Lannisport. \'93They like you well, my lady,\'94 Robert whispered in her ear. \'93See, every face is smiling.\'94
 For that one short moment she had been happy in her marriage . . . until she chanced to glance at Jaime. }{\cs28\i No}{, she remembered thinking, }{\cs28\i not every face, my lord.}{ 
\par No one was smiling now. The looks the sparrows gave her were dull, sullen, hostile. They made way but reluctantly. }{\cs28\i If they were truly sparrows, a shout would s
end them flying. A hundred gold cloaks with staves and swords and maces could clear this rabble quick enough.}{ That was what Lord Tywin would have done. }{\cs28\i He would have ridden over them instead of walking through.}{ 
\par When she saw what they had done to Baelor the Beloved, the queen had cause to rue her soft heart. The great marble statue that had smiled serenely over the plaza for a hundred years was waist-deep in a heap of bones and skulls. Some of the skulls had scra
ps of flesh still clinging to them. A crow sat atop one such, enjoying a dry, leathery feast. Flies were everywhere. \'93What is the meaning of this?\'94 Cersei demanded of the crowd. \'93Do you mean to bury Blessed Baelor in a mountain of carrion?\'94 

\par A one-legged man stepped forward, leaning on a wooden crutch. \'93
Your Grace, these are the bones of holy men and women, murdered for their faith. Septons, septas, brothers brown and dun and green, sisters white and blue and grey. Some were hanged, some disemboweled. Septs 
have been despoiled, maidens and mothers raped by godless men and demon worshipers. Even silent sisters have been molested. The Mother Above cries out in her anguish. We have brought their bones here from all over the realm, to bear witness to the agony o
f the Holy Faith.\'94 
\par Cersei could feel the weight of eyes upon her. \'93The king shall know of these atrocities,\'94 she answered solemnly. \'93Tommen will share your outrage. This is the work of Stannis and his red witch, and the savage northmen who worship trees and wolves.
\'94 She raised her voice. }{\cs28\i \'93Good people, your dead shall be avenged!\'94}{ 
\par A few cheered, but only a few. \'93We ask no vengeance for our dead,\'94 said the one-legged man, \'93only protection for the living. For the septs and holy places.\'94 
\par \'93The Iron Throne must defend the Faith,\'94 growled a hulking lout with a seven-pointed star painted on his brow. \'93A king who does not protect his people is no king at all.\'94
 Mutters of assent went up from those around him. One man had the temerity to grasp Ser Meryn by the wrist, and say, \'93
It is time for all anointed knights to forsake their worldly masters and defend our Holy Faith. Stand with us, ser, if you love the Seven.\'94 
\par \'93Unhand me,\'94 said Ser Meryn, wrenching free. 
\par \'93I hear you,\'94 Cersei said. \'93My son is young, but he loves the Seven well. You shall have his protection, and mine own.\'94 
\par The man with the star upon his brow was not appeased. \'93The Warrior will defend us,\'94 he said, \'93not this fat boy king.\'94 
\par Meryn Trant reached for his sword, but Cersei stopped him before he could unsheathe it. She had only two knights amidst a sea of sparrows. She saw staves and scythes, cudgels and clubs, several axes. \'93I will have no blood shed in this holy place, ser.
\'94 }{\cs28\i Why are all men such children? Cut him down, and the rest will tear us limb from limb.}{ \'93We are all the Mother\rquote s children. Come, His High Holiness awaits us.\'94
 But as she made her way through the press to the steps of the sept, a gaggle of armed men stepped out to block the doors. They wore mail and boiled leather, with here and ther
e a bit of dinted plate. Some had spears and some had longswords. More favored axes, and had sewn red stars upon their bleached white surcoats. Two had the insolence to cross their spears and bar her way. 
\par \'93Is this how you receive your queen?\'94 she demanded of them. \'93Pray, where are Raynard and Torbert?\'94 It was not like those two to miss a chance to fawn on her. Torbert always made a show of getting down on his knees to wash her feet. 
\par \'93I do not know the men you speak of,\'94 said one of the men with a red star on his surcoat, \'93but if they are of the Faith, no doubt the Seven had need of their service.\'94 
\par \'93Septon Raynard and Septon Torbert are of the }{\cs28\i Most Devout,}{\'94 Cersei said, \'93and will be furious to learn that you obstructed me. Do you mean to deny me entrance to Baelor\rquote s holy sept?\'94 
\par \'93Your Grace,\'94 said a greybeard with a stooped shoulder. \'93You are welcome here, but your men must leave their swordbelts. No weapons are allowed within, by command of the High Septon.\'94 
\par \'93Knights of the Kingsguard do not set aside their swords, not even in the presence of the king.\'94 
\par \'93In the king\rquote s house, the king\rquote s word must rule,\'94 replied the aged knight, \'93but this is the house of the gods.\'94 
\par Color rose to her cheeks. One word to Meryn Trant, and the stoop-backed greybeard would be meeting his gods sooner than he might have liked. }{\cs28\i Not here, though. Not now.}{ \'93Wait for me,\'94
 she told the Kingsguard curtly. Alone, she climbed the steps. The spearmen uncrossed their spears. Two other men put their weight against the doors, and with a great groan they swung apart. 
\par In the Hall of Lamps, Cersei found a score of septons on their knees, but not in prayer. They had pails of soap and water, and were scrubbing at the floor. Their roughspun robes and sandals led Cersei to take them for sparrows, un
til one raised his head. His face was red as a beet, and there were broken blisters on his hands, bleeding. \'93Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93Septon Raynard?\'94 The queen could scarce believe what she was seeing. \'93What are you doing on your knees?\'94 
\par \'93He is cleaning the floor.\'94 The speaker was shorter than the queen by several inches and as thin as a broom handle. \'93Work is a form of prayer, most pleasing to the Smith.\'94 He stood, scrub brush in hand. \'93
Your Grace. We have been expecting you.\'94 
\par The man\rquote s beard was grey and brown a
nd closely trimmed, his hair tied up in a hard knot behind his head. Though his robes were clean, they were frayed and patched as well. He had rolled his sleeves up his elbows as he scrubbed, but below the knees the cloth was soaked and sodden. His face w
as sharply pointed, with deep-set eyes as brown as mud. }{\cs28\i His feet are bare,}{ she saw with dismay. They were hideous as well, hard and horny things, thick with callus. \'93You are His High Holiness?\'94 
\par \'93We are.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Father, give me strength.}{ The queen knew that she should kneel, but the floor was wet with soap and dirty water and she did not wish to ruin her gown. She glanced over at the old men on their knees. \'93I do not see my friend Septon Torbert.
\'94 
\par \'93Septon Torbert has been confined to a penitent\rquote s cell on bread and water. It is sinful for any man to be so plump when half the realm is starving.\'94 
\par Cersei had suffered quite enough for one day. She let him see her anger. \'93Is this how you greet me? With a scrub brush in your hand, dripping water? Do you know who I am?\'94 
\par \'93Your Grace is the Queen Regent of the Seven Kingdoms,\'94 the man said, \'93but in }{\cs28\i The Seven-Pointed Star}{ it is written that as men bow to their lords, and lords to their kings, so kings and queens must bow before the Seven Who Are One.
\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Is he telling me to kneel?}{ If so, he did not know her very well. \'93By rights you should have met me on the steps in your finest robes, with the crystal crown upon your head.\'94 
\par \'93We have no crown, Your Grace.\'94 
\par Her frown deepened. \'93My lord father gave your predecessor a crown of rare beauty, wrought in crystal and spun gold.\'94 
\par \'93And for that gift we honor him in our prayers,\'94 the High Septon said, \'93but the poor need food in their bellies more than we need gold and crystal on our head. That crown has been s
old. So have the others in our vaults, and all our rings, and our robes of cloth-of-gold and cloth-of-silver. Wool will keep a man as warm. That is why the Seven gave us sheep.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He is utterly mad.}{ The Most Devout must have been mad as well, to elevate this creature . . . mad, or terrified of the beggars at their doors. Qyburn\rquote 
s whisperers claimed that Septon Luceon had been nine votes from elevation when those doors had given way, and the sparrows came pouring into the Great Sept with their leader on their shoulders and their axes in their hands. 
\par She fixed the small man with an icy stare. \'93Is there someplace where we may speak more privily, Your Holiness?\'94 
\par The High Septon surrendered his scrub brush to one of the Most Devout. \'93If Your Grace will follow us?\'94 
\par He led her through the inner doors, into the sept proper. Their footsteps echoed off the marble floor. Dust motes swam in the beams of colored light slanting down through the leaded glass of the great dome. Incense sweetened the air, and beside the sev
en altars candles shone like stars. A thousand twinkled for the Mother and near as many for the Maid, but you could count the Stranger\rquote s candles on two hands and still have fingers left. 
