\par THE REAVER
\par The drums were pounding out a battle beat as the }{\cs28\i Iron Victory}{
 swept forward, her ram cutting through the choppy green waters. The smaller ship ahead was turning, oars slapping at the sea. Roses streamed upon her banners; fore and aft a white rose upon a red escutcheon
, atop her mast a golden one on a field as green as grass. The }{\cs28\i Iron Victory}{ raked her side so hard that half the boarding party lost their feet. Oars snapped and splintered, sweet music to the captain\rquote s ears. 
\par He vaulted over the gunwale, landing on the de
ck below with his golden cloak billowing behind him. The white roses drew back, as men always did at the sight of Victarion Greyjoy armed and armored, his face hidden behind his kraken helm. They were clutching swords and spears and axes, but nine of ever
y ten wore no armor, and the tenth had only a shirt of sewn scales. }{\cs28\i These are no ironmen,}{ Victarion thought. }{\cs28\i They still fear drowning. }{
\par \'93Get him!\'94 one man shouted. \'93He\rquote s alone!\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93COME!\'94}{ he roared back. }{\cs28\i \'93Come kill me, if you can.\'94}{ 
\par From all sides the rosey warriors converged, with grey steel in their hands and terror behind their eyes. Their fear was so ripe Victarion could taste it. Left and right he laid about, hewing off the first man\rquote 
s arm at the elbow, cleaving through the shoulder of the second. The third buried his own axehead in the soft pine of Victarion\rquote s shield. He slammed it into the fool\rquote 
s face, knocked him off his feet, and slew him when he tried to rise again. As he was struggling to free his axe from the dead man\rquote s rib cage, a spear jabbed him
 between the shoulder blades. It felt as though someone had slapped him on the back. Victarion spun and slammed his axe down onto the spearman\rquote 
s head, feeling the impact in his arm as the steel went crunching through helm and hair and skull. The man swayed
 for half a heartbeat, till the iron captain wrenched the steel free and sent his corpse staggering loose-limbed across the deck, looking more drunk than dead. 
\par By then his ironborn had followed him down onto the deck of the broken longship. He heard Wulfe
 One-Ear let out a howl as he went to work, glimpsed Ragnor Pyke in his rusted mail, saw Nute the Barber send a throwing axe spinning through the air to catch a man in the chest. Victarion slew another man, and another. He would have killed a third, but R
agnor cut him down first. \'93Well struck,\'94 Victarion bellowed at him. 
\par When he turned to find the next victim for his axe, he spied the other captain across the deck. His white surcoat was spotted with blood and gore, but Victarion could make out the arms upo
n his breast, the white rose within its red escutcheon. The man bore the same device upon his shield, on a white field with a red embattled border. }{\cs28\i \'93You!\'94}{ the iron captain called across the carnage. }{\cs28\i \'93
You of the rose! Be you the lord of Southshield?\'94}{ 
\par The other raised his visor to show a beardless face. \'93His son and heir. Ser Talbert Serry. And who are you, kraken?\'94 
\par \'93Your death.\'94 Victarion bulled toward him. 
\par Serry leapt to meet him. His longsword was good castle-forged steel, and the young knight made it sing. His first cut was low, and Victarion deflected it off his axe. His second caught the iron captain on the helm before he got his shield up. Victarion an
swered with a sidearm blow of his axe. Serry\rquote s shield got in the way. Wooden splinters flew, and the white rose split lengthwise with a sweet sharp }{\cs28\i crack}{. The young knight\rquote 
s longsword hammered at his thigh, once, twice, thrice, screaming against the steel. }{\cs28\i This boy is quick,}{ the iron captain realized. He smashed his shield in Serry\rquote 
s face and sent him staggering back against the gunwale. Victarion raised his axe and put all his weight behind his cut, to open the boy from neck to groin, but Serry spun away. T
he axehead crashed through the rail, sending splinters flying, and lodged there when he tried to pull it free. The deck moved under his feet, and he stumbled to one knee. 
\par Ser Talbert cast away his broken shield and slashed down with his longsword. Victarion\rquote s own shield had twisted half around when he stumbled. He caught Serry\rquote 
s blade in an iron fist. Lobstered steel crunched, and a stab of pain made him grunt, yet Victarion held on. \'93I am quick as well, boy,\'94 he said as he ripped the sword from the knight\rquote s hand and flung it into the sea. 
\par Ser Talbert\rquote s eyes went wide. \'93My sword . . .\'94 
\par Victarion caught the lad about the throat with a bloody fist. \'93Go and get it,\'94 he said, forcing him backwards over the side into the bloodstained waters. 
\par That won him a re
spite to pull his axe loose. The white roses were falling back before the iron tide. Some tried to flee belowdecks, as others cried for quarter. Victarion could feel warm blood trickling down his fingers beneath the mail and leather and lobstered plate, b
ut that was nothing. Around the mast a thick knot of foemen fought on, standing shoulder to shoulder in a ring. }{\cs28\i These few are men, at least. They would sooner die than yield.}{
 Victarion would grant some of them that wish. He beat his axe against his shield and charged them. 
\par The Drowned God had not shaped Victarion Greyjoy to fight with words at kingsmoots, nor struggle against furtive sneaking foes in endless bogs. }{\cs28\i This}{ was why he had been put on earth; to stand steel-clad with an axe red and dripping in his
 hand, dealing death with every blow. 
\par They hacked at him from front and back, but their swords might have been willow switches for all the harm they did him. No blade could cut through Victarion Greyjoy\rquote s heavy plate, nor did he give his foes the time to 
find the weak points at the joints, where only mail and leather warded him. Let three men assail him, or four, or five; it made no matter. He slew them one at a time, trusting in his steel to protect him from the others. As each foe fell he turned his wro
th upon the next. 
\par The last man to face him must have been a smith; he had shoulders like a bull, and one much more muscular than the other. His armor was a studded brigandine and a cap of boiled leather. The only blow he landed completed the ruin of Victarion\rquote 
s shield, but the cut the captain dealt in answer split his head in two. }{\cs28\i Would that I could deal with the Crow\rquote s Eye as simply.}{ When he jerked his axehead free again, the smith\rquote 
s skull seemed to burst. Bone and blood and brain went everywhere, and the corpse fell forward, up against his legs. }{\cs28\i Too late to plead for quarter now,}{ Victarion thought as he untangled himself from the dead man. 
\par By then the deck was slick beneath his feet, and the dead and the dying lay in heaps on every side. He threw his shield away and sucked in air. \'93Lord Captain,\'94 he heard the Barber say beside him, \'93the day is ours.\'94 
\par All around the sea was full of ships. Some were burning, some were sinking, some had been smashed to splinters. Between the hulls the water was thick as stew
, full of corpses, broken oars, and men clinging to the wreckage. In the distance, half a dozen of southron longships were racing back toward the Mander. }{\cs28\i Let them go,}{ Victarion thought, }{\cs28\i let them tell the tale.}{
 Once a man had turned his tail and run from battle he ceased to be a man. 
\par His eyes were stinging from the sweat that had run down into them during the fight. Two of his oarsmen helped undo his kraken helm so he might lift it off. Victarion mopped at his brow. \'93That knight,\'94 he grumbled, \'93the knight o
f the white rose. Did any of you pull him out?\'94 A lord\rquote s son would be worth a goodly ransom; from his father, if Lord Serry had survived the day. From his liege at Highgarden, if not. 
\par None of his men had seen what became of the knight after he went over the side, however. Most like the man had drowned. \'93May he feast as he fought, in the Drowned God\rquote s watery halls.\'94
 Though the men of the Shield Islands called themselves sailors, they crossed the seas in dread and went lightly clad in battle for fear of drowning. Young Serry had been different. }{\cs28\i A brave man,}{ thought Victarion. }{\cs28\i Almost ironborn.}{ 

\par He gave the captured ship to Ragnor Pyke, named a dozen men to crew her, and clambered back up onto his own }{\cs28\i Iron Victory.}{ \'93Strip the captives of arms and armor and have their wounds bound up,\'94 he told Nute the Barber. \'93
Throw the dying in the sea. If any beg for mercy, cut their throats first.\'94 He had only contempt for such; better to drown on seawater than on blood. \'93I want a count of the ships we won and all the knights
 and lordlings we took captive. I want their banners too.\'94 One day he would hang them in his hall, so when he grew old and feeble he could remember all the foes he had slain when he was young and strong. 
\par \'93It will be done.\'94 Nute grinned. \'93It is a great victory.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Aye,}{ he thought, }{\cs28\i a great victory for the Crow\rquote s Eye and his wizards.}{ The other captains would shout his brother\rquote 
s name anew when the tidings reached Oakenshield. Euron had seduced them with his glib tongue and smiling eye and bound them to his caus
e with the plunder of half a hundred distant lands; gold and silver, ornate armor, curved swords with gilded pommels, daggers of Valyrian steel, striped tiger pelts and the skins of spotted cats, jade manticores and ancient Valyrian sphinxes, chests of nu
tmeg, cloves, and saffron, ivory tusks and the horns of unicorns, green and orange and yellow feathers from the Summer Sea, bolts of fine silk and shimmering samite . . . and yet all that was little and less, compared to this. }{\cs28\i 
Now he has given them conquest, and they are his for good and all,}{ the captain thought. The taste was bitter on his tongue. }{\cs28\i 
This was my victory, not his. Where was he? Back on Oakenshield, lazing in a castle. He stole my wife and he stole my throne, and now he steals my glory.}{ 
\par Obedience came naturally to Victarion Greyjoy; he had been born to it. Growing to manhood in the shadow of his brothers, he had followed Balon dutifully in everything he did. Later, when Balon\rquote 
s sons were born, he had grown to accept that one day he would kneel to them as well, when one of them took his father\rquote 
s place upon the Seastone Chair. But the Drowned God had summoned Balon and his sons down to his watery halls, and Victarion could not call Euron \'93king\'94 without tasting bile in his throat. 
\par The wind was fres
hening, and his thirst was raging. After a battle he always wanted wine. He gave the deck to Nute and went below. In his cramped cabin aft, he found the dusky woman wet and ready; perhaps the battle had warmed her blood as well. He took her twice, in quic
k succession. When they were done there was blood smeared across her breasts and thighs and belly, but it was his blood, from the gash in his palm. The dusky woman washed it out for him with boiled vinegar. 
\par \'93The plan was good, I grant him,\'94 Victarion said as she knelt beside him. \'93The Mander is open to us now, as it was of old.\'94
 It was a lazy river, wide and slow and treacherous with snags and sandbars. Most seagoing vessels dared not sail beyond Highgarden, but longships with their shallow draughts could n
avigate as far upstream as Bitterbridge. In ancient days, the ironborn had boldly sailed the river road and plundered all along the Mander and its vassal streams . . . until the kings of the green hand had armed the fisherfolk on the four small islands of
f the Mander\rquote s mouth and named them his shields. 
\par Two thousand years had passed, but in the watchtowers along their craggy shores, greybeards still kept the ancient vigil. At the first glimpse of longships the old men would light their beacon fires, and the
 call would leap from hill to hill and island to island. }{\cs28\i Fear! Foes! Raiders! Raiders!}{
 When the fisherfolk saw the fires burning on the high places they would put their nets and plows aside and take up their swords and axes. Their lords would rush from the
ir castles, attended by their knights and men-at-arms. Warhorns would echo across the waters, from Greenshield and Greyshield, Oakenshield and Southshield, and their longships would come sliding out from moss-covered stone pens along the shores, oars flas
hing as they swarmed across the straits to seal the Mander and hound and harry the raiders upriver to their doom. 
\par Euron had sent Torwold Browntooth and the Red Oarsman up the Mander with a dozen swift longships, so the lords of the Shield Islands would spi
ll forth in pursuit. By the time his main fleet arrived, only a handful of fighting men remained to defend the isles themselves. The ironborn had come in on the evening tide, so the glare of the setting sun would keep them hidden from the greybeards in th
e watchtowers until it was too late. The wind was at their backs, as it had been all the way down from Old Wyk. It was whispered about the fleet that Euron\rquote s wizards had much and more to do with that, that the Crow\rquote 
s Eye appeased the Storm God with blood sacrifice. How else would he have dared sail so far to the west, instead of following the shoreline as was the custom? 
\par The ironborn ran their longships up onto the stony shingles and spilled out into the purple dusk with steel glimmering in their hands. By 
then the fires were burning in the high places, but few remained to take up arms. Greyshield, Greenshield, and Southshield fell before the sun came up. Oakenshield lasted half a day longer. And when the men of the Four Shields broke off their pursuit of T
orwold and the Red Oarsman and turned downriver, they found the Iron Fleet waiting at the Mander\rquote s mouth. 
\par \'93All fell out as Euron said it would,\'94 Victarion told the dusky woman as she bound up his hand with linen. \'93His wizards must have seen it.\'94 He had three aboard the }{\cs28\i Silence,}{
 Quellon Humble had confided in a whisper. Queer men and terrible, they were, but the Crow\rquote s Eye had made them slaves. \'93He still needs me to fight his battles, though,\'94 Victarion insisted. \'93Wizards may be well and good, but blood and 
steel win wars.\'94 The vinegar made his wound hurt worse than ever. He shoved the woman away and closed his fist, glowering. \'93Bring me wine.\'94 
\par He drank in the darkness, brooding on his brother. }{\cs28\i If I do not strike the blow with mine own hand, am I still a kinslayer?}{ Victarion feared no man, but the Drowned God\rquote s curse gave him pause. }{\cs28\i 
If another strikes him down at my command, will his blood still stain my hands?}{ Aeron Damphair would know the answer, but the priest was somewhere back on the Iron Islands, still hoping to raise the ironborn against their new-crowned king. }{\cs28\i 
Nute the Barber can shave a man with a thrown axe from twenty yards away. And none of Euron\rquote s mongrels could stand against Wulfe One-Ear or Andrik the Unsmiling. Any of them could do it.}{ But what a man }{\cs28\i can}{ do and what a man }{\cs28\i 
will}{ do are two different things, he knew. 
\par \'93Euron\rquote s blasphemies will bring down the Drowned God\rquote s wroth upon us all,\'94 Aeron had prophesied, back on Old Wyk. \'93We must stop him, brother. We are still of Balon\rquote s blood, are we not?\'94 
\par \'93So is he,\'94 Victarion had said. \'93I like it no more than you, but Euron is the king. Your kingsmoot raised him up, and you put the driftwood crown upon his head yourself!\'94 
\par \'93I placed the crown upon his head,\'94 said the priest, seaweed dripping in his hair, \'93and gladly will I wrest it off again and crown you in his stead. Only you are strong enough to fight him.\'94 
\par \'93The Drowned God raised him up,\'94 Victarion complained. \'93Let the Drowned God cast him down.\'94 
\par Aeron gave him a baleful look, the look that had been known to sour wells and make women barren. \'93
It was not the god who spoke. Euron is known to keep wizards and foul sorcerers on that red ship of his. They sent some spell among us, so we could not hear the sea. The captains and the kings were drunk with all this talk of dragons.\'94 
\par \'93Drunk, and fearful of that horn. You heard the sound it made. It makes no matter. Euron is our king.\'94 
\par \'93Not mine,\'94 the priest declared. \'93The Drowned God helps bold men, not those who cower below their decks when the storm is rising. If you will not bestir yourself to remove the Crow\rquote 
s Eye from the Seastone Chair, I must take the task upon myself.\'94 
\par \'93How? You have no ships, no swords.\'94 
\par \'93I have my voice,\'94 the priest replied, \'93and the god is with me. Mine is the strength of the sea, a strength the Crow\rquote 
s Eye cannot hope to withstand. The waves may break upon the mountain, yet still they come, wave upon wave, and in the end only pebbles remain where once the mountain stood. And soon even the pebbles a
re swept away, to be ground beneath the sea for all eternity.\'94 
\par \'93Pebbles?\'94 Victarion grumbled. \'93You are mad if you think to bring the Crow\rquote s Eye down with talk of waves and pebbles.\'94 
\par \'93The ironborn shall be waves,\'94 the Damphair said. \'93Not the great and lor
dly, but the simple folk, tillers of the soil and fishers of the sea. The captains and the kings raised Euron up, but the common folk shall tear him down. I shall go to Great Wyk, to Harlaw, to Orkmont, to Pyke itself. In every town and village shall my w
ords be heard. }{\cs28\i No godless man may sit the Seastone Chair!}{\'94
