If the girl keeps her wits about her, she will wed some northern lord and live with him in his castle, far from the sea and Euron Crow\rquote s Eye.}{ 
\par \'93Lord Hewett\rquote s Town, Lord Captain,\'94 a crewman called. 
\par Victarion rose. The wine had dulled the throbbing in his hand. Perhaps he would have Hewett\rquote s maester look at it, if the man had not been killed. He returned to deck as they came around a headland. The way Lord Hewett\rquote 
s castle sat above the harbor reminded him of Lordsport, though this town was twice as big. A score of longships prowled the waters beyond the port, the golden kraken writhing on their sails. Hundreds more were beach
ed along the shingles and drawn up to the piers that lined the harbor. At a stone quay stood three great cogs and a dozen smaller ones, taking on plunder and provisions. Victarion gave orders for the }{\cs28\i Iron Victory}{ to drop anchor. \'93
Have a boat made ready.\'94 
\par The town seemed strangely still as they approached. Most of the shops and houses had been looted, as their smashed doors and broken shutters testified, but only the sept had been put to the torch. The streets were strewn with corpses, each with a small fl
o
ck of carrion crows in attendance. A gang of sullen survivors moved amongst them, chasing off the black birds and tossing the dead into the back of a wagon for burial. The notion filled Victarion with disgust. No true son of the sea would want to rot bene
ath the ground. How would he ever find the Drowned God\rquote s watery halls, to drink and feast for all eternity? 
\par The }{\cs28\i Silence}{ was amongst the ships they passed. Victarion\rquote s gaze was drawn to the iron figurehead at her prow, the mouthless maiden with the windblown hair and outstretched arm. Her mother-of-pearl eyes seemed to follow him. }{\cs28\i 
She had a mouth like any other woman, till the Crow\rquote s Eye sewed it shut.}{ 
\par As they neared the shore, he noticed a line of women and children herded up onto the deck of one of the great cogs. Some had their hands bound behind their backs, and all wore loops of hempen rope about their necks. \'93Who are they?\'94
 he asked the men who helped tie up their boat. 
\par \'93Widows and orphans. They\rquote re to be sold as slaves.\'94 
\par \'93Sold?\'94 There were no slaves 
in the Iron Islands, only thralls. A thrall was bound to service, but he was not chattel. His children were born free, so long as they were given to the Drowned God. And thralls were never bought nor sold for gold. A man paid the iron price for thralls, o
r else had none. \'93They should be thralls, or salt wives,\'94 Victarion complained. 
\par \'93It\rquote s by the king\rquote s decree,\'94 the man said. 
\par \'93The strong have always taken from the weak,\'94 said Nute the Barber. \'93Thralls or slaves, it makes no matter. Their men could not defend them, so now they are ours, to do with as we will.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i It is not the Old Way,}{ he might have said, but there was no time. His victory had preceded him, and men were gathering round to offer congratulations. Victarion let them fawn, until one began to praise Euron\rquote s daring. \'93
It is daring to sail out of sight of land, so no word of our coming could reach these islands before us,\'94 he growled, \'93but crossing half the world to hunt for dragons, that is something else.\'94 He did not wait for a reply, but shouldered 
through the press and on up to the keep. 
\par Lord Hewett\rquote s castle was small but strong, with thick walls and studded oaken gates that evoked his House\rquote s ancient arms, an oak escutcheon studded with iron upon a field of undy blue and white. But it was the krak
en of House Greyjoy that flew atop his green-roofed towers now, and they found the great gates burned and broken. On the ramparts walked ironborn with spears and axes, and some of Euron\rquote s mongrels too. 
\par In the yard Victarion came on Gorold Goodbrother and old Drumm, speaking quietly with Rodrik Harlaw. Nute the Barber gave a hoot at the sight of them. \'93Reader,\'94 he called out, \'93
why is your face so long? Your misgivings were for nought. The day is ours, and ours the prize!\'94 
\par Lord Rodrik\rquote s mouth puckered. \'93These rocks, you mean? All four together wouldn\rquote t make Harlaw. We have won some stones and trees and trinkets, and the enmity of House Tyrell.\'94 
\par \'93The roses?\'94 Nute laughed. \'93What rose can harm the krakens of the deep? We have taken their shields from them, and smashed them all to pieces. Who will protect them now?\'94 
\par \'93Highgarden,\'94 replied the Reader. \'93Soon enough all the power of the Reach will be marshaled against us, Barber, and then you may learn that some roses have steel thorns.\'94 
\par Drumm nodded, one hand on the hilt of his Red Rain. \'93Lord Tarly bears the greatsword Heartsbane, forged of Valyrian steel, and he is always in Lord Tyrell\rquote s van.\'94 
\par Victarion\rquote s hunger flared. \'93Let him come. I will take his sword for mine own, as your own forebear took Red Rain. Let them all come, and bring the Lannisters as well. A lion may be fierce enough on land, but at sea the kraken rules supreme.\'94
 He would give half his teeth for the chance to try his axe against the Kingslayer or the Knight of Flowers. That was the sort of battle that he understood. The kinslayer was accursed in the eyes of gods and men, but the warrior was honored and revered. 

\par \'93Have no fear, Lord Captain,\'94 said the Reader. \'93They will come. His Grace desires it. Why else would he have commanded us to let Hewett\rquote s ravens fly?\'94 
\par \'93You read too much and fight too little,\'94 Nute said. \'93Your blood is milk.\'94 But the Reader made as if he had not heard. 
\par A riotous feast was in progress when Victarion entered the hall. Ironborn filled the tables, drinking and shouting and jostling each other, boasting of the men that they had slain, the deeds that they had done, the prizes they had won. Many were bedecked 
w
ith plunder. Left-Hand Lucas Codd and Quellon Humble had torn tapestries off the walls to serve as cloaks. Germund Botley wore a rope of pearls and garnets over his gilded Lannister breastplate. Andrik the Unsmiling staggered by with a woman under each ar
m; though he remained unsmiling, he had rings on every finger. Instead of trenchers carved from old stale bread, the captains were eating off solid silver platters. 
\par Nute the Barber\rquote s face grew dark with anger as he looked about. \'93The Crow\rquote s Eye sends us forth to face the longships, whilst his own men take the castles and the villages and grab all the loot and women. What has he left for us?\'94 

\par \'93We have the glory.\'94 
\par \'93Glory is good,\'94 said Nute, \'93but gold is better.\'94 
\par Victarion shrugged. \'93The Crow\rquote s Eye says we shall have all of Westeros. The Arbor, Oldtown, Highgarden . . . that\rquote s where you\rquote ll find your gold. But enough talk. I\rquote m hungry.\'94 
\par By right of blood Victarion might have claimed a seat on the dais, but he did not care to eat with Euron and his creatures. Instead, he chose a place by Ralf the Limper, the captain of the }{\cs28\i Lord Quellon.}{ \'93A great victory, Lord Captain,\'94
 said the Limper. \'93A victory worthy of a lordship. You should have an island.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Lord Victarion. Aye, and why not?}{ It might not be the Seastone Chair, but it would be something. 
\par Hotho Harlaw was across the table, sucking meat off a bone. He flicked it aside and hunched forward. \'93The Knight\rquote s to have Greyshield. My cousin. Did you hear?\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 Victarion looked across the hall, to where Ser Harras Harlaw sat drinking wine from a golden cup; a tall man, long-faced and austere. \'93Why would Euron give that one an island?\'94 
\par Hotho held out his empty wine cup, and a pale young woman in a gown of blue velvet and gilt lace refilled it for him. \'93The Knight to
ok Grimston by himself. He planted his standard beneath the castle and defied the Grimms to face him. One did, and then another, and another. He slew them all . . . well, near enough, two yielded. When the seventh man went down, Lord Grimm\rquote 
s septon decided the gods had spoken and surrendered the castle.\'94 Hotho laughed. \'93He\rquote ll be the Lord of Greyshield, and welcome to it. With him gone, I am the Reader\rquote s heir.\'94 He thumped his wine cup against his chest. \'93
Hotho the Humpback, Lord of Harlaw.\'94 
\par \'93Seven, you say.\'94
