\par \'93It is the Arbor we want,\'94 said Red Ralf, and other men took up the cry. The Crow\rquote s Eye let the shouts wash over him. Then he leapt down from the table, grabbed his slattern by the arm, and pulled her from the hall. 
\par }{\cs28\i Fled, like a dog.}{ Euron\rquote s hold upon the Seastone Chair suddenly did not seem as secure as it had a few moments before. }{\cs28\i They will not follow him to Slaver\rquote s Bay. Perhaps they are not such dogs and fools as I had feared.}
{ That was such a merry thought that Victarion had to wash it down. He drained a cup with the Barber, to show him that he did not begrudge him his lordship, even if it came from Euron\rquote s hand. 
\par Outside the sun went down. Darkness gathered beyond the walls, but inside the torch
es burned with a ruddy orange glow, and their smoke gathered under the rafters like a grey cloud. Drunken men began to dance the finger dance. At some point Left-Hand Lucas Codd decided he wanted one of Lord Hewett\rquote 
s daughters, so he took her on a table whilst her sisters screamed and sobbed. 
\par Victarion felt a tap upon his shoulder. One of Euron\rquote s mongrel sons stood behind him, a boy of ten with woolly hair and skin the color of mud. \'93My father wishes words with you.\'94 
\par Victarion rose unsteadily. He was a big man, with a large capacity for wine, but even so, he had drunk too much. }{\cs28\i I beat her to death with mine own hands,}{ he thought, }{\cs28\i but the Crow\rquote 
s Eye killed her when he shoved himself inside her. I had no choice.}{ He followed the bastard boy from the hall and 
up a winding stone stair. The sounds of rape and revelry diminished as they climbed, until there was only the soft scrape of boots on stone. 
\par The Crow\rquote s Eye had taken Lord Hewett\rquote s bedchamber along with his bastard daughter. When he entered, the girl was s
prawled naked on the bed, snoring softly. Euron stood by the window, drinking from a silver cup. He wore the sable cloak he took from Blacktyde, his red leather eye patch, and nothing else. \'93When I was a boy, I dreamt that I could fly,\'94
 he announced. \'93When I woke, I couldn\rquote t . . . or so the maester said. But what if he lied?\'94 
\par Victarion could smell the sea through the open window, though the room stank of wine and blood and sex. The cold salt air helped to clear his head. \'93What do you mean?\'94 
\par Euron turned to face him, his bruised blue lips curled in a half smile. \'93Perhaps we can fly. All of us. How will we ever know unless we leap from some tall tower?\'94
 The wind came gusting through the window and stirred his sable cloak. There was something obscene and disturbing about his nakedness. \'93No man ever truly knows what he can do unless he dares to leap.\'94 
\par \'93There is the window. Leap.\'94 Victarion had no patience for this. His wounded hand was troubling him. \'93What do you want?\'94 
\par \'93The world.\'94 Firelight glimmered in Euron\rquote s eye. }{\cs28\i His smiling eye.}{ \'93Will you take a cup of Lord Hewett\rquote s wine? There\rquote s no wine half so sweet as wine taken from a beaten foe.\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 Victarion glanced away. \'93Cover yourself.\'94 
\par Euron seated himself and gave his cloak a twitch, so it covered his private parts. \'93I had forgotten what a small and noisy folk they are, my ironborn. I would bring them dragons, and they shout out for grapes.\'94 
\par \'93Grapes are real. A man can gorge himself on grapes. Their juice is sweet, and they make wine. What do dragons make?\'94 
\par \'93Woe.\'94 The Crow\rquote s Eye sipped from his silver cup. \'93I once held a dragon\rquote 
s egg in this hand, brother. This Myrish wizard swore he could hatch it if I gave him a year and all the gold that he required. When I grew bored with his excuses, I slew him. As he watched his entrails sliding through his fingers he said, \lquote }{
\cs28\i But it has not been a year.\rquote }{\'94 He laughed. \'93Cragorn\rquote s died, you know.\'94 
\par \'93Who?\'94 
\par \'93The man who blew my dragon horn. When the maester cut him open, his lungs were charred as black as soot.\'94 
\par Victarion shuddered. \'93Show me this dragon\rquote s egg.\'94 
\par \'93I threw it in the sea during one of my dark moods.\'94 Euron gave a shrug. \'93It comes to me that the Reader was not wrong. Too large a fleet could never hold together over such a distance. The voyage is too long, too
 perilous. Only our finest ships and crews could hope to sail to Slaver\rquote s Bay and back. The Iron Fleet.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i The Iron Fleet is mine,}{ Victarion thought. He said nothing. 
\par The Crow\rquote s Eye filled two cups with a strange black wine that flowed as thick as honey. \'93Drink with me, brother. Have a taste of this.\'94 He offered one of the cups to Victarion. 
\par The captain took the cup Euron had not offered, sniffed at its contents suspiciously. Seen up close, it looked more blue than black. It was thick and oily, with a smell like rotted flesh. He tried a small swallow, and spit it out at once. \'93
Foul stuff. Do you mean to poison me?\'94 
\par \'93I mean to open your eyes.\'94 Euron drank deep from his own cup, and smiled. \'93}{\cs28\i Shade-of-the-evening,}{
 the wine of the warlocks. I came upon a cask of it when I captured a certain galleas out of Qarth, along with some cloves and nutmeg, forty bolts of green silk, and four warlocks who told a curious tale. One presumed to threaten me, so I killed him and f
ed him to the other three. They refused to eat of their friend\rquote s flesh at first, but when they grew hungry enough they had a change of heart. Men are meat.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Balon was mad, Aeron is madder, and Euron is maddest of them all.}{ Victarion was turning to go when the Crow\rquote s Eye said, \'93A king must have a wife, to give him heirs. Brother, I have need of you. Will you go to Slaver\rquote 
s Bay and bring my love to me?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I had a love once too.}{ Victarion\rquote s hands coiled into fists, and a drop of blood fell to patter on the floor. }{\cs28\i I should beat you raw and red and feed you to the crabs, the same as I did her.}{ \'93You have sons,\'94
 he told his brother. 
\par \'93Baseborn mongrels, born of whores and weepers.\'94 
\par \'93They are of your body.\'94 
\par \'93So are the contents of my chamber pot. None is fit to sit the Seastone Chair, much less the Iron Throne. No, to make an heir that\rquote s worthy of him, I need a different woman. When the kraken weds the dragon, brother, let all the world beware.\'94
 
\par \'93What dragon?\'94 said Victarion, frowning. 
\par \'93The last of her line. They say she is the fairest woman in the world. Her hair is silver-gold, and her eyes are amethysts . . . but you need not take my word for it, brother. Go to Slaver\rquote s Bay, behold her beauty, and bring her back to me.\'94 

\par \'93Why should I?\'94 Victarion demanded. 
\par \'93For love. For duty. Because your king commands it.\'94 Euron chuckled. \'93And for the Seastone Chair. It is yours, once I claim the Iron Throne. You shall follow me as I followed Balon . . . and your own trueborn sons shall one day follow you.\'94 

\par }{\cs28\i My own sons.}{ But to have a trueborn son a man must first have a wife. Victarion had no luck with wives. }{\cs28\i Euron\rquote s gifts are poisoned,}{ he reminded himself, }{\cs28\i but still . . . }{
\par \'93The choice is yours, brother. Live a thrall or die a king. Do you dare to fly? Unless you take the leap, you\rquote ll never know.\'94 
\par Euron\rquote s smiling eye was bright with mockery. \'93Or do I ask too much of you? It is a fearsome thing to sail beyond Valyria.\'94 
\par \'93I could sail the Iron Fleet to hell if need be.\'94 When Victarion opened his hand, his palm was red with blood. \'93I\rquote ll go to Slaver\rquote s Bay, aye. I\rquote ll find this dragon woman, and I\rquote ll bring her back.\'94 }{\cs28\i 
But not for you. You stole my wife and despoiled her, so I\rquote ll have yours. The fairest woman in the world, for me.}{
