\par JAIME
\par The fields outside the walls of Darry were being tilled once more. The burned crops had been plowed under, and Ser Addam\rquote s scouts reported seeing women in the furrows pulling weeds, whilst a team of oxen broke new groun
d on the edge of a nearby wood. A dozen bearded men with axes stood guard over them as they worked. 
\par By the time Jaime and his column reached the castle, all of them had fled within the walls. He found Darry closed to him, just as Harrenhal had been. }{\cs28\i A chilly welcome from mine own blood. }{
\par \'93Sound the horn,\'94 he commanded. Ser Kennos of Kayce unslung the Horn of Herrock and let it wind. As he waited for a response from the castle, Jaime eyed the banner floating brown and crimson above his cousin\rquote s barbican. La
ncel had taken to quartering the lion of Lannister with the Darry plowman, it would seem. He saw his uncle\rquote s hand in that, as in Lancel\rquote 
s choice of bride. House Darry had ruled these lands since the Andals cast down the First Men. No doubt Ser Kevan realiz
ed that his son would have an easier time of it if the peasants saw him as a continuation of the old line, holding these lands by right of marriage rather than royal decree. }{\cs28\i Kevan should be Tommen\rquote 
s Hand. Harys Swyft is a toad, and my sister is a fool if she thinks elsewise.}{ 
\par The castle gates swung open slowly. \'93My coz will not have room to accommodate a thousand men,\'94 Jaime told Strongboar. \'93We\rquote ll make camp beneath the western wall. I want the perimeters ditched and staked. There are still bands of outlaws
 in these parts.\'94 
\par \'93They\rquote d need to be mad to attack a force as strong as ours.\'94 
\par \'93Mad or starving.\'94 Until he had a better notion of these outlaws and their strength, Jaime was not inclined to take any risks with his defenses. \'93Ditched and staked,\'94 he said 
again, before spurring Honor toward the gate. Ser Dermot rode beside him with the royal stag and lion, and Ser Hugo Vance with the white standard of the Kingsguard. Jaime had charged Red Ronnet with the task of delivering Wylis Manderly to Maidenpool, so 
he would not need to look on him henceforth. 
\par Pia rode with Jaime\rquote s squires, on the gelding Peck had found for her. \'93It\rquote s like some toy castle,\'94 Jaime heard her say. }{\cs28\i She\rquote s known no home but Harrenhal,}{ he reflected. }{\cs28\i 
Every castle in the realm will seem small to her, except the Rock.}{ 
\par Josmyn Peckleton was saying the same thing. \'93You must not judge by Harrenhal. Black Harren built too big.\'94 Pia listened as solemnly as a girl of five being lessoned by her septa. }{\cs28\i That\rquote s all she is, a little girl in a woman\rquote 
s body, scarred and scared.}{ Peck was taken with her, though. Jaime suspected that the boy had never known a woman, and Pia was still pretty enough, so long as she kept her mouth closed. }{\cs28\i There\rquote 
s no harm in him bedding her, I suppose, so long as she\rquote s willing. }{
\par One of the Mountain\rquote s men had tried to rape the girl at Harrenhal, and had seemed honestly perplexed when Jaime commanded Ilyn Payne to take his head off. \'93I had her before, a hunnerd times,\'94 he kept saying as they forced him to his knees. 
\'93A hunnerd times, m\rquote lord. We all had her.\'94 When Ser Ilyn presented Pia with his head, she had smiled through her ruined teeth. 
\par Darry had changed hands several times during the fighting, and its castle had been burned once and sacked at least twice, but Lancel had seemingly 
wasted little time setting things to rights. The castle gates were newly hung, raw oaken planks reinforced with iron studs. A new stable was going up where an older one had been put to the torch. The steps to the keep had been replaced, and the shutters o
n many of the windows. Blackened stones showed where the flames had licked, but time and rain would fade those. 
\par Within the walls, crossbowmen walked the ramparts, some in crimson cloaks and lion-crested helms, others in the blue and grey of House Frey. As Jaime trotted across the yard, chickens ran out from under Honor\rquote 
s hooves, sheep bleated, and peasants stared at him with sullen eyes. }{\cs28\i Armed peasants,}{ he did not fail to note. Some had scythes, some staves, some hoes sharpened to cruel points. There were a
xes in evidence as well, and he spied several bearded men with red, seven-pointed stars sewn onto ragged, filthy tunics. }{\cs28\i More bloody sparrows. Where do they all come from?}{ 
\par Of his uncle Kevan he saw no sign. Nor of Lancel. Only a maester emerged to greet him, with a grey robe flapping about his skinny legs. \'93
Lord Commander, Darry is honored by this . . . unexpected visit. You must forgive our lack of preparations. We had been given to understand that you were bound for Riverrun.\'94 
\par \'93Darry was on my way,\'94 lied Jaime. }{\cs28\i Riverrun will keep.}{ And if perchance the siege had ended before he reached the castle, he would be spared the need to take up arms against House Tully. 
\par Dismounting, he handed Honor to a stableboy. \'93Will I find my uncle here?\'94 He did not supply a name. Ser Kevan was the only uncle he had left, the last surviving son of Tytos Lannister. 
\par \'93No, my lord. Ser Kevan took his leave of us after the wedding.\'94 The maester pulled at the chain collar, as if it had grown too tight for him. \'93I know Lord Lance
l will be pleased to see you and . . . and all your gallant knights. Though it pains me to confess that Darry cannot feed so many.\'94 
\par \'93We have our own provisions. You are?\'94 
\par \'93Maester Ottomore, if it please my lord. Lady Amerei wished to welcome you herself, but she is seeing to the preparation of a feast in your honor. It is her hope that you and your chief knights and captains will join us at table this evening.\'94 

\par \'93A hot meal would be most welcome. The days have been cold and wet.\'94 Jaime glanced about the yard, at the bearded faces of the sparrows. }{\cs28\i Too many. And too many Freys as well.}{ \'93Where will I find Hardstone?\'94 
\par \'93We had a report of outlaws beyond the Trident. Ser Harwyn took five knights and twenty archers and went to deal with them.\'94 
\par \'93And Lord Lancel?\'94 
\par \'93He is at his prayers. His lordship has commanded us never to disturb him when he is praying.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He and Ser Bonifer should get on well.}{ \'93Very well.\'94 There would be time enough to talk with his cousin later. \'93Show me to my chambers and have a bath brought up.\'94 
\par \'93If it please my lord, we have put you in the Plowman\rquote s Keep. I will show you there.\'94 
\par \'93I know the way.\'94 Jaime was no stranger to this castle. He and Cersei had been guests here twice before, once on their way to Winterfell with Robert, and again on the way back to King\rquote 
s Landing. Though small as castles went, it was larger than an inn, with good hunting along the river. Robert Baratheon had never been never loath to impose upon the hospitality of his subjects. 
\par The keep was much as he recalled it. \'93The walls are still bare,\'94 Jaime observed as the maester led him down a gallery. 
\par \'93Lord Lancel hopes one day to cover them with hangings,\'94 said Ottomore. \'93Scenes of piety and devotion.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Piety and devotion.}{ It was all he could do not to laugh. The walls ha
d been bare on his first visit too. Tyrion had pointed out the squares of darker stone where tapestries had once hung. Ser Raymun could remove the hangings, but not the marks they\rquote 
d left. Later, the Imp had slipped a handful of stags to one of Darry\rquote s serv
ing men for the key to the cellar where the missing tapestries were hidden. He showed them to Jaime by the light of a candle, grinning; woven portraits of all the Targaryen kings, from the first Aegon to the second Aenys. \'93If I tell Robert, mayhaps he
\rquote ll make }{\cs28\i me}{ Lord of Darry,\'94 the dwarf said, chortling. 
\par Maester Ottomore led Jaime to the top of the keep. \'93I trust you will be comfortable here, my lord. There is a privy, when nature calls. Your window looks out upon the godswood. The bedchamber adjoins her ladyship\rquote s, with a servant\rquote 
s cell between.\'94 
\par \'93These were Lord Darry\rquote s own apartments.\'94 
\par \'93Yes, my lord.\'94 
\par \'93My cousin is too kind. I did not intend to put Lancel out of his own bedchamber.\'94 
\par \'93Lord Lancel has been sleeping in the sept.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Sleeping with the Mother and the Maiden, when he has a warm wife just through that door?}{ Jaime did not know whether to laugh or weep. }{\cs28\i Maybe he is praying for his cock to harden.}{ In King\rquote 
s Landing it had been rumored that Lancel\rquote s wounds had left him incapable. }{\cs28\i Still, he ought to have sense enough to try.}{ His cousin\rquote 
s hold on his new lands would not be secure until he fathered a son on his half-Darry wife. Jaime had begun to rue the impulse that had brought him here. He gave thanks to Ottomore, reminded him about the bath, and had Peck see him out. 
\par The lord\rquote s bedchamber had changed since his last visit, and not for the better. Old stale rushes covered the floor in place of the fine Myrish carpet that had been there previously, and all the furnishings were new and crudely made. Se
r Raymun Darry\rquote s bed had been large enough to sleep six, with brown velvet draperies and oakwood posts carved with vines and leaves; Lancel\rquote 
s was a lumpy straw pallet, placed beneath the window where the first light of day would be sure to wake him. The other bed had no doubt been burned or smashed or stolen, but even so . . . 
\par When the tub arrived, Little Lew pulled off Jaime\rquote s boots and helped remove his golden hand. Peck and Garrett hauled water, and Pia found him something clean to sup in. The girl glan
ced at him shyly as she shook his doublet out. Jaime was uncomfortably aware of the curve of hip and breast beneath her roughspun brown dress. He found himself remembering the things that Pia had whispered to him at Harrenhal, the night that Qyburn sent h
er to his bed. }{\cs28\i Sometimes when I\rquote m with some man,}{ she\rquote d said, }{\cs28\i I close my eyes and pretend it\rquote s you on top of me.}{ 
\par He was grateful when the bath was deep enough to conceal his arousal. As he lowered himself into the steaming water, he recalled another bath, the one he\rquote 
d shared with Brienne. He had been feverish and weak from loss of blood, and the heat had made him so dizzy he found himself saying things better left unsaid. This time he had no such excuse. }{\cs28\i Remember your vows. Pia is more fit for Tyrion
\rquote s bed than yours.}{ \'93Fetch me soap and a stiff brush,\'94 he told Peck. \'93Pia, you may leave us.\'94 
\par \'93Aye, m\rquote lord. Thank you, m\rquote lord.\'94 She covered her mouth when she spoke, to hide her broken teeth. 
\par \'93Do you want her?\'94 Jaime asked Peck, when she was gone. 
\par The squire turned beet red. 
\par \'93If she\rquote ll have you, take her. She\rquote ll teach you a few things you\rquote ll find useful on your wedding night, I don\rquote t doubt, and you\rquote re not like to get a bastard by her.\'94 Pia had spread her legs for half his father
\rquote s army and never quickened; most like the girl was barren. \'93If you bed her, though, be kind to her.\'94 
\par \'93Kind, my lord? How . . . how would I . . . ?\'94 
\par \'93Sweet words. Gentle touches. You don\rquote t want to wed her, but so long as you\rquote re abed treat her as you would your bride.\'94 
\par The lad nodded. \'93My lord, I . . . where should I take her? There\rquote s never a place to . . . to . . .\'94 
\par \'93. . . to be alone?\'94 Jaime grinned. \'93We\rquote ll be at supper several hours. The straw looks lumpy, but it should serve.\'94 
\par Peck\rquote s eyes grew wide. \'93His lordship\rquote s bed?\'94 
\par \'93You\rquote ll feel a lord yourself when you\rquote re done, if Pia knows her business.\'94 }{\cs28\i And someone ought to make some use of that miserable straw mattress.}{ 
\par When he descended for the feast that night, Jaime Lannister wore a doublet of red velvet slashed with cloth-of-gold, and
 a golden chain studded with black diamonds. He had strapped on his golden hand as well, polished to a fine bright sheen. This was no fit place to wear his whites. His duty awaited him at Riverrun; a darker need had brought him here. 
\par Darry\rquote s great hall was great only by courtesy. Trestle tables crowded it from wall to wall, and the ceiling rafters were black with smoke. Jaime had been seated on the dais, to the right of Lancel\rquote s empty chair. \'93
Will my cousin not be joining us for supper?\'94 he asked as he sat down. 
\par \'93My lord prefers to fast,\'94 said Lancel\rquote s wife, the Lady Amerei. \'93He\rquote s sick with grief for the poor High Septon.\'94
 She was a long-legged, full-breasted, strapping girl of some eight-and-ten years; a healthy wench to look at her, though her pinched, chinless face reminded Jaime of his late and unlamented cousin Cleos, who had always looked somewhat like a weasel. 

\par }{\cs28\i Fasting? He is an even bigger fool than I suspected.}{ His cousin should be busy fathering a little weasel-faced heir on his widow instead of starving himself to death. He wondered what Ser Kevan might have had to say about his son\rquote 
s new fervor. Could that be the reason for his uncle\rquote s abrupt departure? 
\par Over bowls of bean-and-bacon soup Lady Amerei told Jaime how her first husband had been slain by Ser Gregor Clegane when the Freys were still fighting for Robb Stark. \'93I begged him not to go, but my Pate was oh so }{\cs28\i very}{
 brave, and swore he was the man to slay that monster. He wanted to make a great name for himself.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i We all do.}{ \'93When I was a squire I told myself I\rquote d be the man to slay the Smiling Knight.\'94 
\par \'93The Smiling Knight?\'94 She sounded lost. \'93Who was that?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i The Mountain of my boyhood. Half as big but twice as mad. }{
\par \'93An outlaw, long dead. No one who need concern your ladyship.\'94 
\par Amerei\rquote s lip trembled. Tears rolled from her brown eyes. 
\par \'93You must forgive my daughter,\'94 said an older woman. Lady Amerei had brought a score of Freys to Darry with her; a sister, an uncle, a half uncle, various cousins . . . and her mother, who had been born a Darry. \'93She still grieves for her father.
\'94 
\par \'93Outlaws }{\cs28\i killed}{ him,\'94 sobbed Lady Amerei. \'93Father had only gone out to ransom Petyr Pimple. He brought them the gold they asked for, but they hung him anyway.\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i Hanged,}{ Ami. Your father was not a tapestry.\'94 Lady Mariya turned back to Jaime. \'93I believe you knew him, ser.\'94 
\par \'93We were squires together once, at Crakehall.\'94 He would not go so far as to claim they had been friends. When Jaime had arrived, Merrett Frey had been the castle bully, lording it over all the younger boys. }{\cs28\i Then he tried to bully me.}{ 
\'93He was . . . very strong.\'94 It was the only praise that came to mind. Merrett had been slow and clumsy and stupid, but he }{\cs28\i was}{ strong. 
\par \'93You fought against the Kingswood Brotherhood together,\'94 sniffed Lady Amerei. \'93Father used to tell me stories.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Father used to boast and lie, you mean.}{ \'93We did.\'94 Frey\rquote s chief contributions to the fight had consisted of contracting the pox from a camp follower and getting himself captured by the White Fawn. The outlaw queen burned he
r sigil into his arse before ransoming him back to Sumner Crakehall. Merrett had not been able to sit down for a fortnight, though Jaime doubted that the red-hot iron was half so nasty as the kettles of shit his fellow squires made him eat once he was ret
urned. }{\cs28\i Boys are the cruelest creatures on the earth.}{ He slipped his golden hand around his wine cup and raised it up. \'93To Merrett\rquote s memory,\'94 he said. It was easier to drink to the man than to talk of him. 
\par After the toast Lady Amerei stopped weeping and the table talk turned to wolves, of the four-footed kind. Ser Danwell Frey claimed there were more of them about than even his grandfather could remember. \'93They\rquote 
ve lost all fear of men. Packs of them attacked our baggage train on our way down from the Twins. Our archers had to feather a dozen before the others fled.\'94
 Ser Addam Marbrand confessed that their own column had faced similar troubles on their way up from King\rquote s Landing. 
\par Jaime concentrated on the fare before him, tearing off chunks of bread with his left hand and fumbling at his wine cup with his right. He watched Addam Marbrand charm the girl beside him, watched Steffon Swyft refight the battle for King\rquote 
s Landing with bread and nuts and carrots. Ser Kennos pulled a serving girl into his lap, urging h
er to stroke his horn, whilst Ser Dermot regaled some squires with tales of knight errantry in the rainwood. Farther down the table Hugo Vance had closed his eyes. }{\cs28\i Brooding on the mysteries of life,}{ thought Jaime. }{\cs28\i 
That, or napping between courses.}{ He turned back to Lady Mariya. \'93The outlaws who killed your husband . . . was it Lord Beric\rquote s band?\'94 
\par \'93So we thought, at first.\'94 Though Lady Mariya\rquote s hair was streaked with grey, she was still a handsome woman. \'93The killers scattered when they left Oldstones. Lord
 Vypren tracked one band to Fairmarket, but lost them there. Black Walder led hounds and hunters into Hag\rquote 
s Mire after the others. The peasants denied seeing them, but when questioned sharply they sang a different song. They spoke of a one-eyed man and another who wore a yellow cloak . . . and a woman, cloaked and hooded.\'94 
\par \'93A woman?\'94 He would have thought that the White Fawn would have taught Merrett to stay clear of outlaw wenches. \'93There was a woman in the Kingswood Brotherhood as well.\'94 
\par \'93I know of her.\'94 }{\cs28\i How not,}{ her tone suggested, }{\cs28\i when she left her mark upon my husband?}{ \'93
The White Fawn was young and fair, they say. This hooded woman is neither. The peasants would have us believe that her face was torn and scarred, and her eyes terrible to look upon. They claim she led the outlaws.\'94 
\par \'93Led them?\'94 Jaime found that hard to believe. \'93Beric Dondarrion and the red priest . . .\'94 
\par \'93. . . were not seen.\'94 Lady Mariya sounded certain. 
\par \'93Dondarrion\rquote s dead,\'94 said Strongboar. \'93The Mountain drove a knife through his eye, we have men with us who saw it.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s one tale,\'94 said Addam Marbrand. \'93Others will tell you that Lord Beric can\rquote t be killed.\'94 
\par \'93Ser Harwyn says those tales are lies.\'94 Lady Amerei wound a braid around her finger. \'93He has promised me Lord Beric\rquote s head. He\rquote s very gallant.\'94 She was blushing beneath her tears. 
\par Jaime thought back on the head he\rquote d given to Pia. He could almost hear his little brother chuckle. }{\cs28\i Whatever became of giving women flowers?}{ Tyrion might have asked. He would have had a few choice words for Harwyn Plumm as well, though }
{\cs28\i gallant}{ would not have been one of them. Plumm\rquote s brothers were big, fleshy fellows with thick necks and red faces; loud and lusty, quick to laugh, quick to anger, quick to forgive. Harwyn was a different sort of 
Plumm; hard-eyed and taciturn, unforgiving . . . and deadly, with his hammer in his hand. A good man to command a garrison, but not a man to love. }{\cs28\i Although . . . }{Jaime gazed at Lady Amerei. 
\par The serving men were bringing out the fish course, a river pike baked in a crust of herbs and crushed nuts. Lancel\rquote 
s lady tasted it, approved, and commanded that the first portion be served to Jaime. As they set the fish before him, she leaned across her husband\rquote s place to touch his golden hand. \'93}{\cs28\i You}{ could kill Lord Ber
ic, Ser Jaime. You slew the Smiley Knight. Please, my lord, I beg you, stay and help us with Lord Beric and the Hound.\'94 Her pale fingers caressed his golden ones. 
\par }{\cs28\i Does she think that I can feel that?}{ \'93The Sword of the Morning slew the Smiling Knight, my lady. Ser Arthur Dayne, a better knight than me.\'94 Jaime pulled back his golden fingers and turned once more to Lady Mariya. \'93
How far did Black Walder track this hooded woman and her men?\'94 
\par \'93His hounds picked up their scent again north of Hag\rquote s Mire,\'94 the older woman told him. \'93He swears that he was no more than half a day behind them when they vanished into the Neck.\'94 
\par \'93Let them rot there,\'94 declared Ser Kennos cheerfully. \'93If the gods are good, they\rquote ll be swallowed up in quicksand or gobbled down by lizard-lions.\'94 
