\par Their supper in the septry was as strange a meal as Brienne had ever eaten, though not at all unpleasant. The food was plain, but very good; there were loaves of crusty bread still warm from the ovens, crocks of fresh-churned butter, honey from the septry
\rquote s hives, and a thick stew of crabs, mussels, and at least three different kinds of fish. Septon Meribald and Ser Hyle drank the mead the brothers made, and pronou
nced it excellent, whilst she and Podrick contented themselves with more sweet cider. Nor was the meal a somber one. Meribald pronounced a prayer before the food was served, and whilst the brothers ate at four long trestle tables, one of their number play
ed for them on the high harp, filling the hall with soft sweet sounds. When the Elder Brother excused the musician to take his own meal, Brother Narbert and another proctor took turns reading from }{\cs28\i The Seven-Pointed Star.}{ 
\par By the time the readings were completed, the last of the food had been cleared away by the novices whose task it was to serve. Most were boys near Podrick\rquote 
s age, or younger, but there were grown men as well, amongst them the big gravedigger they had encountered on the hill, who walked with 
the awkward lurching gait of one half-crippled. As the hall emptied, the Elder Brother asked Narbert to show Podrick and Ser Hyle to their pallets in the cloisters. \'93
You will not mind sharing a cell, I hope? It is not large, but you will find it comfortable.\'94 
\par \'93I want to stay with ser,\'94 said Podrick. \'93I mean, my lady.\'94 
\par \'93What you and Lady Brienne may do elsewhere is between you and the Seven,\'94 said Brother Narbert, \'93but on the Quiet Isle, men and women do not sleep beneath the same roof unless they are wed.\'94 
\par \'93We have some modest cottages set aside for the women who visit us, be they noble ladies or common village girls,\'94 said the Elder Brother. \'93
They are not oft used, but we keep them clean and dry. Lady Brienne, would you allow me to show you the way?\'94 
\par \'93Yes, thank you. Podrick, go with Ser Hyle. We are guests of the holy brothers here. Beneath their roof, their rules.\'94 
\par The women\rquote s cottages were on the east side of the isle, looking out over a broad expanse of mud and the distant waters of the Bay of Crab
s. It was colder here than on the sheltered side, and wilder. The hill was steeper, and the path meandered back and forth through weeds and briars, wind-carved rocks, and twisted, thorny trees that clung tenaciously to the stony hillside. The Elder Brothe
r brought a lantern to light their way down. At one turn he paused. \'93On a clear night you could see the fires of Saltpans from here. Across the bay, just there.\'94 He pointed. 
\par \'93There\rquote s nothing,\'94 Brienne said. 
\par \'93Only the castle remains. Even the fisherfolk ar
e gone, the fortunate few who were out on the water when the raiders came. They watched their houses burn and listened to screams and cries float across the harbor, too fearful to land their boats. When at last they came ashore, it was to bury friends and
