Saltpans was never an important port, but ships did call there from tim
e to time. That was what the raiders wanted, a galley or a cog to carry them across the narrow sea. When none was at hand, they took their rage and desperation out upon the townsfolk. I wonder, my lady . . . what do you hope to find there?\'94 
\par \'93A girl,\'94 she told him. \'93A highborn maid of three-and-ten, with a fair face and auburn hair.\'94 
\par \'93Sansa Stark.\'94 The name was softly said. \'93You believe this poor child is with the Hound?\'94 
\par \'93The Dornishman said that she was on her way to Riverrun. Timeon. He was a sellsword, one of the Brave Companions, a killer and a raper and a liar, but I do not think he lied about this. He said that the Hound stole her and carried her away.\'94 

\par \'93I see.\'94 The path turned, and there were the cottages ahead of them. The Elder Brother had called them modest. That they were. They looked like beehives made of stone, low and rounded, windowless. \'93This one,\'94
