\par JAIME
\par The trumpets made a brazen blare, and cut the still blue air of dusk. Josmyn Peckledon was on his feet at once, scrambling for his master\rquote s swordbelt. 
\par }{\cs28\i The boy has good instincts.}{ \'93Outlaws don\rquote t blow trumpets to herald their arrival,\'94 Jaime told him. \'93I shan\rquote t need my sword. That will be my cousin, the Warden of the West.\'94 
\par The riders were dismounting when he emerged from his tent; half a dozen knights, and twoscore mounted archers and men-at-arms. }{\cs28\i \'93Jaime!\'94}{ roared a shaggy man clad in gilded ringmail and a fox-fur cloak. \'93
So gaunt, and all in white! And bearded too!\'94 
\par \'93This? Mere stubble, against that mane of yours, coz.\'94 Ser Daven\rquote 
s bristling beard and bushy mustache grew into sidewhiskers as thick as a hedgerow, and those into the tangled yellow thicket atop his head, matted down by the helm he was removing. Somewhere in the
 midst of all that hair lurked a pug nose and a pair of lively hazel eyes. \'93Did some outlaw steal your razor?\'94 
\par \'93I vowed I would not let my hair be cut until my father was avenged.\'94 For a man who looked so leonine, Daven Lannister sounded oddly sheepish. \'93The Young Wolf got to Karstark first, though. Robbed me of my vengeance.\'94
 He handed his helm to a squire and pushed his fingers through his hair where the weight of the steel had crushed it down. \'93I like a bit of hair. The nights grow colder, and a little 
foliage helps to keep your face warm. Aye, and Aunt Genna always said I had a brick for a chin.\'94 He clasped Jaime by the arms. \'93We feared for you after the Whispering Wood. Heard Stark\rquote s direwolf tore out your throat.\'94 
\par \'93Did you weep bitter tears for me, coz?\'94 
\par \'93Half of Lannisport was mourning. The female half.\'94 Ser Daven\rquote s gaze went to Jaime\rquote s stump. \'93So it\rquote s true. The bastards took your sword hand.\'94 
\par \'93I have a new one, made of gold. There\rquote s much to be said for being one-handed. I drink less wine for fear of spilling and am seldom inclined to scratch my arse at court.\'94 
\par \'93Aye, there\rquote s that. Maybe I should have mine off as well.\'94 His cousin laughed. \'93Was it Catelyn Stark who took it?\'94 
\par \'93Vargo Hoat.\'94 }{\cs28\i Where do these tales come from? }{
\par \'93The Qohorik?\'94 Ser Daven spat. \'93That\rquote s for him and all his Brave Companions. I told your father I would forage for him, but he refused me. Some tasks are fit for lions, he said, but foraging is best left for goats and dogs.\'94 
\par Lord Tywin\rquote s very words, Jaime knew; he could almost hear his father\rquote s voice. \'93Come inside, coz. We need to talk.\'94 
\par Garrett had lit the braziers, and their glowing coals filled Jaime\rquote s tent with a ruddy heat. Ser Daven shrugged out of his cloak and tossed it at Little Lew. \'93You a Piper, boy?\'94 he growled. \'93You have a runty look to you.\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote m Lewys Piper, if it please my lord.\'94 
\par \'93I beat your brother bloody in a m\'eal\'e9e once. The runty little fool took offense when I asked him if that was his sister dancing naked on his shield.\'94 
\par \'93She\rquote s the sigil of our House. We don\rquote t have a sister.\'94 
\par \'93More\rquote s the pity. Your sigil has nice teats. What sort of man hides behind a naked woman, though? Every time I thumped your brother\rquote s shield, I felt unchivalrous.\'94 
\par \'93Enough,\'94 said Jaime, laughing. \'93Leave him be.\'94 Pia was mulling wine for them, stirring the kettle with a spoon. \'93I need to know what I can expect to find at Riverrun.\'94 
\par His cousin shrugged. \'93The siege drags on. The Blackfish sits inside the castle, we sit outside in our camps. Bloody boring, if you want the truth.\'94 Ser Daven seated himself upon a camp stool. \'93Tully ought to make a sortie, to remind us all we
\rquote re still at war. Be nice if he culled some Freys too. Ryman, for a start. The man\rquote s drunk more oft than not. Oh, and Edwyn. Not as thick as his father, but as full of hate as a boil\rquote s full of pus. And our own Ser Emmon . . . no, }{
\cs28\i Lord}{ Emmon, Seven save us, must not forget his new title . . . our Lord of Riverrun does nought but try to tell me how to run the siege. He wants me to take the castle without }{\cs28\i damaging}{ it, since it is now his lordly seat.\'94 
\par \'93Is that wine hot yet?\'94 Jaime asked Pia. 
\par \'93Yes, m\rquote lord.\'94 The girl covered her mouth when she spoke. Peck served the wine on a golden platter. Ser Daven pulled off his gloves and took a cup. \'93Thank you, boy. Who might you be?\'94 
\par \'93Josmyn Peckledon, if it please my lord.\'94 
\par \'93Peck was a hero on the Blackwater,\'94 Jaime said. \'93He slew two knights and captured two more.\'94 
\par \'93You must be more dangerous than you look, lad. Is that a beard, or did you forget to wash the dirt off your face? Stannis Baratheon\rquote s wife has a thicker mustache. How old are you?\'94 
\par \'93Fifteen, ser.\'94 
\par Ser Daven snorted. \'93You know the best thing about heroes, Jaime? They all die young and leave more women for the rest of us.\'94 He tossed the cup back to the squire. \'93Fill that full again, and I\rquote ll call you hero too. I have a thirst.\'94 

\par Jaime lifted his own cup left-handed and took a swallow. The warmth spread through his chest. \'93You were speaking of the Freys you wanted dead. Ryman, Edwyn, Emmon . . .\'94 
\par \'93And Walder Rivers,\'94 Daven said, \'93that whoreson. Hates that he\rquote s a bastard, and hates everyone who\rquote s not. Ser Perwyn seems a decent fellow, though, might as well spare him. The women too. I\rquote 
m to marry one, I hear. Your father might have seen fit to consult with me about this marriage, by the bye. My own father was treating with Paxter Redwyne before Oxcross, did you know? Redwyne has a nicely dowered daughter . . .\'94 
\par \'93Desmera?\'94 Jaime laughed. \'93How well do you like freckles?\'94 
\par \'93If my choice is Freys or freckles, well . . . half of Lord Walder\rquote s brood look like stoats.\'94 
\par \'93Only half? Be thankful. I saw Lancel\rquote s bride at Darry.\'94 
\par \'93Gatehouse Ami, gods be good. I couldn\rquote t believe that Lancel picked that one. What\rquote s wrong with that boy?\'94 
\par \'93He\rquote s grown pious,\'94 said Jaime, \'93but it wasn\rquote t him who did the picking. Lady Amerei\rquote s mother is a Darry. Our uncle thought she\rquote d help Lancel win the Darry smallfolk.\'94 
\par \'93How, by fucking them? You know why they call her Gatehouse Ami? She raises her portcullis for every knight who happens by. Lancel had best find an armorer to make him a horned helm.\'94 
\par \'93That won\rquote t be necessary. Our coz is off to King\rquote s Landing to take vows as one of the High Septon\rquote s swords.\'94 
\par Ser Daven could not have looked more astonished if Jaime had told him that Lancel had decided to become a mummer\rquote s monkey. \'93Not truly? You are japing with me. Gatehouse Ami must be more stoatish than I\rquote 
d heard if she could drive the boy to }{\cs28\i that.}{\'94 
\par When Jaime had taken his leave of Lady Amerei, she had been weeping softly at the dissolution of her m
arriage whilst letting Lyle Crakehall console her. Her tears had not troubled him half so much as the hard looks on the faces of her kin as they stood about the yard. \'93I hope you do not intend to take vows as well, coz,\'94 he said to Daven. \'93
The Freys are prickly where marriage contracts are concerned. I would hate to disappoint them again.\'94 
\par Ser Daven snorted. \'93I\rquote ll wed and bed my stoat, never fear. I know what happened to Robb Stark. From what Edwyn tells me, though, I\rquote d best pick one who hasn\rquote t flowered yet, or I\rquote 
m like to find that Black Walder has been there first. I\rquote ll wager he\rquote s had Gatehouse Ami, and more than thrice. Maybe that explains Lancel\rquote s godliness, and his father\rquote s mood.\'94 
\par \'93You have seen Ser Kevan?\'94 
\par \'93Aye. He passed here on his way west. I ask
ed him to help us take the castle, but Kevan would have none of it. He brooded the whole time he was here. Courteous enough, but chilly. I swore to him that I never asked to be made Warden of the West, that the honor should have gone to him, and he declar
ed that he held no grudge against me, but you would never have known it from his tone. He stayed three days and hardly said three words to me. Would that he\rquote 
d remained, I could have used his counsel. Our friends of Frey would not have dared vex Ser Kevan the way that they\rquote ve been vexing me.\'94 
\par \'93Tell me,\'94 said Jaime. 
\par \'93I would, but where to begin? Whilst I\rquote ve been building rams and siege towers, Ryman Frey has raised a gibbet. Every day at dawn he brings forth Edmure Tully, drapes a noose around his neck, and 
threatens to hang him unless the castle yields. The Blackfish pays his mummer\rquote s show no mind, so come evenfall Lord Edmure is taken down again. His wife\rquote s with child, did you know?\'94 
\par He hadn\rquote t. \'93Edmure bedded her, after the Red Wedding?\'94 
\par \'93He was bedding her }{\cs28\i during}{ the Red Wedding. Roslin\rquote s a pretty little thing, hardly stoatish at all. And fond of Edmure, queerly. Perwyn tells me she\rquote s praying for a girl.\'94 
\par Jaime considered that a moment. \'93Once Edmure\rquote s son is born, Lord Walder will have no more need of Edmure.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s how I see it too. Our good-uncle Emm . . . ah, }{\cs28\i Lord}{
 Emmon, that is . . . he wants Edmure hanged at once. The presence of a Tully Lord of Riverrun distresses him almost as much as the prospective birth of yet another. Daily he beseeches me to }{\cs28\i make}{
 Ser Ryman dangle Tully, never mind how. Meanwhile, I have Lord Gawen Westerling tugging at my other sleeve. The Blackfish has his lady wife inside the castle, along with three of his snot-nosed whelps. His lordship fears Tully will kill them if the 
Freys hang Edmure. One of them is the Young Wolf\rquote s little queen.\'94 
\par Jaime had met Jeyne Westerling, he thought, though he could not recall what she looked like. }{\cs28\i She must be fair indeed, to have been worth a kingdom.}{ \'93Ser Brynden won\rquote t kill children,\'94 he assured his cousin. \'93He\rquote 
s not as black a fish as that.\'94 He was beginning to grasp why Riverrun had not yet fallen. \'93Tell me of your dispositions, coz.\'94 
\par \'93We have the castle well encircled. Ser Ryman and the Freys are north of the Tumblestone. South of Red For
k sits Lord Emmon, with Ser Forley Prester and with what remains of your old host, plus the river lords who came over to us after the Red Wedding. A sullen lot, I don\rquote 
t mind saying. Good for sulking in their tents, but not much more. Mine own camp is between the rivers, facing the moat and Riverrun\rquote s main gates. We\rquote 
ve thrown a boom across the Red Fork, downstream of the castle. Manfryd Yew and Raynard Ruttiger have charge of its defense, so no one can escape by boat. I gave them nets as well, to fish. It helps keep us fed.\'94 
\par \'93Can we starve the castle out?\'94 
\par Ser Daven shook his head. \'93The Blackfish expelled all the useless mouths from Riverrun and picked this country clean. He has enough stores to keep man and horse alive for two full years.\'94 
\par \'93And how well are we provisioned?\'94 
\par \'93So long as there are fish in the rivers, we won\rquote t starve, though I don\rquote t know how we\rquote 
re going to feed the horses. The Freys are hauling food and fodder down from the Twins, but Ser Ryman claims he does not have enough to share, so we 
must forage for ourselves. Half the men I send off to look for food do not return. Some are deserting. Others we find ripening under trees, with ropes about their necks.\'94 
\par \'93We came on some, the day before last,\'94 said Jaime. Addam Marbrand\rquote s scouts had foun
d them, hanging black-faced beneath a crabapple tree. The corpses had been stripped naked, and each man had a crabapple shoved between his teeth. None bore any wounds; plainly, they had yielded. Strongboar had grown furious at that, vowing bloody vengeanc
e on the heads of any men who would truss up warriors to die like suckling pigs. 
\par \'93It might have been outlaws,\'94 Ser Daven said, when Jaime told the tale, \'93or not. There are still bands of northmen about. And these Lords of the Trident may have bent their knees, but methinks their hearts are still . . . wolfish.\'94 
\par Jaime glanced at his two younger squires, who were hovering near the braziers pretending not to listen. Lewys Piper and Garrett Paege were both the sons of river lords. He had grown fond of both of them and would hate to have to give them to Ser Ilyn. 
\'93The ropes suggest Dondarrion to me.\'94 
\par \'93Your lightning lord\rquote s not the only man who knows how to tie a noose. Don\rquote t get me started on Lord Beric. He\rquote s here, he\rquote s there, he\rquote s everywhere, but when you send
 men after him, he melts away like dew. The river lords are helping him, never doubt it. A bloody marcher lord, if you can believe it. One day you hear the man is dead, the next they\rquote re saying how he can\rquote t be killed.\'94
 Ser Daven put his wine cup down. \'93My scouts report fires in the high places at night. Signal fires, they think . . . as if there were a ring of watchers all around us. And there are fires in the villages as well. Some new god . . .\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i No, an old one.}{ \'93Thoros is with Dondarrion, the fat Myrish priest who used to drink with Robert.\'94 His golden hand was on the table. Jaime touched it and watched the gold glimmer in the sullen light of the braziers. \'93We\rquote 
ll deal with Dondarrion if we have to, but the Blackfish must come first. He has to know his cause is hopeless. Have you tried to treat with him?\'94 
\par \'93Ser Ryman did. Rode up to the castle gates half-drunk and blustering, making threats. The Blackfish appeared on the ramparts long enough to say that he would not waste fair words on foul men. Then he put an arrow in the rump of Ryman\rquote 
s palfrey. The horse reared, Frey fell into the mud, and I laughed so hard I almost pissed myself. If it had been me inside the castle, I would have put that arrow through Ryman\rquote s lying throat.\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote ll wear a gorget when I treat with them,\'94 said Jaime, with a half smile. \'93I mean to offer him generous terms.\'94 If he could end this siege without bloodshed, then it could not be said that he had taken up arms against House Tully. 

\par \'93You are welcome to try, my lord, but I doubt that words will win the day. We need to storm the castle.\'94 
\par There had been a time, not so long ago, when Jaime would doubtless have urged the same course. He knew he could not sit here for two years to starve the Blackfish out. \'93Whatever we do needs to be done quickly,\'94 he told Ser Daven. \'93
My place is back at King\rquote s Landing, with the king.\'94 
\par \'93Aye,\'94 his cousin said. \'93I don\rquote t doubt your sister needs you. Why did she send off Kevan? I thought she\rquote d make him Hand.\'94 
\par \'93He would not take it.\'94 }{\cs28\i He was not as blind as I was. }{
\par \'93Kevan should be the Warden of the West. Or you. It\rquote s not that I\rquote m not grateful for the honor, mind you, but our uncle\rquote s twice my age and has more experience of command. I hope he knows I never asked for this.\'94 
\par \'93He knows.\'94 
\par \'93How is Cersei? As beautiful as ever?\'94 
\par \'93Radiant.\'94 }{\cs28\i Fickle.}{ \'93Golden.\'94 }{\cs28\i False as fool\rquote s gold.}{ Last night he dreamed he\rquote d found her fucking Moon Boy. He\rquote d killed the fool and smashed his sister\rquote 
s teeth to splinters with his golden hand, just as Gregor Clegane had done to poor Pia. In his dreams Jaime always had two hands; one was made of gold, but it worked just like the other. \'93The sooner we are done with Riverrun, the sooner I\rquote 
ll be back at Cersei\rquote s side.\'94 What Jaime would do then he did not know. 
\par He talked with his cousin for another hour before the Warden of the West finally took his leave. When he was gone, Jaime donned his gold hand and brown cloak to walk amongst the tents. 
\par If truth be told, he liked this life. He felt more comfortable amongst soldiers in the field than he ever had at court. And his men seemed comfortable with him as well. At one cookfire three crossbowmen offered him a share of a hare they\rquote 
d caught. At another a young knight asked his counsel on the best way to defend against a wa
rhammer. Down beside the river, he watched two washerwomen jousting in the shallows, mounted on the shoulders of a pair of men-at-arms. The girls were half-drunk and half-naked, laughing and snapping rolled-up cloaks at one another as a dozen other men ur
ged them on. Jaime bet a copper star on the blond girl riding Raff the Sweetling, and lost it when the two of them went down splashing amongst the reeds. 
\par Across the river wolves were howling, and the wind was gusting through a stand of willows, making their branches writhe and whisper. Jaime found Ser Ilyn Payne alone outside his tent, honing his greatsword with a whetstone. \'93Come,\'94
 he said, and the silent knight rose, smiling thinly. }{\cs28\i He enjoys this,}{ he realized. }{\cs28\i It pleases him to humiliate me nightly. It might please him even more to kill me.}{
 He liked to believe that he was getting better, but the improvement was slow and not without cost. Underneath his steel and wool and boiled leather Jaime Lannister was a tapestry of cuts and scabs and bruises. 
\par A sentry challenged them as they led their horses from the camp. Jaime clapped the man\rquote s shoulder with his golden hand. \'93Stay vigilant. There are wolves about.\'94
 They rode back along the Red Fork to the ruins of a burned village they had passed that afternoon. It 
was there they danced their midnight dance, amongst blackened stones and old cold cinders. For a little while Jaime had the better of it. Perhaps his old skill }{\cs28\i was}{
 coming back, he allowed himself to think. Perhaps tonight it would be Payne who went to sleep bruised and bloody. 
\par It was as if Ser Ilyn heard his thoughts. He parried Jaime\rquote s last cut lazily and launched a counterattack that drove Jaime back into the river, where his boot slipped out from under him in the mud. He ended on his knees, with the silent knight
\rquote s sword at his throat and his own lost in the reeds. In the moonlight the pockmarks on Payne\rquote s face were large as craters. He made that clacking sound that might have been a laugh and drew his sword up Jaime\rquote 
s throat till the point came to rest between his lips. Only then did he step back and sheathe his steel. 
\par }{\cs28\i I would have done better to challenge Raff the Sweetling, with a whore upon my back,}{ Jaime thought as he shook mud off his gilded hand. Part of him wanted to tear the thing off and fling 
it in the river. It was good for nothing, and the left was not much better. Ser Ilyn had gone back to the horses, leaving him to find his own feet. }{\cs28\i At least I still have two of those. }{
\par The last day of their journey was cold and gusty. The wind rattled amon
gst the branches in the bare brown woods and made the river reeds bow low along the Red Fork. Even mantled in the winter wool of the Kingsguard, Jaime could feel the iron teeth of that wind as he rode beside his cousin Daven. It was late afternoon when th
e
y sighted Riverrun, rising from the narrow point where the Tumblestone joined the Red Fork. The Tully castle looked like a great stone ship with its prow pointed downriver. Its sandstone walls were drenched in red-gold light, and seemed higher and thicker
 than Jaime had remembered. }{\cs28\i This nut will not crack easily,}{ he thought gloomily. If the Blackfish would not listen, he would have no choice but to break the vow he\rquote d made to Catelyn Stark. The vow he\rquote d sworn his king came first. 

\par The boom across the river and the three great camps of the besieging army were just as his cousin had described. Ser Ryman Frey\rquote 
s encampment north of the Tumblestone was the largest, and the most disorderly. A great grey gallows loomed above the tents, as tall as any trebuchet. On it stood a solitary figure with a rope about his neck. }{\cs28\i Edmure Tully.}{
 Jaime felt a stab of pity. }{\cs28\i To keep him standing there day after day, with that noose around his neck . . . better to have his head off and be done with it.}{ 
\par Behind the gallows, tents and cookfires spread out in ragged disarray. The Frey lordlings and their knights had raised their pavilions comfortably upstream of the latrine trenches; downstream were muddy hovels, wayns, and oxcarts. \'93Ser Ryman don
\rquote t want his boys getting bored, so he gives them whores and cockfights and boar baiting,\'94 Ser Daven said. \'93He\rquote s even got himself a bloody }{\cs28\i singer.}{
 Our aunt brought Whitesmile Wat from Lannisport, if you can believe it, so Ryman had to have a singer too. Couldn\rquote t we just dam the river and drown the whole lot of them, coz?\'94 
\par Jaime could see archers moving behind the merlons on the castle ramparts. Above them streamed the banners of House Tully, the silver trout defiant on its striped field of red and blue. But the highest tower flew a different flag; 
a long white standard emblazoned with the direwolf of Stark. \'93The first time I saw Riverrun, I was a squire green as summer grass,\'94 Jaime told his cousin. \'93
Old Sumner Crakehall sent me to deliver a message, one he swore could not be entrusted to a raven. Lord Hoster kept me for a fortnight whilst mulling his reply, and sat me beside his daughter Lysa at every meal.\'94 
\par \'93Small wonder you took the white. I\rquote d have done the same.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, Lysa was not so fearsome as all that.\'94 She had been a pretty girl, in truth; dimpled and delicate, with long auburn hair. }{\cs28\i Timid, though. Prone to tongue-tied silences and fits of giggles, with none of Cersei\rquote s fire.}{
 Her older sister had seemed more interesting, though Catelyn was promised to some northern boy, the heir of Winterfell . . . but at that age, no girl interested Jaime half so much as Hoster\rquote 
s famous brother, who had won renown fighting the Ninepenny Kings upon the Stepstones. At table he had ignored poor Lysa, whilst pressing Brynden Tully for tales of Maelys the Monstrous and the Ebon Prince. }{\cs28\i 
Ser Brynden was younger then than I am now,}{ Jaime reflected, }{\cs28\i and I was younger than Peck.}{ 
\par The nearest ford across the Red Fork was upstream of the castle. To reach Ser Daven\rquote s camp they had to ride through Emmon Frey\rquote s, past the pavilions of the river lords who had bent their knees and been accepted back into the king\rquote 
s peace. Jaime noted the banners of Lychester and Vance, of Roote and Goodbrook, the acorns of House Smallford and Lord Piper\rquote s dancing maiden, but the banners he did }{\cs28\i not}{
 see gave him pause. The silver eagle of Mallister was nowhere in evidence; nor the red horse of Bracken, the willow of the Rygers, the twining snakes of Paege. Though all had renewed their fealty to the Iron Throne, none had come to join the siege. The
 Brackens were fighting the Blackwoods, Jaime knew, which accounted for their absence, but as for the rest . . . 
\par }{\cs28\i Our new friends are no friends at all. Their loyalty goes no deeper than their skins.}{ Riverrun had to be taken, and soon. The longer the siege dragged on, the more it would hearten other recalcitrants, like Tytos Blackwood. 
\par At the ford, Ser Kennos of Kayce blew the Horn of Herrock. }{\cs28\i That should bring the Blackfish to the battlements.}{ Ser Hugo and Ser Dermot led Jaime\rquote s way across the river, spla
shing through the muddy red-brown waters with the white standard of the Kingsguard and Tommen\rquote s stag and lion streaming in the wind. The rest of the column followed hard behind them. 
\par The Lannister camp rang to the sound of wooden hammers where a new siege
 tower was rising. Two other towers stood completed, half-covered with raw horsehide. Between them sat a rolling ram; a tree trunk with a fire-hardened point suspended on chains beneath a wooden roof. }{\cs28\i My coz has not been idle, it would seem.}{ 

\par \'93My lord,\'94 Peck asked, \'93where do you want your tent?\'94 
\par \'93There, upon that rise.\'94 He pointed with his golden hand, though it was not well suited to that task. \'93Baggage there, horse lines there. We\rquote ll use the latrines my cousin has so kindly dug for us. Ser Addam, inspect
 our perimeter with an eye for any weaknesses.\'94 Jaime did not anticipate an attack, but he had not anticipated the Whispering Wood either. 
\par \'93Shall I summon the stoats for a war council?\'94 Daven asked. 
\par \'93Not until I\rquote ve spoken to the Blackfish.\'94 Jaime beckoned to Beardless Jon Bettley. \'93
Shake out a peace banner and bear a message to the castle. Inform Ser Brynden Tully that I would have words with him, at first light on the morrow. I will come to the edge of the moat and meet him on his drawbridge.\'94 
\par Peck looked alarmed. \'93My lord, the bowmen could . . .\'94 
\par \'93They won\rquote t.\'94 Jaime dismounted. \'93Raise my tent and plant my standards.\'94 }{\cs28\i And we\rquote ll see who comes running, and how quickly.}{ 
\par It did not require long. Pia was fussing at a brazier, trying to light the coals. Peck went to help her. Of late, Jaime oft went to sleep to the sound of them fucking in a corner of the tent. As Garrett was undoing the clasps on Jaime\rquote 
s greaves, the tent flapped open. \'93Here at last, are you?\'94 boomed his aunt. She filled the door, with her Frey husband peering out from behind her. \'93Past time. Have you no hug for your old fat aunt?\'94
 She held out her arms and left him no choice but to embrace her. 
\par Genna Lannister had bee
n a shapely woman in her youth, always threatening to overflow her bodice. Now the only shape she had was square. Her face was broad and smooth, her neck a thick pink pillar, her bosom enormous. She carried enough flesh to make two of her husband. Jaime h
ugged her dutifully and waited for her to pinch his ear. She had been pinching his ear for as long as he could remember, but today she forbore. Instead, she planted soft and sloppy kisses on his cheeks. \'93I am sorry for your loss.\'94 
\par \'93I had a new hand made, of gold.\'94 He showed her. 
\par \'93Very nice. Will they make you a gold father too?\'94 Lady Genna\rquote s voice was sharp. \'93Tywin was the loss I meant.\'94 
\par \'93A man such as Tywin Lannister comes but once in a thousand years,\'94 declared her husband. Emmon Frey was a fretful man 
