\par SAMWELL
\par The }{\cs28\i Cinnamon Wind}{ was a swan ship out of Tall Trees Town on the Summer Isles, where men were black, women were wanton, and even the gods were strange. She had no septon aboard her to lead them in the prayers of pa
ssing, so the task fell to Samwell Tarly, somewhere off the sun-scorched southern coast of Dorne. 
\par Sam donned his blacks to say the words, though the afternoon was warm and muggy, with nary a breath of wind. \'93He was a good man,\'94 he began . . . but as soon as he had said the words he knew that they were wrong. \'93No. He was a }{\cs28\i great}{
 man. A maester of the Citadel, chained and sworn, and Sworn Brother of the Night\rquote s Watch, ever faithful. When he was born they named him for a hero who had died too young, but thoug
h he lived a long long time, his own life was no less heroic. No man was wiser, or gentler, or kinder. At the Wall, a dozen lords commander came and went during his years of service, but he was always there to counsel them. He counseled kings as well. He 
could have been a king himself, but when they offered him the crown he told them they should give it to his younger brother. How many men would do that?\'94 Sam felt the tears welling in his eyes, and knew he could not go on much longer. \'93
He was the blood of the dragon, but now his fire has gone out. He was Aemon Targaryen. And now his watch is ended.\'94 
