 Still half asleep, Dorcas stumbled from the bed and went scampering across the chamber for her clothing, her bare feet rustling on the rushes. 
\par Ages later, Grand Maester Pycelle entered shuffling, and stood before her with bowed head, blinking his heavy-lidded eyes and struggling not to yawn. He looked as if the weight of the huge maester\rquote s chain about his 
wattled neck was dragging him down to the floor. Pycelle had been old as far back as Cersei could remember, but there was a time when he had also been magnificent: richly clad, dignified, exquisitely courteous. His immense white beard had given him an air
 of wisdom. Tyrion had shaved his beard off, though, and what had grown back was pitiful, a few patchy tufts of thin, brittle hair that did little to hide the loose pink flesh beneath his sagging chin. }{\cs28\i This is no man,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i 
only the ruins of one. The black cells robbed him of whatever strength he had. That, and the Imp\rquote s razor. }{
\par \'93How old are you?\'94 Cersei asked, abruptly. 
\par \'93Four-and-eighty, if it please Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93A younger man would please me more.\'94 
\par His tongue flicked across his lips. \'93I was but 
two-and-forty when the Conclave called me. Kaeth was eighty when they chose him, and Ellendor was nigh on ninety. The cares of office crushed them, and both were dead within a year of being raised. Merion came next, only six-and-sixty, but he died of a ch
ill on his way to King\rquote s Landing. Afterward King Aegon asked the Citadel to send a younger man. He was the first king I served.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i And Tommen shall be the last.}{ \'93I need a potion from you. Something to help me sleep.\'94 
\par \'93A cup of wine before bed will oft\emdash \'94 
\par \'93I }{\cs28\i drink}{ wine, you witless cretin. I require something stronger. Something that will not let me dream.\'94 
\par \'93You . . . Your Grace does not wish to dream?\'94 
\par \'93What did I just say? Have your ears grown as feeble as your cock? Can you make me such a potion, or must I command Lord Qyburn to rectify another of your failures?\'94 
\par \'93No. There is no need to involve that . . . to involve Qyburn. Dreamless sleep. You shall have your potion.\'94 
\par \'93Good. You may go.\'94 As he turned toward the door, though, she called him back. \'93One more thing. What does the Citadel teach concerning prophecy? Can our morrows be foretold?\'94 
\par The old man hesitated. One wrinkled hand groped blindly at his chest, as if to stroke the beard that was not there. \'93Can our morrows be foretold?\'94 he repeated slowly. \'93
Mayhaps. There are certain spells in the old books . . . but Your Grace might ask instead, \lquote }{\cs28\i Should}{ our morrows be foretold?\rquote  And to that I should answer, \lquote No.\rquote  Some doors are best left closed.\'94 
\par \'93See that you close mine as you leave.\'94 She should have known that he would give her an answer as useless as he was. 
\par The next morning she broke her fast with Tommen. The boy seemed much subdued; ministering to Pate had served its purpose, it would seem. They ate fried eggs, fried bread, bacon, and some blood or
anges newly come by ship from Dorne. Her son was attended by his kittens. As she watched the cats frolic about his feet, Cersei felt a little better. }{\cs28\i No harm will ever come to Tommen whilst I still live.}{
 She would kill half the lords in Westeros and all the common people, if that was what it took to keep him safe. \'93Go with Jocelyn,\'94 she told the boy after they had eaten. 
\par Then she sent for Qyburn. \'93Is Lady Falyse still alive?\'94 
\par \'93Alive, yes. Perhaps not entirely . . . comfortable.\'94 
\par \'93I see.\'94 Cersei considered a moment. \'93This man Bronn . . . I cannot say I like the notion of an enemy so close. His power all derives from Lollys. If we were to produce her elder sister . . .\'94 
\par \'93Alas,\'94 said Qyburn. \'93I fear that Lady Falyse is no longer capable of ruling Stokeworth
. Or, indeed, of feeding herself. I have learned a great deal from her, I am pleased to say, but the lessons have not been entirely without cost. I hope I have not exceeded Your Grace\rquote s instructions.\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 Whatever she had intended, it was too late. There was no sense dwelling on such things. }{\cs28\i It is better if she dies}{, she told herself. }{\cs28\i 
She would not want to go on living without her husband. Oaf that he was, the fool seemed fond of him.}{ \'93There is another matter. Last night I had a dreadful dream.\'94 
