\par \'93This dream concerned a witch woman I visited as a child.\'94 
\par \'93A woods witch? Most are harmless creatures. They know a little herb-craft and some midwifery, but elsewise . . .\'94 
\par \'93She was more than that. Half of Lannisport used to go to her for charms and potions. She was mother to a petty lord, a wealthy merchant upjumped by my grandsire. This lord\rquote 
s father had found her whilst trading in the east. Some say she cast a spell on him, though more like the only charm she needed was the one between her thighs. She was not always hideous, or so they said. I don\rquote t recall the woman\rquote 
s name. Something long and eastern and outlandish. The smallfolk used to call her Maggy.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i \'93Maegi?\'94 }{
\par \'93Is that how you say it? The woman would suck a drop of blood from your finger, and tell you what your morrows held.\'94 
\par \'93Bloodmagic is the darkest kind of sorcery. Some say it is the most powerful as well.\'94 
\par Cersei did not want to hear that. \'93This }{\cs28\i maegi}{ made certain
 prophecies. I laughed at them at first, but . . . she foretold the death of one of my bedmaids. At the time she made the prophecy, the girl was one-and-ten, healthy as a little horse and safe within the Rock. Yet she soon fell down a well and drowned.
\'94 Melara had begged her never to speak of the things they heard that night in the }{\cs28\i maegi}{\rquote s tent. }{\cs28\i If we never talk about it we\rquote ll soon forget, and then it will be just a bad dream we had,}{ Melara had said. }{\cs28\i 
