\par BRIENNE
\par They came upon the first corpse a mile from the crossroads. 
\par He swung beneath the limb of a dead tree whose blackened trunk still bore the scars of the lightning that had killed it. The carrion crows had been at work on his face, and wolves had feasted on his lower legs where they dangled near the
 ground. Only bones and rags remained below his knees . . . along with one well-chewed shoe, half-covered by mud and mold. 
\par \'93What does he have in his mouth?\'94 asked Podrick. 
\par Brienne had to steel herself to look. His face was grey and green and ghastly, his mouth open and distended. Someone had shoved a jagged white rock between his teeth. A rock, or . . . 
\par \'93Salt,\'94 said Septon Meribald. 
\par Fifty yards farther on they spied the second body. The scavengers had torn him down, so what remained of him was strewn on the ground beneath a frayed rope looped about the limb of an elm. Brienne might have ridden past him, unawares, if Dog had not sniff
ed him out and loped into the weeds for a closer smell. 
\par \'93What do you have there, Dog?\'94 Ser Hyle dismounted, strode after the dog, and came up with a halfhelm. The dead man\rquote s skull was still inside it, along with some worms and beetles. \'93Good steel,\'94 he pronounced, \'93
and not too badly dinted, though the lion\rquote s lost his head. Pod, would you like a helm?\'94 
\par \'93Not that one. It\rquote s got worms in it.\'94 
\par \'93Worms wash out, lad. You\rquote re squeamish as a girl.\'94 
\par Brienne scowled at him. \'93It is too big for him.\'94 
\par \'93He\rquote ll grow into it.\'94 
\par \'93I don\rquote t want to,\'94 said Podrick. Ser Hyle shrugged, and tossed the broken helm back into the weeds, lion crest and all. Dog barked and went to lift his leg against the tree. 
\par After that, hardly a hundred yards went by without a corpse. They dangled 
under ash and alder, beech and birch, larch and elm, hoary old willows and stately chestnut trees. Each man wore a noose around his neck, and swung from a length of hempen rope, and each man\rquote 
s mouth was packed with salt. Some wore cloaks of grey or blue or
 crimson, though rain and sun had faded them so badly that it was hard to tell one color from another. Others had badges sewn on their breasts. Brienne spied axes, arrows, several salmon, a pine tree, an oak leaf, beetles, bantams, a boar\rquote 
s head, half a dozen tridents. }{\cs28\i Broken men,}{ she realized, }{\cs28\i dregs from a dozen armies, the leavings of the lords. }{
\par Some of the dead men had been bald and some bearded, some young and some old, some short, some tall, some fat, some thin. Swollen in death, with faces gnawed and rotten, they all looked the same. }{\cs28\i On the gallows tree, all men are brothers.}{
 Brienne had read that in a book, though she could not recall which one. 
\par It was Hyle Hunt who finally put words to what all of them had realized. \'93These are the men who raided Saltpans.\'94 
\par \'93May the Father judge them harshly,\'94 said Meribald, who had been a friend to the town\rquote s aged septon. 
\par Who they were did not concern Brienne half so much as who had hanged them. The noose was the preferred method of execution for Beric Dondarrion and his band of outlaws, it was said. If so, the so-called lightning lord might well be near. 
\par Dog barked, and Septon Meribald glanced about and frowned. \'93Shall we keep a brisker pace? The sun will soon be setting, and corpses make poor company by night. These were dark and dangerous men, alive. I doubt that death will have improved them.\'94 

\par \'93There we disagree,\'94 said Ser Hyle. \'93These are just the sort of fellows who are most improved by death.\'94 All the same, he put his heels into his horse, and they moved a little faster. 
\par Farther on the trees began to thin, though not the corpses. The woods gave way to muddy fields, tree limbs to gibbets. Clouds of crows rose screeching from the bodies as the travelers came near, and settled again once they had passed. }{\cs28\i These
 were evil men,}{
 Brienne reminded herself, yet the sight still made her sad. She forced herself to look at every man in turn, searching for familiar faces. A few she thought she recognized from Harrenhal, but their condition made it hard to be certain. None had a hound
\rquote s head helm, but few had helms of any sort. Most had been stripped of arms, armor, and boots before they were strung up. 
\par When Podrick asked the name of the inn where they hoped to spend the night, Septon Meribald seized upon the question eagerly, perhaps to take their minds off the grisly sentinels along the roadside. \'93
The Old Inn, some call it. There has been an inn there for many hundreds of years, though }{\cs28\i this}{ inn was only raised during the reign of the first Jaehaerys, the king who built th
e kingsroad. Jaehaerys and his queen slept there during their journeys, it is said. For a time the inn was known as the Two Crowns in their honor, until one innkeep built a bell tower, and changed it to the Bellringer Inn. Later it passed to a crippled kn
i
ght named Long Jon Heddle, who took up ironworking when he grew too old to fight. He forged a new sign for the yard, a three-headed dragon of black iron that he hung from a wooden post. The beast was so big it had to be made in a dozen pieces, joined with
 rope and wire. When the wind blew it would clank and clatter, so the inn became known far and wide as the Clanking Dragon.\'94 
\par \'93Is the dragon sign still there?\'94 asked Podrick. 
\par \'93No,\'94 said Septon Meribald. \'93When the smith\rquote s son was an old man, a bastard son o
f the fourth Aegon rose up in rebellion against his trueborn brother and took for his sigil a black dragon. These lands belonged to Lord Darry then, and his lordship was fiercely loyal to the king. The sight of the black iron dragon made him wroth, so he 
cut down the post, hacked the sign into pieces, and cast them into the river. One of the dragon\rquote 
s heads washed up on the Quiet Isle many years later, though by that time it was red with rust. The innkeep never hung another sign, so men forgot the dragon and
 took to calling the place the River Inn. In those days, the Trident flowed beneath its back door, and half its rooms were built out over the water. Guests could throw a line out their window and catch trout, it\rquote 
s said. There was a ferry landing here as well, so travelers could cross to Lord Harroway\rquote s Town and Whitewalls.\'94 
\par \'93We left the Trident south of here, and have been riding north and west . . . not toward the river but away from it.\'94 
\par \'93Aye, my lady,\'94 the septon said. \'93The river moved. Seventy years ago, it was. Or was it eighty? It was when old Masha Heddle\rquote 
s grandfather kept the place. It was her who told me all this history. A kindly woman, Masha, fond of sourleaf and honey cakes. When she did not have a room for me, she would let me sleep beside th
e hearth, and she never sent me on my way without some bread and cheese and a few stale cakes.\'94 
\par \'93Is she the innkeep now?\'94 asked Podrick. 
\par \'93No. The lions hanged her. After they moved on, I heard that one of her nephews tried opening the inn again, but the 
wars had made the roads too dangerous for common folk to travel, so there was little custom. He brought in whores, but even that could not save him. Some lord killed him as well, I hear.\'94 
\par Ser Hyle made a wry face. \'93I never dreamed that keeping an inn could be so deadly dangerous.\'94 
\par \'93It is being common-born that is dangerous, when the great lords play their game of thrones,\'94 said Septon Meribald. \'93Isn\rquote t that so, Dog?\'94 Dog barked agreement. 
\par \'93So,\'94 said Podrick, \'93does the inn have a name }{\cs28\i now}{?\'94 
\par \'93The smallfolk call it the crossroads inn. Elder Brother told me that two of Masha Heddle\rquote s nieces have opened it to trade once again.\'94 He raised his staff. \'93
If the gods are good, that smoke rising beyond the hanged men will be from its chimneys.\'94 
\par \'93They could call the place the Gallows Inn,\'94 Ser Hyle said. 
\par By any name the inn was large, rising three stories above the muddy roads, its walls and turrets and chimneys made of fine white stone that glimmered pale and ghostly against the grey sky. Its south wing had been bui
lt upon heavy wooden pilings above a cracked and sunken expanse of weeds and dead brown grass. A thatch-roofed stable and a bell tower were attached to the north side. The whole sprawl was surrounded by a low wall of broken white stones overgrown by moss.
 
\par }{\cs28\i At least no one has burned it down.}{ At Saltpans, they had found only death and desolation. By the time Brienne and her companions were ferried over from the Quiet Isle, the survivors had fled and 
the dead had been given to the ground, but the corpse of the town itself remained, ashen and unburied. The air still smelled of smoke, and the cries of the seagulls floating overhead sounded almost human, like the lamentations of lost children. Even the c
a
stle had seemed forlorn and abandoned. Grey as the ashes of the town around it, the castle consisted of a square keep girded by a curtain wall, built so as to overlook the harbor. It was closed tight as Brienne and the others led their horses off the ferr
y, nothing moving on its battlements but banners. It took a quarter hour of Dog barking and Septon Meribald knocking on the front gate with his quarterstaff before a woman appeared above them to demand their business. 
\par By that time the ferry had departed and it had begun to rain. \'93I am a holy septon, good lady,\'94 Meribald had shouted up, \'93and these are honest travelers. We seek shelter from the rain, and a place by your fire for the night.\'94
 The woman had been unmoved by his appeals. \'93The closest inn is at the crossroads, to the west,\'94 she replied. \'93We want no strangers here. Begone.\'94 Once she vanished, neither Meribald\rquote s prayers, Dog\rquote s barks, nor Ser Hyle\rquote 
s curses could bring her back. In the end they had spent the night in the woods, beneath a shelter made of woven branches. 
\par There was life at the crossroads inn, though. Even before they reached the gate, Brienne heard the sound: a hammering, faint but steady. It had a steely ring. 
\par \'93A forge,\'94 Ser Hyle said. \'93Either they have themselves a smith, or the old innkeep\rquote s ghost is making another iron dragon.\'94 He put his heels into his horse. \'93
I hope they have a ghostly cook as well. A crisp roast chicken would set the world aright.\'94 
\par The inn\rquote s yard was a sea of brown mud that sucked at the hooves of the horses. The c
lang of steel was louder here, and Brienne saw the red glow of the forge down past the far end of the stables, behind an oxcart with a broken wheel. She could see horses in the stables too, and a small boy was swinging from the rusted chains of the weathe
red gibbet that loomed above the yard. Four girls stood on the inn\rquote s porch, watching him. The youngest was no more than two, and naked. The oldest, nine or ten, stood with her arms protectively about the little one. \'93Girls,\'94
 Ser Hyle called to them, \'93run and fetch your mother.\'94 
\par The boy dropped from the chain and dashed off toward the stables. The four girls stood fidgeting. After a moment one said, \'93We have no mothers,\'94 and another added, \'93I had one but they killed her.\'94 The oldest of the four stepped forwa
rd, pushing the little one behind her skirts. \'93Who are you?\'94 she demanded. 
\par \'93Honest travelers seeking shelter. My name is Brienne, and this is Septon Meribald, who is well-known through the riverlands. The boy is my squire, Podrick Payne, the knight Ser Hyle Hunt.\'94 
\par The hammering stopped suddenly. The girl on the porch looked them over, wary as only a ten-year-old can be. \'93I\rquote m Willow. Will you be wanting beds?\'94 
\par \'93Beds, and ale, and hot food to fill our bellies,\'94 said Ser Hyle Hunt as he dismounted. \'93Are you the innkeep?\'94 
\par She shook her head. \'93That\rquote s my sister Jeyne. She\rquote s not here. All we have to eat is horse meat. If you come for whores, there are none. My sister run them off. We have beds, though. Some featherbeds, but more are straw.\'94 
\par \'93And all have fleas, I don\rquote t doubt,\'94 said Ser Hyle. 
\par \'93Do you have coin to pay? Silver?\'94 
\par Ser Hyle laughed. \'93Silver? For a night\rquote s bed and a haunch of horse? Do you mean to rob us, child?\'94 
\par \'93We\rquote ll have silver. Else you can sleep in the woods with the dead men.\'94 Willow glanced toward the donkey, and the casks and bundles on his back. \'93Is that food? Where did you get it?\'94 
\par \'93Maidenpool,\'94 said Meribald. Dog barked. 
\par \'93Do you question all your guests this way?\'94 asked Ser Hyle. 
\par \'93We don\rquote t have so many guests. Not like before the war. It\rquote s mostly sparrows on the roads these days, or worse.\'94 
\par \'93Worse?\'94 Brienne asked. 
\par \'93Thieves,\'94 said a boy\rquote s voice from the stables. \'93Robbers.\'94 
\par Brienne turned, and saw a ghost. 
\par }{\cs28\i Renly.}{ No hammerblow to the heart could have felled her half so hard. \'93My lord?\'94 she gasped. 
\par \'93Lord?\'94 The boy pushed back a lock of black hair that had fallen across his eyes. \'93I\rquote m just a smith.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He is not Renly,}{ Brienne realized. }{\cs28\i Renly is dead. Renly died in my arms, a man of one-and-twenty. This is a only a boy.}{ A boy who looked as Renly had, the first time he came to Tarth. }{\cs28\i 
No, younger. His jaw is squarer, his brows bushier.}{ Renly had been lean and lithe, whereas this boy had the heavy shoulders and muscular right arm so often seen on smiths. He wore a long leather apron, but und
er it his chest was bare. A dark stubble covered his cheeks and chin, and his hair was a thick black mop that grew down past his ears. King Renly\rquote 
s hair had been that same coal black, but his had always been washed and brushed and combed. Sometimes he cut 
it short, and sometimes he let it fall loose to his shoulders, or tied it back behind his head with a golden ribbon, but it was never tangled or matted with sweat. And though his eyes had been that same deep blue, Lord Renly\rquote 
s eyes had always been warm and welcoming, full of laughter, whereas this boy\rquote s eyes brimmed with anger and suspicion. 
\par Septon Meribald saw it too. \'93We mean no harm, lad. When Masha Heddle owned this inn she always had a honey cake for me. Sometimes she even let me have a bed, if the inn was not full.\'94 
\par \'93She\rquote s dead,\'94 the boy said. \'93The lions hanged her.\'94 
\par \'93Hanging seems your favorite sport in these parts,\'94 said Ser Hyle Hunt. \'93Would that I had some land hereabouts. I\rquote d plant hemp, sell rope, and make my fortune.\'94 
\par \'93All these children,\'94 Brienne said to the girl Willow. \'93Are they your . . . sisters? Brothers? Kin and cousins?\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 Willow was staring at her, in a way that she knew well. \'93They\rquote re just . . . I don\rquote t know . . . the sparrows bring them here, sometimes. Others find their own way. If you\rquote re a woman, why are you dressed up like a man?
\'94 
\par Septon Meribald answered. \'93Lady Brienne is a warrior maid upon a quest. Just now, though, she is in need of a dry bed and a warm fire. As are we all. My old bones say it\rquote s going to rain again, and soon. Do you have rooms for us?\'94 
\par \'93No,\'94 said the boy smith. \'93Yes,\'94 said the girl Willow. 
\par They glared at one another. Then Willow stomped her foot. \'93They have }{\cs28\i food,}{ Gendry. The little ones are hungry.\'94 
She whistled, and more children appeared as if by magic; ragged boys with unshorn locks crept from under the porch, and furtive girls appeared in the windows overlooking the yard. Some clutched crossbows, wound and loaded. 
\par \'93They could call it Crossbow Inn,\'94 Ser Hyle suggested. 
\par }{\cs28\i Orphan Inn would be more apt,}{ thought Brienne. 
\par \'93Wat, you help them with those horses,\'94 said Willow. \'93Will, put down that rock, they\rquote ve not come to hurt us. Tansy, Pate, run get some wood to feed the fire. Jon Penny, you help the septon with those bundles. I\rquote 
ll show them to some rooms.\'94 
\par In the end they took three rooms adjoining one another, each boasting a featherbed, a chamber pot, and a window. Brienne\rquote s room had a hearth as well. She paid a few pennies more for some wood. \'93Will I sleep in your room, or Ser Hyle\rquote s?
\'94 Podrick asked as she was opening the shutters. \'93This is not the Quiet Isle,\'94 she told him. \'93You can stay with me.\'94 Come the morrow she meant for the two of them to strike out on their own. Septon Meribald was going on 
to Nutten, Riverbend, and Lord Harroway\rquote s Town, but Brienne saw no sense in following him any farther. He had Dog to keep him company, and the Elder Brother had persuaded her that she would not find Sansa Stark along the Trident. \'93
I mean to rise before the sun comes up, whilst Ser Hyle is still sleeping.\'94 Brienne had not forgiven him for Highgarden . . . and as he himself had said, Hunt had sworn no vows concerning Sansa. 
\par \'93Where will we go, ser? I mean, my lady?\'94 
\par Brienne had no ready answer for him. They 
had come to the crossroads, quite literally; the place where the kingsroad, the river road, and the high road all came together. The high road would take them east through the mountains to the Vale of Arryn, where Lady Sansa\rquote 
s aunt had ruled until her death. West ran the river road, which followed the course of the Red Fork to Riverrun and Sansa\rquote 
s great-uncle, who was besieged but still alive. Or they could ride the kingsroad north, past the Twins and through the Neck with its bogs and marshes. If she could
 find a way past Moat Cailin and whoever held it now, the kingsroad would bring them all the way to Winterfell. 
\par }{\cs28\i Or I could take the kingsroad south,}{ Brienne thought. }{\cs28\i I could slink back to King\rquote s Landing, confess my failure to Ser Jaime, give him back his sword, and find a ship to carry me home to Tarth, as the Elder Brother urged.}{
 The thought was a bitter one, yet there was part of her that yearned for Evenfall and her father, and another part that wondered if Jaime would comfort her should she weep upon his shoulder. That was what men wanted, wasn\rquote 
t it? Soft helpless women that they needed to protect? 
\par \'93Ser? My lady? I asked, where are we going?\'94 
\par \'93Down to the common room, to supper.\'94 
\par The common room was crawling with children. Brienne tried to count them
, but they would not stand still even for an instant, so she counted some of them twice or thrice and others not at all, until she finally gave it up. They had pushed the tables together in three long rows, and the older boys were wrestling benches from t
he back. }{\cs28\i Older}{ here meant ten or twelve. Gendry was the closest thing to a man grown, but it was Willow shouting all the orders, as if she were a queen in her castle and the other children were no more than servants. 
\par }{\cs28\i If she were highborn, command would come naturally to her, and deference to them.}{
