\par Outside, the last light of day was fading. Inside, Willow had four greasy tallow candles lit and told the girls to keep the hearthfire burning high and hot. The boys helped Podrick Payne unpack the donkey and carried in the salt cod, mutton, vegetab
les, nuts, and wheels of cheese, whilst Septon Meribald repaired to the kitchens to take charge of the porridge. \'93Alas, my oranges are gone, and I doubt that I shall see another till the spring,\'94 he told one small boy. \'93
Have you ever had an orange, lad? Squeezed one and sucked down that fine juice?\'94 When the boy shook his head no, the septon mussed his hair. \'93Then I\rquote ll bring you one, come spring, if you will be a good lad and help me stir the porridge.\'94 

\par Ser Hyle pulled off his boots to warm his feet by the fire. When Brienne sat down next to him, he nodded at the far end of the room. \'93There are bloodstains on the floor over there where Dog is sniffing. They\rquote 
ve been scrubbed, but the blood soaked deep into the wood, and there\rquote s no getting it out.\'94 
