\par \'93What I want to win is you, Lord Selwyn\rquote s only living child. I\rquote ve known men to we
d lackwits and suckling babes for prizes a tenth the size of Tarth. I am not Renly Baratheon, I confess it, but I have the virtue of being still amongst the living. Some would say that is my only virtue. Marriage would serve the both of us. Lands for me, 
and a castle full of these for you.\'94 He waved his hand at the children. \'93I am capable, I assure you. I\rquote ve sired at least one bastard that I know of. Have no fear, I shan\rquote 
t inflict her upon you. The last time I went to see her, her mother doused me with a kettle of soup.\'94 
\par A flush crept up her neck. \'93My father\rquote s only four-and-fifty. Not too old to wed again and get a son by his new wife.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s a risk . . . }{\cs28\i if}{ your father weds again and }{\cs28\i if}{ his bride proves fertile and }{\cs28\i if}{ the babe\rquote s a boy. I\rquote ve made worse wagers.\'94 
\par \'93And lost them. Play your game with someone else, ser.\'94 
\par \'93So speaks a maid who has never played the game with anyone. Once you do you\rquote ll take a different view. In the dark you\rquote d be as beautiful as any other woman. Your lips were made for kissing.\'94 
\par \'93They are lips,\'94 said Brienne. \'93All lips are the same.\'94 
\par \'93And all lips are made for kissing,\'94 Hunt agreed pleasantly. \'93Leave your chamber door unbarred tonight, and I will steal into your bed and prove the truth of what I say.\'94 
\par \'93If you do, you\rquote ll be a eunuch when you leave.\'94 Brienne got up and walked away from him. 
\par Septon Meribald asked if he might lead the children in a grace, ignoring the small girl crawling naked across the table. \'93Aye,\'94 said Willow, snatching up the crawler before she reach
ed the porridge. So they bowed their heads together and thanked the Father and the Mother for their bounty . . . all but the black-haired boy from the forge, who crossed his arms against his chest and sat glowering as the others prayed. Brienne was not th
e only one to notice. When the prayer was done Septon Meribald looked across the table, and said, \'93Do you have no love for the gods, son?\'94 
\par \'93Not for your gods.\'94 Gendry stood abruptly. \'93I have work to do.\'94 He stalked out without a bite of food. 
\par \'93Is there some other god he loves?\'94 asked Hyle Hunt. 
\par \'93The Lord of Light,\'94 piped one scrawny boy, nigh to six. 
\par Willow hit him with her spoon. \'93Ben Big Mouth. There\rquote s }{\cs28\i food}{. You should be eating it, not bothering m\rquote lords with talk.\'94 
\par The children fell upon the supper l
ike wolves upon a wounded deer, quarreling over codfish, tearing the barley bread to pieces, and getting porridge everywhere. Even the huge wheel of cheese did not long survive. Brienne contented herself with fish and bread and carrots, whilst Septon Meri
bald fed two morsels to Dog for every one he ate himself. Outside, a rain began to fall. Inside, the fire crackled, and the common room was filled by the sounds of chewing, and Willow smacking children with her spoon. \'93
One day that little girl will make some man a frightful wife,\'94 Ser Hyle observed. \'93That poor \rquote prentice boy, most like.\'94 
\par \'93Someone should take him some food before it\rquote s all gone.\'94 
\par \'93You\rquote re someone.\'94 
\par She wrapped a wedge of cheese, a heel of bread, a dried apple, and two chunks of flaky fried cod in a square of cloth. When Podrick got up to follow her outside, she told him to sit back down and eat. \'93I will not be long.\'94 
\par The rain was coming down heavy in the yard. Brienne covered the food with a fold of her cloak. Some of the horses whinnied at her as she made her way past the stables. }{\cs28\i They are hungry too.}{ 
\par Gendry was at his forge, bare-chested beneath his leather apron. He was beating on a sword as if he wished it were a foe, his sweat-soaked hair falling across his brow. She watched him for a moment. }{\cs28\i He has Renly\rquote s eyes and Renly\rquote 
s hair, but not his build. Lord Renly was more lithe than brawny . . . not like his brother Robert, whose strength was fabled.}{ 
\par It was not until he stopped to wipe his brow that Gendry saw her standing there. \'93What do }{\cs28\i you}{ want?\'94 
\par \'93I brought supper.\'94 She opened the cloth for him to see. 
\par \'93If I wanted food, I would have eaten some.\'94 
\par \'93A smith needs to eat to keep his strength up.\'94 
\par \'93Are you my mother?\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 She put down the food. \'93Who was your mother?\'94 
\par \'93What\rquote s that to you?\'94 
\par \'93You were born in King\rquote s Landing.\'94 The way he spoke made her certain of it. 
\par \'93Me and many more.\'94 He plunged the sword into a tub of rainwater to quench it. The hot steel hissed angrily. 
\par \'93How old are you?\'94 Brienne asked. \'93Is your mother still alive? And your father, who was he?\'94 
\par \'93You ask too many questions.\'94 He set down the sword. \'93My mother\rquote s dead and I never knew my father.\'94 
\par \'93You\rquote re a bastard.\'94 
\par He took it for an insult. \'93I\rquote m a }{\cs28\i knight}{. That sword will be mine own, once it\rquote s done.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i What would a knight be doing working at a smithy?}{ \'93You have black hair and blue eyes, and you were born in the shadow of the Red Keep. Has no one ever remarked upon your face?\'94 
\par \'93What\rquote s wrong with my face? It\rquote s not as ugly as yours.\'94 
\par \'93In King\rquote s Landing you must have seen King Robert.\'94 
\par He shrugged. \'93Sometimes. At tourneys, from afar. Once at Baelor\rquote s Sept. The gold cloaks shoved us aside so he could pass. Another time I was playing near the Mud Gate when he come back from a hunt. He was so drunk he almost rode me down. A 
big fat sot, he was, but a better king than these sons of his.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i They are not his sons. Stannis told it true, that day he met with Renly. Joffrey and Tommen were never Robert\rquote s sons. This boy, though . . . }{\'93Listen to me,\'94 Brienne began. Then she heard Dog barking, loud and frantic. \'93
Someone is coming.\'94 
\par \'93Friends,\'94 said Gendry, unconcerned. 
\par \'93What sort of friends?\'94 Brienne moved to the door of the smithy to peer out through the rain. 
\par He shrugged. \'93You\rquote ll meet them soon enough.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I may not want to meet them,}{ Brienne thought, as the first riders came splashing through the puddles into the yard. Beneath the patter of the rain and Dog\rquote 
s barking, she could hear the faint clink of swords and mail from beneath their ragged cloaks. She counted them as they came. }{\cs28\i Two, four, six, seven.}{
 Some of them were wounded, judging from the way they rode. The last man was massive and hulking, as big as two of the others. His horse was blown and bloody, staggering beneath his weight. All the riders had their hoods up ag
ainst the lashing rain, save him alone. His face was broad and hairless, maggot white, his round cheeks covered with weeping sores. 
\par Brienne sucked in her breath and drew Oathkeeper. }{\cs28\i Too many,}{ she thought, with a start of fear, }{\cs28\i they are too many.}{ \'93Gendry,\'94 she said in a low voice, \'93you\rquote ll want a sword, and armor. These are not your friends. They
\rquote re no one\rquote s friends.\'94 
\par \'93What are you talking about?\'94 The boy came and stood beside her, his hammer in his hand. 
\par Lightning cracked to the south as the riders swung 
down off their horses. For half a heartbeat darkness turned to day. An axe gleamed silvery blue, light shimmered off mail and plate, and beneath the dark hood of the lead rider Brienne glimpsed an iron snout and rows of steel teeth, snarling. 
\par Gendry saw it too. \'93Him.\'94 
\par \'93Not him. His helm.\'94 Brienne tried to keep the fear from her voice, but her mouth was dry as dust. She had a pretty good notion who wore the Hound\rquote s helm. }{\cs28\i The children,}{ she thought. 
\par The door to the inn banged open. Willow stepped out into the rain, a crossbow in her hands. The girl was shouting at the riders, but a clap of thunder rolled across the yard, drowning out her words. As it faded, Brienne heard the man in the Hound\rquote 
s helm say, \'93Loose a quarrel at me and I\rquote ll shove that crossbow up your cunt and fuck you with it. Then I\rquote ll pop your fucking eyes out and make you eat them.\'94 The fury in the man\rquote s voice drove Willow back a step, trembling. 

\par }{\cs28\i Seven,}{ Brienne thought again, despairing. She had no chance against seven, she knew. }{\cs28\i No chance, and no choice.}{ 
\par She stepped out into the rain, Oathkeeper in hand. \'93}{\cs28\i Leave her be.}{ If you want to rape someone, try me.\'94 
\par The oulaws turned as one. One laughed, and another said something in a tongue Brienne did not know. The huge one with the broad white face gave a malevolent }{\cs28\i hissssssssssssssss.}{ The man in the Hound\rquote s helm began to laugh. \'93You\rquote 
re even uglier than I remembered. I\rquote d sooner rape your horse.\'94 
\par \'93Horses, that\rquote s what we want,\'94 one of the wounded men said. \'93Fresh horses, and some food. There are outlaws after us. Give us your horses and we\rquote ll be gone. We won\rquote t do you harm.\'94 
\par \'93Fuck that.\'94 The outlaw in the Hound\rquote s helm yanked a battle axe off his saddle. \'93I want to cut her bloody legs off. I\rquote ll set her on her stumps so she can watch me fuck the crossbow girl.\'94 
\par \'93With what?\'94 taunted Brienne. \'93Shagwell said they cut your manhood off when they took your nose.\'94 
\par She meant it to provoke him, and it did. Bellowing curses, he came at her, his feet sending up splashes of black water as he charged. The others s
tood back to watch the show, as she had prayed they might. Brienne stayed as still as stone, waiting. The yard was dark, the mud slippery underfoot. }{\cs28\i Better to let him come to me. If the gods are good, he\rquote ll slip and fall.}{ 
\par The gods were not that good, but her sword was. }{\cs28\i Five steps, four steps, now,}{
 Brienne counted, and Oathkeeper swept up to meet his rush. Steel crashed against steel as her blade bit through his rags and opened a gash in his chainmail, even as his axe came crashing down at her. She twisted 
aside, slashing at his chest again as she retreated. 
\par He followed, staggering and bleeding, roaring rage. }{\cs28\i \'93Whore!\'94}{ he boomed. }{\cs28\i \'93Freak! Bitch! I\rquote ll give you to my dog to fuck, you bloody bitch!\'94}{ His axe whirled in murderous arcs, a brutal black shadow that t
urned silver every time the lightning flashed. Brienne had no shield to catch the blows. All she could do was slide back away from him, darting this way and that as the axehead flew at her. Once the mud gave way under her heel and she almost fell, but som
ehow she recovered herself, though the axe grazed her left shoulder that time and left a blaze of pain in its wake. \'93You got the bitch!\'94 one of the others called, and another said, \'93Let\rquote s see her dance away from that one.\'94 
\par Dance she did, relieved that they were watching. Better that than have them interfere. She could not fight seven, not alone, even if one or two were wounded. Old Ser Goodwin was long in his grave, yet she could hear him whispering in her ear. }{\cs28\i 
Men will always underestimate you,}{ he said, }{\cs28\i 
and their pride will make them want to vanquish you quickly, lest it be said that a woman tried them sorely. Let them spend their strength in furious attacks, whilst you conserve your own. Wait and watch, girl, wait and watch.}{
 She waited, watching, moving 
sideways, then backwards, then sideways again, slashing now at his face, now at his legs, now at his arm. His blows came more slowly as his axe grew heavier. Brienne turned him so the rain was in his eyes, and stepped back two quick steps. He wrenched his
 axe up once more, cursing, and lurched after her, one foot sliding in the mud . . . 
\par . . . and she leapt to meet his rush, both hands on her sword hilt. His headlong charge brought him right onto her point, and Oathkeeper punched through cloth and mail and
 leather and more cloth, deep into his bowels and out his back, rasping as it scraped along his spine. His axe fell from limp fingers, and the two of them slammed together, Brienne\rquote s face mashed up against the dog\rquote 
s head helm. She felt the cold wet metal against her cheek. Rain ran down the steel in rivers, and when the lightning flashed again she saw pain and fear and rank disbelief through the eye slits. }{\cs28\i \'93Sapphires,\'94}{
 she whispered at him, as she gave her blade a hard twist that made him shudder. His weight sagged heavily against her, and all at once it was a corpse that she embraced, there in the black rain. She stepped back and let him fall . . . 
\par . . . and Biter crashed into her, shrieking. 
\par He fell on her like an avalanche of wet wool and milk-white fle
sh, lifting her off her feet and slamming her down into the ground. She landed in a puddle with a splash that sent water up her nose and into her eyes. All the air was driven out of her, and her head snapped down against some half-buried stone with a }{
\cs28\i crack.}{ \'93No,\'94
 was all that she had time to say before he fell on top of her, his weight driving her deeper into the mud. One of his hands was in her hair, pulling her head back. The other groped for her throat. Oathkeeper was gone, torn from her grasp. She had o
nly her hands to fight him off, but when she slammed a fist into his face it was like punching a ball of wet white dough. He }{\cs28\i hissed}{ at her. 
\par She hit him again, again, }{\cs28\i again,}{ smashing the heel of her hand into his eye, but he did not seem to feel her blows.
 She clawed at his wrists, but his grip just grew tighter, though blood ran from the gouges where she scratched him. He was crushing her, smothering her. She pushed at his shoulders to get him off her, but he was heavy as a horse, impossible to move. When
 she tried to knee him in the groin, all she did was drive her knee into his belly. Grunting, Biter tore out a handful of her hair. 
\par }{\cs28\i My dagger.}{ Brienne clutched at the thought, desperate. She worked her hand down between them, fingers squirming under his so
ur, suffocating flesh, searching until they finally found the hilt. Biter locked both his hands about her neck and began to slam her head against the ground. The lightning flashed again, this time inside her skull, yet somehow her fingers tightened, pulle
d the dagger from its sheath. With him on top of her, she could not raise the blade to stab, so she drew it hard across his belly. Something warm and wet gushed between her fingers. Biter }{\cs28\i hissed}{
 again, louder than before, and let go of her throat just long 
enough to smash her in the face. She heard bones crack, and the pain blinded her for an instant. When she tried to slash at him again, he wrenched the dagger from her fingers and slammed a knee down onto her forearm, breaking it. Then he seized her head a
gain and resumed trying to tear it off her shoulders. 
\par Brienne could hear Dog barking, and men were shouting all about her, and between the claps of thunder she heard the clash of steel on steel. }{\cs28\i Ser Hyle,}{ she thought, }{\cs28\i Ser Hyle has joined the fight,}{ but all
 that seemed far away and unimportant. Her world was no larger than the hands at her throat and the face that loomed above her. The rain ran off his hood as he leaned closer. His breath stank like cheese gone rotten. 
\par Brienne\rquote s chest was burning, and the storm was behind her eyes, blinding her. Bones ground against each other inside of her. Biter\rquote 
s mouth gaped open, impossibly wide. She saw his teeth, yellow and crooked, filed into points. When they closed on the soft meat of her cheek, she hardly felt it. She could feel herself spiraling down into the dark. }{\cs28\i I cannot die yet,}{
 she told herself, }{\cs28\i there is something I still need to do.}{ 
\par Biter\rquote s mouth tore free, full of blood and flesh. He spat, grinned, and sank his pointed teeth into her flesh again. This time he chewed and swallowed. }{\cs28\i He is eating me,}{
 she realized, but she had no strength left to fight him any longer. She felt as if she were floating above herself, watching the horror as if it were happening to some other woman, to some stupid girl who thought she was a knight. }{\cs28\i 
It will be finished soon,}{ she told herself. }{\cs28\i Then it will not matter if he eats me.}{ Biter threw back his head and opened his mouth again, howling, and stuck his tongue out at her. It was sharply pointed, dripping blood, longer than any tong
ue should be. Sliding from his mouth, out and out and out, red and wet and glistening, it made a hideous sight, obscene. }{\cs28\i His tongue is a foot long,}{ Brienne thought, just before the darkness took her. }{\cs28\i 
