\par CERSEI
\par Septa Moelle was a white-haired harridan with a face as sharp as an axe and lips pursed in perpetual disapproval. }{\cs28\i This one still has her maidenhead, I\rquote ll wager,}{ Cersei thought, }{\cs28\i though by now it\rquote 
s hard and stiff as boiled leather.}{ Six of the High Sparrow\rquote s knights escorted her, with the rainbow sword of their reborn order emblazoned on their kite shields. 
\par \'93Septa.\'94 Cersei sat beneath the Iron Throne, clad in green silk and golden lace. \'93Tell his High Holiness that we are vexed with him. He presumes too much.\'94
 Emeralds glimmered on her fingers and in her golden hair. The eyes of court and city were upon her, and she meant for them to see Lord Tywin\rquote s daughter. By the time this mummer\rquote s farce was done they would know they had but one true queen. }
{\cs28\i But first we must dance the dance and never miss a step.}{ \'93Lady Margaery is my son\rquote s true and gentle wife, 
his helpmate and consort. His High Holiness had no cause to lay his hands upon her person, or to confine her and her young cousins, who are so dear to all of us. I demand that he release them.\'94 
\par Septa Moelle\rquote s stern expression did not flicker. \'93I shall convey Your Grace\rquote s words to His High Holiness, but it grieves me to say that the young queen and her ladies cannot be released until and unless their innocence has been proved.
\'94 
\par \'93}{\cs28\i Innocence?}{ Why, you need only look upon their sweet young faces to see how innocent they are.\'94 
\par \'93A sweet face oft hides a sinner\rquote s heart.\'94 
\par Lord Merryweather spoke up from the council table. \'93What offense have these young maids been accused of, and by whom?\'94 
\par The septa said, \'93Megga Tyrell and Elinor Tyrell stand accused of lewdness,
 fornication, and conspiracy to commit high treason. Alla Tyrell has been charged with witnessing their shame and helping them conceal it. All this Queen Margaery has also been accused of, as well as adultery and high treason.\'94 
\par Cersei put a hand to her breast. \'93Tell me who is spreading such calumnies about my good-daughter! I do not believe a word of this. My sweet son loves Lady Margaery with all his heart, she could never have been so cruel as to play him false.\'94 
\par \'93The accuser is a knight of your own household. Ser Osney Kettleblack has confessed his carnal knowledge of the queen to the High Septon himself, before the altar of the Father.\'94 
\par At the council table Harys Swyft gasped, and Grand Maester Pycelle turned away. A buzz filled the air, as if a thous
and wasps were loose in the throne room. Some of the ladies in the galleries began to slip away, followed by a stream of petty lords and knights from the back of the hall. The gold cloaks let them go, but the queen had instructed Ser Osfryd to make note o
f all who fled. }{\cs28\i Suddenly the Tyrell rose does not smell so sweet.}{ 
\par \'93Ser Osney is young and lusty, I will grant you,\'94 the queen said, \'93but a faithful knight for all that. If he says that he was part of this . . . no, it cannot be. Margaery is a maiden!\'94 
\par \'93She is not. I examined her myself, at the behest of His High Holiness. Her maidenhead is not intact. Septa Aglantine and Septa Melicent will say the same, as will Queen Margaery\rquote s own septa, Nysterica, who has been confined to a penitent
\rquote s cell for her part in the queen\rquote s shame. Lady Megga and Lady Elinor were examined as well. Both were found to have been broken.\'94 
\par The wasps were growing so loud that the queen could hardly hear herself think. }{\cs28\i I do hope the little queen and her cousins enjoyed those rides of theirs. }{
\par Lord Merryweather thumped his fist on the table. \'93Lady Margaery had sworn solemn oaths attesting to her maidenhood, to Her Grace the queen and her late father. Many here bore witness. Lord Tyrell has also testified to her innocence, as has the Lad
y Olenna, whom we all know to be above reproach. Would you have us believe that all of these noble people }{\cs28\i lied}{ to us?\'94 
\par \'93Perhaps they were deceived as well, my lord,\'94 said Septa Moelle. \'93I cannot speak to this. I can only swear to the truth of what I discovered for myself when I examined the queen.\'94 
\par The picture of this sour old crone poking her wrinkled fingers up Margaery\rquote s little pink cunt was so droll that Cersei almost laughed. \'93We insist that His High Holiness allow our own maesters to examine my good
-daughter, to determine if there is any shred of truth to these slanders. Grand Maester Pycelle, you shall accompany Septa Moelle back to Beloved Baelor\rquote s Sept, and return to us with the truth about our Margaery\rquote s maidenhead.\'94 
\par Pycelle had gone the color of curdled white. }{\cs28\i At council meetings the wretched old fool cannot say enough, but now that I need a few words from him he has lost the power of speech,}{ the queen thought, before the old man finally came out with, 
\'93There is no need for me to examine her . . . her privy parts.\'94 His voice was a quaver. \'93I grieve to say . . . Queen Margaery is no maiden. She has required me to make her moon tea, not once, but many times.\'94 
\par The uproar that followed that was all that Cersei Lannister could ever have hoped for. 
\par Even the royal herald beating on the floor with his staff did little to quell the noise. The queen let it wash over her for a few heartbeats, savoring the sounds of the little queen\rquote 
s disgrace. When it had gone on long enough, she rose stone-faced and commanded that the gold cloaks clear the hall. }{\cs28\i Margaery Tyrell is done,}{ she thought, exulting. Her white knights fell in around her as she made her exit through the king
\rquote s door behind the Iron Throne; Boros Blount, Meryn Trant, and Osmund Kettleblack, the last of the Kingsguard still remaining in the city. 
\par Moon Boy was standing beside the door, holding his rattle in his hand and gaping at the confusion with his big round eyes. }{\cs28\i A fool he may be, but he wears his folly honestly. Maggy the Frog should have been in
 motley too, for all she knew about the morrow.}{ Cersei prayed the old fraud was screaming down in hell. The younger queen whose coming she\rquote d foretold was finished, and if that prophecy could fail, so could the rest. }{\cs28\i 
No golden shrouds, no }{valonqar}{\cs28\i , I am free of your croaking malice at last.}{ 
\par The remnants of her small council followed her out. Harys Swyft appeared dazed. He stumbled at the door and might have fallen if Aurane Waters had not caught him by the arm. Even Orton Merryweather seemed anxious. \'93The s
mallfolk are fond of the little queen,\'94 he said. \'93They will not take well to this. I fear what might happen next, Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93Lord Merryweather is right,\'94 said Lord Waters. \'93If it please Your Grace, I will launch the rest of our new dromonds. The sight of them upon the Blackwater with King Tommen\rquote 
s banner flying from their masts will remind the city who rules here, and keep them safe should the mobs decide to run riot again.\'94 
\par He left the rest unspoken; once on the Blackwater, his dromonds could stop Mac
e Tyrell from bringing his army back across the river, just as Tyrion had once stopped Stannis. Highgarden had no sea power of its own this side of Westeros. They relied upon the Redwyne fleet, presently on its way back to the Arbor. 
\par \'93A prudent measure,\'94 the queen announced. \'93Until this storm has passed, I want your ships crewed and on the water.\'94 
\par Ser Harys Swyft was so pale and damp he looked about to faint. \'93When word of this reaches Lord Tyrell, his fury will know no bounds. There will be blood in the streets . . .\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i The knight of the yellow chicken,}{ Cersei mused. }{\cs28\i You ought to take a worm for your sigil, ser. A chicken is too bold for you. If Mace Tyrell will not even assault Storm\rquote 
s End, how do you imagine that he would ever dare attack the gods?}{ When he was done blathering she said, \'93It must not come to blood, and I mean to see that it does not. I will go to Baelor\rquote s Sept myself to speak to Queen Margaery an
d the High Septon. Tommen loves them both, I know, and would want me to make peace between them.\'94 
\par \'93Peace?\'94 Ser Harys dabbed at his brow with a velvet sleeve. \'93If peace is possible . . . that is very brave of you.\'94 
\par \'93Some sort of trial may be necessary,\'94 said the queen, \'93to disprove these base calumnies and lies and show the world that our sweet Margaery is the innocent we all know her to be.\'94 
\par \'93Aye,\'94 said Merryweather, \'93but this High Septon may want to try the queen himself, as the Faith once tried men of old.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i I hope so,}{ Cersei thought. Such a court was not like to look with favor on treasonous queens who spread their legs for singers and profaned the Maiden\rquote s holy rites to hide their shame. \'93
The important thing is to find the truth, I am sure we all agree,\'94 she said. \'93And now, my lords, you must excuse me. I must go see the king. He should not be alone at such a time.\'94 
\par Tommen was fishing for cats when his mother returned to him. Dorcas had made him a mouse with scraps of fur and tied it on a long string 
at the end of an old fishing pole. The kittens loved to chase it, and the boy liked nothing better than jerking it about the floor as they pounced after it. He seemed surprised when Cersei gathered him up in her arms and kissed him on his brow. \'93What
\rquote s that for, Mother? Why are you crying?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Because you\rquote re safe,}{ she wanted to tell him. }{\cs28\i Because no harm will ever come to you.}{ \'93You are mistaken. A lion never cries.\'94 There would be time later to tell him about Margaery and her cousins. \'93
There are some warrants that I need you to sign.\'94 
\par For the king\rquote s sake, the queen had left the names off the arrest warrants. Tommen signed them blank, and pressed his seal into the warm wax happily, as he always did. Afterward she sent him off with Jocelyn Swyft. 
\par Ser Osfryd Ket
tleblack arrived as the ink was drying. Cersei had written in the names herself: Ser Tallad the Tall, Jalabhar Xho, Hamish the Harper, Hugh Clifton, Mark Mullendore, Bayard Norcross, Lambert Turnberry, Horas Redwyne, Hobber Redwyne, and a certain churl na
med Wat, who called himself the Blue Bard. 
\par \'93So many.\'94 Ser Osfryd shuffled through the warrants, as wary of the words as if they had been roaches crawling across the parchment. None of the Kettleblacks could read. 
\par \'93Ten. You have six thousand gold cloaks. S
ufficient for ten, I would think. Some of the clever ones may have fled, if the rumors reached their ears in time. If so, it makes no matter, their absence only makes them look that much more guilty. Ser Tallad is a bit of an oaf and may try to resist you
. See that he does not die before confessing, and do no harm to any of the others. A few may well be innocent.\'94
 It was important that the Redwyne twins be found to have been falsely accused. That would demonstrate the fairness of the judgments against the others. 
\par \'93We\rquote ll have them all before the sun comes up, Your Grace.\'94 Ser Osfryd hesitated. \'93There\rquote s a crowd gathering outside the door of Baelor\rquote s Sept.\'94 
\par \'93What sort of crowd?\'94 Anything unexpected made her wary. She remembered what Lord Waters had said about the riots. }{\cs28\i I had not considered how the smallfolk might react to this. Margaery has been their little pet.}{ \'93How many?\'94 
\par \'93A hundred or so. They\rquote re shouting for the High Septon to release the little queen. We can send them running, if you like.\'94 
\par \'93No. Let them shout until they\rquote re hoarse, it will not sway the Sparrow. He only listens to the gods.\'94
 There was a certain irony in His High Holiness having an angry mob encamped upon his doorstep, since just such a mob had raised him to the crystal crown. }{\cs28\i Which he promptly sold.}{ \'93
The Faith has its own knights now. Let them defend the sept. Oh, and close the city gates as well. No one is to enter or leave King\rquote s Landing without my leave, until all this is done and settled.\'94 
\par \'93As you command, Your Grace.\'94 Ser Osfryd bowed and went off to find someone to read the warrants to him. 
\par By the time the sun went down that day, all of the accused traitors were in custody. Hamish the Harper had collapsed when they came for him, and Ser Tallad the Tall had wounded three gold cloak
s before the others overwhelmed him. Cersei ordered that the Redwyne twins be given comfortable chambers in a tower. The rest went down to the dungeons. 
\par \'93Hamish is having difficulty breathing,\'94 Qyburn informed her when he came to call that night. \'93He is calling for a maester.\'94 
\par \'93Tell him he can have one as soon as he confesses.\'94 She thought a moment. \'93He is too old to have been amongst the lovers, but no doubt he was made to play and sing for Margaery whilst she was entertaining other men. We will need details.\'94 

\par \'93I shall help him to remember them, Your Grace.\'94 
\par The next day, Lady Merryweather helped Cersei dress for their visit to the little queen. \'93Nothing too rich or colorful,\'94 she said. \'93Something suitably devout and drab for the High Septon. He\rquote s like to make me pray with him.\'94 
\par In the end, she chose a soft woolen dress that covered her from throat to ankle, with only a few small vines embroidered on the bodice and the sleeves in golden thread to soften the severity of its lines. Even better, brown woul
d help conceal the dirt if she was made to kneel. \'93Whilst I am comforting my good-daughter you shall speak with the three cousins,\'94 she told Taena. \'93Win Alla if you can, but be careful what you say. The gods may not be the only ones listening.
\'94 
\par Jaime always said that the hardest part of any battle is just before, waiting for the carnage to begin. When she stepped outside, Cersei saw that the sky was grey and bleak. She could not take the risk of being caught in a downpour and arriving at Baelor
\rquote s Sept soaked and bedraggled. That meant the litter. For her escort, she took ten Lannister house guards and Boros Blount. \'93Margaery\rquote s mob may not have the wit to tell one Kettleblack from another,\'94 she told Ser Osmund, \'93
and I cannot have you cutting through the commons. Best we keep you out of sight for a time.\'94 
\par As they made their way across King\rquote s Landing, Taena had a sudden doubt. \'93This trial,\'94 she said, in a quiet voice, \'93what if Margaery demands that her guilt or innocence be determined by wager of battle?\'94 
\par A smile brushed Cersei\rquote s lips. \'93As queen, her honor must be defended by a knight of the Kingsguard. Why, every child in Westeros knows how Prince Aemon the Dragonknight championed his sister Queen Naerys against Ser Morghil\rquote 
s accusations. With Ser Loras so gravely wounded, though, I fear Prince Aemon\rquote s part must fall to one of his Sworn Brothers.\'94 She shrugged. \'93
Who, though? Ser Arys and Ser Balon are far away in Dorne, Jaime is off at Riverrun, and Ser Osmund is the brother of the man accusing her, which leaves only . . . oh, dear . . .\'94 
\par \'93Boros Blount and Meryn Trant.\'94 Lady Taena laughed. 
\par \'93Yes, and Ser Meryn has been feeling ill of late. Remind me to tell him that when we return to the castle.\'94 
\par \'93I shall, my sweet.\'94 Taena took her hand and kissed it. \'93I pray that I never offend you. You are terrible when roused.\'94 
\par \'93Any mother would do the same to protect her children,\'94 said Cersei. \'93When do you mean to bring that boy of yours to court? Russell, was that his name? He could train with Tommen.\'94 
\par \'93That would thrill the boy, I know . . . but things are so uncertain just now, I thought it best to wait until the danger passed.\'94 
\par \'93Soon enough,\'94 promised Cersei. \'93Send word to Longtable and have Russell pack his best doublet and his wooden sword. A new young friend will be just the thing to help Tommen forget his loss, after Margaery\rquote s little head has rolled.\'94 

\par They descended from the litter under Blessed Baelor\rquote s statue. The queen was pleased to see that the bones and filth had been cleaned away. Ser Osfr
yd had told it true; the crowd was neither as numerous nor as unruly as the sparrows had been. They stood about in small clumps, gazing sullenly at the doors of the Great Sept, where a line of novice septons had been drawn up with quarterstaffs in their h
ands. }{\cs28\i No steel,}{ Cersei noted. That was either very wise or very stupid, she was not sure which. 
\par No one made any attempt to hinder her. Smallfolk and novices alike parted as they passed. Once inside the doors, they were met by three knights in the Hall of Lamps, each clad in the rainbow-striped robes of the Warrior\rquote s Sons. \'93
I am here to see my good-daughter,\'94 Cersei told them. 
\par \'93His High Holiness has been expecting you. I am Ser Theodan the True, formerly Ser Theodan Wells. If Your Grace will come with me.\'94 
\par The High Sparrow was on his knees, as ever. This time he was praying before the Father\rquote s altar. Nor did he break off his prayer when the queen approached, but made her wait impatiently until he had finished. Only then did he rise and bow to her. 
\'93Your Grace. This is a sad day.\'94 
\par \'93Very sad. Do we have your leave to speak with Margaery and her cousins?\'94 She chose a meek and humble manner; with this man, that was like to work the best. 
\par \'93If that is your wish. Come to me afterward, my child. We must pray together, you and I.\'94 
\par The little queen had been confined atop one of the Great Sept\rquote s slender towers. Her cell was eight feet long and six feet wide, with no furnishings but a straw-stuffed pallet and a bench for prayer, a ewer of water, a copy of }{\cs28\i The Seven-Po
inted Star,}{ and a candle to read it by. The only window was hardly wider than an arrow slit. 
\par Cersei found Margaery barefoot and shivering, clad in the roughspun shift of a novice sister. Her locks were all a tangle, and her feet were filthy. \'93They took my }{\cs28\i clothes}{ from me,\'94 the little queen told her once they were alone. \'93
I wore a gown of ivory lace, with freshwater pearls on the bodice, but the septas laid their }{\cs28\i hands}{
 on me and stripped me to the skin. My cousins too. Megga sent one septa crashing into the candles and set her robe afire. I fear for Alla, though. She went as white as milk, too frightened even to cry.\'94 
\par \'93Poor child.\'94 There were no chairs, so Cersei sat beside the little queen on her pallet. \'93Lady Taena has gone to speak with her, to let her know that she is not forgotten.\'94 
\par \'93He will not even let me see them,\'94 fumed Margaery. \'93He keeps each of us apart from the others. Until you came, I was allowed no visi
tors but septas. One comes every hour to ask if I wish to confess my fornications. They will not even let me sleep. They wake me to demand confessions. Last night I confessed to Septa Unella that I wished to scratch her eyes out.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i A shame you did not do it,}{ Cersei thought. }{\cs28\i Blinding some poor old septa would certainly persuade the High Sparrow of your guilt.}{ \'93They are questioning your cousins the same way.\'94 
\par \'93Damn them, then,\'94 said Margaery. \'93Damn them all to seven hells. Alla is gentle and shy, how can they do this to her? And Megga . . . she laughs as loud as a dockside whore, I know, but inside she\rquote 
s still just a little girl. I love them all, and they love me. If this sparrow thinks to make them lie about me . . .\'94 
\par \'93They stand accused as well, I fear. All three.\'94 
\par \'93My }{\cs28\i cousins}{?\'94 Margaery paled. \'93Alla and Megga are hardly more than children. Your Grace, this . . . this is obscene. Will you take us out of here?\'94 
\par \'93Would that I could.\'94 Her voice was full of sorrow. \'93His High Holiness has his new knights guarding you. To free you I would need to send the gold cloaks and profane this holy place with killing.\'94 Cersei took Margaery\rquote s hand in hers. 
\'93I have not been idle, though. I have gathered up all those that Ser Osney named as your lovers. They will tell His High Holiness of your innocence, I am certain, and swear to it at your trial.\'94 
\par \'93Trial?\'94 There was real fear in the girl\rquote s voice now. \'93Must there be a trial?\'94 
\par \'93How else will you prove your innocence?\'94 Cersei gave Margaery\rquote s hand a reassuring squeeze. \'93It is your right to decide the manner of the trial, to be sure. You are the queen. The knights of the Kingsguard are sworn to defend you.\'94 

\par Margaery understood at once. \'93A trial by battle? Loras is hurt, though, elsewise he . . .\'94 
\par \'93He has six brothers.\'94 
\par Margaery stared at her, then pulled her hand away. \'93Is that a jape? Boros is a craven, Meryn is old and slow, your brother is maimed, the other two are off in Dorne, and Osmund is a bloody }{\cs28\i Kettleblack.}{ Loras has }{\cs28\i two}{
 brothers, not six. If there\rquote s to be a trial by battle, I want Garlan as my champion.\'94 
\par \'93Ser Garlan is not a member of the Kingsguard,\'94 the queen said. \'93When the queen\rquote s honor is at issue, law and custom require that her champion be one of the king\rquote s sworn seven. The High Septon will insist, I fear.\'94 }{\cs28\i 
I will make certain of it.}{ 
\par Margaery did not answer at once, but her brown eyes narrowed in suspicion. \'93Blount or Trant,\'94 she said at last. \'93It would have to be one of them. You\rquote d like that, wouldn\rquote t you? Osney Kettleblack would cut either one to pieces.\'94 

\par }{\cs28\i Seven hells.}{ Cersei donned a look of hurt. \'93You wrong me, daughter. All I want\emdash \'94 
\par \'93\emdash is your son, all for yourself. He will never have a wife that you don\rquote t hate. And I am }{\cs28\i not}{ your daughter, thank the gods. Leave me.\'94 
\par \'93You are being foolish. I am only here to help you.\'94 
\par \'93To help me to my grave. I asked for you to leave. Will you make me call my gaolers and have you dragged away, you vile, scheming, evil bitch?\'94 
\par Cersei gathered up her skirts and dignity. \'93This must be very frightening for you. I shall forgive those words.\'94 Here, as at court, one never knew who might be listening. \'93
I would be afraid as well, in your place. Grand Maester Pycelle has admitted providing you with moon tea, and your Blue Bard . .
 . if I were you, my lady, I would pray to the Crone for wisdom and to the Mother for her mercy. I fear you may soon be in dire need of both.\'94 
\par Four shriveled septas escorted the queen down the tower steps. Each of the crones seemed more feeble than the last. When they reached the ground they continued down, into the heart of Visenya\rquote 
