ll come free me, and we\rquote ll drag the bloody High Sparrow back to the Red Keep in chains.}{ 
\par She screamed and kicked and howled until her throat was raw, at the door and at the window. No one shouted back, nor came to rescue her. The cell began to darken. It was growing cold as well. Cersei began to shiver. }{\cs28\i 
How can they leave me like this, without so much as a fire? I am their queen.}{ She began to regret tearing apart the shift they\rquote d given her. There was a blanket on the pallet in the corner, a threadbare thing of thin brown wool. It was rou
gh and scratchy, but it was all she had. Cersei huddled underneath to keep from shivering, and before long she had fallen into an exhausted sleep. 
\par The next she knew, a heavy hand was shaking her awake. It was black as pitch inside the cell, and a huge ugly woman was kneeling over her, a candle in her hand. \'93Who are you?\'94 the queen demanded. \'93Are you come to set me free?\'94 
\par \'93I am Septa Unella. I am come to hear you tell of all your murders and fornications.\'94 
\par Cersei knocked her hand aside. \'93I will have your head. Do not presume to touch me. Get away.\'94 
\par The woman rose. \'93Your Grace. I will be back in an hour. Mayhaps by then you will be ready to confess.\'94 
\par An hour and an hour and an hour. So passed the longest night that Cersei Lannister had ever known, save for the night of Joffrey\rquote 
s wedding. Her throat was so raw from shouting that she could hardly swallow. The cell turned freezing cold. She had smashed the chamber pot, so she had to squat in a corner to make her water and watch it trickle across the floor. Ev
ery time she closed her eyes, Unella was looming over her again, shaking her and asking her if she wanted to confess her sins. 
\par Day brought no relief. Septa Moelle brought her a bowl of some waterly grey gruel as the sun was coming up. Cersei flung it at h
er head. When they brought a fresh ewer of water, though, she was so thirsty that she had no choice but to drink. When they brought another shift, grey and thin and smelling of mildew, she put it on over her nakedness. And that evening when Moelle appeare
d again she ate the bread and fish and demanded wine to wash it down. No wine appeared, only Septa Unella, making her hourly visit to ask if the queen was ready to confess. 
\par }{\cs28\i What can be happening?}{ Cersei wondered, as the thin slice of sky outside her window began to darken once again. }{\cs28\i Why has no one come to pry me out of here?}{
