\par }{\cs28\i Even from the grave, Lord Tywin\rquote s dead hand moves us all.}{ \'93Joy is my late uncle Gerion\rquote s natural 
daughter. A betrothal can be arranged, if that is your wish, but any marriage will need to wait. Joy was nine or ten when last I saw her.\'94 
\par \'93His }{\cs28\i natural}{ daughter?\'94 Lady Sybell looked as if she had swallowed a lemon. \'93You want a Westerling to wed a }{\cs28\i bastard?}{\'94 
\par \'93No more than I want Joy to marry the son of some scheming turncloak bitch. She deserves better.\'94 Jaime would happily have strangled the woman with her seashell necklace. Joy was a sweet child, albeit a lonely one; her father had been Jaime\rquote 
s favorite uncle. \'93Your daughter is worth ten of you, my lady. You\rquote ll leave with Edmure and Ser Forley on the morrow. Until then, you would do well to stay out of my sight.\'94
 He shouted for a guardsman, and Lady Sybell went off with her lips pressed primly together. Jaime had to wonder how much Lord Gawen knew about his wife\rquote s scheming. }{\cs28\i How much do we men ever know? }{
\par When Edmure and the Westerlings departed, four hundred men rode with them; Jaime had doubled the escort again at the last moment. He rode with them a few miles, to talk with Ser Forley Prester. Though he bore a bull\rquote 
s head upon his surcoat and horns upon his helm, Ser Forley could not have been less bovine. He was a short, spare, hard-bitten man. With his pinched nose, bald pate, and grizzled brown beard, he looked more like an innkeep than a knight. \'93We don
\rquote t know where the Blackfish is,\'94 Jaime reminded him, \'93but if he can cut Edmure free, he will.\'94 
\par \'93That will not happen, my lord.\'94 Like most innkeeps, Ser Forley was no man\rquote s fool. \'93Scouts and outriders will screen our march, and we\rquote 
ll fortify our camps by night. I have picked ten men to stay with Tully day and night, my best longbowmen. If he should ride so much as a foot off the road, they will loose so many shafts at him that his own mother would take him for a goose.\'94 
\par \'93Good.\'94 Jaime would as lief have Tully reach Casterly Rock safely, but better dead than fled. \'93Best keep some archers near Lord Westerling\rquote s daughter as well.\'94 
\par Ser Forley seemed taken aback. \'93Gawen\rquote s girl? She\rquote s\emdash \'94 
\par \'93\emdash the Young Wolf\rquote s widow,\'94 Jaime finished, \'93and twice as dangerous as Edmure if she were ever to escape us.\'94 
\par \'93As you say, my lord. She will be watched.\'94 
\par Jaime had to canter past the Westerlings as he rode down the column on his way back to Riverrun. Lord Gawen nodded gravely as 
he passed, but Lady Sybell looked through him with eyes like chips of ice. Jeyne never saw him at all. The widow rode with downcast eyes, huddled beneath a hooded cloak. Underneath its heavy folds, her clothes were finely made, but torn. }{\cs28\i 
She ripped them herself, as a mark of mourning,}{ Jaime realized. }{\cs28\i That could not have pleased her mother.}{ He found himself wondering if Cersei would tear her gown if she should ever hear that he was dead. 
\par He did not go straight back to the castle but crossed the Tumblestone once more to call on Edwyn Frey and discuss the transfer of his great-grandfather\rquote s prisoners. The Frey host had begun to break up within hours of Riverrun\rquote 
s surrender, as Lord Walder\rquote s bannermen and freeriders pulled up stakes to make for home. The Freys who still remained were striking camp, but he found Edwyn with his bastard uncle in the latter\rquote s pavilion. 
\par The two of them were huddled over a map, arguing heatedly, but they broke off when Jaime entered. \'93Lord Commander,\'94 Rivers said with cold courtesy, but Edwyn blurted out, \'93My father\rquote s blood is on your hands, ser.\'94 
\par That took Jaime a bit aback. \'93How so?\'94 
\par \'93You were the one who sent him home, were you not?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Someone had to.}{ \'93Has some ill befallen Ser Ryman?\'94 
\par \'93Hanged with all his party,\'94 said Walder Rivers. \'93The outlaws caught them two leagues south of Fairmarket.\'94 
\par \'93Dondarrion?\'94 
\par \'93Him, or Thoros, or this woman Stoneheart.\'94 
\par Jaime frowned. Ryman Frey had been a fool, a craven, and a sot, and no one was like to miss him much, least of all his fellow Freys. If Edwyn\rquote s dry eyes were any clue, even his own sons would not mourn him long. }{\cs28\i 
Still . . . these outlaws are growing bold, if they dare hang Lord Walder\rquote s heir not a day\rquote s ride from the Twins.}{ \'93How many men did Ser Ryman have with him?\'94 he asked. 
\par \'93Three knights and a dozen men-at-arms,\'94 said Rivers. \'93It is almost as if they knew that he would be returning to the Twins, and with a small escort.\'94 
\par Edwyn\rquote s mouth twisted. \'93My brother had a hand in this, I\rquote ll wager. He allowed the outlaws to escape after they murdered Merrett and Petyr, and this is why. With our father dead, there\rquote 
s only me left between Black Walder and the Twins.\'94 
\par \'93You have no proof of this,\'94 said Walder Rivers. 
\par \'93I do not need proof. I know my brother.\'94 
\par \'93Your brother is at Seagard,\'94 Rivers insisted. \'93How could he have known that Ser Ryman was returning to the Twins?\'94 
\par \'93Someone told him,\'94 said Edwyn in a bitter tone. \'93He has his spies in our camp, you can be sure.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i And you have yours at Seagard.}{ Jaime knew that the enmity between Edwyn and Black Walder ran deep, but cared not a fig which of them succeeded their great-grandfather as Lord of the Crossing. 
\par \'93If you will pardon me for intruding on your grief,\'94 he said, in a dry tone, \'93we have other matters to consider. When you return to the Twins, please inform Lord Walder that King Tommen requires all the captives you took at the Red Wedding.\'94 

\par Ser Walder frowned. \'93These prisoners are valuable, ser.\'94 
\par \'93His Grace would not ask for them if they were worthless.\'94 
\par Frey and Rivers exchanged a look. Edwyn said, \'93My lord grandfather will expect recompense for these prisoners.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i And he\rquote ll have it, as soon as I grow a new hand,}{ thought Jaime. \'93We all have expectations,\'94 he said mildly. \'93Tell me, is Ser Raynald Westerling amongst these captives?\'94 
\par \'93The knight of seashells?\'94 Edwyn sneered. \'93You\rquote ll find that one feeding the fish at the bottom of the Green Fork.\'94 
\par \'93He was in the yard when our men came to put the direwolf down,\'94 said Walder Rivers. \'93Whalen demanded his sword and he gave it over meek enough, but when the crossbowmen began feathering the wolf he seized Whalen\rquote 
s axe and cut the monster loose of the net they\rquote d thrown over him. Whalen says he took a quarrel in his shoulder and another in the gut, but still managed to reach the wallwalk and throw himself into the river.\'94 
\par \'93He left a trail of blood on the steps,\'94 said Edwyn. 
\par \'93Did you find his corpse afterward?\'94 asked Jaime. 
\par \'93We found a thousand corpses afterward. Once they\rquote ve spent a few days in the river they all look much the same.\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote ve heard the same is true of hanged men,\'94 said Jaime, before he took his leave. 
\par By the next morning little remained of the Frey encampment but flies, horse dung, and Ser Ryman\rquote s gallows, standing forlorn beside the Tumbl
estone. His coz wanted to know what should be done with it, and with the siege equipment he had built, his rams and sows and towers and treb-uchets. Daven proposed that they drag it all to Raventree and use it there. Jaime told him to put everything to th
e torch, starting with the gallows. \'93I mean to deal with Lord Tytos myself. It won\rquote t require a siege tower.\'94 
\par Daven grinned through his bushy beard. \'93Single combat, coz? Scarce seems fair. Tytos is an old grey man.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i An old grey man with two hands. }{
\par That night he and Ser Ilyn fought for three hours. It was one of his better nights. If they had been in earnest, Payne only would have killed him twice. Half a dozen deaths were more the rule, and some nights were worse than that. \'93
If I keep at this for another year, I may be as good as Peck,\'94 Jaime declared, and Ser Ilyn made that clacking sound that meant he was amused. \'93Come, let\rquote s drink some more of Hoster Tully\rquote s good red wine.\'94 
\par Wine had become a part of their nightly ritual. Ser Ilyn made the perfect drinking companion. He never interrupted, never disagreed, never complained or asked for favors or told long pointless stories. All he did was drink and listen. 
\par \'93I should have the tongues removed from all my friends,\'94 said Jaime as he filled their cups, \'93and from my kin as well. A silent Cersei would be sweet. Though I\rquote d miss her tongue when we kissed.\'94
 He drank. The wine was a deep red, sweet and heavy. It warmed him going down. \'93I can\rquote t remember when we first began to kiss. It was innocent at first. Until it wasn\rquote t.\'94 He finished the wine and set his cup aside. \'93
Tyrion once told me that most whores will not kiss you. They\rquote ll fuck you blind, he said, but you\rquote ll never feel their lips on yours. Do you think my sister kisses Kettleblack?\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn did not answer. 
\par \'93I don\rquote t think it would be proper for me to slay mine own Sworn Brother. What I need to do is geld him and send him to the Wall. That\rquote 
s what they did with Lucamore the Lusty. Ser Osmund may not take kindly to the gelding, to be sure. And there are his brot
hers to consider. Brothers can be dangerous. After Aegon the Unworthy put Ser Terrence Toyne to death for sleeping with his mistress, Toyne\rquote 
s brothers did their best to kill him. Their best was not quite good enough, thanks to the Dragonknight, but it was not for want of trying. It\rquote s written down in the White Book. All of it, save what to do with Cersei.\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn drew a finger across his throat. 
\par \'93No,\'94 said Jaime. \'93Tommen has lost a brother, and the man he thought of as his father. If I were to kill his m
other, he would hate me for it . . . and that sweet little wife of his would find a way to turn that hatred to the benefit of Highgarden.\'94 
\par Ser Ilyn smiled in a way Jaime did not like. }{\cs28\i An ugly smile. An ugly soul.}{ \'93You talk too much,\'94 he told the man. 
\par The next day Ser Dermot of the Rainwood returned to the castle, empty-handed. When asked what he\rquote d found, he answered, \'93Wolves. Hundreds of the bloody beggars.\'94 He\rquote 
d lost two sentries to them. The wolves had come out of the dark to savage them. \'93Armed men in 
mail and boiled leather, and yet the beasts had no fear of them. Before he died, Jate said the pack was led by a she-wolf of monstrous size. A direwolf, to hear him tell it. The wolves got in amongst our horse lines too. The bloody bastards killed my favo
rite bay.\'94 
\par \'93A ring of fires round your camp might keep them off,\'94 said Jaime, though he wondered. Could Ser Dermot\rquote s direwolf be the same beast that had mauled Joffrey near the crossroads? 
\par Wolves or no, Ser Dermot took fresh horses and more men and went o
ut again the next morning, to resume the search for Brynden Tully. That same afternoon, the lords of the Trident came to Jaime asking his leave to return to their own lands. He granted it. Lord Piper also wanted to know about his son Marq. \'93
All the captives will be ransomed,\'94 Jaime promised. As the riverlords took their leave, Lord Karyl Vance lingered to say, \'93
Lord Jaime, you must go to Raventree. So long as it is Jonos at his gates Tytos will never yield, but I know he will bend his knee for you.\'94 Jaime thanked him for his counsel. 
\par Strongboar was the next to depart. He wanted to return to Darry as he\rquote d promised and fight the outlaws. \'93We rode across half the bloody realm and for what? So you could make Edmure Tully piss his breeches? There\rquote s no song in th
at. I need a }{\cs28\i fight.}{ I want the Hound, Jaime. Him, or the marcher lord.\'94 
\par \'93The Hound\rquote s head is yours if you can take it,\'94 Jaime said, \'93but Beric Dondarrion is to be captured alive, so he can be brought back to King\rquote s Landing. A thousand people need to see him die, or else he won\rquote t stay dead.\'94
 Strongboar grumbled at that, but finally agreed. The next day he departed with his squire and men-at-arms, plus Beardless Jon Bettley, who had decided that hunting outlaws was preferable to returning to his famously hom
ely wife. Supposedly she had the beard that Bettley lacked. 
\par Jaime still had the garrison to deal with. To a man, they swore that they knew nothing of Ser Brynden\rquote s plans or where he might have gone. \'93They are lying,\'94 Emmon Frey insisted, but Jaime thought not. \'93
If you share your plans with no one, no one can betray you,\'94 he pointed out. Lady Genna suggested that a few of the men might be put to the question. He refused. \'93I gave Edmure my word that if he yielded, the garrison could leave unharmed.\'94 

\par \'93That was chivalrous of you,\'94 his aunt said, \'93but it\rquote s strength that\rquote s needed here, not chivalry.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Ask Edmure how chivalrous I am,}{ thought Jaime. }{\cs28\i Ask him about the trebuchet.}{ Somehow he did not think the maesters were like to confuse him with Prince Aemon 
the Dragonknight when they wrote their histories. Still, he felt curiously content. The war was all but won. Dragonstone had fallen and Storm\rquote 
s End would soon enough, he could not doubt, and Stannis was welcome to the Wall. The northmen would love him no more than the storm lords had. If Roose Bolton did not destroy him, winter would. 
\par And he had done his own part here at Riverrun without actually ever taking up arms against the Starks or Tullys. Once he found the Blackfish, he would be free to return to King\rquote s Landing, where he belonged. }{\cs28\i 
My place is with my king. With my son.}{ Would Tommen want to know that? The truth could cost the boy his throne. }{\cs28\i Would you sooner have a father or a chair, lad?}{ Jaime wished he knew the answer. }{\cs28\i He does like stamping papers w
ith his seal.}{ The boy might not even believe him, to be sure. Cersei would say it was a lie. }{\cs28\i My sweet sister, the deceiver.}{
 He would need to find some way to winkle Tommen from her clutches before the boy became another Joffrey. And whilst at that, he should find the lad a new small council too. }{\cs28\i If Cersei can be put aside, Ser Kevan may agree to serve as Tommen
\rquote s Hand.}{ And if not, well, the Seven Kingdoms did not lack for able men. Forley Prester would make a good choice, or Roland Crakehall. If someone oth
er than a westerman was needed to appease the Tyrells, there was always Mathis Rowan . . . or even Petyr Baelish. Littlefinger was as amiable as he was clever, but too lowborn to threaten any of the great lords, with no swords of his own. }{\cs28\i 
The perfect Hand.}{ 
\par The Tully garrison departed the next morning, stripped of all their arms and armor. Each man was allowed three days\rquote  food and the clothing on his back, after he swore a solemn oath never to take up arms against Lord Emmon or House Lannister. \'93
If you\rquote re fortunate, one man in ten may keep that vow,\'94 Lady Genna said. 
\par \'93Good. I\rquote d sooner face nine men than ten. The tenth might have been the one who would have killed me.\'94 
\par \'93The other nine will kill you just as quick.\'94 
\par \'93Better that than die in bed.\'94 }{\cs28\i Or on the privy. }{
\par Two men did not choose to depart with the others. Ser Desmond Grell, Lord Hoster\rquote s old master-at-arms, preferred to take the black. So did Ser Robin Ryger, Riverrun\rquote s captain of guards. \'93This castle\rquote s been my home for forty years,
\'94 said Grell. \'93You say I\rquote m free to go, but where? I\rquote m too old and too stout to make a hedge knight. But men are always welcome at the Wall.\'94 
\par \'93As you wish,\'94 said Jaime, though it was a bloody nuisance. He allowed them to keep their arms and armor, and assigned a dozen of Gregor Clegane\rquote 
s men to escort the two of them to Maidenpool. The command he gave to Rafford, the one they called the Sweetling. \'93See to it that the prisoners reach Maidenpool unspoiled,\'94 he told the man, \'93or what Ser Gregor did to the Goat will seem a jolly 
lark compared to what I\rquote ll do to you.\'94 
\par More days passed. Lord Emmon assembled all of Riverrun in the yard, Lord Edmure\rquote s people and his own, and spoke to them for close on three hours about what would be expected of them now that he was their lord and mas
ter. From time to time he waved his parchment, as stableboys and serving girls and smiths listened in a sullen silence and a light rain fell down upon them all. 
\par The singer was listening too, the one that Jaime had taken from Ser Ryman Frey. Jaime came upon him standing inside an open door, where it was dry. \'93His lordship should have been a singer,\'94 the man said. \'93
This speech is longer than a marcher ballad, and I don\rquote t think he\rquote s stopped for breath.\'94 
\par Jaime had to laugh. \'93Lord Emmon does not need to breathe, so long as he can chew. Are you going to make a song of it?\'94 
\par \'93A funny one. I\rquote ll call it \lquote Talking to the Fish.\rquote \'94 
\par \'93Just don\rquote t play it where my aunt can hear.\'94 Jaime had never paid the man much mind before. He was a small fellow, garbed in ragged green b
reeches and a frayed tunic of a lighter shade of green, with brown leather patches covering the holes. His nose was long and sharp, his smile big and loose. Thin brown hair fell to his collar, snaggled and unwashed. }{\cs28\i Fifty if he\rquote s a day,}{
 thought Jaime, }{\cs28\i a hedge harp, and hard used by life.}{ \'93Weren\rquote t you Ser Ryman\rquote s man when I found you?\'94 he asked. 
\par \'93Only for a fortnight.\'94 
\par \'93I would have expected you to depart with the Freys.\'94 
\par \'93That one up there\rquote s a Frey,\'94 the singer said, nodding at Lord Emmon, \'93and this castle seems a nice snug place to pass the winter. Whitesmile Wat went home with Ser Forley, so I thought I\rquote d see if I could win his place. Wat\rquote 
s got that high sweet voice that the likes o\rquote  me can\rquote t hope to match. But I know twice as many bawdy songs as he does. Begging my lord\rquote s pardon.\'94 
\par \'93You should get on famously with my aunt,\'94 said Jaime. \'93If you hope to winter here, see that your playing pleases Lady Genna. She\rquote s the one that matters.\'94 
\par \'93Not you?\'94 
\par \'93My place is with the king. I shall not stay here long.\'94 
\par \'93I\rquote m sorry to hear that, my lord. I know better songs than \lquote The Rains of Castamere.\rquote  I could have played you . . . oh, all sorts o\rquote  things.\'94 
\par \'93Some other time,\'94 said Jaime. \'93Do you have a name?\'94 
\par \'93Tom of Sevenstreams, if it please my lord.\'94 The singer doffed his hat. \'93Most call me Tom o\rquote  Sevens, though.\'94 
\par \'93Sing sweetly, Tom o\rquote  Sevens.\'94 
\par That night he dreamt that he was back in the Great Sept of Baelor, still standing vigil over his father\rquote s corpse. The sept was still and dark, until a woman emerged from the shadows and walked slowly to the bier. \'93Sister?\'94 he said. 
\par But it was not Cersei. She was all in grey, a silent sister. A hood and veil concealed her features, but he could see the candles burning in the green pools of her eyes. \'93Sister,\'94 he said, \'93what would you have of me?\'94
 His last word echoed up and down the sept, }{\cs28\i mememememememememememe.}{ 
\par \'93I am not your sister, Jaime.\'94 She raised a pale soft hand and pushed her hood back. \'93Have you forgotten me?\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i Can I forget someone I never knew?}{ The words caught in his throat. He }{\cs28\i did}{ know her, but it had been so long . . . 
\par \'93Will you forget your own lord father too? I wonder if you ever knew him, truly.\'94 Her eyes were green, her hair spun gold. He could not tell how old she was. }{\cs28\i Fifteen,}{ he thought, }{\cs28\i or fifty.}{ She cl
imbed the steps to stand above the bier. \'93He could never abide being laughed at. That was the thing he hated most.\'94 
\par \'93Who are you?\'94 He had to hear her say it. 
\par \'93The question is, who are you?\'94 
\par \'93This is a dream.\'94 
\par \'93Is it?\'94 She smiled sadly. \'93Count your hands, child.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i One.}{ One hand, clasped tight around the sword hilt. Only one. \'93In my dreams I always have two hands.\'94 He raised his right arm and stared uncomprehending at the ugliness of his stump. 
\par \'93We all dream of things we cannot have. Tywin dreamed that his son would be a great knight, that his daughter would be a queen. He dreamed they would be so strong and brave and beautiful that no one would ever laugh at them.\'94 
\par \'93I am a knight,\'94 he told her, \'93and Cersei is a queen.\'94 
\par A tear rolled down her cheek. The woman raised her hood again and turned her back on him. Jaime called after her, but already she was moving away, her skirt whispering lullabies as it brushed across the floor. }{\cs28\i Don\rquote t leave me,}{
 he wanted to call, but of course she\rquote d left them long ago. 
\par He woke in darkness, shivering. The room had grown cold as ice. Jaime flung aside the covers with the stump of his sword hand. The fire in the hearth had died, he saw, and the window had blown open. He crossed the pitch-dark chamber to fumble w
ith the shutters, but when he reached the window his bare foot came down in something wet. Jaime recoiled, startled for a moment. His first thought was of blood, but blood would not have been so cold. 
\par It was snow, drifting through the window. 
\par Instead of 
closing the shutters he threw them wide. The yard below was covered by a thin white blanket, growing thicker even as he watched. The merlons on the battlements wore white cowls. The flakes fell silently, a few drifting in the window to melt upon his face.
 Jaime could see his own breath. 
\par }{\cs28\i Snow in the riverlands.}{ If it was snowing here, it could well be snowing on Lannisport as well, and on King\rquote s Landing. }{\cs28\i Winter is marching south, and half our granaries are empty.}{ Any crops still in the fields were doomed. T
here would be no more plantings, no more hopes of one last harvest. He found himself wondering what his father would do to feed the realm, before he remembered that Tywin Lannister was dead. 
\par When morning broke the snow was ankle deep, and deeper in the go
dswood, where drifts had piled up under the trees. Squires, stableboys, and highborn pages turned to children again under its cold white spell, and fought a snowball war up and down the wards and all along the battlements. Jaime heard them laughing. There
 was a time, not long ago, when he might have been out making snowballs with the best of them, to fling at Tyrion when he waddled by, or slip down the back of Cersei\rquote s gown. }{\cs28\i You need two hands to make a decent snowball, though.}{ 
\par There was a rap upon his door. \'93See who that is, Peck.\'94 
\par It was Riverrun\rquote s old maester, with a message clutched in his lined and wrinkled hand. Vyman\rquote s face was as pale as the new-fallen snow. \'93I know,\'94 Jaime said, \'93there has been a white raven from the Citadel. Winter has come.\'94 

\par \'93No, my lord. The bird was from King\rquote s Landing. I took the liberty . . . I did not know . . .\'94 He held the letter out. 
\par Jaime read it in the window seat, bathed in the light of that cold white morning. Qyburn\rquote s words were terse and to the point, Cersei\rquote s fevered and fervent. }{\cs28\i Come at once,}{ she said. }{\cs28\i 
Help me. Save me. I need you now as I have never needed you before. I love you. I love you. I love you. Come at once.}{ 
\par Vyman was hovering by the door, waiting, and Jaime sensed that Peck was watching too. \'93Does my lord wish to answer?\'94 the maester asked, after a long silence. 
\par A snowflake landed on the letter. As it melted, the ink began to blur. Jaime rolled the parchment up again, as tight as one hand would allow, and handed it to Peck. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93Put this in the fire.\'94 
