\par Hey, wait a minute!\'94 some of you may be saying about now. \'93Wait a minute, wait a minute! Where\rquote s Dany and the dragons? Where\rquote s Tyrion? We hardly saw Jon Snow. That can\rquote t be all of it. . . .\'94 
\par Well, no. There\rquote s more to come. Another book as big as this one. 
\par I did not forget to write about the other characters. Far from it. I wrote lots about them. Pages and pages and pages. Chapters and more chapters. 
I was still writing when it dawned on me that the book had become too big to publish in a single volume . . . and I wasn\rquote t close to finished yet. To tell all of the story that I wanted to tell, I was going to have to cut the book in two. 
\par The simplest way to do that would have been to take what I had, chop it in half around the middle, and end with \'93To Be Continued.\'94
 The more I thought about that, however, the more I felt that the readers would be better served by a book that told all the story for half the characters, rather than half the story for all the characters. So that\rquote s the route I chose to take. 

\par Tyrion, Jon, Dany, Stannis and Melisandre, Davos Seaworth, and all the rest of the characters you love or love to hate will be along next year (I devoutly hope) in }{\cs28\i A Dance with Dragons}{
, which will focus on events along the Wall and across the sea, just as the present book focused on King\rquote s Landing. 
