. Hizdahr, if you could marshal armies as you marshal arguments, you could conquer the world . . . but my answer is still no. For the sixth time.\'94 
\par He bowed again, as deeply as before. His pearls and amethysts clattered softly against the marble floor. A very limber man was Hizdahr zo Loraq. \'93The queen has spoken.\'94 
\par }{\cs28\i He might be handsome, but for that silly hair.}{ Reznak and the Green Grace had been urging Dany to take a Meereenese noble for her husband, to reconcile the city to her rule. If it came to that, Hizdahr zo Loraq might be worth a careful look. }
{\cs28\i Sooner him than Skahaz.}{ The Shavepate had offered to set aside his wife for her, but the notion made her shudder. Hizdahr at least knew how to smile, though when Dany tried to imagine what it would be like to
 share a bed with him, she almost laughed aloud. 
\par \'93Magnificence,\'94 said Reznak, consulting his list, \'93the noble Grazdan zo Galare would address you. Will you hear him?\'94 
\par \'93It would be my pleasure,\'94 said Dany, admiring the glimmer of the gold and the sheen of the green pearls on Cleon\rquote 
s slippers while doing her best to ignore the pinching in her toes. Grazdan, she had been forewarned, was a cousin of the Green Grace, whose support she had found invaluable. The priestess was a voice for peace, acceptance, and o
bedience to lawful authority. }{\cs28\i I can give her cousin a respectful hearing, whatever he desires.}{ 
\par What he desired turned out to be gold. Dany had refused to compensate any of the Great Masters for the value of the slaves that she had freed, but the Meereenes
e kept devising other ways to try to squeeze coin from her. The noble Grazdan was one such. He had once owned a slave woman who was a very fine weaver, he told her; the fruits of her loom were greatly valued, not only in Meereen, but in New Ghis and Astap
o
r and Qarth. When this woman had grown old, Grazdan had purchased half a dozen young girls and commanded the crone to instruct them in the secrets of her craft. The old woman was dead now. The young ones, freed, had opened a shop by the harbor wall to sel
l their weavings. Grazdan zo Galare asked that he be granted a portion of their earnings. \'93They owe their skill to me,\'94 he insisted. \'93I plucked them from the auction bloc and gave them to the loom.\'94 
\par Dany listened quietly, her face still. When he was done, she said, \'93What was the name of the old weaver?\'94 
\par \'93The slave?\'94 Grazdan shifted his weight, frowning. \'93She was . . . Elza, it might have been. Or Ella. It was six years ago she died. I have owned so many slaves, Your Grace.\'94 
\par \'93Let us say Elza.\'94 Dany raised a hand. \'93
Here is our ruling. From the girls, you shall have nothing. It was Elza who taught them weaving, not you. From you, the girls shall have a new loom, the finest coin can buy. That is for forgetting the name of the old woman. You may go.\'94 
\par Reznak would have summoned another }{\cs28\i tokar}{
 next, but Dany insisted that he call upon one of the freedmen instead. From that point on she alternated between the former masters and the former slaves. Many and more of the matters brought before her involved redress. Mee
reen had been sacked savagely after its fall. The stepped pyramids of the mighty had been spared the worst of the ravages, but the humbler parts of the city had been given over to an orgy of looting and killing as the city\rquote 
s slaves rose up and the starving
 hordes who had followed her from Yunkai and Astapor came pouring through the broken gates. Her Unsullied had finally restored order, but the sack had left a plague of problems in its wake, and no one was quite certain which laws still held true. And so t
hey came to see the queen. 
\par A rich woman came, whose husband and sons had died defending the city walls. During the sack she had fled to her brother in fear. When she returned, she found her house had been turned into a brothel. The whores had bedecked them
selves in her jewels and clothes. She wanted her house back, and her jewels. \'93They can keep the clothes,\'94 she allowed. Dany granted her the jewels, but ruled the house was lost when she abandoned it. 
\par A former slave came, to accuse a certain noble of the Zhak. The man had recently taken to wife a freedwoman who had been the noble\rquote 
s bedwarmer before the city fell. The noble had taken her maidenhood, used her for his pleasure, and gotten her with child. Her new husband wanted the noble gelded for the crime of
 rape, and he wanted a purse of gold as well, to pay him for raising the noble\rquote s bastard as his own. Dany granted him the gold, but not the gelding. \'93
When he lay with her, your wife was his property, to do with as he would. By law, there was no rape.\'94 Her decision did not please him, she could see, but if she gelded every man who ever forced a bedslave, she would soon rule a city of eunuchs. 
\par A boy came, younger than Dany, slight and scarred, dressed up in a frayed grey }{\cs28\i tokar}{ trailing silver fringe. His voice broke when he told of how two of his father\rquote 
s household slaves had risen up the night the gate broke. One had slain his father, the other his elder brother. Both had raped his mother before killing her as well. The boy had escaped with no more than the 
scar upon his face, but one of the murderers was still living in his father\rquote s house, and the other had joined the queen\rquote s soldiers as one of the Mother\rquote s Men. He wanted them both hanged. 
\par }{\cs28\i I am queen over a city built on dust and death.}{ Dany had no choice but to deny him. She had declared a blanket pardon for all crimes committed during the sack. Nor would she punish slaves for rising up against their masters. 
\par When she told him, the boy rushed at her, but his feet tangled in his }{\cs28\i tokar}{ an
d he went sprawling headlong on the purple marble. Strong Belwas was on him at once. The huge brown eunuch yanked him up one-handed and shook him like a mastiff with a rat. \'93Enough, Belwas,\'94 Dany called. \'93Release him.\'94 To the boy she said, 
\'93Treasure that }{\cs28\i tokar,}{ for it saved your life. Had you laid a hand on us in anger, you would have lost that hand. You are only a boy, so we will forget what happened here. You should do the same.\'94
 But as he left, the boy looked back over his shoulder, and when she saw his eyes Dany thought, }{\cs28\i The harpy has another son.}{ 
\par And so her day crept by, tedious and terrifying by turns. By midday Daenerys was feeling the weight of the crown upon her head, and the hardness of the bench beneath her. With so many still waiting on her plea
sure, she did not stop to eat. Instead she dispatched Jhiqui to the kitchens for a platter of flatbread, olives, figs, and cheese. She nibbled whilst she listened, and sipped from a cup of watered wine. The figs were fine, the olives even finer, but the w
ine left a tart metallic aftertaste in her mouth. The small, pale yellow grapes native to these regions produced a notably inferior vintage. }{\cs28\i We shall have no trade in wine,}{
 Dany realized as she sipped. Besides, the Great Masters had burned the best arbors along with the olive trees. 
\par In the afternoon a sculptor came, proposing to replace the head of the great bronze harpy in the Plaza of Purification with one cast in Dany\rquote s image. She denied him with as much courtesy as she could muster, struggling not to sh
udder. A pike of unprecedented size had been caught in the Skahazadhan, and the fisherman wished to give it to the queen. She admired the fish extravagantly, rewarded the fisherman with a plump purse of silver, and sent the pike down to her kitchens. A co
