persmith had fashioned her a suit of burnished rings to wear to war. She accepted it with fulsome thanks; it was lovely to behold, and all that burnished copper would flash prettily in the sun, though if actual battle threatened she would sooner be clad i
n steel. Even a young girl who knew nothing of the ways of war knew }{\cs28\i that.}{ 
\par The slippers the Butcher King had sent her had grown too uncomfortable. Dany kicked them off, and sat with one foot tucked beneath her and the other swinging back and forth. It was n
ot a very regal pose, but she was tired of being regal. The crown had given her a headache, and her buttocks had gone to sleep. \'93Ser Barristan,\'94 she called, \'93I know what quality a king needs most.\'94 
